window.EXAM_DATA = [{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2006","year":"2006","title":"2006 年英语一","fileName":"2006 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2006 年英语 1.md","content":"In spite of “endless talk of difference,” American society is an amazing machine for <font color=\"#ffff00\">homogenizing</font> people.\n翻译: <u>尽管有“关于差异的无休止谈论”，美国社会却是一台令人惊叹的、使人同质化的机器。</u>\n\n-**homogenizing people**：<u>把人变得相似。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is</font> “the <font color=\"#ffff00\">democratizing</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">uniformity</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">dress and discourse</font>, and the <font color=\"#ffff00\">casualness</font> and<font color=\"#ffff00\"> absence of deference</font>” <font color=\"#ffff00\">characteristic</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">popular culture.</font>\n翻译: <u>存在着流行文化所特有的“服饰和话语的民主化一致性，以及随意性和敬意的缺失”。</u>\n\n-**There is…**：<u>有、存在。</u>  \n-**democratizing**：<u>民主化的，使阶层差异减少的。</u>  \n-**uniformity**：<u>一致性、相似性。</u>  \n-**dress and discourse**：<u>穿着和话语/言谈方式。</u>  \n-**casualness**：<u>随意、不拘礼。</u>  \n-**absence of deference**：<u>缺少恭敬、等级服从。</u>  \n-**characteristic of…**：<u>具有……特征的、是……典型特征的。</u>  \n- popular culture. <u>大众文化。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nPeople <font color=\"#ffff00\">are absorbed into</font> “a culture of consumption” launched by the 19th-century department stores that offered “vast arrays of goods in an elegant atmosphere.”\n翻译: <u>人们被吸纳进一种“消费文化”之中，这种文化由19世纪的百货商店开启；这些商店在“优雅的氛围中”提供“琳琅满目的商品”。</u>\n\n-**be absorbed into…**：<u>被吸收到……中、融入……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nInstead of intimate shops catering to a knowledgeable elite, these were stores “anyone could enter, regardless of class or background.”\n翻译: <u>这些商店不同于服务于见多识广的精英阶层的亲密小店，而是“任何人都可以进入的商店，不论阶级或背景”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis turned shopping into a public and <font color=\"#ffff00\">democratic</font> act.\n翻译: <u>这使购物变成了一种公共的、民主的行为。</u>\n\n-**democratic**：<u>民主的、大众化的。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThe mass media, advertising and sports are other forces for homogenization.\n翻译: <u>大众传媒、广告和体育是其他推动同质化的力量。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nImmigrants are quickly fitting into this common culture, which may not be <font color=\"#ffff00\">altogether</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> elevating</font> but is <font color=\"#ffff00\">hardly poisonous</font>.\n翻译: <u>移民正迅速融入这种共同文化；这种文化也许并不完全高尚，但也绝非有害。</u>\n\n-**altogether**：<u>完全地。</u>  \n-**elevating**：<u>提升人的、高尚的、有教化作用的。</u> \n-**hardly poisonous**：<u>几乎不能说是有害的 / 绝不是有毒的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWriting for the National Immigration Forum, Gregory Rodriguez reports that today’s immigration is neither at unprecedented levels nor resistant to assimilation.\n翻译: <u>Gregory Rodriguez在为National Immigration Forum撰文时报告说，如今的移民既没有达到史无前例的水平，也并不抗拒同化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn 1998 immigrants were 9.8 percent of the population; in 1900, 13.6 percent.\n翻译: <u>1998年，移民占人口的9.8%；1900年则为13.6%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn the 10 years <font color=\"#ffff00\">prior to</font> 1990, 3.1 immigrants<font color=\"#ffff00\"> arrived </font>for every 1,000 residents; in the 10 years prior to 1890, 9.2 for every 1,000.\n翻译: <u>在1990年前的10年里，每1,000名居民中有3.1名移民到来；在1890年前的10年里，每1,000名居民中则有9.2名。</u>\n\n-**prior to**：<u>在……之前。</u>  \n-**arrived**：<u>到来、移入。</u>  \n-in <u>表示的是一个阶段的时间 在十年内</u>\n\n---\n\nNow, consider three <font color=\"#ffff00\">indices</font> of assimilation — language, <font color=\"#ffff00\">home ownership</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">intermarriage</font>.\n翻译: <u>现在，请考虑同化的三个指标——语言、住房拥有率和通婚。</u>\n\n-**indices**：index <u>的复数，指标。</u>  \n-**home ownership**：<u>住房拥有率。</u>  \n-**intermarriage**：<u>族际/跨族群婚姻。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe 1990 <font color=\"#ffff00\">Census</font> revealed that “a majority of immigrants from each of the fifteen most common countries of origin spoke English ‘well’ or ‘very well’ after ten years of residence.”\n翻译: <u>1990年人口普查显示，“来自十五个最常见原籍国的移民中，大多数人在居住十年后英语说得‘好’或‘非常好’。”</u>\n\n-**Census**：<u>人口普查。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe children of immigrants tend to be bilingual and proficient in English.\n翻译: <u>移民的子女往往会双语，并且熟练掌握英语。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">By</font> the third generation, the original language is lost in the majority of immigrant families.”\n翻译: <u>“到第三代时，大多数移民家庭的原有语言便消失了。”</u>\n\n-**By**：<u>到……时为止。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nHence the description of America as a “graveyard” for languages.\n翻译: <u>因此，美国被描述为语言的“墓地”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBy 1996 foreign-born immigrants who had arrived before 1970 had a home ownership rate of 75.6 percent, higher than the 69.8 percent rate among native-born Americans.\n翻译: <u>到1996年，1970年前到达的外国出生移民的住房拥有率为75.6%，高于美国本土出生者69.8%的比例。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nForeign-born Asians and <font color=\"#ffff00\">Hispanics</font> “have higher rates of intermarriage than do U.S.-born whites and blacks.”\n翻译: <u>外国出生的亚裔和西班牙裔“比美国出生的白人和黑人有更高的通婚率”。</u>\n\n-**Hispanics**：<u>西语裔/拉美裔。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nBy the third generation, one third of Hispanic women are married to non-Hispanics, and 41 percent of Asian-American women are married to non-Asians.\n翻译: <u>到第三代时，三分之一的西班牙裔女性嫁给了非西班牙裔，41%的亚裔美国女性嫁给了非亚裔。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRodriguez notes that children in remote villages around the world are fans of superstars like Arnold Schwarzenegger and Garth Brooks.\n翻译: <u>Rodriguez指出，世界各地偏远村庄的孩子都是Arnold Schwarzenegger和Garth Brooks等超级明星的粉丝。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYet “some Americans fear that immigrants living within the United States remain somehow immune to the nation’s assimilative power.”\n翻译: <u>然而，“一些美国人担心，生活在美国境内的移民不知何故仍能不受这个国家同化力量的影响”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAre there <font color=\"#ffff00\">divisive issues</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">pockets</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">seething anger</font> in America?\n翻译: <u>美国是否存在造成分裂的问题和一处处怒火暗涌的地方？</u>\n\n-**divisive issues**：<u>分裂性议题，会引发社会对立的问题。</u>  \n-**pockets of…**：<u>局部地区/小群体中的……。</u>  \n-**seething anger**：<u>强烈但压抑的愤怒、暗流涌动的怒气。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Indeed.</font>\n\n-<u>意思说明：确实如此。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is big enough to have <font color=\"#ffff00\">a bit of everything.</font>\n翻译: <u>它足够大，什么都有一点。</u>\n\n-**a bit of everything**：<u>什么都有一点。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut particularly when viewed against America’s turbulent past, today’s social indices hardly suggest a dark and deteriorating social environment.\n翻译: <u>但是，尤其是把今天的社会指标同美国动荡的过去相比时，它们几乎并不显示出一种黑暗且不断恶化的社会环境。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nStratford-on-Avon, as we all know, has only one <font color=\"#ffff00\">industry</font> — William Shakespeare — but there are two<font color=\"#ffff00\"> distinctly separate </font>and increasingly hostile branches.\n翻译: <u>众所周知，斯特拉特福德-埃文只有一个产业——William Shakespeare——但它有两个截然分离且日益敌对的分支。</u>\n\n-**industry**：<u>产业、行业。</u>  \n-**distinctly separate**：<u>明显分开的。</u>  \n\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is</font> the Royal Shakespeare Company, or RSC, which presents superb productions of the plays at the Shakespeare Memorial Theatre on the Avon.\n翻译: <u>一个是皇家莎士比亚剧团，即RSC，它在埃文河畔的莎士比亚纪念剧院上演精彩的戏剧作品。</u>\n\n-there is <u>一边是</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAnd there are the townsfolk who largely <font color=\"#ffff00\">live off</font> the tourists who come, not to see the plays, but to look at Anne Hathaway’s Cottage, Shakespeare’s birthplace and the other sights.\n翻译: <u>另一个则是镇民，他们很大程度上靠游客为生；这些游客来这里不是为了看戏，而是为了参观Anne Hathaway故居、莎士比亚出生地以及其他景点。</u>\n\n-**live off…**：<u>靠……生活、以……为生。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">worthy residents</font> of Stratford doubt that the theater <font color=\"#ffff00\">adds a penny to</font> their revenue.\n翻译: <u>斯特拉特福德那些体面的居民怀疑，剧院是否给他们的收入增加了一分钱。</u>\n\n-**worthy residents**：<u>可敬的居民、体面的居民。</u>  \n<u>这里可能带一点讽刺意味，指当地居民自认为正派、务实。</u> \n-**add a penny to…**：<u>给……增加一分钱。   **a penny** 用来强调“哪怕一点点”。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#ffff00\">frankly</font> dislike the RSC’s actors, <font color=\"#ffff00\">them with</font> their long hair and beards and sandals and noisiness.\n翻译: <u>他们坦率地不喜欢RSC的演员，那些人留着长发和胡子，穿着凉鞋，又吵吵闹闹。</u>\n\n-**frankly**：<u>坦率地、直白地。</u>  \n-**them with…** <u>是一种带贬义的补充表达，有点像中文“就他们那副……样子”。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s all <font color=\"#ffff00\">deliciously ironic</font> when you consider that Shakespeare, who <font color=\"#ffff00\">earns their living</font>, was himself an actor with a beard and <font color=\"#ffff00\">did his share of </font>noise-making.\n翻译: <u>当你想到养活他们的莎士比亚本人也是一名留胡子的演员，并且也曾制造过不少喧闹时，这一切就显得极其讽刺。</u>\n\n-**deliciously ironic**：<u>非常讽刺，而且讽刺得令人觉得妙。</u>  \n-**earn their living**：<u>养活他们、让他们有收入。</u>  \n-**do one’s share of…**：<u>也做了相当一份……、也没少……。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe tourist streams are not entirely separate.\n翻译: <u>游客流并非完全分开的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe sightseers who come by bus — and often <font color=\"#ffff00\">take in</font> Warwick Castle and Blenheim Palace <font color=\"#ffff00\">on the side</font> — don’t usually see the plays, and some of them are even surprised to find a theatre in Stratford.\n翻译: <u>那些乘公共汽车来的观光客——而且常常顺便游览Warwick Castle和Blenheim Palace——通常不看戏，其中一些人甚至惊讶地发现斯特拉特福德竟然有一座剧院。</u>\n\n-**take in**：<u>参观、游览。</u>  \n-**on the side**：<u>顺便、附带。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHowever, the playgoers <font color=\"#ffff00\">do manage</font> a little sight-seeing along with their playgoing.\n翻译: <u>然而，看戏的人在看戏之余也确实会设法做一点观光。</u>\n\n-**do manage**：<u>确实设法做到。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt is the playgoers, the RSC contends, who bring in much of the town’s revenue because they spend the night, some of them four or five nights, pouring cash into the hotels and restaurants.\n翻译: <u>RSC主张，正是这些看戏的人带来了镇上相当大一部分收入，因为他们会过夜，有些人住四五晚，把现金源源不断地花在旅馆和餐馆里。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe sightseers can take in everything and get out of town<font color=\"#ffff00\"> by nightfall</font>.\n翻译: <u>观光客可以把一切都看完，并在天黑前离开小镇。</u>\n\n-**nightfall**：<u>黄昏、夜幕降临。</u>  \n**by nightfall**：<u>到天黑前。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe townsfolk don’t see it this way and the local council does not <font color=\"#ffff00\">contribute directly to</font> the subsidy of the Royal Shakespeare Company.\n翻译: <u>镇民并不这样看，当地议会也不直接为皇家莎士比亚剧团的补贴出资。</u>\n\n-**contribute directly to…**：<u>直接向……出资。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nStratford cries poor <font color=\"#ffff00\">traditionally</font>.\n翻译: <u>斯特拉特福德向来喊穷。</u>\n\n-**traditionally**：<u>一向、历来。</u>\n\n---\n\nNevertheless every hotel in town seems to be adding a new wing or cocktail lounge.\n翻译: <u>然而，镇上的每家旅馆似乎都在增建新翼楼或鸡尾酒廊。</u>\n\n-Nevertheless <u>然而 尽管如此</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nHilton is building its own hotel there, which you may be sure will be decorated with Hamlet Hamburger Bars, the Lear Lounge, the Banquo Banqueting Room, <font color=\"#ffff00\">and so forth</font>, and will be very expensive.\n翻译: <u>Hilton正在那里建自己的酒店，你可以确信，它会装饰上Hamlet Hamburger Bars、Lear Lounge、Banquo Banqueting Room之类的东西，而且会非常昂贵。</u>\n\n-**and so forth**：<u>等等。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnyway, the townsfolk can’t understand why the Royal Shakespeare Company needs a subsidy.\n翻译: <u>不管怎样，镇民无法理解为什么皇家莎士比亚剧团需要补贴。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe theatre has broken <font color=\"#ffff00\">attendance records</font> for three years <font color=\"#ffff00\">in a row.</font>\n翻译: <u>这家剧院已经连续三年打破上座纪录。</u>\n\n-**attendance records**：<u>观众出席/上座纪录。</u>\n-**in a row**：<u>连续地。</u>  \n\n---\n\nLast year its 1,431 seats were 94 per cent occupied all year long and this year they’ll do better.\n翻译: <u>去年，它的1,431个座位全年上座率达到94%，而今年还会更好。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe reason, of course, is that <font color=\"#ffff00\">costs</font> have rocketed and ticket prices have stayed low.\n翻译: <u>原因当然是成本飞涨，而票价一直保持低廉。</u>\n\n-**costs have rocketed**：<u>成本急剧上升。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It would be a shame to</font> raise prices too much because it would drive away the young people who are Stratford’s most attractive <font color=\"#ffff00\">clientele.</font>\n翻译: <u>票价涨得太多会很可惜，因为那会赶走年轻人，而他们是斯特拉特福德最有吸引力的顾客群。</u>\n\n-**It would be a shame to…**：<u>做……会很可惜、很遗憾。</u> \n-**clientele**：<u>顾客群、客户群。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey come entirely for the plays, not the sights.\n翻译: <u>他们完全是为戏剧而来，不是为景点而来。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nThey all <font color=\"#ffff00\">seem to look alike</font>, though they <font color=\"#ffff00\">come from all over</font> — <font color=\"#ffff00\">lean</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">pointed</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">dedicated</font> faces, wearing jeans and sandals, eating their buns and <font color=\"#ffff00\">bedding down</font> for the night on the flagstones outside the theatre to buy the 20 seats and 80 standing-room tickets <font color=\"#ffff00\">held for</font> the sleepers and sold to them when the box office opens at 10:30 a.m.\n翻译: <u>他们虽然来自各地，却似乎都长得很像——瘦削、尖脸、神情专注，穿着牛仔裤和凉鞋，吃着小圆面包，在剧院外的石板地上过夜，为的是购买留给露宿者的20个座位票和80张站票；这些票会在上午10:30售票处开门时卖给他们。</u>\n\n-**seem to look alike**：<u>似乎长得/看起来一样。</u>  \n-**come from all over**：<u>来自四面八方、各地。</u>  \n-**lean**：<u>瘦削的。</u>\n-**pointed**：<u>尖瘦的、轮廓分明的。</u>  \n-**dedicated**：<u>专注的、投入的。</u>  \n-**bed down**：<u>临时睡下、铺地睡觉。</u>  \n-**held for…**：<u>为……保留。</u>  \n\n-<u>他们虽然来自各地，却似乎看起来都一样——瘦削、尖瘦、专注的脸，穿着牛仔裤和凉鞋，吃着圆面包，在剧院外石板地上过夜，为了购买那 20 个座位票和 80 张站票；这些票是为过夜者保留的，并在售票处上午 10:30 开门时卖给他们。</u>\n-\n---\n\n21. From the text we can conclude that the author  C\n\n[A] is supportive of both sides.\n\n[B] favors the townsfolk’s view.\n\n[C] takes a <font color=\"#ffff00\">detached</font> attitude.\n\n[D] is sympathetic to the RSC.\n\n\n-detached <u>客观的 超然的</u>\n\n\n第三篇阅读\n\nWhen prehistoric man arrived in new parts of the world, something strange happened to the large animals: they suddenly became extinct.\n翻译: <u>当史前人类来到世界的新地区时，大型动物身上发生了奇怪的事情：它们突然灭绝了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSmaller species survived.\n翻译: <u>较小的物种存活了下来。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe large, slow-growing animals were <font color=\"#ffff00\">easy game</font>, and were quickly <font color=\"#ffff00\">hunted to extinction</font>.\n翻译: <u>那些体型庞大、生长缓慢的动物很容易成为猎物，并很快被猎杀至灭绝。</u>\n\n-**game** <u>在这里不是“游戏”，而是“猎物”。</u>  \n**easy game**：<u>容易捕到的猎物。</u> \n-**hunt to extinction**：<u>把……猎杀到灭绝。</u>  \n\n---\n\nNow something similar could be happening in the oceans.\n翻译: <u>现在，海洋中可能正在发生类似的事情。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nThat the seas are being overfished has been known for years.\n翻译: <u>多年来，人们一直知道海洋正在被过度捕捞。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhat researchers such as Ransom Myers and Boris Worm have shown is <font color=\"#ffff00\">just how fast</font> things are changing.\n翻译: <u>Ransom Myers和Boris Worm等研究人员所展示的，是事情变化得究竟有多快。</u>\n\n-**just how fast…**：<u>究竟多快。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThey have <font color=\"#ffff00\">looked at</font> half a century of data from fisheries around the world.\n翻译: <u>他们研究了世界各地渔业半个世纪的数据。</u>\n\n-**look at**：<u>研究、查看、分析。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nTheir methods do not attempt to estimate the <font color=\"#ffff00\">actual biomass</font>, the amount of <font color=\"#ffff00\">living biological matter,</font> of fish species in <font color=\"#ffff00\">particular parts of the ocean</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> but rather </font>changes in that biomass <font color=\"#ffff00\">over time</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们的方法并不试图估算海洋特定区域中鱼类物种的实际生物量，即活的生物物质的数量，而是估算这种生物量随时间的变化。</u>\n\n-**actual biomass**：<u>实际生物量。</u>  \n-**living biological matter**：<u>活体生物物质。</u>  \n-**particular parts of the ocean**：<u>海洋中的特定区域。</u>  \n-**but rather**：<u>而是。</u>  \n-**over time**：<u>随着时间。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nAccording to their latest paper published in Nature, the biomass of large predators, animals that kill and eat other animals, in a new fishery <font color=\"#ffff00\">is reduced on </font>average by 80% within 15 years of the start of <font color=\"#ffff00\">exploitation.</font>\n翻译: <u>根据他们发表在Nature上的最新论文，在一个新渔场中，大型捕食者，即捕杀并食用其他动物的动物，其生物量在开始开发后的15年内平均减少80%。</u>\n\n-**is reduced**：<u>被减少、下降。</u>  \n-**exploitation** <u>在这里指商业捕捞开发，不是单纯“剥削”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn some long-fished areas, it has halved again <font color=\"#ffff00\">since then</font>.\n翻译: <u>在一些长期捕捞的地区，此后它又减少了一半。</u>\n\n-since then <u>从那以后</u>\n\n---\n\nDr. Worm <font color=\"#ffff00\">acknowledges</font> that these figures are conservative.\n翻译: <u>Worm博士承认，这些数字是保守的。</u>\n\n-**acknowledge**：<u>承认、认可。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOne reason for this is that fishing technology has improved.\n翻译: <u>其中一个原因是捕捞技术已经改进。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nToday’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">vessels</font> can find their prey using satellites and <font color=\"#ffff00\">sonar,</font> which were not available 50 years ago.\n翻译: <u>如今的船只可以利用卫星和声呐寻找猎物，而这些技术在50年前并不存在。</u>\n\n-**Today’s vessels**：<u>今天的船只，指现代渔船。</u>  \n-**sonar**：<u>声呐。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThat means a higher proportion of what is in the sea is being caught, so the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> real difference between present and past</font> is likely to be worse than the one recorded by changes in catch sizes.\n翻译: <u>这意味着海洋中更高比例的生物正在被捕获，因此现在与过去之间的真实差异很可能比捕获量变化所记录的差异更糟。</u>\n\n-**real difference between present and past**：<u>现在和过去之间的真实差异。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn the early days, <font color=\"#ffff00\">too</font>, longlines would have been more saturated with fish.\n翻译: <u>在早期，延绳钓钓线上也会更密集地挂满鱼。</u>\n\n-**too**：<u>也、另外。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Some individuals</font> would therefore not have been caught,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> since</font> no <font color=\"#ffff00\">baited hooks </font>would have been available to trap them, leading to an underestimate of <font color=\"#ffff00\">fish stocks</font> in the past.\n翻译: <u>因此，一些个体本不会被捕获，因为没有带饵的鱼钩可用来困住它们，这导致过去鱼类种群数量被低估。</u>\n\n-**Some individuals**：<u>某些个体，指某些鱼。</u>  \n-**since**：<u>因为。</u>  \n-**baited hooks**：<u>带饵的鱼钩。</u>  \n-**fish stocks**：<u>鱼类资源量、鱼群储量。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Furthermore</font>, in the early days of longline fishing, a lot of fish were lost to sharks after they had been hooked.\n翻译: <u>此外，在延绳钓捕捞的早期，许多鱼在上钩后被鲨鱼夺走。</u>\n\n-Furthermore  <u>此外</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThat is no longer a problem, because there are fewer sharks around now.\n翻译: <u>这不再是一个问题，因为现在周围的鲨鱼少了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDr. Myers and Dr. Worm argue that their work gives a correct baseline, which future management efforts must <font color=\"#ffff00\">take into account</font>.\n翻译: <u>Myers博士和Worm博士认为，他们的工作提供了一个正确的基准线，未来的管理努力必须将其纳入考虑。</u>\n\n-**take into account**：<u>考虑到、纳入考量。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nThey believe the data support an idea <font color=\"#ffff00\">current</font> among <font color=\"#ffff00\">marine biologists,</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> that of </font>the “<font color=\"#ffff00\">shifting baseline</font>”.\n翻译: <u>他们认为，这些数据支持了海洋生物学家中当前流行的一种观点，即“基准线转移”。</u>\n\n-**current**：<u>流行的、通行的、当前存在的。</u>  \n-**among marine biologists**：<u>在海洋生物学家之间。</u>  \n-**that of…**：<u>即……的那个。</u>  \n-**shifting baseline**：<u>漂移的基线。</u>  \n-<u>他们认为这些数据证明了海洋生物学界常说的“基线漂移”：人们对“正常海洋状态”的参照点会随着时间不断下降。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The notion</font> is that people have failed to detect the massive changes which have happened in the ocean because they have been looking back only a relatively short time into the past.\n翻译: <u>这一观点认为，人们未能察觉海洋中已经发生的巨大变化，是因为他们回顾过去的时间相对较短。</u>\n\n-**notion**：<u>观念、想法。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">That matters </font>because theory suggests that the <font color=\"#ffff00\">maximum sustainable yield </font>that can <font color=\"#ffff00\">be cropped</font> from a fishery <font color=\"#ffff00\">comes when</font> the biomass of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">target species</font> is about 50% of its original levels.\n翻译: <u>这一点很重要，因为理论表明，当目标物种的生物量约为其原始水平的50%时，能够从一个渔场获得的最大可持续产量就会出现。</u>\n\n-**maximum sustainable yield**：<u>最大可持续产量，指在不破坏长期资源的前提下可持续捕捞的最大数量。</u> \n-**crop** <u>在这里不是“农作物”，而是动词，表示“收获、捕捞”。</u>  \n-come when… <u>表示“出现在……时候”。</u>\n-**target species**：<u>目标物种，指被捕捞的鱼类。</u>  \n\n-<u>这一点很重要，因为理论表明，一个渔场能够收获的最大可持续产量，出现在目标物种的生物量约为其原始水平 50% 的时候。</u>  \n\n---\n\nMost fisheries are <font color=\"#ffff00\">well below</font> that, which is a bad way to do business.\n翻译: <u>大多数渔场都远低于这一水平，这是一种糟糕的经营方式。</u>\n\n-**well below**：<u>远低于。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2007","year":"2007","title":"2007 年英语一","fileName":"2007年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2007年英语 1.md","content":"第一篇阅读 句 13 题\n\nIf you were to examine，/ the <font color=\"#ffff00\">birth certificates of every soccer</font> player/ in 2006’s World Cup tournament/ you would most likely find/ a noteworthy <font color=\"#ffff00\">quirk</font>:/ elite soccer players/ are more likely to have been born in the earlier months/ of the year/ than in the later months.\n翻译: <u>如果你查看2006年世界杯锦标赛中每一位足球运动员的出生证明，你很可能会发现一个值得注意的怪现象：精英足球运动员更有可能出生在一年中较早的月份，而不是较晚的月份。</u>\n\n( -quirk <u>奇事,但是不懂也不影响,前面的形容词认识就行</u>\n\n-of <u>不要连着读进去,当做一个符号,链接后面的形容词和前面被修饰的</u>\n\n-in <u>作为介词,还有其它任意的介词同理,当做符号连接</u>\n\n-were to <u>虚拟语气,意思是对未来不太可能发生的事情进行假设,核心是:假设未来发生了一件可能性微乎其微、甚至根本不可能的事，那将会导致什么样的结果。固定搭配:</u>\n**<u>条件句（从句）：** `If + 主语 + were to + 动词原形`</u> \n**<u>结果句（主句）：** `主语 + would / could / might / should + 动词原形`</u>\n-`If` + `the sun` (<u>主语) + `were to` + `rise` (动词原形) in the west...</u>\n-<u>其它两种虚拟语气的情况</u>\n-should + <u>动词原形</u> \n\nhad + <u>过去分词</u> \nIf the company **had adapted** to the internet age, it **would not have gone** bankrupt.  <u>表示“与过去事实相反”，侧重遗憾或反思</u> \nhad<u>表示事情已经发生了,然后用一个虚拟语态</u>\n<u>如果只有 if 的话,不确定事情是否已经发生了</u>\n\"If he **took** the poison, he is dead now.\"(<u>不确定吃了没有)</u>\nIf he **had taken** the poison, he would be dead now. (<u>没有吃)</u>\n\n)\n\n---\n\nIf you then examined the European national youth teams that feed the World Cup and professional ranks, you would find this strange phenomenon to be even more pronounced.\n翻译: <u>如果你接着查看为世界杯和职业队伍输送人才的欧洲国家青年队，你会发现这种奇怪现象更加明显。</u>\n\n-feed <u>输送</u>\n\n-pronounced <u>明显的</u>\n\n\n---\n\nWhat might <font color=\"#ffff00\">account fo</font>r this strange phenomenon?\n翻译: <u>什么可以解释这种奇怪现象呢？</u>\n\n-account for <u>导致</u>\n\n---\n\nHere are a few guesses: a) certain <font color=\"#ffff00\">astrological</font> signs confer superior soccer skills; b) winter-born babies tend to have higher oxygen capacity, which increases soccer <font color=\"#ffff00\">stamina</font>; c) soccer-mad parents are more likely to <font color=\"#ffff00\">conceive</font> children in springtime, at the annual peak of soccer <font color=\"#ffff00\">mania</font>; d) none of the above.\n翻译: <u>这里有几种猜测：a）某些星座赋予人更出色的足球技能；b）冬季出生的婴儿往往具有更高的氧气容量，从而增强足球耐力；c）痴迷足球的父母更可能在春季怀上孩子，那是一年中足球狂热的高峰期；d）以上都不是。</u>\n\n( -astrological <u>星座的 来源于**astrology**（占星术、星象学）</u>\n\n-stamina <u>耐力</u>\n\n-conceive <u>怀孕</u>\n\n-mania <u>狂热</u>\n\n)\n\n---\n\nAnders Ericsson, <font color=\"#ffff00\">a 58-year-old psychology professor</font> at Florida State University<font color=\"#ffff00\">, says he believes strongly in “none of the above.”</font>\n翻译: <u>佛罗里达州立大学58岁的心理学教授Anders Ericsson说，他坚定地相信“以上都不是”。</u>\n\n-says <u>后面省略了 that 是一个宾语从句</u>\n\n-a 58-year-old psychology professor <u>同位语,补充说明</u>\n\n---\n\nEricsson grew up in Sweden, and studied nuclear engineering until he realized he would have more opportunity to <font color=\"#ffff00\">conduct</font> his own research if he switched to psychology.\n翻译: <u>Ericsson在瑞典长大，学习过核工程，直到他意识到如果转向心理学，自己将有更多机会开展自己的研究。</u>\n\n-conduct <u>进行</u>\n\n\n---\n\nHis first experiment, nearly 30 years ago, involved memory: training a person to hear and then repeat a random series of numbers.\n翻译: <u>他近30年前的第一个实验涉及记忆：训练一个人听取并随后重复一串随机数字。</u>\n\n-nearly 30 years ago <u>作为插入语 和同位语一样,删掉对句子意思都不影响,</u>\n<u>同位语是“画等号”，插入语是“加旁白”。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\n“With the first subject, after about 20 hours of training, his digit span had risen from 7 to 20,” Ericsson recalls.\n翻译: <u>“对于第一个受试者，经过大约20小时的训练后，他的数字记忆广度从7位提高到了20位，”Ericsson回忆道。</u>\n\n-with, after <u>都是介词短语 引导从句,要分清楚主句</u>\n-subject <u>受试者  还有学科 主题 的意思</u>\n\n---\n\n“He kept improving, and after about 200 hours of training he had risen to over 80 numbers.”\n翻译: <u>“他不断进步，经过大约200小时的训练后，他已经提高到能记住80多个数字。”</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nThis success, coupled with later research showing that memory itself is not genetically determined, led Ericsson to conclude that the act of memorizing is more of a cognitive exercise than an intuitive one.\n翻译: <u>这次成功，加上后来表明记忆本身并非由基因决定的研究，使Ericsson得出结论：记忆这一行为更多是一种认知练习，而不是一种直觉行为。</u>\n\n( -coupled with <u>过去分词做状语 修饰success</u>\n-<u>这里的showing 充当定语 修饰的是 later research</u>\n-<u>定语修饰的是“名词”（相当于形容词），状语修饰的是“动词或整个句子”（相当于副词）。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn other words, whatever inborn differences two people may exhibit in their abilities to memorize, those differences are swamped by how well each person “encodes” the information.\n翻译: <u>换言之，无论两个人在记忆能力上可能表现出怎样的先天差异，这些差异都会被每个人“编码”信息的能力所淹没。</u>\n\n( -swamp <u>淹没 沼泽)</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd the best way to learn how to encode information meaningfully, Ericsson determined, was a process known as deliberate practice.\n翻译: <u>Ericsson断定，学习如何有意义地编码信息的最佳方式，是一个被称为刻意练习的过程。</u>\n\n( he best way to <u>在这个句子里，`to` 只是个没有实际意思的**不定式符号**，它带着后面的动词原形 `learn` 组成了一个**不定式短语**，完美地充当了修饰 `way` 的**后置定语**。</u>\n\n---\n\nDeliberate practice entails more than simply repeating a task.\n翻译: <u>刻意练习所包含的内容不只是简单地重复一项任务。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nRather, it involves setting specific goals, obtaining immediate feedback and concentrating as much on technique as on outcome.\n翻译: <u>相反，它包括设定具体目标、获得即时反馈，并且像关注结果一样关注技巧。</u>\n\n( rather <u>带有隐藏的 “Not A, but B” 逻辑</u>\n<u>通常意味着前一句说了一个否定的意思,这一步说了一个肯定的意思</u>\n<u>这里翻译为更进一步说</u>\n<u>有时候也翻译为相反</u>\n\n---\n\nEricsson and his colleagues have <font color=\"#ffff00\">thus</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">taken to</font> studying expert performers in a wide range of <font color=\"#ffff00\">pursuits</font>, including soccer.\n翻译: <u>因此，Ericsson 和他的同事们开始研究广泛领域中的专家级表现者，其中包括足球领域。</u>\n\n( -take to <u>开始从事</u>\n-thus <u>因此 于是 (副词) 相当于 therefore或者 as a result</u>\n-pursuit <u>事业 爱好</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThey gather <font color=\"#ffff00\">all the data they can</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">not just performance statistics and biographical details but also the results</font> of their own laboratory experiments <font color=\"#ffff00\">with high achievers</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们收集一切能收集的数据，不只是表现统计和传记细节，还包括他们自己对高成就者进行实验室实验所得的结果。</u>\n\n( -all the data they can <u>实际上省略了 that they can gather</u>\n-not just performance statistics and biographical details but also the results <u>作为同位语</u>  \n\n<u>同位语的作用是把前面那个抽象的、宽泛的名词  “具体化”</u>\n<u>他们词性一致,语法地位平等,经常会跟着一些解释性的搭配出现</u>\n<u>比如not just... but also../namely/such as/including</u>\n\n-with high achievers <u>作为后置定语 修饰 experiments</u>\n)\n\n---\n\nTheir work makes a rather startling assertion: the trait we commonly call talent is highly overrated.\n翻译: <u>他们的研究提出了一个颇为惊人的论断：我们通常称为天赋的特质被大大高估了。</u>\n\n( -startling <u>惊人的</u>\n-\n\n\n---\n\nOr, put another way, expert performers – whether in memory or surgery, ballet or computer programming – are nearly always made, not born.\n翻译: <u>或者换句话说，专家级表现者——无论是在记忆、外科手术、芭蕾还是计算机编程方面——几乎总是后天造就的，而不是天生的。</u>\n\n( <u>这里的put another way,  whether in memory or surgery,  都是插入语</u>\n\n\n---\n\n21. The birthday phenomenon found among soccer players is mentioned to\n    \n    [A] stress the importance of professional training.\n    \n    [B] spotlight the soccer superstars in the World Cup.\n    \n    [C] introduce the topic of what makes expert performance.\n    \n    [D] explain why some soccer teams play better than others.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n22. The word “mania” (Line 4, Paragraph 2) most probably means\n    \n    [A] fun.\n    \n    [B] craze.\n    \n    [C] hysteria.\n    \n    [D] excitement.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n23. According to Ericsson, good memory\n    \n    [A] depends on meaningful processing of information.\n    \n    [B] results from intuitive rather than cognitive exercises.\n    \n    [C] is determined by genetic rather than psychological factors.\n    \n    [D] requires immediate feedback and a high degree of concentration.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n24. Ericsson and his colleagues believe that\n    \n    [A] talent is a dominating factor for professional success.\n    \n    [B] biographical data provide the key to excellent performance.\n    \n    [C] the role of talent tends to be overlooked.\n    \n    [D] high achievers owe their success mostly to nurture.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n25. Which of the following proverbs is closest to the message the text tries to convey?\n    \n    [A] “Faith will move mountains.”\n    \n    [B] “One reaps what one sows.”\n    \n    [C] “Practice makes perfect.”\n    \n    [D] “Like father, like son.”\n    \n    ( )\n\n第四篇\n\nIt never rains but it pours.\n翻译: <u>祸不单行。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Just</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> bosses and boards have finally <font color=\"#ffff00\">sorted out</font> their worst accounting and <font color=\"#ffff00\">compliance</font> troubles, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">improved</font> their feeble corporation governance, a new problem threatens to <font color=\"#ffff00\">earn</font> them – especially in America – the sort of nasty headlines that inevitably lead to heads rolling in the executive suite: data insecurity.\n翻译: <u>正当老板们和董事会终于理清了他们最糟糕的会计和合规问题，并改善了薄弱的公司治理时，一个新问题又威胁着要让他们——尤其是在美国——登上那种令人难堪的头条，而这种头条不可避免地会导致高管层有人被迫下台：数据不安全。</u>\n\n( -just <u>表示节点十分临近,时间节点\\</u>\n-as <u>这里等同于 when while</u>\n-sorted out <u>理清</u>\n-improved <u>翻译为改善比较通顺</u>\n-<u>双宾语 `earn somebody something`  “给……带来”、“使……招致（通常是不好的结果）”</u>\n-<u>这句话中两个一级从句,一个 as 引导,一个 that 引导</u>\n \n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Left</font>, until now, to odd, low-level IT staff to <font color=\"#ffff00\">put right</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">and</font> seen as a concern only of data-rich industries such as banking, telecoms and air travel, information protection is now high on the boss’ s agenda in businesses of every variety.\n翻译: <u>直到现在，信息保护一直被留给一些零散的低级 IT 员工去纠正，并被视为只是银行、电信和航空旅行等数据密集型行业才关心的问题；如今，它已成为各类企业老板议程上的重要事项。</u>\n\n\n\n-Left <u>过去分词放在句首做状语,表达一种被动完成的状态,信息是被留给 low level 的 it staff,实际上是省略了其它成分,但是这个状语必然有是有一个主语的,主语是后面的information protection,实际上完整的话是_Because information protection was left_</u>\n-odd <u>平时有 奇数,古怪的意思,在这里是零工 odd jobs</u>\n-put right  <u>修正的意思 相当于 fix</u>\n-and <u>作为一个并列,这里说明了 left 和 seen 是并列的,有一个共同的主语</u>\n\n---\n\nSeveral massive leakages of customer and employee data this year – <font color=\"#ffff00\">f</font><font color=\"#ffff00\">rom organizations as diverse as Time Warner, the American defense contractor Science Applications International Corp and even the University of California, Berkeley</font> – have left managers hurriedly peering into their intricate IT systems and business processes in search of potential vulnerabilities.\n翻译: <u>今年发生的几起大规模客户和员工数据泄露事件——涉及的组织各不相同，从 Time Warner、美国国防承包商 Science Applications International Corp，甚至到 University of California, Berkeley——已经使管理者们匆忙审视其复杂的 IT 系统和业务流程，以寻找潜在漏洞。</u>\n\n-from <u>后面的一大块都是插入语,因为有个-</u>\n-peer into <u>深挖、严审、细查  偷窥是 peep</u>\n`-peer through`（<u>透过……费力地看）。</u>\npeer <u>的本意就是因为看不清楚而费力地看</u>\n\n---\n\n“Data is becoming an asset which needs to be guarded as much as any other asset,” <font color=\"#ffff00\">says Haim Mendelson</font> of Stanford University’ s business school.\n翻译: <u>“数据正在成为一种资产，需要像任何其他资产一样受到保护，”Stanford University 商学院的 Haim Mendelson 说。</u>\n\n-<u>倒装句,实际上是 Mendelson said that</u>\n\n---\n\n“The ability to guard customer data is the key to market value, <font color=\"#ffff00\">which the board is responsible for on behalf of shareholders”.</font>\n翻译: <u>“保护客户数据的能力是市场价值的关键，而董事会代表股东对此负有责任。”</u>\n\n-<u>还原语序是  the board is responsible for which,显然知道 which 指代的是market value,而不是一整个句子</u>\n-<u>状语最核心的工作，就是交代一个动作发生的“时间、地点、原因、方式或条件”。这里的 on behalf of shareholders作为一个状语,它是说明一个动作的,并且它在从句里,说明它修饰的是is responsible for这个动作,也就是说:董事会需要负责,那么对谁负责,也就是说对股东负责</u>\n\n---\n\nIndeed, <font color=\"#ffff00\">just</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> there is the concept of Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP), perhaps it is time for GASP, Generally Accepted Security Practices,suggested Eli Noam of New York’ s Columbia Business School.\n翻译: <u>事实上，正如存在“公认会计原则”（GAAP）这一概念一样，也许现在是提出 GASP，即“公认安全实践”的时候了，New York 的 Columbia Business School 的 Eli Noam 建议道。</u>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n-just <u>就</u>\n-as  “<u>正如……”**或**“像……那样”。 方式状语从句</u>\nas <u>作为一个引导词,有三个意思,完全看代入哪个意思通顺,就翻译成哪个意思</u>\n1 <u>当 xx 的时候</u>\n2 <u>因为</u>\n3 <u>正如 xx 一样</u>\n\n---\n\n“Setting the proper investment level for security, <font color=\"#ffff00\">redundancy</font>, and recovery is a management issue, not a technical one,” he says.\n翻译: <u>他说：“为安全、冗余和恢复设定适当的投资水平，是一个管理问题，而不是技术问题。”</u>\n\n-redundancy <u>多余 重复</u>\n-level <u>标准</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The mystery is that</font> this <font color=\"#ffff00\">should</font> come as a surprise to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> any</font> boss.\n翻译: <u>令人费解的是，这件事竟会让任何老板感到意外。</u>\n\n\n\n\n\n-The mystery is that <u>令人难以理解的是</u>\n-`should` <u>在这里的特殊情感：惊讶与费解</u>\n-any <u>所有的</u>\n\n---\n\nSurely it should be obvious to the <font color=\"#ffff00\">dimmest</font> executive that<font color=\"#ffff00\"> trust, that most valuable of economic assets</font>, is easily destroyed and hugely expensive to restore – and that <font color=\"#ffff00\">few things are more likely to</font> destroy trust than a company letting sensitive personal data get into the wrong hand\n翻译: <u>当然，即便是最迟钝的高管也应当明白，信任这一最有价值的经济资产很容易被摧毁，而恢复起来代价极其高昂；而且，没有什么比一家公司让敏感的个人数据落入不当之手更可能摧毁信任了。</u>\n\n\n\n\n\n-dimmest dim <u>的最高级 dim 迟钝,暗淡</u>\n-trust <u>后面跟了个逗号,同位语</u>\n-few things are more likely to <u>表示否定,没有什么比这个更破坏信任了,用比较级的形式来表达最高级的含义。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe current state of affairs may have been encouraged – though not justified – by the lack of legal penalty (in America, but not Europe) for data leakage.\n翻译: <u>目前的状况也许受到了数据泄露缺乏法律处罚这一事实的助长——尽管这不能成为正当理由——这种情况存在于美国，而不是欧洲。</u>\n\n-state of affairs <u>看做一个整体,翻译成事态,比 situation 复杂的那种</u>\n\n---\n\nUntil California recently passed a law, American firms did not have to tell anyone, even the victim, when data went astray.\n翻译: <u>在 California 最近通过一项法律之前，美国公司在数据出错时不必告知任何人，甚至不必告知受害者。</u>\n\n-`Until A, B happened` <u>这种结构，是用 A（法律通过）这个**终点**，来界定 B（不通知受害者）这个**持续状态**。固定的用法.直到最近颁布了这个法案,才结束了后面的那个状态,所以翻译的时候多加了一句,在此之前.</u>\n\n---\n\nThat may change fast: lots of proposed data-security legislation is now <font color=\"#ffff00\">doing the rounds</font> in Washington, D.C.\n翻译: <u>这种情况可能很快改变：大量拟议中的数据安全立法现在正在 Washington, D.C. 流传讨论。</u>\n\n-doing the rounds <u>逐个访问,文中引申为接收审议</u>\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">theft</font> of information about some 40 million credit-card accounts in America, disclosed on June 17th, <font color=\"#ffff00\">overshadowed</font> a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> hugely important decision a day earlier by America’ s Federal Trade Commission (FTC)</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">puts corporate America on notice that</font> regulators will act if firms fail to provide adequate data security.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，6月17日披露的美国约 4000 万个信用卡账户信息被盗事件，使美国联邦贸易委员会（FTC）前一天作出的一项极其重要的决定黯然失色；该决定向美国企业界发出警告：如果公司未能提供足够的数据安全保障，监管机构将采取行动。</u>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n-overshadow <u>使黯然失色</u>\n-<u>阅读逻辑</u>\n<u>使important decision黯然失色,然后一个同位语跟着,什么样的decision,是一天之前 由FTC发起的decision 那么顺过来就是 使一天前,ftc 发起的决定 黯然失色,意思就是显得很呆很蠢了</u>\n-<u>注意别丢了,put xx on notice xx</u>\n-Corporate America<u>是一个集合名词,表示美国的企业</u> \n\n\n---\n\n21. The statement “It never rains but it pours” is used to introduce\n    \n    [A] the fierce business competition.\n    \n    [B] the feeble boss-board relations.\n    \n    [C] the threat from news reports.\n    \n    [D] the severity of data leakage.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n22. According to Paragraph 2, some organizations check their systems to find out\n    \n    [A] whether there is any weak point.\n    \n    [B] what sort of data has been stolen.\n    \n    [C] who is responsible for the leakage.\n    \n    [D] how the potential spies can be located.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n23. In bringing up the concept of GASP the author is making the point that\n    \n    [A] shareholders’ interests should be properly attended to.\n    \n    [B] information protection should be given due attention.\n    \n    [C] businesses should enhance their level of accounting security.\n    \n    [D] the market value of customer data should be emphasized.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n24. According to Paragraph 4, what puzzles the author is that some bosses fail to\n    \n    [A] see the link between trust and data protection.\n    \n    [B] perceive the sensitivity of personal data.\n    \n    [C] realize the high cost of data restoration.\n    \n    [D] appreciate the economic value of trust.\n    \n    ( )\n    \n\n---\n\n25. It can be inferred from Paragraph 5 that\n    \n    [A] data leakage is more severe in Europe.\n    \n    [B] FTC’s decision is essential to data security.\n    \n    [C] California takes the lead in security legislation.\n    \n    [D] legal penalty is a major solution to data leakage.\n    \n    ( )\n\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">完形填空</font> \n\nBy 1830 the former Spanish and Portuguese colonies had become independent nations.\n翻译: <u>到 1830 年，原先的西班牙和葡萄牙殖民地已经成为独立国家。</u>\n\n( former <u>昔日的</u>\n)\n\n---\n\nThe roughly 20 million (inhabitants) of these nations looked (hopefully) to the future.\n翻译: <u>这些国家大约 2000 万居民满怀希望地展望未来。</u>\n\n( )\n\n1. A. natives B. inhabitants C. peoples D. individuals\nnative <u>强调本地的,一直都生存在哪个地方的有点原住民的感觉</u>\ninhabitants <u>哪个地方的居民都算</u>\npeoples <u>加上复数指的是民族</u>\nindividuals<u>个人</u>\n    \n2. A. confusedly B. cheerfully C. worriedly D. hopefully\n-look to <u>是作为一个整体 表示展望的意思 作为一个抽象动作</u>\n-cheerfully <u>表示的虽然也是积极的情感色彩,但是通常用于修饰,笑,说,这种具体的行为</u>\n\n---\n\nBorn in the crisis of the old regime and <font color=\"#ffff00\">Iberian</font> colonialism, many of the leaders of independence (shared) the ideals of r<font color=\"#ffff00\">epresentative government</font>, careers (open) to talent, freedom of commerce and trade, the (right) to private property, and a belief in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">individual as the basis of society</font>.\n翻译: <u>许多独立运动的领导人诞生于旧制度和伊比利亚殖民主义的危机之中，他们共同秉持代议制政府、向有才能者开放职业机会、商业和贸易自由、私有财产权，以及把个人视为社会基础的信念等理想。</u>\n\n-Iberian <u>利比里亚</u>\n-representative government <u>代议制政府</u> \n-<u>一排名词,逗号并列,同位语,补充说明 the ideals of representative goverment</u>\n-careers open to talent   to+talent <u>两个合起来相当于一个形容词,修饰open这个形容词,这里的 to 相当于一个介词,表示对象，“对……而言 / 向……”不是去的意思.并且这里的 open 是个形容词</u>\n-individual as the basis of society <u>个人是社会的基石</u>\n\n\n\n3. A. shared B. forgot C. attained D. rejected\n-share <u>表示有同样的感情和想法</u>\n\n4. A. related B. close C. open D. devoted\n<u>只有 open 才能服务于原文,虽然related填进去,也是通顺的,但是,open 相比于它更能服务于文章的表达的意思,这个是完形填空判断的重要基准</u>\n5. A. access B. succession C. right D. return\n-access <u>使用权 接近,</u>\n-succession <u>继承</u>\n-right <u>权利 正当的要求</u>\n\n---\n\n(Generally) there was a belief that the new nations should be <u>sovereign</u> and independent states, large enough to be economically <u>viable</u> and integrated by a (common) set of laws.\n\n-sovereign <u>有主权的</u>\n-viable <u>切实可行的 能独立发展的</u>\n-integrated <u>使成为一体</u>\n\n6. A. Presumably B. Incidentally C. Obviously D. Generally\n-Presumably <u>大概 据推测</u>\n-Incidentally <u>顺便提一句</u>\n-Generally <u>总体上来说</u>\n\n7. A. unique B. common C. particular D. typical\n-<u>这题的关键是哪个词能和前面的 intergrated 对上,整合成一个整体必然需要共识,这也是一个服务原文意思的题</u>\n---\n\nOn the issue of (freedom) of religion and the position of the Church, (however), there was less agreement (among) the leadership.\n翻译: <u>然而，在宗教自由和教会地位问题上，领导层内部的共识较少。</u>\n\n( )\n\n8. A. freedom B. origin C. impact D. reform<u>改革</u>\n\n9. A. therefore B. however<u>转折关系 C. indeed D. moreover</u>\n-therefore <u>因果关系</u>\n-indeed <u>强调或者递进关系</u>\n-moreover <u>同样递进关系</u>\n10. A. with B. about C. among D. by\n\n---\n\nRoman Catholicism had been the state religion and the only one (<font color=\"#ffff00\">allowed</font>) by the Spanish crown.\n翻译: <u>罗马天主教曾是国教，也是西班牙王室唯一允许的宗教。</u>\n\n( )\n\n11. A. allowed B. <font color=\"#ffff00\">preached</font> C. <font color=\"#ffff00\">granted</font> D. funded\n-allowed <u>认可的</u>\n-preached <u>宣扬 布道</u>\n-granted <u>允许 承认 表示承认观点属实,但是可能并不认可,带有勉强意味</u>\n\n---\n\n(While) most leaders sought to maintain Catholicism (as) the official religion of the new states, some sought to end the (exclusion) of other faiths.\n\n( )\n\n12. A. Since B. If C. Unless D. While\n-Since <u>既然,自 xx 以来</u>\n-Unless <u>除非 如果不</u> \n13. A. as B. for C. under D. against\n-for <u>为了</u>\n-under <u>由 xx 控制</u>\n14. A. spread B. interference C. exclusion D. influence\n<u>这题需要体现一种对比关系,while 的转折对比关系,所以句子前后需要表达的意思是对比的</u>\n-spread <u>即使放进去是通顺的 但是没有体现对比关系,放进去和分句是一个意思</u>\n-interference <u>也一样,放进去和分句意思一样</u>\n\n---\n\nThe defense of the Church became a rallying (cry) for the conservative forces.\n翻译: <u>捍卫教会成为保守势力的集结口号。</u>\n-**`rallying` <u>是“聚集、集结、号召”的意思**，而 **`rallying cry` 是一个非常经典的固定搭配，意思是“战斗口号”、“集结号”或“精神旗帜”。**</u>\n-\n( )\n\n15. A. support B. cry C. plea D. wish\n-plea <u>恳求</u>\n---\n\nThe ideals of the early leaders of independence were often egalitarian, valuing equality of everything.\n翻译: <u>早期独立运动领导人的理想常常是平等主义的，重视一切方面的平等。</u>\n-egalitarian <u>主张人人平等</u>\n-valuing <u>本身有重视的意思 这里引申为崇尚</u>\n( )\n\n---\n\nBolivar had received aid from Haiti and had (promised) in return to abolish slavery in the areas he liberated.\n翻译: <u>Bolivar 曾得到 Haiti 的援助，并作为回报承诺在他解放的地区废除奴隶制。</u>\n\n( )\n\n16. A. urged B. intended C. expected D. promised\n-intended<u>一般后面有跟 to do sth</u>\n---\n\nBy 1854 slavery had been abolished everywhere except Spain’s (remaining) colonies.\n翻译: <u>到 1854 年，除 Spain 剩余的殖民地外，奴隶制在各地都已被废除。</u>\n\n\n\n17. A. controlling B. former C. remaining D. original\n-original <u>起初的</u>\n---\n\nEarly promises to end Indian <font color=\"#ffff00\">tribute</font> and taxes on people of mixed origin came much (slower) because the new nations still needed the revenue such policies (produced).\n翻译: <u>早期关于终止印第安人贡赋以及取消对混血人群征税的承诺实现得要慢得多，因为这些新国家仍然需要这些政策所产生的收入。</u>\n-`tax` <u>是现代意义上的税收，而 `tribute` 带有强烈的**“阶级压迫”和“臣服”**色彩。**普通语境里的 tribute：** 通常指“致敬、颂词”**历史语境里的 tribute：** 指的是弱者向强者、被征服者向征服者交的**“进贡、贡赋”**。</u>\n\n\n18. A. slower B. faster C. easier D. tougher\n\n19. A. created B. produced C. contributed D. preferred\n-created <u>创造出原本不存在的东西</u>\n-contributed <u>意思行得通 但是必须要加 to 才能加宾语</u>\n\n---\n\nEgalitarian <font color=\"#ffff00\">sentiments</font> were often <font color=\"#ffff00\">tempered</font> by fears that the mass of the population was (unprepared for) self-rule and democracy.\n翻译: <u>平等主义情绪常常因担心广大民众尚未准备好实行自治和民主而受到调和。</u>\n\n-sentiments <u>情绪 观点</u>\n-temper vt <u>使缓和 n 脾气 怒气 心情</u>\n-\n\n20. A. puzzled by B. <u>hostile to</u> C. pessimistic about D. unprepared for\n-hostile to <u>与 xx 敌对的,对 xx 强烈反对的</u>\n---\n\n第二篇阅读\n\n\nFor the past several years, the Sunday newspaper <font color=\"#ffff00\">supplemen</font>t <font color=\"#ffff00\">Parade</font> has featured a column called “Ask Marilyn.”\n翻译: <u>在过去几年里，Sunday newspaper 的增刊 Parade 开设了一个名为“Ask Marilyn”的专栏。</u>\n\n-supplemen <u>报纸的副刊</u>\n-Parade <u>首字母大写,专有名词作定语补充</u>\n\n---\n\nPeople <font color=\"#ffff00\">are invited to</font> query Marilyn vos Savant, who at age 10 had tested at a mental level of someone about 23 years old; that gave her an IQ of 228 – the highest score ever recorded.\n翻译: <u>人们被邀请向 Marilyn vos Savant 提问；她在 10 岁时测出的智力水平相当于约 23 岁的人，这使她的 IQ 达到 228——有记录以来的最高分。</u>\n-are invited to <u>人们被邀请来</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIQ tests <font color=\"#ffff00\">ask</font> you to complete verbal and visual analogies, to envision paper after it has been folded and cut, and to deduce numerical sequences, among other similar tasks.\n翻译: <u>IQ 测试要求你完成语言和视觉类比，想象纸张被折叠和剪裁后的样子，并推断数字序列，以及完成其他类似任务。</u>\n\n-ask <u>要求</u>\n\n---\n\nSo it is a bit confusing when vos Savant <font color=\"#ffff00\">fields</font> such queries from the <font color=\"#ffff00\">average Joe</font> (whose IQ is 100) <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font>, What’s the difference between love and fondness?\n翻译: <u>因此，当 vos Savant 回答普通人（其 IQ 为 100）提出的诸如“爱和喜爱有什么区别？”这类问题时，就有点令人困惑。</u>\n\n-fields <u>处理</u>\n-average Joe <u>路人甲</u> \n-as <u>在这里作为像的意思</u> \n\n---\n\nOr what is the <font color=\"#ffff00\">nature</font> of luck and <font color=\"#ffff00\">coincidence</font>?\n翻译: <u>或者，运气和巧合的本质是什么？</u>\n\n-nature <u>本质</u>\n-coincidence <u>巧合</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’ s not obvious <font color=\"#ffff00\">how</font> the capacity to visualize objects and to figure out numerical patterns<font color=\"#ffff00\"> suits</font> one to answer questions <font color=\"#ffff00\">that</font> have <font color=\"#ffff00\">eluded</font> some of the best poets and philosophers.\n翻译: <u>能够在脑中想象物体并弄清数字模式的能力，如何使一个人适合回答那些曾令一些最优秀的诗人和哲学家都无从解答的问题，这一点并不明显。</u>\n\n-<u>这里的 that 补足修饰 question 定语从句</u>\n-eluded   <u>使不理解</u>\n-- **<u>主语 (能力/特质)** + **suits** + **someone** + **to do (动作)**</u>\n    \n- _The capacity... **suits** one **to answer**..._ （<u>这种能力……使一个人……适合去回答……）</u>\n\n---\n\nClearly, intelligence <font color=\"#ffff00\">encompasses</font> more than a score on a test.\n翻译: <u>显然，智力所包含的不只是一次测试中的分数。</u>\n\n-encompasses <u>包含</u>\n\n---\n\nJust what does it mean to be smart?\n翻译: <u>聪明到底意味着什么？</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nHow much of intelligence can be specified, and how much can we learn about it from neurology, genetics, computer science and other fields?\n翻译: <u>智力中有多少可以被明确界定？我们又能从神经学、遗传学、计算机科学及其他领域中了解多少关于智力的内容？</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">defining term</font> of intelligence in humans still seems to be the IQ score, <font color=\"#ffff00\">even though</font> IQ tests are not <font color=\"#ffff00\">given</font> as often as they used to be.\n翻译: <u>尽管 IQ 测试不像过去那样经常进行，但人类智力的定义性术语似乎仍然是 IQ 分数。</u>\n\n-even though <u>这个部分翻译的时候可以提前到第一句</u>\n-<u>所以这一句话包含了一个微妙的预期,表达但是的句子是作者所带有批判的意思</u>\n-defining term <u>定义性术语</u>\n-**give a test** <u>进行测试 这里是一个被动形式</u>\n\n---\n\nThe test comes primarily in two forms: the Stanford-Binet Intelligence <font color=\"#ffff00\">Scale</font> and the Wechsler Intelligence Scales (both come in adult and children’ s version).\n翻译: <u>这种测试主要有两种形式：Stanford-Binet 智力量表和 Wechsler 智力量表（两者都有成人版和儿童版）。</u>\n\n-Scale <u>量表</u>\n\n\n---\n\nGenerally costing several hundred dollars, they are usually given only by psychologists, <font color=\"#ffff00\">although</font> variations of them populate bookstores and the World Wide Web.\n翻译: <u>它们通常花费数百美元，一般只由心理学家施测，尽管它们的各种变体充斥着书店和 World Wide Web。</u>\n\n-<u>这里的 although 也体现了,既然有 although,那么必然另外的那一句是更重要的事情</u>\n\n---\n\nSuperhigh scores like vos Savant’ s are no longer possible, because scoring is now based on a statistical population distribution among age peers, rather than simply <font color=\"#ffff00\">dividing</font> the mental age by the <font color=\"#ffff00\">chronological</font> age and <font color=\"#ffff00\">multiplying</font> by 100.\n翻译: <u>像 vos Savant 那样的超高分数如今已不再可能出现，因为现在的评分依据的是同龄人群中的统计分布，而不再是简单地用智力年龄除以实际年龄再乘以 100。</u>\n\n-chronological <u>实龄的 按时间顺序排序的</u>\n-dividing <u>除</u>\n-multiplying <u>乘</u>\n\n---\n\nOther standardized tests, such as the Scholastic Assessment Test (SAT) and the Graduate Record Exam (GRE), <font color=\"#ffff00\">capture</font> the main aspects of IQ tests.\n翻译: <u>其他标准化考试，如 Scholastic Assessment Test（SAT）和 Graduate Record Exam（GRE），捕捉到了 IQ 测试的主要方面。</u>\n\n-capture <u>充分体现/俘获/取得</u>\n\n---\n\nSuch standardized tests may not assess all the important elements necessary <font color=\"#ffff00\">to succeed</font> in school and in life, argues Robert J. Sternberg.\n翻译: <u>Robert J. Sternberg 认为，这类标准化考试可能无法评估在学校和生活中取得成功所必需的所有重要要素。</u>\n\n-to succeed <u>是一个定语短语,necessary 是一个形容词,也是做定语修饰 elements</u>\n\n---\n\nIn his article “How<font color=\"#ffff00\"> Intelligent </font>Is Intelligence Testing?”, Sternberg notes that traditional tests best assess analytical and verbal skills but fail to measure creativity and practical knowledge, components also critical to problem solving and life success.\n翻译: <u>在他的文章“How Intelligent Is Intelligence Testing?”中，Sternberg 指出，传统测试最擅长评估分析能力和语言能力，却未能衡量创造力和实践知识，而这些也是解决问题和人生成功的关键组成部分。</u>\n\n- Intelligent <u>这里的是智能的意思 智商测试有多智能</u>\n\n---\n\nMoreover, IQ tests do not necessarily predict so well once populations or situations change.\n翻译: <u>此外，一旦群体或情境发生变化，IQ 测试并不一定还能很好地作出预测。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nResearch has found that IQ predicted leadership skills when the tests were given under low-stress conditions, but under high-stress conditions, IQ was <font color=\"#ffff00\">negatively correlated</font> with leadership – that is, it predicted the opposite.\n翻译: <u>研究发现，当测试在低压力条件下进行时，IQ 能预测领导能力；但在高压力条件下，IQ 与领导能力呈负相关——也就是说，它预测的是相反的结果。</u>\n\n-negatively correlated <u>负相关 negatively 在这里不是负面的意思,而是相反,反面定</u>\n\n---\n\nAnyone who has toiled through SAT will testify that test-taking skill also matters, <font color=\"#ffff00\">whether</font> it's knowing when to guess <font color=\"#ffff00\">or</font> what questions to skip.\n翻译: <u>任何费力考过 SAT 的人都会证明，应试技巧同样重要，无论是知道什么时候该猜，还是知道哪些题该跳过。</u>\n\n`whether... or...`（<u>无论是……还是……）的固定搭配</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇阅读  解析 191 逐句 24\n\nDuring the past generation, the American middle-class family that once could count on hard work and fair play to keep itself financially secure has been transformed by economic risk and new realities.\n翻译: <u>在过去一代人的时间里，美国中产阶级家庭曾经可以依靠努力工作和公平竞争来维持自身的财务安全，如今却因经济风险和新的现实而发生了转变。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nNow a <font color=\"#ffff00\">pink slip</font>, a bad diagnosis, or a <font color=\"#ffff00\">disappearing spouse</font> can reduce a family from solidly middle class to newly poor in a few months.\n翻译: <u>现在，一张解雇通知、一份糟糕的诊断，或者一个消失的配偶，都可能在几个月内使一个家庭从稳固的中产阶级沦为新贫困群体。</u>\n\n-pink slip <u>解雇通知单</u>\n-disappearing spouse <u>失去配偶</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In</font> just one generation, millions of mothers have gone to work, transforming basic family economics.\n翻译: <u>仅仅一代人的时间里，数百万母亲走上工作岗位，改变了基本的家庭经济结构。</u>\n\n-<u>仅仅在这一代里</u>\n\n---\n\nScholars, policymakers, and critics <font color=\"#ffff00\">of all stripes</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">have debated</font> the social <font color=\"#ffff00\">implications</font> of these changes, but few have looked at the side effect: family risk has risen as well.\n翻译: <u>各类学者、政策制定者和批评人士一直在争论这些变化的社会影响，但很少有人关注其副作用：家庭风险也上升了。</u>\n\n-have debated <u>已经讨论过</u>\n-implications <u>潜在的后果</u>\n-of all stripes <u>修饰 critics</u>\n\n---\n\nToday’ s families <font color=\"#ffff00\">have budgeted</font> to the limits of their new two-paycheck status.\n翻译: <u>如今的家庭已经按照新的双薪状态把预算安排到了极限。</u>\n\n-have budgeted <u>已经安排了开支</u> \n\n---\n\nAs a result, they have lost the parachute/ they <font color=\"#ffff00\">once</font> had/ in times/ of financial setback/ – a back-up earner (usually Mom) who could go into the workforce if the primary earner got laid off or fell sick.\n翻译: <u>因此，他们失去了过去在遭遇财务挫折时拥有的“降落伞”——一个备用挣钱者（通常是母亲），当主要挣钱者被解雇或生病时，她可以进入劳动力市场。</u>\n\n-once <u>曾经</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThis “added-worker effect” could support the safety net offered by unemployment insurance or disability insurance to help families weather bad times.\n翻译: <u>这种“附加劳动者效应”可以支撑由失业保险或伤残保险提供的安全网，帮助家庭渡过困难时期。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nBut today, a <font color=\"#ffff00\">disruption</font> to family fortunes can no longer be made up with extra income from an <font color=\"#ffff00\">otherwise</font>-stay-at-home partner.\n翻译: <u>但如今，家庭财富一旦遭遇冲击，就再也无法通过原本待在家中的伴侣所带来的额外收入来弥补。</u>\n\n-disruption <u>扰乱 中断</u>\n-otherwise `otherwise` 的意思是：<u>**“原本”、“本来”、“在其他情况下”**。</u>\notherwise <u>本来的意思是一个转折的联系词: 否则,要不然</u>\n\n---\n\nDuring the same period, families have been asked to absorb much more risk in their retirement income.\n翻译: <u>在同一时期，家庭还被要求在退休收入方面承担更多风险。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nSteelworkers, airline employees, and now those in the auto industry are joining millions of families who must worry about interest rates, stock market fluctuation, and the harsh reality that they may <font color=\"#ffff00\">outlive</font> their retirement money.\n翻译: <u>钢铁工人、航空公司员工，以及现在汽车行业的从业者，正在加入数百万家庭的行列；这些家庭必须担心利率、股市波动，以及一个严酷现实：他们可能活得比自己的退休金更久。</u>\n\n-outlive <u>在 xx 消失后继续存在</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For much of the past year</font>, President Bush <font color=\"#ffff00\">campaigned</font> to move Social Security to a savings-account model, <font color=\"#ffff00\">with retirees trading</font> much or all of their guaranteed payments <font color=\"#ffff00\">for </font>payments depending on investment returns.\n翻译: <u>在过去一年中的大部分时间里，Bush 总统一直在推动把 Social Security 转向储蓄账户模式，让退休人员用他们许多甚至全部有保障的给付，换取取决于投资回报的给付。</u>\n\n-For much of the past year <u>过去的大半年</u>\n-campaigned <u>这里有四处游说的意思 发起运动对于政治人物来说就是四处游说</u>\n-with retirees trading with <u>做独立主格  就在布什推动这个模式的**同时/在这个新模式下（伴随的情况）**，发生了一件主语不再是“布什”的事情，而是关于“退休人员”的：</u>\n<u>这个在翻译的时候有用,with 后面</u> \n<u>直译成:伴随的情况是</u>   \n<u>实际上可以翻译成:在这种情况下</u> \n-trading for <u>的结构,比较不容易看出来</u>\n\n---\n\nFor younger families, the picture is not any better.\n翻译: <u>对较年轻的家庭来说，情况也没有好到哪里去。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nBoth the <font color=\"#ffff00\">absolute cost</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">healthcare</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">the share of</font> it <font color=\"#ffff00\">borne by families</font> have risen – and newly fashionable health-savings plans <font color=\"#ffff00\">are spreading</font> from legislative halls to Wal-Mart workers, <font color=\"#ffff00\">with </font>much higher <font color=\"#ffff00\">deductibles</font> and a large new dose of investment risk for families’ future healthcare.\n翻译: <u>医疗保健的绝对成本以及由家庭承担的比例都已上升；而新近流行的医疗储蓄计划正从立法机构扩展到 Wal-Mart 员工那里，伴随着高得多的免赔额，以及家庭未来医疗保健中一大笔新的投资风险。</u>\n\n-absolute cost <u>绝对成本</u> \n-healthcare <u>医疗保健</u>\n-the share of <u>它的份额</u>\n-borne by families <u>由家庭承担 这里的 it 指代healthcare</u>\n-are spreading <u>正在蔓延 / 正在普及)</u>\n-deductibles <u>免赔额</u>\n-<u>这里的 with 是随之而来的是 指的是前面那半句话带来的结果 翻译:</u>\n<u>伴随这些计划而来的，是高得多的自付额，以及给家庭未来医疗带来的一大波全新的投资风险</u>\n\n---\n\nEven <font color=\"#ffff00\">demographics</font> are <font color=\"#ffff00\">working against</font> the middle class family, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">odds</font> of having a weak elderly parent <font color=\"#ffff00\">– and </font>all the <font color=\"#ffff00\">attendant</font> need for physical and financial assistance – have jumped <font color=\"#ffff00\">eightfold</font> in just one generation.\n翻译: <u>甚至人口结构也在对中产阶级家庭不利，因为拥有一位体弱年迈父母的可能性——以及随之而来的身体照护和经济援助需求——在短短一代人的时间里已经增加了八倍。</u>\n\n-demographics<u>人口统计数据</u> \n-working against <u>对 xx 不利</u>\n-as <u>因为</u>\n-odds <u>几率 概率</u>\n-attendant <u>随之而来的</u>\n-<u>这里的连接号加上 and 是补足说明,补充性质的同位成分,可以翻译成 还有随之而来的巨大的“体力照料和经济援助的需求</u>\n-eightfold <u>八倍</u>\n\n---\n\nFrom the middle-class family perspective, much of this, understandably, looks <font color=\"#ffff00\">far less like</font> an opportunity to exercise more financial responsibility, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">a good deal more like</font> a frightening acceleration /<font color=\"#ffff00\">of</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">wholesale</font> shift/ <font color=\"#ffff00\">of</font> financial risk/ onto their already overburdened shoulders.\n翻译: <u>从中产阶级家庭的角度看，可以理解的是，这其中许多内容看起来远不像是一个承担更多财务责任的机会，而更像是把财务风险大规模转移到他们本已负担过重的肩上这一过程的令人恐惧的加速。</u>\n\n-<u>核心骨架是`far less like` (远不像...) 和 `a good deal more like` (在很大程度上更像...)。</u>\n-wholesale <u>大规模的</u>\n-<u>连用了两个 of 但是其实都可以省略 acceleration 可以直接加到 onto 前面</u>\n\n---\n\nThe financial <font color=\"#ffff00\">fallout</font> has begun, and the political fallout may not be far behind.\n翻译: <u>财务后果已经开始显现，政治后果也许也不会太远了。</u>\n\n-fallout <u>后果</u>\n\n\n21. Today’ s double-income families are at greater financial risk<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in that</font>\n    \n    -in that <u>原因在于</u>\n    \n\n\n\n---\n\n[C] they <font color=\"#ffff00\">are more vulnerable to</font> changes in family economics.\n-are more vulnerable to <u>更容易受 xx 的影响</u>\n\n---\n\n[D] they are <font color=\"#ffff00\">deprived of unemployment or disability insurance</font>.x\n\n-<u>失去了失业和残疾保险</u>\n\n\n---\n\n[A] financial risks tend to <font color=\"#ffff00\">outweigh</font> political risks.\n\n-outweigh <u>超过</u>\n\n---\n\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2008","year":"2008","title":"2008 年英语一","fileName":"2008 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2008 年英语 1.md","content":"While <font color=\"#ffff00\">still catching up</font> to men in some spheres of modern life, women appear to be way ahead in at least one <font color=\"#ffff00\">undesirable</font> category.\n翻译: <u>尽管女性在现代生活的一些领域仍在追赶男性，但至少在一个令人不快的类别中，女性似乎已经遥遥领先。</u>\n\n-still catching up <u>进行时表示还在追赶</u>\n-undesirable <u>不利的 不好的</u>\n\n---\n\n“Women are particularly susceptible to developing depression and anxiety disorders in response to stress compared to men,” according to Dr. Yehuda, chief <font color=\"#ffff00\">psychiatrist</font> at New York’s Veteran’s Administration Hospital.\n翻译: <u>“与男性相比，女性在面对压力时特别容易患上抑郁症和焦虑症，”纽约 Veteran’s Administration Hospital 的首席精神科医生 Yehuda 博士说。</u>\n\n-psychiatrist <u>神经科</u>\n\n---\n\nStudies of both animals and humans have shown that sex hormones somehow affect the stress response, causing females under stress to produce more of the trigger chemicals than do males under the same conditions.\n翻译: <u>对动物和人类的研究都表明，性激素以某种方式影响压力反应，使处于压力下的雌性比同等条件下的雄性产生更多触发性化学物质。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn several of the studies, when stressed-out female rats had their <font color=\"#ffff00\">ovaries</font> (the female reproductive organs) removed, their chemical responses became equal to those of the males.\n翻译: <u>在其中几项研究中，当压力过大的雌性大鼠被摘除卵巢（雌性生殖器官）后，它们的化学反应变得与雄性相同。</u>\n\n-ovary <u>卵巢</u> \n\n---\n\nAdding to a woman’s increased dose of stress chemicals, are her increased “opportunities” for stress.\n翻译: <u>使女性体内压力化学物质剂量增加的，还有她们更多的压力“机会”。</u>\n\n-<u>英语表达中有一个原则叫“末尾重心（End-weight）” 这个是一个倒装句</u> \n<u>倒装是为了行文衔接上更加流畅,实际语序是</u>\nHer increased “opportunities” for stress are adding to a woman’s increased dose of stress chemicals.\n翻译: <u>女性更多的压力“机会”正在增加她们体内压力化学物质的剂量。</u>\n<u>她（女性）不断增加的承受压力的“机会”，正不断增加着女性体内压力化学物质的剂量。</u>\n\n---\n\n“It’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">not necessarily</font> that women don’t cope as well.\n翻译: <u>“这并不一定是因为女性应对得不够好。</u>\n\n-not necessarily <u>未必</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s just that they have so much more to cope with,” says Dr. Yehuda.\n翻译: <u>只是她们需要应对的事情多得多，”Yehuda 博士说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Their capacity for tolerating stress may even be greater than men’s,” she <font color=\"#ffff00\">observes</font>, “<font color=\"#ffff00\">it’s just that</font> they’re dealing with so many more things that they become worn out from it <font color=\"#ffff00\">more visibly and sooner.</font>”\n翻译: <u>“她们承受压力的能力甚至可能比男性更强，”她观察道，“只是她们要处理的事情多得多，以至于她们因此更明显、更早地变得筋疲力尽。”</u>\n\n-observes <u>说话 评论</u>\n-it’s just that <u>这只是因为</u>\n-more visibly and sooner. <u>用来修饰前面那句话 更加明显 更加快 visibly 明显</u>\n\n---\n\nDr. Yehuda notes another difference between the sexes.\n翻译: <u>Yehuda 博士指出了两性之间的另一个差异。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I think that the kinds of things that women are exposed to tend to be in more of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">chronic</font> or repeated nature.\n翻译: <u>“我认为，女性所接触到的事情往往更具有慢性或反复发生的性质。</u>\n\n-chronic <u>除了慢性的还有长期的意思</u>\n\n---\n\nMen go to war and are exposed to combat stress.\n翻译: <u>男性去参战，承受战斗压力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMen are exposed to more acts of random physical violence.\n翻译: <u>男性接触到更多随机的身体暴力行为。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe kinds of <font color=\"#ffff00\">interpersonal</font> violence that women are exposed to tend to <font color=\"#ffff00\">be in</font> domestic situations, by, unfortunately, parents or other family members, and they tend not to be one-shot deals.\n翻译: <u>女性所遭受的人际暴力往往发生在家庭环境中，不幸的是，施暴者常常是父母或其他家庭成员，而且这些暴力往往不是一次性的事件。</u>\n\n-interpersonal <u>人际关系的</u>\n-be in <u>在</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe wear-and-tear that comes from these longer relationships can be quite devastating.”\n翻译: <u>这些较长期关系所带来的磨损和消耗可能是相当具有破坏性的。\"</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nAdeline Alvarez married at 18 and gave birth to a son, but was determined to finish college.\n翻译: <u>Adeline Alvarez 18岁结婚并生下一个儿子，但她决心完成大学学业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I struggled a lot to get the college degree.\n翻译: <u>\"为了拿到大学学位，我费了很大劲。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nI was living in <font color=\"#ffff00\">so</font> much frustration <font color=\"#ffff00\">that</font> that was my escape, to go to school, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">get ahead</font> and do better.”\n翻译: <u>我生活在太多的沮丧之中，以至于上学、出人头地、做得更好成了我的逃避方式。\"</u>\n\n-so that <u>句型 结果状语从句</u> \n-get ahead <u>取得成功 出人头地</u>\n\n---\n\nLater, her marriage ended and she became a single mother.\n翻译: <u>后来，她的婚姻结束了，她成了一名单身母亲。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It’s the hardest thing to take care of a teenager, have a job, pay the rent, pay the car payment, and pay the debt.\n翻译: <u>\"照顾一个十几岁的孩子、有一份工作、付房租、还车贷、还债，这是最难的事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nI<font color=\"#ffff00\"> lived from paycheck to paycheck.</font>”\n翻译: <u>我过着靠每张工资支票勉强度日的生活。\"</u>\n\n -lived from paycheck to paycheck.  <u>靠着一份又一份的薪水勉强度日</u>\n\n---\n\nNot everyone experiences the kinds of severe chronic stresses Alvarez describes.\n翻译: <u>并非每个人都会经历 Alvarez 所描述的那种严重的慢性压力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut most women today are coping with a lot of obligations, with <font color=\"#ffff00\">few</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">breaks</font>, and feeling the strain.\n翻译: <u>但如今大多数女性都在应对许多义务，几乎没有喘息机会，并且感受着这种压力。</u>\n\n-few <u>本身带有否定意味,很少 几乎没有</u> \n-breaks <u>休息</u>\n\n---\n\nAlvarez’s experience demonstrates the importance of finding ways to diffuse stress before it threatens your health and your ability to function.\n翻译: <u>Alvarez 的经历表明，在压力威胁到你的健康和正常生活能力之前，找到办法来化解压力是多么重要。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n\n第二篇阅读\nIt used to be so <font color=\"#ffff00\">straightforward.</font>\n翻译: <u>过去事情曾经是如此简单明了。</u>\n\n-straightforward. <u>直率的 简单的</u>\n\n---\n\nA team of researchers working together in the laboratory would submit the results of their research to a journal.\n翻译: <u>一组在实验室共同工作的研究人员会把他们的研究结果提交给一家期刊。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA journal editor would then remove the authors’ names and affiliations from the paper and send it to their <font color=\"#ffff00\">peers</font> for review.\n翻译: <u>然后，期刊编辑会从论文中去掉作者的姓名和所属机构，并把论文送交他们的同行评审。</u>\n\n-peers <u>同行</u> \n\n---\n\nDepending on the comments received, the editor would accept the paper for publication or decline it.\n翻译: <u>根据收到的评论，编辑会接受该论文发表，或拒绝发表。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCopyright <font color=\"#ffff00\">rested with</font> the journal publisher, and researchers seeking knowledge of the results <font color=\"#ffff00\">would have to</font> subscribe to the journal.\n翻译: <u>版权归期刊出版商所有，而寻求了解研究结果的研究人员则必须订阅该期刊。</u>\n\n-rested with <u>归属于</u> \n-would have to <u>指的是想要实现前面的事情的 必须要干后面的事情</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">No longer.</font>\n翻译: <u>现在不再如此了。</u>\n\n-<u>省略说法 说明这件事情不再那么简单</u> \n\n---\n\nThe Internet – and pressure from <font color=\"#ffff00\">funding agencies</font>, who are questioning why commercial publishers are making money from government-funded research <font color=\"#ffff00\">by</font> restricting access to it – is making free access to scientific results a reality.\n翻译: <u>互联网，以及来自资助机构的压力，正在使免费获取科学成果成为现实；这些资助机构质疑，商业出版商为什么要通过限制获取由政府资助的研究成果来赚钱。</u>\n\n-funding agencies <u>资助机构</u>\n-by <u>作为方式状语 必然修饰的是规格句子或者动词 所以必然是去找一个动作的,而不是看到 by就自动回到前面的  government-funded research</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) has just issued a report describing the <font color=\"#ffff00\">far-reaching</font> consequences of this.\n翻译: <u>经济合作与发展组织（OECD）刚刚发布了一份报告，描述了这一变化的深远影响。</u>\n\n-far-reaching <u>深远的</u>\n\n---\n\nThe report, by John Houghton of Victoria University in Australia and Graham Vickery of the OECD, makes heavy reading for publishers who have, so far, made handsome profits.\n翻译: <u>这份由澳大利亚 Victoria University 的 John Houghton 和 OECD 的 Graham Vickery 撰写的报告，对于迄今为止赚取了丰厚利润的出版商来说读起来并不轻松。</u>\n\n() \n\n---\n\nBut it goes further than that.\n翻译: <u>但它的意义还不止于此。</u>\n\n-<u>但其意义远不止如此</u>\n\n---\n\nIt signals a change in what has, <font color=\"#ffff00\">until now</font>, been a key element of scientific endeavour.\n翻译: <u>它标志着科学事业中一个迄今为止关键要素的变化。</u>\n\n-until now <u>插入语 可以跳过不看 直接连起来句子</u>\n\n---\n\nThe value of knowledge and the return on the public investment in research depends, <font color=\"#ffff00\">in part</font>, upon <font color=\"#ffff00\">wide distribution</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">ready access</font>.\n翻译: <u>知识的价值以及公共研究投资的回报，在一定程度上取决于广泛传播和便捷获取。</u>\n\n-in part <u>某种某种程度上来说</u>\n-wide distribution <u>广泛传播</u> \n-ready access <u>易获取性</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIt is big business.\n翻译: <u>这是一门大生意。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn America, the core scientific publishing market is estimated at between $7 <font color=\"#ffff00\">billion</font> and $11 billion.\n翻译: <u>在美国，核心科学出版市场估计在70亿至110亿美元之间。</u>\n\n-billion <u>十亿</u>\n\n---\n\nThe International Association of Scientific, Technical and Medical Publishers says that there are more than 2,000 publishers worldwide <font color=\"#ffff00\">specializing</font> in these subjects.\n翻译: <u>国际科学、技术与医学出版商协会表示，全球有2000多家出版商专门从事这些学科的出版。</u>\n\n- specializing <u>专门从事</u> \n---\n\nThey publish more than 1.2 million articles each year in some 16,000 journals.\n翻译: <u>它们每年在约16000种期刊上发表120多万篇文章。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis is now changing.\n翻译: <u>这一切现在正在改变。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAccording to the OECD report, <font color=\"#ffff00\">some</font> 75% of scholarly journals are now online.\n翻译: <u>根据 OECD 的报告，大约75%的学术期刊现在已经上线。</u>\n\n-some <u>大约</u>\n\n---\n\nEntirely new business models are emerging; three main ones were identified by the <font color=\"#ffff00\">report’s authors.</font>\n翻译: <u>全新的商业模式正在出现；报告作者确认了其中三种主要模式。</u>\n\n-report’s authors. <u>报告的作者</u>\n \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is</font> the so-called <font color=\"#ffff00\">big dea</font>l, where institutional subscribers pay for access to a collection of online journal <font color=\"#ffff00\">titles</font> through <font color=\"#ffff00\">site-licensing</font> agreements.\n翻译: <u>其中有所谓的“大交易”，即机构订阅者通过站点许可协议付费获取一系列在线期刊标题的访问权。</u>\n\n-big deal <u>大单订阅模式</u>\n-titles  <u>在出版界和图书馆学中，**\"title\"** 这里**不是指一篇文章的“标题”，而是指“一种出版物”或“一种具体的期刊/书籍”**。</u>\n-site-licensing <u>网站证书</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is</font> open-access publishing, <font color=\"#ffff00\">typically</font> supported by asking the author (or his <font color=\"#ffff00\">employer</font>) to pay for the paper to be published.\n翻译: <u>还有开放获取出版，通常是通过要求作者（或其雇主）支付论文发表费用来支持。</u>\n\n-There is <u>和前面的 there is 一样 都是列举案例</u>\n-typically <u>通常</u>\n-employer <u>是雇主 ee 是下属</u>\n\n\n---\n\nFinally, there are open-access archives, where organizations such as universities or international laboratories support institutional <font color=\"#ffff00\">repositories</font>.\n翻译: <u>最后，还有开放获取档案，在这种模式下，大学或国际实验室等组织支持机构知识库。</u>\n\n-repositories <u>知识库</u>\n\n---\n\nOther models exist that are hybrids of these three, such as delayed open-access, where journals allow only subscribers to read a paper for the first six months, before making it freely available to everyone who wishes to see it.\n翻译: <u>还存在其他模式，是这三种模式的混合形式，例如延迟开放获取，即期刊在最初六个月只允许订阅者阅读一篇论文，之后再向所有希望阅读的人免费开放。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAll this <font color=\"#ffff00\">could</font> change the traditional form of the peer-review process, at least for the publication of papers.\n翻译: <u>所有这一切都可能改变同行评审过程的传统形式，至少在论文发表方面如此。</u>\n\n-could <u>可能会</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nIn the early 1960s Wilt Chamberlain was one of the only three players in the National Basketball Association (NBA) listed at over seven feet.\n翻译: <u>20世纪60年代初，Wilt Chamberlain 是美国国家篮球协会（NBA）中仅有的三名身高列为超过七英尺的球员之一。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nIf he had played last season, however, he would have been one of 42.\n翻译: <u>然而，如果他在上个赛季打球，他就会是42人中的一员。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nThe bodies playing major professional sports have changed dramatically over the years, and managers have been <font color=\"#ffff00\">more than</font> willing to adjust team uniforms to fit the growing numbers of bigger, longer <font color=\"#ffff00\">frames</font>.\n翻译: <u>多年来，参加主要职业体育运动的身体已经发生了巨大变化，而管理者也非常愿意调整球队制服，以适应越来越多更高大、更修长的身材。</u>\n\n-frames <u>体格</u>\n-more than + <u>形容词 翻译成非常</u> \n\n---\n\nThe trend in sports, <font color=\"#ffff00\">though</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">may be obscuring</font> an <font color=\"#ffff00\">unrecognized</font> reality: Americans have generally stopped growing.\n翻译: <u>不过，体育界的这一趋势可能正在掩盖一个未被认识到的现实：美国人总体上已经停止长高。</u>\n\n-though <u>然而 不过</u> \n-may be obscuring  <u>掩盖</u>\n-unrecognized <u>未被注意到的</u> \n-may be obscuring     be doing <u>表示正在进行时态</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Though</font> typically about two inches taller now than 140 years ago, today’s people <font color=\"#ffff00\">–</font> especially those born to families who have lived in the U.S. for many generations <font color=\"#ffff00\">–</font> apparently reached their limit in the early 1960s.\n翻译: <u>尽管如今的人通常比140年前高大约两英寸，但今天的人，尤其是那些出生于已在美国生活了许多代的家庭的人，显然在20世纪60年代初就达到了他们的身高极限。</u>\n\n-<u>两个横杠之间的插入语可以省去 观察主句</u>\n-Though <u>引导的也是从句 可以省去(不是这句的核心意思)</u>\n\n\n---\n\nAnd they <font color=\"#ffff00\">aren’t likely</font> to get any taller.\n翻译: <u>而且他们不太可能再变得更高。</u>\n\n-be likely <u>可能 加上否定就是不不大可能</u>\n\n---\n\n“In the <font color=\"#ffff00\">general population</font> today, at this genetic, environmental level, we’ve pretty much gone as far as we can go,” says anthropologist William Cameron Chumlea of Wright State University.\n翻译: <u>Wright State University 的人类学家 William Cameron Chumlea 说：\"就今天的普通人群而言，在这种遗传和环境水平上，我们差不多已经走到了能走的最远处。\"</u>\n\n-general population <u>总人口</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the case of NBA players, their increase in height appears to result from the increasingly common practice of recruiting players from all over the world.\n翻译: <u>就 NBA 球员而言，他们身高的增加似乎源于从世界各地招募球员这一日益普遍的做法。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nGrowth, which rarely continues beyond the age of 20, demands calories and nutrients – notably, protein – to feed expanding tissues.\n翻译: <u>生长很少会持续到20岁以后，它需要热量和营养，尤其是蛋白质，来供给正在扩张的组织。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nAt the start of the 20th century, under-nutrition and <font color=\"#ffff00\">childhood infections</font> got in the way.\n翻译: <u>20世纪初，营养不良和儿童期感染妨碍了这种生长。</u>\n\n-childhood infections <u>儿童传染病</u>\n\n---\n\nBut as diet and health improved, children and adolescents have, on average, increased in height by about an inch and a half every 20 years, <font color=\"#ffff00\">a pattern</font> known as <font color=\"#ffff00\">the secular trend</font> in height.\n翻译: <u>但随着饮食和健康状况的改善，儿童和青少年平均每20年身高增加约一英寸半，这种模式被称为身高的长期趋势。</u>\n\n-the secular trend  <u>长期趋势</u>\n-a pattern <u>作为的是一整句话的同位语(概括性同位语) 不针对具体的词 用一个总结性的词总结全句</u>\n\n---\n\nYet according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, average height – 5′9″ for men, 5′4″ for women – hasn’t really changed since 1960.\n翻译: <u>然而，根据疾病控制与预防中心的数据，平均身高，男性为5英尺9英寸，女性为5英尺4英寸，自1960年以来其实并没有变化。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nGenetically speaking, there are advantages to avoiding <font color=\"#ffff00\">substantial</font> height.\n翻译: <u>从遗传角度来说，避免身材过高是有好处的。</u>\n\n-substantial <u>相当程度的 重大的 这里作为\"过高\"出现</u>\n\n---\n\nDuring childbirth, larger babies have more difficulty passing through the birth canal.\n翻译: <u>分娩时，体型较大的婴儿更难通过产道。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nMoreover, even though humans have been upright for millions of years, our feet and back continue to struggle with <font color=\"#ffff00\">bipedal</font> posture and cannot easily withstand repeated strain imposed by oversize limbs.\n翻译: <u>此外，尽管人类已经直立行走了数百万年，我们的脚和背部仍然在努力适应双足姿势，并且难以承受由过大四肢带来的反复压力。</u>\n\n-bipedal <u>双足行走的(不影响阅读)</u>\n\n---\n\n“There are some real constraints that are set by the genetic architecture of the individual <font color=\"#ffff00\">organism,</font>” says <font color=\"#ffff00\">anthropologist</font> William Leonard of Northwestern University.\n翻译: <u>Northwestern University 的人类学家 William Leonard 说：\"个体生物的遗传结构确实设定了一些真实的限制。\"</u>\n\n-organism, <u>有机体</u> \n-anthropologist <u>人类学家</u>\n\n---\n\nGenetic maximums can change, but don’t expect this to happen soon.\n翻译: <u>遗传上的最大值可能会改变，但不要指望这很快发生。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nClaire C. Gordon, senior anthropologist at the Army Research Center in Natick, Mass.,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> ensures </font>that 90 percent of the uniforms and <font color=\"#ffff00\">workstations</font> fit <font color=\"#ffff00\">recruits</font> without <font color=\"#ffff00\">alteration</font>.\n翻译: <u>Claire C. Gordon 是马萨诸塞州 Natick 陆军研究中心的高级人类学家，她确保90%的制服和工作站无需改动就能适合新兵。</u>\n\n-ensures <u>确信</u>\n-recruits <u>作为名词是新招聘的成员</u>\n-workstations <u>工作台</u>\n-alteration <u>改变</u>\n\n---\n\nShe says that, unlike those for basketball, the length of military uniforms has not changed for some time.\n翻译: <u>她说，与篮球服不同，军装的长度已经有一段时间没有变化了。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nAnd if you need to predict human height in the near future to design a piece of equipment, Gordon says that by and large, “you could use today’s data and feel fairly confident.”\n翻译: <u>Gordon 说，如果你需要预测近期的人类身高来设计一件设备，总体而言，\"你可以使用今天的数据，并且相当有信心。\"</u>\n\n\n第四篇 \n\nIn 1784, five years before he became president of the United States, George Washington, 52, was nearly toothless.\n翻译: <u>1784年，在成为美国总统的五年前，52岁的 George Washington 几乎已经没有牙齿了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSo he hired a dentist to transplant nine teeth into his jaw –<font color=\"#ffff00\"> having</font> extracted them from the mouths of his slaves.\n翻译: <u>于是他雇了一名牙医，把九颗牙齿移植到他的颌骨中，而这些牙齿是从他的奴隶口中拔出来的。</u>\n\n-`having extracted...` <u>是一个分词短语，在句中作**状语**</u>\n-<u>修饰的主语是 he  因为是他发起或者下令发起的</u>\n\n---\n\nThat’s a far different image from the cherry-tree-chopping George most people <font color=\"#ffff00\">()</font>remember from their history books.\n翻译: <u>这与大多数人从历史书中记得的那个砍樱桃树的 George 形象大不相同。</u>\n\n-that <u>省略了</u> \n\n---\n\nBut recently, many historians have begun to focus on the role slavery played in the lives of the founding generation.\n翻译: <u>但最近，许多历史学家开始关注奴隶制在建国一代人生活中所扮演的角色。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey have been spurred <font color=\"#ffff00\">in part</font> by DNA evidence <font color=\"#ffff00\">made available</font> in 1998, which almost certainly proved Thomas Jefferson had <font color=\"#ffff00\">fathered</font> at least one child with his slave Sally Hemings.\n翻译: <u>部分原因是1998年公布的 DNA 证据推动了他们；这些证据几乎可以肯定地证明 Thomas Jefferson 与他的奴隶 Sally Hemings 至少生育了一个孩子。</u>\n\n-in part <u>某种程度上说</u>\n-made available 1998 <u>年获取的意思</u>\n-fathered <u>成为 xx 的父亲</u> \n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">only</font> over the past 30 years <font color=\"#ffff00\">have</font> scholars examined history from the bottom up.\n翻译: <u>而且，只是在过去30年里，学者们才从底层向上审视历史。</u>\n\n-only have  <u>部分倒装,表示强调,仅仅过去了 30 年 就</u>\n\n---\n\nWorks of several historians reveal the moral compromises made by the nation’s early leaders and the <font color=\"#ffff00\">fragile nature</font> of the country’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">infancy.</font>\n翻译: <u>几位历史学家的著作揭示了这个国家早期领导人所作的道德妥协，以及这个国家初创时期的脆弱性。</u>\n\n-infancy <u>初期</u>\n-fragile nature <u>脆弱性</u>\n\n---\n\nMore significantly, they <font color=\"#ffff00\">argue</font> that many of the Founding Fathers knew slavery was wrong – and yet most did little to fight it.\n翻译: <u>更重要的是，他们认为，许多 Founding Fathers 知道奴隶制是错误的，然而大多数人几乎没有采取行动反对它。</u>\n\n-argue <u>认为</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">More than anything</font>, the historians say, the founders were <font color=\"#ffff00\">hampered</font> by the culture of their time.\n翻译: <u>历史学家们说，最重要的是，建国者们受到了他们所处时代文化的束缚。</u>\n\n-More than anything <u>最重要的是</u> \n-hampered <u>限制 阻碍</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile Washington and Jefferson privately expressed <font color=\"#ffff00\">distaste</font> for slavery, they also understood that it was part of the political and economic <font color=\"#ffff00\">bedrock</font> of the country they helped to create.\n翻译: <u>尽管 Washington 和 Jefferson 私下表达过对奴隶制的厌恶，但他们也明白，奴隶制是他们帮助创建的这个国家政治和经济基础的一部分。</u>\n\n-distaste <u>厌恶 不满 反感</u>\n-bedrock <u>基石</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For one thing</font>, the South could not afford to <font color=\"#ffff00\">part with</font> its slaves.\n翻译: <u>首先，南方承受不起与奴隶分离的代价。</u>\n\n-For one thing <u>首先</u>\n-part with <u>放弃 退出</u>\n\n---\n\nOwning slaves was “like having a large bank account,” says Wiencek, author of <font color=\"#ffff00\">An Imperfect God: George Washington</font>, His Slaves, and the Creation of America.\n翻译: <u>《An Imperfect God: George Washington, His Slaves, and the Creation of America》的作者 Wiencek 说，拥有奴隶“就像拥有一个大银行账户”。</u>\n\n-An Imperfect God: George Washington <u>都是大写 所以是书名</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThe southern states <font color=\"#ffff00\">would not have signed</font> the Constitution without protections for the “<font color=\"#ffff00\">peculiar institution,</font>” including a clause that counted a slave as three fifths of a man for purposes of <font color=\"#ffff00\">congressional representation</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果没有对这一“特殊制度”的保护，南方各州就不会签署宪法；这些保护包括一项条款，即在国会代表权计算中，一名奴隶按五分之三个人计算。</u>\n\n-would + not + have + <u>过去分词 (signed)  虚拟语气 是**与过去事实相反的假设**。</u>\n-peculiar institution <u>特殊制度</u> \n-congressional representation <u>国会代表权</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd the <font color=\"#ffff00\">statesmen</font>’s political lives depended on slavery.\n翻译: <u>而这些政治家的政治生涯依赖于奴隶制。</u>\n\n-statesmen <u>政治家</u>\n\n---\n\nThe three-fifths formula handed Jefferson his <font color=\"#ffff00\">narrow victory </font>in the presidential election of 1800 by inflating the votes of the southern states in t<font color=\"#ffff00\">he Electoral College</font>.\n翻译: <u>五分之三公式通过扩大南方各州在选举人团中的票数，使 Jefferson 在1800年总统选举中险胜。</u>\n\n-the Electoral College  <u>总统选举团</u>\n-narrow victory  <u>险胜</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Once in office</font>, Jefferson <font color=\"#ffff00\">extended slavery with</font> the Louisiana Purchase in 1803; the new land <font color=\"#ffff00\">was carved into</font> 13 states, including three slave states.\n翻译: <u>Jefferson 上任后，通过1803年的路易斯安那购地扩展了奴隶制；这片新土地被划分为13个州，其中包括3个蓄奴州。</u>\n\n-Once in office <u>一就职</u>\n-extended slavery with  with <u>后面表示用xx 手段</u>\n-was carved into <u>被划分为</u>\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Still</font>, Jefferson <font color=\"#ffff00\">freed</font> Hemings’s children – though not Hemings herself or his approximately 150 other slaves.\n翻译: <u>尽管如此，Jefferson 释放了 Hemings 的孩子们，却没有释放 Hemings 本人，也没有释放他大约150名其他奴隶。</u>\n\n-Still <u>即便如此</u>\n-freed free <u>的过去式</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nWashington, who had begun to believe that all men were created equal after observing the bravery of the black soldiers during the Revolutionary War, overcame the strong opposition of his relatives to grant his slaves their freedom in his <font color=\"#ffff00\">will</font>.\n翻译: <u>Washington 在独立战争期间目睹黑人士兵的勇敢之后，开始相信人人生而平等；他克服亲属的强烈反对，在遗嘱中给予他的奴隶自由。</u>\n\n-will <u>意志 意愿</u>\n\n---\n\nOnly a decade earlier, <font color=\"#ffff00\">such an ac</font>t would have required legislative approval in Virginia.\n翻译: <u>仅仅十年前，这样的行为在弗吉尼亚还需要立法批准。</u>\n\n-such an ac <u>这种行为</u>\n\n\n| English | 中文 |\n|---|---|\n| still catching up | <u>仍然在追赶；进行时表示“还在追赶中”</u> |\n| undesirable | <u>不利的；不好的；不受欢迎的</u> |\n| psychiatrist | <u>精神科医生</u> |\n| ovaries | <u>卵巢</u> |\n| Adding to a woman’s increased dose of stress chemicals... | <u>倒装句；为了末尾重心，让较长主语放到后面</u> |\n| End-weight | <u>末尾重心；较长、较重的信息常放在句末</u> |\n| Her increased “opportunities” for stress are adding to... | <u>女性不断增加的承受压力的“机会”，正在增加其压力化学物质剂量</u> |\n| not necessarily | <u>未必；不一定</u> |\n| observes | <u>说；评论；指出</u> |\n| it’s just that... | <u>这只是因为……</u> |\n| more visibly and sooner | <u>更加明显而且更快地</u> |\n| visibly | <u>明显地；看得出来地</u> |\n| chronic | <u>长期的；慢性的</u> |\n| interpersonal | <u>人际关系的；人与人之间的</u> |\n| be in | <u>处于……中；在……里面</u> |\n| so...that... | <u>如此……以至于……；结果状语从句</u> |\n| get ahead | <u>取得成功；出人头地</u> |\n| live from paycheck to paycheck | <u>靠一份又一份薪水勉强度日</u> |\n| few | <u>很少；几乎没有；本身带否定意味</u> |\n| breaks | <u>休息；喘息机会</u> |\n| straightforward | <u>简单的；直接的；易懂的</u> |\n| peers | <u>同行；同领域专家</u> |\n| rested with | <u>归属于；由……掌握</u> |\n| would have to | <u>必须；若想实现前面的事，就必须做后面的事</u> |\n| No longer. | <u>省略表达；表示这种情况不再如此</u> |\n| funding agencies | <u>资助机构</u> |\n| by restricting access to it | <u>通过限制获取它的方式</u> |\n| by | <u>作方式状语，修饰动作；不能看到 by 就自动往前找名词</u> |\n| far-reaching | <u>深远的；影响广泛的</u> |\n| But it goes further than that. | <u>但其意义远不止如此</u> |\n| until now | <u>到目前为止；作插入语时可先跳过看主干</u> |\n| in part | <u>在某种程度上；部分地</u> |\n| wide distribution | <u>广泛传播</u> |\n| ready access | <u>容易获取；便捷获取</u> |\n| billion | <u>十亿</u> |\n| specializing in... | <u>专门从事……；专攻……</u> |\n| some 75% | <u>大约 75%</u> |\n| some | <u>大约；约</u> |\n| report’s authors | <u>报告的作者</u> |\n| There is... | <u>用于列举一种情况 / 模式</u> |\n| big deal | <u>大单订阅模式</u> |\n| titles | <u>出版界中指“一种出版物 / 一种期刊”，不是单篇文章标题</u> |\n| site-licensing | <u>网站授权；机构站点许可</u> |\n| typically | <u>通常；典型地</u> |\n| employer | <u>雇主</u> |\n| employee | <u>雇员；下属</u> |\n| repositories | <u>知识库；资料库；存储库</u> |\n| could | <u>可能会；表示可能性</u> |\n| more than + adjective | <u>非常……；十分……</u> |\n| frames | <u>体格；身材；身体框架</u> |\n| though | <u>然而；不过；表示转折</u> |\n| may be obscuring | <u>可能正在掩盖</u> |\n| unrecognized | <u>未被注意到的；未被认识到的</u> |\n| be doing | <u>进行时，表示正在发生</u> |\n| dash 插入语 | <u>两个横杠之间的插入语可以先省去，先看主句</u> |\n| Though 引导从句 | <u>Though 引导让步从句，也可先省去看主句核心</u> |\n| aren’t likely to... | <u>不大可能……</u> |\n| be likely to... | <u>可能……</u> |\n| general population | <u>总人口；普通人群</u> |\n| childhood infections | <u>儿童期感染；儿童传染病</u> |\n| a pattern | <u>概括性同位语，用一个总结性名词概括前面整句话</u> |\n| the secular trend | <u>长期趋势</u> |\n| substantial | <u>相当程度的；重大的；这里可理解为“过高的”</u> |\n| bipedal | <u>双足行走的</u> |\n| organism | <u>有机体；生物体</u> |\n| anthropologist | <u>人类学家</u> |\n| ensures | <u>确保；保证</u> |\n| workstations | <u>工作台；工作站</u> |\n| recruits | <u>新兵；新招募成员</u> |\n| alteration | <u>改变；改动；修改</u> |\n| having extracted... | <u>分词短语作状语</u> |\n| having extracted... 的逻辑主语 | <u>修饰主句主语 he，表示他发起或下令完成这个动作</u> |\n| the George most people remember | <u>省略了 that / who；修饰 George</u> |\n| in part | <u>在某种程度上；部分地</u> |\n| made available | <u>被获取到的；被公开可用的</u> |\n| fathered | <u>成为……的父亲；生下……</u> |\n| only over the past 30 years have scholars... | <u>only 位于句首引起部分倒装，表示强调</u> |\n| fragile nature | <u>脆弱性；脆弱本质</u> |\n| infancy | <u>初期；早期阶段</u> |\n| argue | <u>认为；主张</u> |\n| More than anything | <u>最重要的是；尤其是</u> |\n| hampered | <u>限制；阻碍</u> |\n| distaste | <u>厌恶；不满；反感</u> |\n| bedrock | <u>基石；根基</u> |\n| For one thing | <u>首先；一方面</u> |\n| part with | <u>放弃；舍弃</u> |\n| An Imperfect God: George Washington | <u>书名；标题中主要词首字母大写</u> |\n| would not have signed | <u>本不会签署；would have done 表示与过去事实相反的虚拟假设</u> |\n| peculiar institution | <u>特殊制度；这里指奴隶制</u> |\n| congressional representation | <u>国会代表权</u> |\n| statesmen | <u>政治家；国务活动家</u> |\n| narrow victory | <u>险胜</u> |\n| the Electoral College | <u>总统选举团</u> |\n| Once in office | <u>一就职；上任后</u> |\n| extended slavery with... | <u>通过……扩张奴隶制；with 表示手段</u> |\n| was carved into | <u>被划分为……</u> |\n| Still | <u>即便如此；然而还是</u> |\n| freed | <u>释放；使获得自由；free 的过去式</u> |\n| will | <u>遗嘱；也可表示意志、意愿</u> |\n| such an act | <u>这种行为</u> |\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2009","year":"2009","title":"2009 年英语一","fileName":"2009 年英语一.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2009 年英语一.md","content":"第一篇阅读 逐句精讲 95 页 \n\nHabits are a funny thing.\n翻译: <u>习惯是一件奇妙的事。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nWe <font color=\"#ffff00\">reach for</font> them mindlessly, <font color=\"#ffff00\">setting</font> our brains on auto-pilot and relaxing into the unconscious comfort of familiar routine.\n翻译: <u>我们不假思索地依赖它们，让大脑进入自动驾驶状态，并安然沉入熟悉惯例所带来的无意识舒适之中。</u>\n\n-setting <u>使 xx 处于某种状态</u>\n-reach for <u>伸手去拿 这里具象化为一种习惯做法</u>\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">Not</font> choice, <font color=\"#ffff00\">but</font> habit rules the unreflecting <font color=\"#ffff00\">herd,</font>” William Wordsworth said in the 19th century.\n翻译: <u>William Wordsworth 在19世纪说过：\"支配不思考的群体的，不是选择，而是习惯。\"</u>\n\n-herd <u>人群 兽群</u>\n-not but  <u>不是...而是..</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIn the ever-changing 21st century, even the word “habit” carries a negative implication.\n翻译: <u>在不断变化的21世纪，甚至“习惯”这个词也带有负面含义。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nSo it seems paradoxical to talk about habits in the same <font color=\"#ffff00\">context</font> as creativity and innovation.\n翻译: <u>因此，把习惯与创造力和创新放在同一语境中来谈，似乎是矛盾的。</u>\n\n-context <u>直接翻译成背景</u>\n\n---\n\nBut brain researchers covered that when we consciously develop new habits, we create  <font color=\"#ffff00\">parallel </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">paths</font>, and even entirely new brain cells, that can jump our trains of thought onto new, innovative tracks.\n翻译: <u>但脑科学研究者已经说明，当我们有意识地培养新习惯时，我们会创造出平行路径，甚至全新的脑细胞，它们能够把我们的思路跳转到新的、创新的轨道上。</u>\n\n-parallel  <u>平行的,相应的 作为 n 还有 相似的意思</u> \n-paths <u>神经通路</u>\n\n---\n\nRather than dismissing ourselves <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> unchangeable creatures of habit, we can instead direct our own change by consciously developing new habits.\n翻译: <u>与其把自己视为不可改变的习惯性生物而加以否定，我们不如通过有意识地培养新习惯来引导自身的改变。</u>\n\n-as <u>可以翻译成看做</u>\n\n---\n\nIn fact, the more new things we try – the more we step outside our comfort zone – the more inherently creative we become, both in the workplace and in our personal lives.\n翻译: <u>事实上，我们尝试的新事物越多，我们越走出自己的舒适区，我们就越会在本质上变得有创造力，无论是在工作场所还是在个人生活中。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nBut don’t bother trying to kill off old habits; once those <font color=\"#ffff00\">ruts</font> of procedure are worn into the brain, they’re there to stay.\n翻译: <u>但不要费心去试图消灭旧习惯；一旦那些程序性的惯性轨道在大脑中被磨出来，它们就会一直存在。</u>\n\n-ruts <u>车辙 惯例</u>\n\n---\n\nInstead, the new habits we deliberately press into ourselves create parallel pathways that can <font color=\"#ffff00\">bypass</font> those old roads.\n翻译: <u>相反，我们有意强加给自己的新习惯会创造出平行路径，可以绕过那些旧道路。</u>\n\n-bypass <u>绕开</u>\n\n---\n\n“The first thing needed for innovation is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">fascination with wonder,</font>” says Dawna Markova, author of The Open Mind.\n翻译: <u>《开放的心灵》的作者 Dawna Markova 说：“创新所需要的第一件事，是对惊奇的迷恋。”</u>\n\n-fascination with wonder <u>对奇迹/未知的痴迷</u>\n\n---\n\n“But we are taught <font color=\"#ffff00\">instead </font>to ‘decide’ , just as our president calls himself ‘the Decider’. ”\n翻译: <u>“但我们被教导的却是去‘决定’，正如我们的总统称自己为‘Decider’一样。”</u>\n\n-instead  <u>却 我们却被教导去</u>\n\n---\n\nShe adds, however, that “to decide is to kill off all possibilities but one.\n翻译: <u>不过，她补充说，“决定就是除一个可能性之外，扼杀所有其他可能性。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nA good innovational thinker is always exploring the many other possibilities.”\n翻译: <u>一个优秀的创新型思考者总是在探索许多其他可能性。”</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nAll of us work through problems in ways of which we’re unaware, she says.\n翻译: <u>她说，我们所有人都以自己没有意识到的方式处理问题。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nResearchers in the late 1960s discovered that humans are born with the capacity to approach challenges in four primary ways: analytically, procedurally, relationally (or collaboratively) and innovatively.\n翻译: <u>20世纪60年代末，研究人员发现，人类生来就具有以四种主要方式应对挑战的能力：分析式、程序式、关系式（或协作式）以及创新式。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nAt the end of adolescence, however, the brain shuts down half of that capacity, preserving only those modes of thought that have seemed most valuable during the first decade <font color=\"#ffff00\">or so</font> of life.\n翻译: <u>然而，在青春期结束时，大脑会关闭这种能力的一半，只保留那些在生命最初十年左右似乎最有价值的思维模式。</u>\n\n-or so <u>大约 放在后面当后置定语</u>\n\n---\n\nThe current emphasis on standardized testing highlights analysis and procedure, meaning that few of us inherently use our innovative and collaborative modes of thought.\n翻译: <u>当前对标准化考试的强调突出了分析和程序，这意味着我们中很少有人会本能地使用创新和协作的思维模式。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n“This breaks the major rule in the American belief system – that anyone can do anything,” explains M. J. Ryan, author of the 2006 book This Year I Will... and Ms. Markova’s business partner.\n翻译: <u>2006年出版的《今年我将……》一书的作者、Markova 女士的商业伙伴 M. J. Ryan 解释说：“这打破了美国信念体系中的一条主要规则，即任何人都能做任何事。”</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n“That’s a lie <font color=\"#ffff00\">that</font> we have perpetuated, and it fosters <font color=\"#ffff00\">commonness</font>.\n翻译: <u>“那是一个我们一直延续的谎言，而且它助长了平庸。</u>\n\n-that <u>后面是修饰 light</u>\n-commonness <u>平庸</u>\n\n\n---\n\nKnowing what you’re good at and doing <font color=\"#ffff00\">even more</font> of it creates excellence.”\n翻译: <u>知道自己擅长什么，并且更多地去做它，才能创造卓越。”</u>\n\n-even more <u>这里的更多是 程度的叠加 而不是超出 xx 的范围的那种 even more</u>\n<u>意思是争对这个事情做更狠一点</u>\n\n---\n\nThis is where developing new habits <font color=\"#ffff00\">comes in</font>.\n翻译: <u>这正是培养新习惯发挥作用的地方。</u>\n\n-comes in  <u>起作用,参与,流行起来,  这里翻译成意义所在</u>\n\n---\n\n\n第四篇 真题解析 114 页 \n\nThe most thoroughly studied <font color=\"#ffff00\">intellectuals</font> in the history of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">New World</font> are the ministers and political leaders of seventeenth-century New England.\n翻译: <u>新大陆历史上被研究得最为透彻的知识分子，是17世纪新英格兰的牧师和政治领袖。</u>\n\n-Intellectuals (<u>知识分子 / 思想家)</u> \n-New World <u>特指美洲新大陆</u>\n\n---\n\nAccording to the standard history of American philosophy, <font color=\"#ffff00\">nowhere else</font> in colonial America was “so much importance attached to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> intellectual pursuits.”</font>\n翻译: <u>按照美国哲学的标准史来看，在殖民地时期的美国，没有其他地方“如此重视智力追求”。</u>\n\n-nowhere else <u>其它的任何地方都没有</u>\n-intellectual pursuits.<u>对知识的追求</u>\n\n---\n\nAccording to many books and articles, New England’s leaders established the basic themes and <font color=\"#ffff00\">preoccupations</font> of an<font color=\"#ffff00\"> unfolding</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">dominant</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">Puritan</font> tradition in American <font color=\"#ffff00\">intellectual life.</font>\n翻译: <u>根据许多书籍和文章，新英格兰的领袖们确立了美国知识生活中一种不断展开并占据主导地位的清教传统的基本主题和关注点。</u>\n\n-preoccupations <u>关注</u> \n-unfolding <u>进行时 逐步展开</u> \n-dominant <u>占主导地位的</u>\n-Puritan <u>清教徒</u>\n-intellectual life <u>思想界/精神生活</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">To take this approach</font> to the New Englanders normally means <font color=\"#ffff00\">to start with</font> the Puritans’ theological innovations and their<font color=\"#ffff00\"> distinctive ideas</font> about the church <font color=\"#ffff00\">–</font> important subjects that we <font color=\"#ffff00\">may not </font>neglect.\n翻译: <u>用这种方法研究新英格兰人，通常意味着从清教徒的神学创新以及他们关于教会的独特观念入手，这些都是我们不可忽视的重要主题。</u>\n\n-To take this approach <u>采用这种方法</u>\n-to start with <u>从 xx 地方开始</u> \n-`distinctive ideas`：<u>独特的、与众不同的理念或观念。</u>\n- -<u>引导的同位语修饰一整个句子</u>\n-may not  <u>有两种情况 一种情况表示 可能不会  另一种情况表示不容忽视 文章中是后者</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">in keeping with</font> our <font color=\"#ffff00\">examination of</font> southern intellectual life, we may <font color=\"#ffff00\">consider</font> the original Puritans <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> carriers of European culture, <font color=\"#ffff00\">adjusting</font> to New World circumstances.\n翻译: <u>但是，按照我们对南方知识生活的考察，我们可以把最初的清教徒看作欧洲文化的承载者，他们正在适应新大陆的环境。</u>\n\n-in keeping with <u>与 xx 保持一致</u>\n-examination of <u>对 xx 的考察</u>\n-consider as <u>把 xx 看做</u>\n-adjusting <u>这里的不仅是分词,还作为一个进行时的作用,表示正在适应</u>\n\n---\n\nThe New England colonies were the <font color=\"#ffff00\">scenes</font> of important episodes <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the pursuit</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">widely understood</font> ideals of civility and virtuosity.\n翻译: <u>新英格兰殖民地是追求被广泛理解的文明与高雅理想的一些重要事件的发生地。</u>\n\n-`scene` <u>原意是风景、舞台，在这里引申为历史事件发生的“舞台”或“地点”。</u> \n-<u>介词 `in` 引导的短语作**状语**（说明这些“重要事件”是在什么背景或过程中发生的）。强调的是一段时间</u>\n-widely understood <u>普遍认同的  understood 作为共识/默契/协议 常出现</u>\n-\n \n---\n\nThe early <font color=\"#ffff00\">settlers</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">Massachusetts Bay</font> included men of impressive education and influence in England.\n翻译: <u>马萨诸塞湾的早期定居者中包括一些在英格兰受过良好教育并有影响力的人。</u>\n\n-settlers <u>定居者</u>\n-Massachusetts Bay  <u>马萨诸塞湾的</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBesides the ninety or so learned <font color=\"#ffff00\">ministers</font> who came to Massachusetts churches<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in the decade after</font> 1629, there were political leaders like John Winthrop, an educated gentleman, lawyer, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">official of the Crown</font> before he <font color=\"#ffff00\">journeyed to</font> Boston.\n翻译: <u>除了1629年后十年间来到马萨诸塞各教会的约90位博学牧师之外，还有像 John Winthrop 这样的政治领袖；他在前往波士顿之前，是一位受过教育的绅士、律师和王室官员。</u>\n\n-ministers <u>牧师</u>\n-in the decade after  decade<u>表示的是十年的一个区间,强调区间的概念</u>\n-`journey to` <u>指长途跋涉去某地。</u>\n-official of the Crown <u>王室成员</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThese men wrote and published <font color=\"#ffff00\">extensively</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">reaching</font> both New World and Old World <font color=\"#ffff00\">audiences</font>, and giving New England an atmosphere of <font color=\"#ffff00\">intellectual earnestness</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些人大量写作和出版，影响了新大陆和旧大陆的读者，并赋予新英格兰一种严肃求知的氛围。</u>\n\n-extensively <u>大量地 广泛地</u>\n-reaching <u>触及了</u>\n-audiences <u>受众</u>\n-`intellectual` <u>指智力的、知识的；`earnestness` 指认真、诚挚、热切。合在一起，指的是一种“对知识极其认真渴求、学术氛围浓厚”的状态。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe should not forget, however, that most New Englanders were <font color=\"#ffff00\">less well</font> educated.\n翻译: <u>然而，我们不应忘记，大多数新英格兰人受教育程度较低。</u>\n\n-<u>前面加上 less 构成劣等比较级。它不是说这些人完全没受过教育（那是 uneducated），而是说他们的受教育程度“不如”前文提到的那些牧师和政治领袖。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile <font color=\"#ffff00\">few craftsmen or farmers</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> let alone dependents and servants</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> left literary compositions</font> to be analyzed, it is obvious that their views were less fully intellectualized.\n翻译: <u>尽管很少有手工业者或农民留下可供分析的文学作品，更不用说依附者和仆人了，但显然，他们的观点没有那么充分地知识化。</u>\n\n-few craftsmen or farmers  <u>几乎没有工匠或农民</u>\n-let alone dependents and servants <u>更不用说家属（附庸）和仆人了，</u>\n -left literary compositions  <u>留下了文学（文字）作品</u>\n -\n\n---\n\nTheir thinking often had a traditional superstitious <font color=\"#ffff00\">quality</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们的思想常常带有一种传统的迷信色彩。</u>\n\n-quality <u>特质</u>\n\n---\n\nA tailor named John Dane, who emigrated in the late 1630s, left <font color=\"#ffff00\">an account</font> of his reasons for leaving England that is filled with <font color=\"#ffff00\">signs</font>.\n翻译: <u>一位名叫 John Dane 的裁缝在17世纪30年代末移民，他留下了一份关于自己离开英格兰原因的记述，其中充满了征兆。</u>\n\n-an account <u>一份记述 / 记录</u>\n-signs <u>预兆 这里根据前文指的是迷信的那种</u>\n\n---\n\nSexual confusion, economic frustrations, and religious hope – all came together in a <font color=\"#ffff00\">decisive </font>moment when he opened the Bible, told his father that the first line he saw would settle his fate, and read the magical words: “<font color=\"#ffff00\">Come out from among them</font>, touch no unclean thing, and I will be your God and you shall <font color=\"#ffff00\">be my people</font>.”\n翻译: <u>性方面的困惑、经济上的挫折以及宗教上的希望，全都在一个决定性时刻汇聚在一起：他翻开《圣经》，告诉父亲他看到的第一行字将决定他的命运，然后读到了那些神奇的话：“从他们中间出来，不要沾不洁之物，我将作你们的神，你们将作我的子民。”</u>\n\n-decisive  <u>决定性</u> \n-be my people <u>成为我的子民</u>\n-Come out from among them <u>从 xx 里出来 圣经句子没头没尾的😂</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">One wonders</font> what Dane thought of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">careful sermons</font> explaining the Bible that he heard in Puritan churches.\n翻译: <u>人们不禁想知道，Dane 对他在清教教会中听到的那些仔细阐释《圣经》的布道会作何感想。</u>\n\n-`One` <u>在这里不是数字“一”，而是代词，泛指“一个人”或“人们”。`wonders` 表示“想知道、纳闷”</u>\n<u>人们不禁会想 / 让人感到好奇的是</u>\n-`careful sermons`：<u>严谨的、详尽的布道/讲道。</u>\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, many settlers had slighter<font color=\"#ffff00\"> religious commitments </font>than Dane’s, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as one clergyman learned</font> in <font color=\"#ffff00\">confronting </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">folk</font> along the coast who mocked that they had <font color=\"#ffff00\">not</font> come to the New World <font color=\"#ffff00\">for </font>religion.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，许多定居者的宗教承诺比 Dane 要浅得多；一位牧师在面对沿海地区的民众时就了解到这一点，他们嘲笑说自己来到新大陆并不是为了宗教。</u>\n\n-`religious commitments`：<u>宗教承诺/奉献。在这里指对宗教的虔诚程度或投入程度。</u>\n-as one clergyman learned <u>正如一位神职人员了解到的那样</u>\n-`confronting`：<u>面对、遭遇、对质。</u> \n-`folk`：<u>人们（指代当地的普通百姓）。</u>\n-<u>这里是把否定词更靠近谓语,更强调否定, for 表示为了.</u> \n\n---\n\n“Our main <font color=\"#ffff00\">end </font>was to catch fish.”\n翻译: <u>“我们的主要目的就是捕鱼。”</u>\n\n-`means and ends` <u>常被翻译为“手段与目的”。 end 作为 目的 的意思</u>\n\n---\n\n\n第二篇\n\nIt is a wise father that knows his own child, but today a man can boost his paternal (fatherly) wisdom – or at least confirm that he’s the kid’s dad.\n翻译: <u>了解自己孩子的父亲才是明智的父亲，但如今，一个男人可以提升自己的父亲智慧，或者至少确认自己就是那个孩子的父亲。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nAll he needs to do is <font color=\"#ffff00\">shell out</font> $30 for a paternity testing kit (PTK) at his local drugstore – and another $120 to get the results.\n翻译: <u>他所需要做的，只是在当地药店花30美元买一套亲子鉴定试剂盒（PTK），再花120美元获取结果。</u>\n\n-shell out <u>往往指掏腰包(一大笔钱或者很不情愿)</u>\n\n---\n\nMore than 60, 000 people have purchased the PTKs since they first became available without prescriptions last year, according to Doug Fogg, <font color=\"#ffff00\">chief operating officer </font>of Identigene, which makes the <font color=\"#ffff00\">over-the-counter</font> kits.\n翻译: <u>生产这种非处方试剂盒的 Identigene 公司首席运营官 Doug Fogg 表示，自从去年 PTK 首次无需处方即可购买以来，已有超过60,000人购买了它们。</u>\n\n-**chief operating officer**：<u>首席运营官，通常简称为 COO。</u>\n-**over-the-counter** <u>非处方 直接在柜台卖的</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">More than two dozen</font> companies sell DNA tests directly to the public, ranging in price from a few hundred dollars to more than $ 2, 500.\n翻译: <u>二十多家公司直接向公众销售 DNA 检测，价格从几百美元到2,500多美元不等。</u>\n\n-More than two dozen <u>二十多家</u> \n\n---\n\nAmong the most popular: paternity and kinship testing, which adopted children can use to find their biological relatives and families can use to track down kids <font color=\"#ffff00\">put up</font> for adoption.\n翻译: <u>其中最受欢迎的包括：亲子鉴定和亲属关系检测，被收养的孩子可以利用它们寻找自己的生物学亲属，家庭也可以利用它们追踪被送养的孩子。</u>\n\n-put up <u>提供/公示</u>\n\n---\n\nDNA testing is also the latest rage among passionate <font color=\"#ffff00\">genealogists</font> – and supports businesses that offer to search for a family’s geographic roots.\n翻译: <u>DNA 检测也是热衷族谱研究者中的最新潮流，并支撑着一些提供寻找家族地理根源服务的企业。</u>\n\n-`genealogists` <u>意为“系谱学家、家谱学者”（研究家族历史和血统的人）。</u>\n\n---\n\nMost tests require collecting cells by <font color=\"#ffff00\">swabbing saliva</font> in the mouth and sending it to the company for testing.\n翻译: <u>大多数检测需要通过擦拭口腔中的唾液来收集细胞，并将其送到公司进行检测。</u>\n\n-`swab` <u>在这里用作动词，意为“用棉签/拭子擦拭、提取（样本）”。`saliva` 意为“唾液，口水”。这个短语详细解释了前面“收集细胞”的具体操作方法。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nAll tests require a potential <font color=\"#ffff00\">candidate</font> with <font color=\"#ffff00\">whom</font> to compare DNA.\n翻译: <u>所有检测都需要一个潜在对象，以便与其 DNA 进行比较。</u>\n\n-`candidate` <u>在这里不仅仅指“候选人”，在实验或检测背景下，指代用于“对照或比较的对象”。</u>\n-`whom` <u>指代前面的 `candidate`。使用 `with` 是因为固定搭配是 `compare A with B`（将 A 与 B 进行对比）。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut some observers are skeptical.\n翻译: <u>但一些观察者对此持怀疑态度。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n“There’s a kind of false precision being <font color=\"#ffff00\">hawked</font> by people claiming they are doing ancestry testing,” says Troy Duster, a New York University sociologist.\n翻译: <u>纽约大学社会学家 Troy Duster 说：“那些声称自己在做祖源检测的人兜售的是一种虚假的精确性。”</u>\n\n-`hawk` <u>原意是“像小贩一样叫卖”，这里含有贬义，暗示这种“精确性”是带有忽悠成分的商品。</u>\n\n---\n\nHe <font color=\"#ffff00\">notes</font> that each individual has many ancestors – <font color=\"#ffff00\">numbering</font> in the hundreds just a few centuries back.\n翻译: <u>他指出，每个人都有许多祖先，仅仅往前数几个世纪，数量就达到数百人。</u>\n\n-`note` <u>在这里是“指出、提到”的意思</u>\n-`numbering` <u>在这里是不及物动词，意为“总计、数目达到”</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Yet</font> most ancestry testing only considers a single lineage, <font color=\"#ffff00\">either</font> the Y chromosome inherited through men in a father’s line <font color=\"#ffff00\">or</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">mitochondrial DNA</font>, which is passed down only from mothers.\n翻译: <u>然而，大多数祖源检测只考虑单一血系，要么是通过父系男性遗传的 Y 染色体，要么是只由母亲传下来的线粒体 DNA。</u>\n\n-`Yet` <u>在句首起到强烈的转折作用 然而 但是</u>\n-`either A or B` <u>要么a 要么是 b</u>\n-`mitochondrial DNA`（<u>线粒体 DNA）</u> \n\n---\n\nThis DNA can reveal genetic information about only one or two ancestors, <font color=\"#ffff00\">even though</font>, for example, just three generations back people also have six other great-grandparents or, four generations back, 14 other great-great-grandparents.\n翻译: <u>这种 DNA 只能揭示关于一两个祖先的遗传信息，尽管例如仅往前三代，人们还另有六位曾祖父母，或者往前四代，还有另外14位高祖父母。</u>\n\n-even though <u>这个引导让步状语从句,包含两层意思同时出现,一个是肯定一个句子,另一个是引出转折</u>\n\n---\n\nCritics also argue that commercial genetic testing is only as good as the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> reference collections</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">which</font> a sample is compared.\n翻译: <u>批评者还认为，商业基因检测的可靠性取决于样本被拿来比较的参考数据库的质量。</u>\n\n-<u>参考库（reference collections）</u>\n-which <u>指代这个参考库</u>\n\n---\n\nDatabases used by some companies <font color=\"#ffff00\">don’t </font>rely on data collected systematically<font color=\"#ffff00\"> but rathe</font>r<font color=\"#ffff00\"> lump together</font> information from different research projects.\n翻译: <u>一些公司使用的数据库并不依赖系统收集的数据，而是把来自不同研究项目的信息混在一起。</u>\n\n-`not... but rather...` <u>结构（不是……而是……）</u>\n-**lump together**：<u>意为“把……混在一起”</u>\n\n---\n\nThis means that a DNA database may have a lot of data from <font color=\"#ffff00\">some regions and not others</font>, so a person’s test results may differ depending on the company that processes the results.\n翻译: <u>这意味着，一个 DNA 数据库可能拥有来自某些地区的大量数据，而缺乏其他地区的数据，因此一个人的检测结果可能会因处理结果的公司不同而不同。</u>\n\n-<u>简略表达，全称是 _some regions and not other regions_</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn addition, the computer programs a company uses to estimate relationships may be<font color=\"#ffff00\"> patented </font>and not <font color=\"#ffff00\">subject</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">peer review</font> or outside evaluation.\n翻译: <u>此外，公司用来估算亲缘关系的计算机程序可能受到专利保护，并且不接受同行评审或外部评估。</u>\n\n-`patent` <u>在这里作动词的过去分词，表示“申请了专利”</u>\n-***subject to**：<u>这是一个高频考点，意为“受……的影响、受……的支配/约束”。</u>\n-**peer review**：<u>同行评审。</u>\n\n\n\n第四篇\n\n\n\nThe relationship between formal education and economic growth in poor countries is widely misunderstood by economists and politicians<font color=\"#ffff00\"> alike</font>.\n翻译: <u>贫穷国家中正规教育与经济增长之间的关系，被经济学家和政治家普遍误解了。</u>\n\n-**alike**：<u>副词，意为“同样地”、“两者都”。</u>\n\n---\n\nProgress in both areas is undoubtedly necessary for the social, political, and intellectual development of these and all other societies; however, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">conventional view</font> that education should be one of the very <font color=\"#ffff00\">highest priorities</font> for promoting rapid economic development in poor countries is wrong.\n翻译: <u>这两个领域的进步无疑对于这些社会以及所有其他社会的社会、政治和知识发展都是必要的；然而，认为教育应当成为促进贫穷国家经济快速发展的最高优先事项之一的传统观点是错误的。</u>\n\n-conventional view <u>传统观点</u>\n-highest priorities <u>最高优先级</u>\n\n---\n\nWe are fortunate<font color=\"#ffff00\"> that it is,</font> because building new educational systems there and <font color=\"#ffff00\">putting</font> enough people <font color=\"#ffff00\">through</font> them to improve economic performance would require two or three generations.\n翻译: <u>幸运的是，这种观点是错误的，因为在那里建立新的教育体系，并让足够多的人接受教育以改善经济表现，将需要两三代人的时间。</u>\n\n-**it is**：<u>这是一个省略结构，全称应该是 _it is (wrong)_。</u>\n-**putting ... through**：<u>供某人完成学业、使某人通过（培训/系统）</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe findings of a research institution have consistently shown that workers in all countries can <font color=\"#ffff00\">be trained on the job</font> to achieve radically higher productivity and, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as a result</font>, radically higher standards of living.\n翻译: <u>一个研究机构的发现一直表明，所有国家的工人都可以通过在职培训来实现大幅提高的生产率，并因此获得大幅提高的生活水平。</u>\n\n-<u>在岗培训</u>\n-as a result <u>可以翻译成 并因此（实现）</u>\n\n---\n\nIronically, the first evidence for this idea appeared in the United States.\n翻译: <u>具有讽刺意味的是，这一观点的第一批证据出现在美国。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNot long ago, with the country entering a recession and Japan at its pre-bubble peak, the U.S. workforce was <font color=\"#ffff00\">derided</font> as poorly educated and one of the primary causes of the poor U.S. economic performance.\n翻译: <u>不久以前，当美国进入衰退而日本处于泡沫前的巅峰时期时，美国劳动力被嘲笑为受教育程度低，并被认为是美国经济表现不佳的主要原因之一。</u>\n\n-**deride**：<u>嘲笑、愚弄、蔑视。  被嘲笑为…… / 被诋毁为……</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nJapan was, <font color=\"#ffff00\">and remains</font>, the global leader in automotive-assembly productivity.\n翻译: <u>日本过去是，现在仍然是汽车装配生产率方面的全球领先者。</u>\n\n-and remains <u>现在依然是</u>\n\n---\n\nYet the research revealed that the U.S. factories of Honda, Nissan, and Toyota achieved about 95 percent of the productivity of their Japanese counterparts – a result of the training that U.S. workers received on the job.\n翻译: <u>然而，研究显示，Honda、Nissan 和 Toyota 在美国的工厂达到了其日本同行约95%的生产率，这是美国工人接受在职培训的结果。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMore recently, while <font color=\"#ffff00\">examining</font> housing construction, the researchers discovered that illiterate, non-English-speaking Mexican workers in Houston, Texas, consistently <font color=\"#ffff00\">met</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">best-practice</font> labor productivity <font color=\"#ffff00\">standards</font> despite the complexity of the building industry’s work.\n翻译: <u>最近，在考察住房建设时，研究人员发现，得克萨斯州休斯敦那些不识字、不会说英语的墨西哥工人，尽管建筑行业的工作复杂，却始终达到了最佳实践的劳动生产率标准。</u>\n\n-examining <u>调查</u>\n-**met ... standards**：<u>达到标准。</u>\n-**best-practice**：<u>行业内最先进的、最优秀的做法（标杆）。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat is the real relationship between education and economic development?\n翻译: <u>教育与经济发展之间的真实关系是什么？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe <font color=\"#ffff00\">have to suspect</font> that continuing economic growth promotes the development of education even when governments don’t force it.\n翻译: <u>我们不得不认为，即使政府不强制推行，持续的经济增长也会促进教育的发展。</u>\n\n-have to suspect <u>我们不得不怀疑 / 我们应当推测。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAfter all, that’s how education got started.\n翻译: <u>毕竟，教育最初就是这样开始的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen our ancestors were <font color=\"#ffff00\">hunters and gatherers</font> 10, 000 years ago, they didn’t have time to wonder much about anything <font color=\"#ffff00\">besides</font> finding food.\n翻译: <u>一万年前，当我们的祖先还是猎人和采集者时，他们除了寻找食物之外，没有时间去多想任何事情。</u>\n\n-**hunters and gatherers**：<u>狩猎者和采集者</u>\n-besides <u>除了 xx 之外</u>\n\n---\n\nOnly when humanity began to get its food in a more productive way was there time for other things.\n翻译: <u>只有当人类开始以一种更高效的方式获取食物时，才有了从事其他事情的时间。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs education improved, humanity’s productivity <font color=\"#ffff00\">potential</font> increased as well.\n翻译: <u>随着教育改善，人类的生产率潜力也随之提高。</u>\n\n-potential <u>潜力</u> \n\n---\n\nWhen the competitive environment pushed our ancestors to achieve that potential, they could <font color=\"#ffff00\">in turn</font> afford more education.\n翻译: <u>当竞争环境推动我们的祖先实现这种潜力时，他们反过来又能够负担更多教育。</u>\n\n-**in turn**：<u>继而、转而、反过来。这是一个极其重要的逻辑词，表示因果链条的下一步。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThis increasingly high level of education is probably <font color=\"#ffff00\">a necessary, but not a sufficient, condition </font>for the complex political systems required by advanced economic performance.\n翻译: <u>这种日益提高的教育水平，可能是高级经济表现所需要的复杂政治体系的一个必要条件，但不是充分条件。</u>\n\n-**a necessary, but not a sufficient, condition** <u>必要不充分 指除了它还有别的条件</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Thus</font> poor countries might <font color=\"#ffff00\">not be</font> able to escape their poverty traps <font color=\"#ffff00\">without</font> political changes that may be possible only with broader formal education.\n翻译: <u>因此，如果没有政治变革，贫穷国家也许无法摆脱贫困陷阱，而这种政治变革可能只有在更广泛的正规教育条件下才有可能实现。</u>\n\n-thus <u>于是 因此 承接逻辑关系</u>\n-not be   without   <u>双重否定表示肯定 还是需要教育改革的</u>\n\n---\n\nA lack of formal education, <font color=\"#ffff00\">however</font>, doesn’t constrain the ability of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">developing world’s </font>workforce to <font color=\"#ffff00\">substantially</font> improve productivity for the foreseeable future.\n翻译: <u>然而，在可预见的未来，缺乏正规教育并不会限制发展中世界劳动力大幅提高生产率的能力。</u>\n\n-`however` <u>放在句中是为了平滑转折。它提示读者：尽管前面说了教育很重要，但现在要说一个“不依赖教育也能增长”的情况。</u>\n-<u>发展中国家 developing world</u>\n-**substantially**：<u>大幅度地、本质上地。</u>\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">On the contrary,</font> constraints on improving productivity explain why education isn’t developing more quickly there <font color=\"#ffff00\">than it is.</font>\n翻译: <u>相反，提高生产率所面临的限制解释了为什么那里的教育没有发展得更快。</u>\n\n-`On the contrary`<u>正相反 / 恰恰相反。</u>\n-**than it is.** <u>相比于现在的状况</u>\n\n\n\n<u>七选五</u>\n\nCoinciding with the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> groundbreaking</font> theory of biological evolution <font color=\"#ffff00\">proposed by</font> British naturalist Charles Darwin in the 1860s, British social philosopher Herbert Spencer put forward his own theory of biological and cultural evolution.\n翻译: <u>19世纪60年代，英国博物学家 Charles Darwin 提出了开创性的生物进化理论，与此同时，英国社会哲学家 Herbert Spencer 提出了他自己的生物和文化进化理论。</u>\n\n-**groundbreaking**：<u>开创性的、突破性的。</u>\n-- **proposed by...**：<u>过去分词短语作定语，修饰 theory，意为“由……提出的”。</u>\n\n---\n\nSpencer argued that all worldly phenomena, including human societies, changed over time, advancing toward perfection.\n翻译: <u>Spencer 认为，所有世间现象，包括人类社会，都会随着时间变化，并朝着完善前进。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHe argued that human evolution <font color=\"#ffff00\">was characterized by </font>a <font color=\"#ffff00\">struggle</font> he called the “survival of the fittest,” in which weaker races and societies must eventually be replaced by stronger, more advanced races and societies.\n翻译: <u>他认为，人类进化的特征是一种他称之为“适者生存”的斗争，在这种斗争中，较弱的种族和社会最终必然被更强大、更先进的种族和社会所取代。</u>\n\n-**be characterized by**：<u>以……为特征</u>\n-**struggle**：<u>斗争、竞争。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAmerican social scientist Lewis Henry Morgan introduced another theory of cultural evolution in the late 1800s.\n翻译: <u>19世纪末，美国社会科学家 Lewis Henry Morgan 提出了另一种文化进化理论。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMorgan helped<font color=\"#ffff00\"> found</font> modern <font color=\"#ffff00\">anthropology</font> – the scientific study of human societies, customs and beliefs – thus becoming one of the earliest anthropologists.\n翻译: <u>Morgan 帮助创立了现代人类学，即对人类社会、习俗和信仰的科学研究，因此成为最早的人类学家之一。</u>\n\n-<u>注意 `found` 在这里是原形动词，意为“建立、创立”，</u>\n-**modern anthropology**：<u>现代人类学。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In his work</font>, he attempted to show how all aspects of culture changed together in the evolution of societies.\n翻译: <u>在他的著作中，他试图说明文化的所有方面如何在社会进化中共同变化。</u>\n\n-<u>在他的著作中 / 在他的研究中</u>\n-\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Thus</font>, in his view, diverse aspects of culture, such as the structure of families, forms of marriage, categories of kinship, ownership of property, forms of government, technology, and systems of food production, all changed as societies evolved.\n翻译: <u>因此，在他看来，文化的不同方面，例如家庭结构、婚姻形式、亲属类别、财产所有权、政府形式、技术以及食物生产体系，都会随着社会进化而发生变化。</u>\n\n-**Thus：** <u>逻辑承接词，表示基于前文结论得出的推论。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn the early 1900s in North America, German-born American anthropologist Franz Boas developed a new theory of culture known as historical particularism.\n翻译: <u>20世纪初，在北美，出生于德国的美国人类学家 Franz Boas 发展出一种新的文化理论，被称为历史特殊论。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHistorical particularism, which emphasized the uniqueness of all cultures, gave new direction to anthropology.\n翻译: <u>历史特殊论强调所有文化的独特性，为人类学提供了新的方向。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn order to study particular cultures as completely as possible, he became skilled in linguistics, the study of languages, and in <font color=\"#ffff00\">physical anthropology</font>, the study of human biology and <font color=\"#ffff00\">anatomy</font>.\n翻译: <u>为了尽可能完整地研究特定文化，他熟练掌握了语言学，即语言研究，以及体质人类学，即人类生物学和解剖学研究。</u>\n\n-**physical anthropology：** <u>体质人类学（研究人类的生物演化、遗传等）。</u>\n-**anatomy：** <u>解剖学</u>\n\n---\n\nBoas felt that the culture of any society must be understood as the result of a unique history and not as one of many cultures belonging to a broader evolutionary stage or type of culture.\n翻译: <u>Boas 认为，任何社会的文化都必须被理解为独特历史的结果，而不是被看作许多属于某个更广泛进化阶段或文化类型的文化之一。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOther anthropologists believed that cultural innovations, such as inventions, had a single origin <font color=\"#ffff00\">and</font> passed from society to society.\n翻译: <u>其他人类学家认为，文化创新，例如发明，只有一个起源，并从一个社会传播到另一个社会。</u>\n\n-and <u>翻译成并且 好像对意思的理解会有帮助一点</u>\n\n---\n\nThis theory was known as diffusionism.\n翻译: <u>这一理论被称为传播论。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHistorical particularism became a dominant approach to the study of culture in American anthropology, largely through the influence of many students of Boas.\n翻译: <u>历史特殊论成为美国人类学中文化研究的一种主导方法，这在很大程度上是通过 Boas 的许多学生的影响实现的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut a number of anthropologists in the early 1900s also rejected the particularist theory of culture in favor of diffusionism.\n翻译: <u>但在 20 世纪初，也有许多人类学家拒绝文化特殊论，而支持传播论。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome attributed <font color=\"#ffff00\">virtually</font> every important cultural achievement to the inventions of a few, especially gifted peoples that<font color=\"#ffff00\">, according to diffusionists, </font>then spread to other cultures.\n翻译: <u>有些人把几乎每一项重要的文化成就都归因于少数特别有天赋的民族的发明；按照传播论者的说法，这些发明随后传播到其他文化中。</u>\n\n-**virtually：** <u>几乎、事实上。加强语气，强调这种观点的极端性</u>\n-<u>两个逗号之间经典的插入语 (用来了解背景信息或语气)</u>\n\n---\n\nFor example, British anthropologists Grafton Elliot Smith and W. J. Perry incorrectly suggested, on the basis of inadequate information, that farming, pottery making, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">metallurgy</font> all originated in ancient Egypt and diffused throughout the world.\n翻译: <u>例如，英国人类学家 Grafton Elliot Smith 和 W. J. Perry 基于不足的信息，错误地提出农业、制陶和冶金都起源于古埃及，并传播到世界各地。</u>\n\n-**metallurgy：** <u>冶金术</u>\n\n---\n\nIn fact, all of these cultural developments occurred separately at different times in many parts of the world.\n翻译: <u>事实上，所有这些文化发展都在世界许多地区、在不同时间分别发生。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAlso in the early 1900s, French sociologist Émile Durkheim developed a theory of culture that would greatly influence anthropology.\n翻译: <u>同样在 20 世纪初，法国社会学家 Émile Durkheim 提出了一种文化理论，该理论将极大地影响人类学。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDurkheim proposed that religious beliefs functioned to reinforce social solidarity.\n翻译: <u>Durkheim 提出，宗教信仰的功能是加强社会团结。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAn interest in the relationship between the function of society and culture became a major theme in European, and especially<font color=\"#ffff00\"> British, anthropology.</font>\n翻译: <u>对社会功能与文化之间关系的兴趣，成为欧洲人类学，尤其是英国人类学的一个主要主题。</u>\n\n-<u>英国人类学 后面的作为一个形容词</u> \n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2010","year":"2010","title":"2010 年英语一","fileName":"2010 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2010 年英语 1.md","content":"Of all the changes that have taken place in English-language newspapers during the past quarter-century, perhaps the most <font color=\"#ffff00\">far-reaching</font> has been the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> inexorable </font>decline in the scope and seriousness of their arts coverage.\n翻译: <u>在过去四分之一世纪英文报纸所发生的所有变化中，影响最深远的或许是其艺术报道范围和严肃性不可阻挡的下降。</u>\n\n-**far-reaching**：<u>影响深远的。</u>\n-**inexorable**：<u>不可阻挡的、无情的、无法改变的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is difficult <font color=\"#ffff00\">to the point of impossibility</font> for the average reader under the age of forty to imagine a time when high-quality arts criticism could be found in most big-city newspapers.\n翻译: <u>对于 40 岁以下的普通读者来说，要想象曾经有一个时期，在多数大城市报纸上都能看到高质量的艺术评论，困难到了几乎不可能的地步。</u>\n\n-to the point of impossibility  to <u>介词短语做状语 修饰 difficult</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nYet a considerable number of the most significant collections of criticism published in the 20th century <font color=\"#ffff00\">consisted in large part of</font> newspaper reviews.\n翻译: <u>然而，20 世纪出版的相当多最重要的评论文集，在很大程度上由报纸评论构成。</u>\n\n-**consisted in large part of     in large part of <u>很大程度上由 xx 组成</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nTo read such books today is to <font color=\"#ffff00\">marvel at</font> the fact that their<font color=\"#ffff00\"> learned</font> contents were once deemed suitable for publication in <font color=\"#ffff00\">general-circulation</font> dailies.\n翻译: <u>今天读这样的书，会惊叹于这样一个事实：它们那些学识渊博的内容，曾经被认为适合刊登在面向普通读者发行的日报上。</u>\n\n-**marvel at**：<u>对……感到惊叹/惊奇</u>\n-**learned**：<u>博学的、学术性的、有深度精深的。</u>\n-**general-circulation**：<u>普通发行的、大众流通的（指非专业学术期刊，而是普通人都能买到的报纸）。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe are even <font color=\"#ffff00\">farther removed from</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">unfocused</font> newspaper reviews published in England between the <font color=\"#ffff00\">turn of the 20th century</font> and the eve of World War II, at a time when newsprint was dirt-cheap and stylish arts criticism was considered an ornament to the publications <font color=\"#ffff00\">in which</font> it appeared.\n翻译: <u>我们距离 20 世纪之交到第二次世界大战前夕在英国发表的那些不拘一格的报纸评论甚至更为遥远；那时新闻纸极其便宜，而文采出众的艺术评论被认为是其所在刊物的一种点缀。</u>\n\n-**be removed from**：<u>远离、与……脱节。</u>\n-**unfocused**：<u>不聚焦的、散漫的、漫谈式的（这里指文章篇幅长、议论广泛）。</u>\n-**turn of the 20th century**：20 <u>世纪初（世纪之交）。</u>\n-`in which` <u>等于 `where`，修饰 publications</u>\n\n---\n\nIn those <font color=\"#ffff00\">far-off</font> days, it was taken for granted that the critics of major papers would write in detail and at length about the events they covered.\n翻译: <u>在那些遥远的岁月里，人们理所当然地认为，主要报纸的评论家会对他们所报道的事件进行详细而长篇的写作。</u>\n\n-far off <u>在那些遥远的日子里</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nTheirs was a serious business, and even those reviewers who <font color=\"#ffff00\">wore their learning lightly,</font> like George Bernard Shaw and Ernest Newman, could be trusted to <font color=\"#ffff00\">know what they were about.</font>\n翻译: <u>他们从事的是一项严肃的事业，即便是那些看似轻松展现学识的评论家，如 George Bernard Shaw 和 Ernest Newman，也可以信赖他们知道自己在做什么。</u>\n\n-**wear one’s learning lightly**  <u>指某人很有学问，但写起文章来举重若轻，不卖弄才学，通俗易懂。</u>\n-**know what they were about**：<u>这是一个习语，指“知道自己在做什么”、“对自己的领域非常精通”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese men believed in journalism as a calling, and were proud to be published in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">daily press.</font>\n翻译: <u>这些人相信新闻业是一种使命，并且以在日报上发表文章为荣。</u>\n\n-* **daily press：** <u>日报、每日报刊。</u>\n\n---\n\n“So few authors have brains enough or literary gift enough to <font color=\"#ffff00\">keep their own end up</font> in journalism, ” Newman wrote, “that I am tempted to define ‘journalism’ as ‘<font color=\"#ffff00\">a term of contempt </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">applied by</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">writers who are not read</font> to writers who are ’.”\n翻译: <u>“很少有作者有足够的头脑或文学才华，能在新闻写作中站稳自己的立场，”Newman 写道，“以至于我忍不住想把‘新闻写作’定义为‘那些没人读的作家用来称呼那些有人读的作家的蔑称’。”</u>\n\n-keep their own end up  <u>意为“（在困难处境下）坚持住、不败下阵来、尽到职责”。</u>\n-contempt <u>蔑称</u>\n-applied by <u>施加到</u>\n-writers who are not read <u>指“作品不被阅读的作家（即：没名气或作品没人要看的作家）”。</u>\n\n<u>这句话非常细节 有一个 so that 的结构 还有一个 apply to 的结构 都是拆分开的</u>\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, these critics are virtually forgotten.\n翻译: <u>不幸的是，这些评论家几乎已被遗忘。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNeville Cardus, who wrote for the Manchester Guardian from 1917 until shortly before his death in 1975, is now known solely as a writer of essays on the game of cricket.\n翻译: <u>Neville Cardus 从 1917 年起为 Manchester Guardian 撰稿，直到 1975 年去世前不久；如今他仅仅以板球随笔作家的身份为人所知。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDuring his lifetime, though, he was also one of England’s foremost classical-music critics, and a stylist <font color=\"#ffff00\">so</font> widely admired <font color=\"#ffff00\">that</font> his <font color=\"#ffff00\">Autobiography</font> (1947) became a best-seller.\n翻译: <u>然而，在他生前，他也是英国最杰出的古典音乐评论家之一，并且是一位广受赞赏的文体家，以至于他的《Autobiography》（1947）成为畅销书。</u>\n\n-<u>在阅读时，看到名词后出现 `so`，要立刻有意识地往后寻找 `that`，将它们看作一个整体。</u>\n-Autobiography <u>自传</u>\n\n\n---\n\nHe was <font color=\"#ffff00\">knighted</font> in 1967, the first music critic to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">so</font> honored.\n翻译: <u>他于 1967 年被封为爵士，是第一位获此殊荣的音乐评论家。</u>\n\n-**knighted：** <u>被授予爵士头衔</u>\n-<u>这里的 **so** 是副词，意为“如此、这样”</u>\n\n---\n\nYet only one of his books is now in print, and his vast body of writings on music is unknown <font color=\"#ffff00\">save to</font> specialists.\n翻译: <u>然而，如今他的书只有一本仍在发行，而他关于音乐的大量著述除专家外鲜为人知。</u>\n\n-<u>在这里 **save** 不是“挽救”或“节省”，而是介词，等同于 **except**（除了）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Is there any chance </font>that Cardus’s criticism will <font color=\"#ffff00\">enjoy a revival</font>?\n翻译: <u>Cardus 的评论有没有可能重新受到关注？</u>\n\n-Is there any chance  <u>有xx 可能吗</u>\n-enjoy a revival <u>迎来复兴  **enjoy** 在这里不是“享受”，而是“享有、经历（好事）</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">prospect </font>seems remote.\n翻译: <u>前景似乎渺茫。</u>\n\n-prospect  <u>前景/可能性</u>\n\n---\n\nJournalistic tastes had changed long before his death, and postmodern readers <font color=\"#ffff00\">have little use for</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">richly upholstered</font> Vicwardian prose in which he specialized.\n翻译: <u>早在他去世之前，新闻写作的趣味就已经改变，而后现代读者对他所擅长的那种华丽厚重的维多利亚-爱德华时代文风几乎没有兴趣。</u>\n\n-**have little use for：** ，<u>字面意思是“没多少用处”，实际指“**不感兴趣、不需要、不吃这一套**”。</u>\n-**richly upholstered：** **upholstered** <u>原意指“（家具）装上垫子/包上皮”，这里比喻文字“**堆砌的、辞藻华丽的、过度修饰的**”。</u>\n\n---\n\nMoreover, the amateur tradition in music criticism has been in <font color=\"#ffff00\">headlong</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">retreat</font>.\n翻译: <u>此外，音乐评论中的业余传统一直在急速退却。</u>\n\n-**headlong：** <u>这是一个非常有力的形容词/副词，意为“**头朝下的、迅猛的、仓促的**”。在这里形容这种传统的消失速度极快，势不可挡。</u>\n-**retreat：** <u>撤退、退缩、溃败。</u>\n\n\n第四篇\nBankers <font color=\"#ffff00\">have been blaming</font> themselves for their troubles<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in public.</font>\n翻译: <u>银行家们一直在公开场合为自己的困境责怪自己。</u>\n\n-have been blaming <u>现在完成进行时,强调一直在进行这个事情</u>\n-in public <u>并不是修饰 troubles 而是整个句子 需要代入分别解读</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Behind the scenes</font>, they have been taking aim at someone else: the <font color=\"#ffff00\">accounting</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">standard-setters</font>\n翻译: <u>在幕后，他们却一直把矛头指向别人：会计准则制定者。</u>\n\n-Behind the scenes <u>在幕后 在背后</u>\n-**standard-setters：** <u>准则制定者</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir rules, moan the banks, have forced them to report<font color=\"#ffff00\"> enormous losses</font>, and it’s just not fair.\n翻译: <u>银行抱怨说，他们的规则迫使银行报告巨额亏损，而这实在不公平。</u>\n\n-**enormous losses：** <u>巨额亏损</u>\n\n---\n\nThese rules say they must value some assets at the price a third party would pay, not the price managers and regulators would like them to <font color=\"#ffff00\">fetch</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些规则规定，他们必须按第三方愿意支付的价格来估值某些资产，而不是按管理者和监管者希望它们卖到的价格。</u>\n\n-**fetch** <u>在这里意为“卖得（多少钱）”。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, banks’ lobbying now seems to be working.\n翻译: <u>不幸的是，银行的游说现在似乎正在奏效。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe details may be unknowable, but the independence of standard-setters, essential to the proper functioning of capital markets, is being compromised.\n翻译: <u>细节也许无从知晓，但准则制定者的独立性正在受到损害，而这种独立性对资本市场的正常运行至关重要。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd, unless banks carry toxic assets at prices that attract buyers, r<font color=\"#ffff00\">eviving the banking system will be difficult.</font>\n翻译: <u>而且，除非银行以能吸引买家的价格列账有毒资产，否则重振银行体系将会很困难。</u>\n\n-**Unless:** <u>除非（引导否定条件，相当于 if...not）。 所以后半句翻译的时候 可以自动加上一个 否则</u>\n<u>否则，复苏银行系统将变得十分困难。</u>\n\n---\n\nAfter a <font color=\"#ffff00\">bruising</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">encounter</font> with Congress, America’s Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) <font color=\"#ffff00\">rushed through</font> rule changes.\n翻译: <u>在与国会发生一场激烈交锋之后，美国财务会计准则委员会（FASB）匆忙通过了规则修改。</u>\n\n-**bruising:** <u>原意是“产生淤青的”，引申为“激烈的、伤元气的”</u> \n-**encounter:** <u>遭遇、冲突。</u>\n-**rush through:** <u>这是一个非常负面的表达，意为“快速草率地通过（法律或议案）”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese gave banks more freedom to use models to value <font color=\"#ffff00\">illiquid assets</font> and more flexibility in <font color=\"#ffff00\">recognizing losses</font> on long-term assets in their <font color=\"#ffff00\">income statements</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些修改给予银行更大的自由，可以使用模型来估值流动性差的资产，并在收益表中确认长期资产损失时拥有更大的灵活性。</u>\n\n-illiquid assets  <u>流动性差的资产</u>\n-**recognizing losses:** <u>确认损失</u>\n-**Income statement:** <u>损益表（反映公司一定时间内盈亏的报表）。 在金融和会计英语中，**statement** 并不是指普通的“陈述”或“声明”，而是专指一种“财务报表”**。</u>\n\n---\n\nBob Herz, the FASB’s chairman, <font color=\"#ffff00\">cried out</font> against those who “question our motives.”\n翻译: <u>FASB 主席 Bob Herz 对那些“质疑我们动机”的人发出了抗议。</u>\n\n-**cry out:** <u>原意是“大喊”，这里指在公开场合激昂地辩解或抗议。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Yet bank shares rose</font> and the changes enhance what one lobbying group politely calls “the use of judgment by management.”\n翻译: <u>然而，银行股上涨了，而这些变化加强了一个游说团体礼貌地称为“管理层判断的使用”的做法。</u>\n\n-<u>表示转折 但是 可以 意译为 尽管争议不断，银行股还是应声大涨。</u>\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">European ministers</font> instantly demanded that the International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) <font color=\"#ffff00\">do likewise</font>.\n翻译: <u>欧洲部长们立即要求国际会计准则理事会（IASB）也这样做。</u>\n\n-<u>欧洲的部长们（通常指财政部长）</u>\n-do likewise <u>也这样做</u>\n\n---\n\nThe IASB says it does not want to act without overall planning, but the pressure to <font color=\"#ffff00\">fold</font> when it completes its reconstruction of rules later this year is strong.\n翻译: <u>IASB 表示，它不想在没有总体规划的情况下采取行动，但当它在今年晚些时候完成规则重构时，向压力屈服的压力很大。</u>\n\n-**fold：** <u>这是一个考研高频熟词僻义。原意是“折叠”，在这里意为**“屈服、垮台、让步”**（想象扑克比赛中的“弃牌”）。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nCharlie McCreevy, a <font color=\"#ffff00\">European commissioner</font>, warned the IASB that it did “not live in a political vacuum” but “in the real world” and that Europe <font color=\"#ffff00\">could yet</font> develop different rules.\n翻译: <u>欧盟委员 Charlie McCreevy 警告 IASB，它“并不是生活在政治真空中”，而是“生活在现实世界中”，并且欧洲仍可能制定不同的规则。</u>\n\n-**European commissioner**（<u>欧盟委员）是欧盟的高级官</u>\n-political vacuum  “<u>政治真空”暗示会计准则不该只谈专业、不谈政治；</u>\n-could yet:  <u>依然可能 / 还是会。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It was</font> banks <font color=\"#ffff00\">that</font> were on the wrong planet, with <font color=\"#ffff00\">accounts</font> that vastly overvalued assets.\n翻译: <u>真正身处错误星球的是银行，它们的账目大幅高估了资产。</u>\n\n-`It was ... that ...` <u>强调句型。</u>\n-**accounts:** <u>账目、会计报表。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Today</font> they argue that market prices overstate losses, because they <font color=\"#ffff00\">largely reflect</font> the temporary illiquidity of markets, <font color=\"#ffff00\">not the likely extent</font> of bad debts.\n翻译: <u>如今它们辩称，市场价格夸大了损失，因为这些价格在很大程度上反映的是市场暂时的流动性不足，而不是坏账可能达到的程度。</u>\n\n-Today <u>表示如今 于之前形成对比</u>\n-**largely reflect：** <u>在很大程度上反映了。</u>\n-**likely extent：** <u>可能的程度/范围。</u>\n\n**<u>地道意译：** 银行家们现在反驳说，市场价格夸大了实际亏损。他们认为，目前的低价主要是由于市场暂时“失血”、缺乏流动性造成的，并不代表这些资产真的已经变成了无法回收的烂账。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe truth will not be known for years.\n翻译: <u>真相要多年以后才会被知晓。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut banks’ shares trade below their <font color=\"#ffff00\">book value</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> suggesting that</font> investors are skeptical.\n翻译: <u>但银行股票的交易价格低于其账面价值，这表明投资者持怀疑态度。</u>\n\n-**Book Value:** <u>指公司账本上显示的资产净值。如果股价（Market Value）低于账面价值，意味着投资者认为账本上的数字是“虚高”的。</u>\n-**suggesting that:** <u>表明/暗示……</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAnd dead markets partly reflect the paralysis of banks which will not sell assets for fear of <font color=\"#ffff00\">booking losses</font>, yet are reluctant to buy all those <font color=\"#ffff00\">supposed</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">bargains</font>.\n翻译: <u>而死气沉沉的市场，在一定程度上反映了银行的瘫痪状态：它们因害怕入账损失而不愿出售资产，却又不愿购买所有那些所谓的便宜货。</u>\n\n-**booking losses:** <u>账面记录损失</u>\n-**supposed:** <u>所谓的、据称的。</u>\n-**bargains:** <u>廉价货、便宜货。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo get the system working again, losses must <font color=\"#ffff00\">be recognized</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">dealt with</font>.\n翻译: <u>要让体系重新运转起来，损失必须被确认并加以处理。</u>\n\n-**recognized:** <u>会计术语，指“确认/入账”。</u>\n-**dealt with:** <u>处理、解决。指在确认亏损后，通过注资、重组或清算等手段彻底清除这些“有毒资产”。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmerica’s new plan to buy up toxic assets will not work unless banks mark assets to levels which buyers find attractive.\n翻译: <u>美国购买有毒资产的新计划不会奏效，除非银行将资产按买家觉得有吸引力的水平计价。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSuccessful markets require independent and even <font color=\"#ffff00\">combative</font> standard-setters.\n翻译: <u>成功的市场需要独立甚至敢于对抗的准则制定者。</u>\n\n-**combative:** <u>好斗的、不屈不挠的、富有斗争精神的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe FASB and IASB have been exactly that, <font color=\"#ffff00\">cleaning up</font> rules on <font color=\"#ffff00\">stock options</font> and pensions, for example, against hostility from <font color=\"#ffff00\">special interests.</font>\n翻译: <u>FASB 和 IASB 一直正是如此，例如，它们顶住特殊利益集团的敌意，清理了有关股票期权和养老金的规则。</u>\n\n-**cleaning up：** <u>清理、整顿。指把模糊、有漏洞的规则变得透明。</u>\n-**stock options：** <u>股票期权。</u>\n-**special interests：** <u>利益集团 / 特殊利益群体</u>\n\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">by giving in to</font> critics now they are i<font color=\"#ffff00\">nviting pressure</font> to make more concessions.\n翻译: <u>但现在向批评者让步，它们是在招致要求作出更多让步的压力。</u>\n\n-**giving in to：** <u>屈服于、让步。</u>\n-inviting pressure <u>他们正在招致压力……</u>\n\n第三篇\n\n\nIn his book _The Tipping Point_, Malcolm Gladwell argues that “social epidemics” are driven in large part by the actions of a tiny minority of special individuals, often called influentials, who are unusually <font color=\"#ffff00\">informed</font>, persuasive, or <font color=\"#ffff00\">well connected</font>.\n翻译: <u>Malcolm Gladwell 在他的书《The Tipping Point》中认为，“社会流行”在很大程度上是由极少数特殊个体的行动所推动的，这些人通常被称为有影响力者，他们异常消息灵通、善于说服，或人脉广泛。</u>\n\n-**informed：** <u>见多识广的（信息优势）。</u>\n-**well connected：** <u>人脉广泛的（渠道优势）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The idea is intuitively compelling</font>, but it doesn’t explain how ideas actually spread.\n翻译: <u>这个观点在直觉上很有吸引力，但它并没有解释观念实际上是如何传播的。</u>\n\n-<u>这一观点在直觉上是非常引人入胜的</u>\n\n---\n\nThe supposed importance of influentials derives from a <font color=\"#ffff00\">plausible-sounding</font> but largely untested theory called the “two-step flow of communication”: Information flows from the media to the influentials and from them to everyone else.\n翻译: <u>有影响力者所谓的重要性，源自一种听起来合理但基本未经检验的理论，叫作“传播的两级流动”：信息从媒体流向有影响力者，再由他们流向其他所有人。</u>\n\n-**plausible-sounding：** <u>听起来很有道理的（plausible 常带有一丝“似是而非”的味道）。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Marketers</font> have embraced the two-step flow because it suggests that if they can just find and influence the influentials, those <font color=\"#ffff00\">select people</font> will do most of the work for them.\n翻译: <u>营销人员接受了两级流动理论，因为它表明，只要他们能找到并影响这些有影响力者，那些被选中的人就会为他们完成大部分工作。</u>\n\n-<u>营销人员</u>\n-select <u>在这里是形容词，意为“精选的、挑选出来的”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe theory also seems to explain the sudden and unexpected popularity of certain looks, brands, or <font color=\"#ffff00\">neighborhoods</font>.\n翻译: <u>这一理论似乎也解释了某些外观、品牌或街区突然而出人意料的流行。</u>\n\n-**neighborhoods：** <u>社区、街区。这里暗示某些地段突然变成网红打卡地或热门居住区。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn many such cases, a cursory search for causes finds that some small group of people was wearing, <font color=\"#ffff00\">promoting</font>, or developing whatever it is before anyone else paid attention.\n翻译: <u>在许多这样的案例中，对原因的粗略搜寻会发现，在其他任何人关注之前，总有某个小群体已经在穿戴、推广或开发相关的东西。</u>\n\n-**promoting：** <u>推广（对应 brands，即品牌）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Anecdotal evidence</font> of this kind fits nicely with the idea that only certain special people can drive trends.\n翻译: <u>这种轶事证据与只有某些特殊人物才能推动潮流的观点十分契合。</u>\n\n-**Anecdotal evidence：** <u>轶事证据、传闻证据。指基于个人经验或偶然事例的证据，而非严格的统计数据。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn their recent work, however, some researchers<font color=\"#ffff00\"> have come up with</font> the finding that influentials have far less impact on social epidemics than is generally supposed.\n翻译: <u>然而，在最近的研究中，一些研究人员得出发现：有影响力者对社会流行的影响远比通常认为的要小。</u>\n\n-**come up with：** <u>提出、想出、得出（观点、方案、发现等）。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn fact, they don’t seem to be required at all.\n翻译: <u>事实上，他们似乎根本不是必需的。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nThe researchers’ argument stems from a simple observation about social influence: <font color=\"#ffff00\">With the exception of</font> a few celebrities like Oprah Winfrey – whose <font color=\"#ffff00\">outsize presence</font> is primarily a function of media, not interpersonal, influence – even the most influential members of a population <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply don’t</font> interact with<font color=\"#ffff00\"> that many others</font>.\n翻译: <u>研究人员的论证源自关于社会影响的一个简单观察：除 Oprah Winfrey 等少数名人外，即便一个群体中最有影响力的成员，也根本不会与那么多其他人互动；而这些名人的巨大影响主要是媒体影响，而非人际影响的结果。</u>\n\n-**With the exception of：** <u>除了……之外（排除例外）。</u>\n-**outsize presence：** <u>巨大的存在感、极高的知名度。</u>\n-**simply don’t：** <u>根本没有、确实不。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Yet</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">it is</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">precisely</font> these non-celebrity influentials <font color=\"#ffff00\">who,</font> according to the two-step-flow theory, <font color=\"#ffff00\">are supposed to </font>drive social epidemics, by influencing their friends and colleagues directly.\n翻译: <u>然而，按照两级流动理论，应该正是这些非名人的有影响力者，通过直接影响他们的朋友和同事来推动社会流行。</u>\n\n-Yet <u>然而 但是</u>\n-**It is... who...**：<u>强调句型，被强调的对象是 `these non-celebrity influentials`。可以翻译成 正是这些谁谁谁</u>\n-**precisely**：<u>副词，意为“精确地、恰恰”，加强了强调的语气。</u>\n-**are supposed to：** <u>被认为应该、理应（在此处指理论上的预期）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For</font> a social epidemic <font color=\"#ffff00\">to occur,</font> however, each person so affected must then influence his or her own acquaintances, who must in turn influence theirs, and so on; and <font color=\"#ffff00\">just </font>how many others pay attention to each of these people has little to do with the initial influential.\n翻译: <u>然而，要发生社会流行，每个受到如此影响的人随后都必须影响他或她自己的熟人，而这些熟人又必须影响他们的熟人，如此继续下去；至于这些人中的每一个有多少其他人关注，与最初那个有影响力者几乎没有关系。</u>\n\n\n-**For... to occur：** <u>为了让 xx 发生 这里的 _for_ 引出不定式的逻辑主语。</u>\n-**<u>逻辑主语：** **a social epidemic** 只是 _to occur_ 这个小动作的发出者。它在语法地位上不是全句的老大，但在逻辑关系上，它是 occur 的主体。</u>\n-<u>这里的 just 是至于的意思吗</u><u>究竟</u>\n\n---\n\nIf people in the network just two degrees removed from the initial influential prove resistant,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> for example, </font>the cascade of change won’t propagate very far or affect many people.\n翻译: <u>例如，如果网络中与最初有影响力者相隔仅两度的人表现出抵抗，那么变化的级联就不会传播得很远，也不会影响很多人。</u>\n\n-for example <u>本来是要放在句首的 但是放在了中间 意思也一样</u>\n\n---\n\nBuilding on this basic truth about interpersonal influence, the researchers studied the dynamics of social influence by conducting thousands of computer simulations of populations, <font color=\"#ffff00\">manipulating a number of variables</font> relating to people’s ability to influence others and their tendency to be influenced.\n翻译: <u>基于这一关于人际影响的基本事实，研究人员通过对人群进行数千次计算机模拟来研究社会影响的动态，操控了若干与人们影响他人的能力以及他们受影响倾向有关的变量。</u>\n\n-manipulating a number of variables  <u>操纵（控制）了许多变量</u>\n-variables <u>作为复数名词当做变量,relating to 在修饰 variables 的时候可以翻译成, 他们控制了多个变量，<font color=\"#ffff00\">包括</font>人们影响他人的能力以及他们易受他人影响的程度。 自己加一个<font color=\"#ffff00\">包括</font>进去</u>\n\n---\n\nThey found that the <font color=\"#ffff00\">principal requiremen</font>t for what is called “global cascades” – the <font color=\"#ffff00\">widespread propagation</font> of influence through networks – is the presence not of a few influentials but, rather, of a critical mass of easily influenced people.\n翻译: <u>他们发现，所谓“全球级联”——影响通过网络广泛传播——的主要条件，不是少数有影响力者的存在，而是存在足够数量的、容易受影响的人。</u>\n\n-`principal requirement`：<u>首要条件、主要需求。</u>\n-`widespread propagation`：<u>广泛的传播、扩散。   propagation原意是繁殖</u>\n\n\nOver the past decade, thousands of <font color=\"#ffff00\">patents</font> have <font color=\"#ffff00\">been granted for</font> what are called business methods.\n翻译: <u>在过去十年里，数千项所谓商业方法的专利已经获得授权。</u>\n\n-`patents`：<u>专利。</u>\n-`grant`：<u>授予、批准。这里使用 `have been granted` 是因为“专利”是被有关部门批准的。</u>\n-for <u>在这里就是给的意思,后面跟一个给的对象 作为介词,可以看做没有意思</u>\n\n---\n\nAmazon.com received one<font color=\"#ffff00\"> for</font> its “one-click” online payment system.\n翻译: <u>Amazon.com 的“一键式”在线支付系统获得了一项这样的专利。</u>\n\n-<u>这里的 for 同样作为介词,可以忽略,作为桥梁 看介词两侧就行</u>\n\n---\n\nMerrill Lynch got legal protection for an asset <font color=\"#ffff00\">allocation</font> strategy.\n翻译: <u>Merrill Lynch 的一项资产配置策略获得了法律保护。</u>\n\n-**asset allocation**：<u>资产配置</u>\n\n---\n\nOne inventor patented a technique for lifting a box.\n翻译: <u>一位发明人给一种搬起箱子的技术申请了专利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNow the nation’s top patent court appears completely ready to scale back on business-method patents, which have been controversial <font color=\"#ffff00\">ever since</font> they were first authorized 10 years ago.\n翻译: <u>现在，美国最高专利法院似乎已经完全准备好缩减商业方法专利的范围，而这类专利自 10 年前首次获准以来一直备受争议。</u>\n\n-ever since <u>自从</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a <font color=\"#ffff00\">move</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">has</font> intellectual-property lawyers <font color=\"#ffff00\">abuzz</font>, the U.S. Court of <font color=\"#ffff00\">Appeals for the Federal Circuit</font> said it would use a <font color=\"#ffff00\">particular case</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">conduct</font> a broad review of business-method patents.\n翻译: <u>美国联邦巡回上诉法院表示，将利用一个特定案件对商业方法专利进行广泛审查，此举让知识产权律师们议论纷纷。</u>\n\n-**move：** <u>举动、行动。</u>\n-**abuzz：** <u>嘈杂的、议论纷纷的</u> \n-**`have + sb. + adj./doing`**    <u>令某人处于某种状态</u>\n<u>此举令知识产权律师们议论纷纷，</u>\n-Appeals for the Federal Circuit <u>全部大写 说明是一个专有名词</u>\n-**particular case：** <u>某个具体的案例</u> \n-**conduct：** <u>进行、开展。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In re</font> Bilski, as the case is known, is “a very big deal,” says Dennis D. Crouch of the University of Missouri School of Law.\n翻译: <u>该案被称为 In re Bilski，密苏里大学法学院的 Dennis D. Crouch 说，这是“一件非常重大的事”。</u>\n\n-`In re` <u>是法律拉丁语，常用于案件名称，意为“关于……”或“以……为项下”。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIt “has the potential to eliminate <font color=\"#ffff00\">an entire class</font> of patents.”\n翻译: <u>它“有可能消除整个一类专利”。</u>\n\n-**an entire class of**：<u>整整一类、完整的一大类。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Curbs on</font> business-method <font color=\"#ffff00\">claims </font>would be a <font color=\"#ffff00\">dramatic about-face</font>, because it was the Federal Circuit itself that introduced such patents <font color=\"#ffff00\">with</font> its 1998 decision in the so-called State Street Bank case, approving a patent <font color=\"#ffff00\">on</font>  a way <font color=\"#ffff00\">of</font> pooling mutual-fund assets.\n翻译: <u>对商业方法权利要求的限制将是一次戏剧性的彻底转向，因为正是联邦巡回法院本身在 1998 年所谓 State Street Bank 案的判决中引入了这类专利，批准了一项关于汇集共同基金资产方法的专利。</u>\n\n-**Curbs on：** <u>对……的限制/约束。</u>\n-**business-method claims：** <u>商业方法（专利）权利要求（即申请专利的具体条款）。</u>\n-**dramatic about-face：** <u>戏剧性的态度大转变。`about-face` 原指军事中的“向后转”，这里形容政策的 180 度大拐弯。</u>\n-with <u>这个词 虽然意思简单 但是做不同的状语翻译起来不一样</u>\n1 <u>做方式状语    凭借、通过、利用</u> \n2 (<u>最常用)随着  伴随状语  随着、伴随  在做到这道题之前,看到什么都按这个翻译 理解流畅度差很多</u>\n3 <u>原因状语    由于、因为、有了</u>\n4<u>条件状语    在 xxxx 情况下</u>\n-<u>还是那句话,看到介词要小心,注意力集中在介词前后的内容,而不是一口气把介词连着都进去,很容易当成一个真题把握不到重点</u>\n\n---\n\nThat ruling produced an explosion in business-method patent <font color=\"#ffff00\">filings</font>, initially by <font color=\"#ffff00\">emerging </font>Internet companies trying to <font color=\"#ffff00\">stake out</font> exclusive rights to specific types of online transactions.\n翻译: <u>那项裁决引发了商业方法专利申请的爆炸式增长，最初主要是新兴互联网公司试图对特定类型的在线交易圈定专有权。</u>\n\n-**patent filings：** <u>专利申请（filing 指向主管部门提交正式文件的行为）。</u>\n-**emerging：** <u>新兴的、处于起步阶段的。</u>\n-**stake out：** <u>划定界限、圈地、据为己有</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nLater, more established companies raced to add such patents to their files, <font color=\"#ffff00\">if only</font> as a defensive move against rivals that might beat them to the punch.\n翻译: <u>后来，更成熟的公司也争相把这类专利加入自己的档案，即便只是作为一种防御措施，以防竞争对手抢先一步。</u>\n\n-**if only：** <u>即使仅仅是为了……、哪怕只是。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn 2005, IBM noted in a court filing that it had been issued more than 300 business-method patents, despite the fact that it questioned the legal basis for granting them.\n翻译: <u>2005 年，IBM 在一份法庭文件中指出，尽管它质疑授予这类专利的法律依据，但它已经获得了 300 多项商业方法专利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSimilarly, some Wall Street investment firms armed themselves with patents for financial products, even as they <font color=\"#ffff00\">took positions</font> in court cases opposing the practice.\n翻译: <u>同样，一些华尔街投资公司一边在法庭案件中采取反对这种做法的立场，一边用金融产品专利来武装自己。</u>\n\n-**took positions：** <u>表态、表达立场。</u>\n-as <u>时间状语 在 xx 的时候</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThe Bilski case involves a claimed patent on a method for <font color=\"#ffff00\">hedging risk</font> in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">energy market</font>.\n翻译: <u>Bilski案涉及一项关于能源市场风险对冲方法的专利主张。</u>\n\n-**hedging risk：** <u>对冲风险、避险。</u>\n-energy market <u>能源市场</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Federal Circuit issued an unusual order stating that the case would be heard by all 12 of the court’s judges, rather than a typical <font color=\"#ffff00\">panel of three</font>, and that one issue it wants to evaluate is whether it should “reconsider” its State Street Bank ruling.\n翻译: <u>联邦巡回上诉法院发布了一项不同寻常的命令，称该案将由该法院全部12名法官审理，而不是由通常的三人合议庭审理，并且它想评估的一个问题是，是否应当“重新考虑”其在State Street Bank案中的裁决。</u>\n\n-panel of three \n\n---\n\nThe Federal Circuit’s action <font color=\"#ffff00\">comes in the wake of </font>a series of recent decisions by the Supreme Court that has narrowed the scope of protections for patent holders.\n翻译: <u>联邦巡回上诉法院的这一行动，是在最高法院近期一系列缩小专利持有人保护范围的裁决之后作出的。</u>\n\n-**comes in the wake of**：<u>这是一个极其高频且地道的短语，意为“紧随其后”、“在……之后接踵而来”。</u>\n-<u>也就是说联邦巡回法庭的action 是在最高发布了这个决议之后进行的</u>\n\n---\n\nLast April, for example, the justices<font color=\"#ffff00\"> signaled</font> that too many patents were <font color=\"#ffff00\">being upheld</font> for “inventions” that are obvious.\n翻译: <u>例如，去年4月，大法官们表示，太多针对显而易见的“发明”的专利正在被维持有效。</u>\n\n-**signaled**：<u>释放信号、暗示。在法律评论中，这通常指法院通过某个判决表达了某种倾向。</u>\n-**upheld**：<u>维持（原判）、确认有效。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThe judges on the Federal Circuit are “reacting to the anti-patent trend at the Supreme Court,” says Harold C. Wegner, a patent attorney and professor at George Washington University Law School.\n翻译: <u>专利律师、乔治·华盛顿大学法学院教授Harold C. Wegner说，联邦巡回上诉法院的法官们正在“回应最高法院的反专利趋势”。</u>\n\n()\n\n<u>完形填空</u>\n\n\nIn 1924 America’s National Research Council sent two engineers to supervise a series of experiments at a telephone-parts factory called the Hawthorne Plant near Chicago.\n翻译: <u>1924年，美国国家研究委员会派出两名工程师，监督在芝加哥附近一家名为Hawthorne Plant的电话零件工厂进行的一系列实验。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt hoped they would<font color=\"#ffff00\"> learn</font> how <font color=\"#ffff00\">shop-floor</font> lighting (affected) workers’ productivity.\n翻译: <u>它希望他们能够了解车间照明如何影响工人的生产率。</u>\n\n-learn <u>了解 弄清楚</u>\n-**shop-floor**：<u>车间，生产场地。</u>\n\n1: B. achieved C. extracted D. restored\n\n---\n\nInstead, the studies <font color=\"#ffff00\">ended (up)</font> giving their name to the “Hawthorne effect,” the extremely influential idea that <font color=\"#ffff00\">the very (act) </font>of being experimented upon changed subjects’ behavior.\n翻译: <u>结果，这些研究最终以自身之名命名了“霍桑效应”，即一个极具影响力的观点：仅仅是被实验这一行为本身就会改变受试者的行为。</u>\n\n-**ended up**：<u>固定短语，意为“最终成为……”，“以……告终”。</u>\n-**the very act**：<u>这里的 very 是形容词，起强调作用，意为“正是那个行为/本身”。</u>\n-\n-\n2: A. at C. with D. off\n\n3: A. truth B. sight D. proof\n\n---\n\nThe idea arose because of the (perplexing) behavior of the women in the plant.\n翻译: <u>这一观点的产生，是因为工厂里女工们令人困惑的行为。</u>\n\n()\n\n4: A. controversial C. mischievous D. ambiguous\n\n---\n\nAccording to (accounts) of the experiments, their hourly output rose when lighting was increased, but also when it was dimmed.\n翻译: <u>根据这些实验的记录，当照明增强时，她们的每小时产量上升；但当照明变暗时，产量也上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n5: A. requirements B. explanations D. assessments\n\n---\n\nIt did not (matter) what was done in the experiment; (so long as) something was changed, productivity rose.\n翻译: <u>实验中做了什么并不重要；只要有某些东西被改变，生产率就会上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n6: A. conclude C. indicate D. work\n\n7: A. as far as B. for fear that C. in case that\n\n---\n\nA(n) (awareness) that they were being experimented upon seemed to be (enough) to alter workers’ behavior (by) itself.\n翻译: <u>意识到自己正在被实验这一点本身，似乎就足以改变工人的行为。</u>\n\n()\n\n8: B. expectation C. sentiment D. illusion\n\n9: A. suitable B. excessive D. abundant\n\n10: A. about B. for C. on\n\n---\n\nAfter several decades, the same data were (subjected) to econometric analysis.\n翻译: <u>几十年后，同一批数据又接受了计量经济学分析。</u>\n\n()\n\n11: A. compared B. shown D. conveyed\n\n---\n\nThe Hawthorne experiments had another surprise in store.\n翻译: <u>霍桑实验还另有一个意外发现。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n(Contrary to) the descriptions on record, no systematic (evidence) was found that levels of productivity were related to changes in lighting.\n\n()\n\n12: B. Consistent with C. Parallel with D. Peculiar to\n\n13: B. guidance C. implication D. source\n\n---\n\nIt turns out that the peculiar way of conducting the experiments may have led to (misleading) interpretations of what happened.\n翻译: <u>事实证明，进行这些实验的特殊方式，可能导致了对所发生事情的误导性解释。</u>\n\n()\n\n14: A. disputable B. enlightening C. reliable\n\n---\n\n(For example), lighting was always changed on a Sunday.\n\n()\n\n15: A. In contrast C. In consequence D. As usual\n\n---\n\nWhen work started again on Monday, output (duly) rose compared with the previous Saturday and (continued) to rise for the next couple of days.\n翻译: <u>周一重新开始工作时，产量照例比前一个周六有所上升，并在接下来的几天里继续上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n16: B. accidentally C. unpredictably D. suddenly\n\n17: A. failed B. ceased C. started\n\n---\n\n(However), a comparison with data for weeks when there was no experimentation showed that output always went up on Mondays.\n\n()\n\n18: A. Therefore B. Furthermore D. Meanwhile\n\n---\n\nWorkers (tended) to be diligent for the first few days of the week in any case, before (hitting) a plateau and then slackening off.\n翻译: <u>无论如何，工人们往往在一周的头几天比较勤奋，随后达到一个平台期，然后逐渐懈怠。</u>\n\n()\n\n19: A. attempted C. chose D. intended\n\n20: A. breaking B. climbing C. surpassing\n\n---\n\nThis suggests that the alleged “Hawthorne effect” is hard to pin down.\n翻译: <u>这表明，所谓的“霍桑效应”很难被准确界定。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2011","year":"2011","title":"2011 年英语一","fileName":"2011 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2011 年英语 1.md","content":"## New York Philharmonic & Alan Gilbert: Study Template\n翻译: <u>## 纽约爱乐乐团与Alan Gilbert：学习模板</u>\n\nThe decision of the New York Philharmonic to hire Alan Gilbert as its next music director has been the talk of the classical-music world ever since the sudden announcement of his appointment in 2009.\n翻译: <u>自从2009年突然宣布任命Alan Gilbert以来，纽约爱乐乐团决定聘请他担任下一任音乐总监一事，便一直是古典音乐界热议的话题。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For the most part</font>, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">response </font>has been favorable, to <font color=\"#ffff00\">say the least.</font>\n翻译: <u>至少可以说，大体上，反应是积极的。</u>\n\n-<u>在很大程度上 / 基本上 / 大体上。</u>\n-**response：** <u>指公众、媒体或相关人士对某事（接上句的任命决定）做出的反应。</u>\n-**to say the least**  <u>至少可以这么说 / 绝不夸张地说。</u>\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">Hooray! At last!</font>” wrote Anthony Tommasini, a <font color=\"#ffff00\">sober-sided</font> classical-music critic.\n翻译: <u>“万岁！终于来了！”一向严肃持重的古典音乐评论家Anthony Tommasini写道。</u>\n\n-“<u>万岁！总算等到了！”</u>\n-**sober-sided**：<u>严谨的、严肃的、持重的。</u>\n\n---\n\nOne of the reasons why the appointment came as such a surprise, however, is that Gilbert is comparatively little known.\n翻译: <u>然而，这一任命之所以如此令人意外，其中一个原因是Gilbert相对来说知名度不高。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nEven Tommasini, who had advocated Gilbert’s appointment in <font color=\"#ffff00\">the Times</font>, calls him “an <font color=\"#ffff00\">unpretentious</font> musician with <font color=\"#ffff00\">no air of</font> the formidable conductor about him.”\n翻译: <u>即便是在《泰晤士报》上曾倡议任命Gilbert的Tommasini，也称他为“一位朴实无华的音乐家，身上没有那种令人敬畏的指挥家气派”。</u>\n\n-**the Times：** <u>指《纽约时报》（The New York Times）。</u>\n-**unpretentious**：<u>不炫耀的、谦逊的、低调的（词根 _pretend_ 假装/炫耀，_un-_ 否定，_-tious_ 形容词后缀）。</u>\n-**no air of...：** <u>没有……的神气/派头。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs a description of the next music director of an orchestra that has <font color=\"#ffff00\">hitherto</font> been led by musicians like Gustav Mahler and Pierre Boulez, that seems likely to have<font color=\"#ffff00\"> struck</font> at least some Times readers <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> faint praise.\n翻译: <u>作为对一个迄今曾由Gustav Mahler和Pierre Boulez这样音乐家领导过的管弦乐团下一任音乐总监的描述，这似乎很可能让至少一些《泰晤士报》读者觉得不过是勉强的赞扬。</u>\n\n-**hitherto**：<u>迄今为止（这是一个非常正式的副词）。</u>\n-**strike A as B**：<u>使 A 产生 B 的印象。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nFor my part, I have no idea whether Gilbert is a great conductor or<font color=\"#ffff00\"> even</font> a good one.\n翻译: <u>就我而言，我不知道Gilbert是否是一位伟大的指挥家，甚至不知道他是否是一位优秀的指挥家。</u>\n\n-**even**：<u>甚至（表示程度的进一步降低）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">To be sure,</font> he performs an impressive variety of interesting compositions, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">it is not necessary for me to</font> visit Avery Fisher Hall, or anywhere else, to hear interesting orchestral music.\n翻译: <u>诚然，他演奏的有趣作品种类多得令人印象深刻，但我要听有趣的管弦乐，并不一定非要去Avery Fisher Hall，或其他任何地方。</u>\n\n-to be sure <u>诚然 / 的确 / 固然。</u>\n-<u>当你想要表达“某物虽好，但非必需”时，可以套用：</u>\n> **To be sure, [A<u>有某种优点], but it is not necessary for me to [做某事] to [达到某种目的].**</u>\n\n---\n\nAll I have to do is to go to my CD shelf, or boot up my computer and download still more recorded music from iTunes.\n翻译: <u>我所要做的只是走到我的CD架前，或者启动电脑，从iTunes下载更多录制好的音乐。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Devoted</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">concertgoers</font> who reply that recordings<font color=\"#ffff00\"> are no substitute</font> for live performance are <font color=\"#ffff00\">missing the point.</font>\n翻译: <u>那些忠实的音乐会听众若回应说录音无法替代现场演出，那就没有抓住问题的要点。</u>\n\n-**Concertgoers：** <u>经常去听音乐会的人。</u>\n-**Devoted：** <u>忠实的、投入的。</u>\n-**No substitute for：** <u>无法替代……。</u>\n-missing the point. <u>搞错了重点</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For</font> the time, attention, and money of the art-loving public, classical instrumentalists must compete not only with opera houses, dance troupes, theater companies, and museums, but also with the recorded performances of the great classical musicians of the 20th century.\n翻译: <u>为了争夺热爱艺术的公众的时间、注意力和金钱，古典器乐演奏家不仅必须同歌剧院、舞蹈团、剧团和博物馆竞争，还必须同20世纪伟大古典音乐家的录音演出竞争。</u>\n\n-`For` <u>引导的介词短语，作目的/对象状语。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese recordings are cheap, available everywhere, and very often much higher in artistic quality than today’s liveperformances; moreover, they can be “consumed” at a time and place of the listener’s choosing.\n翻译: <u>这些录音价格低廉、随处可得，而且在艺术质量上往往远高于今天的现场演出；此外，它们还可以在听众选择的时间和地点被“消费”。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nThe widespread availability of such recordings has<font color=\"#ffff00\"> thus</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">brought about </font>a crisis in the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> institution</font> of the traditional classical concert.\n翻译: <u>因此，这类录音的广泛可获得性，已经给传统古典音乐会这一制度带来了一场危机。</u>\n\n-**Thus：** <u>因此（承接上文的逻辑结论）。</u>\n-**Bring about：** <u>引起、导致、造成（常指引发某种变化或结果）。</u>\n-**Institution：** <u>在这里不是“机构”，而是指一种**“习俗、制度、由来已久的习惯”**。</u>\n\n---\n\nOne possible <font color=\"#ffff00\">response</font> is <font color=\"#ffff00\">for</font> classical performers to program attractive new music that is not yet available on record.\n翻译: <u>一种可能的应对方式是，古典演奏者安排那些尚未有录音版本的、有吸引力的新音乐。</u>\n\n-**response** <u>在这里不仅是“回答”，更是指针对上文提到的“生存危机”所做出的“应对、对策”。</u>\n-<u>这里的 for 引导了一个导出不定式的逻辑主语,明确了让谁采取动作</u>\n\n---\n\nGilbert’s own interest in new music has been <font color=\"#ffff00\">widely noted</font>: Alex Ross, a classical-music critic, has described him as a man who is capable of turning the Philharmonic into “a <font color=\"#ffff00\">markedly different</font>, more <font color=\"#ffff00\">vibrant </font>organization.”\n翻译: <u>Gilbert本人对新音乐的兴趣已受到广泛关注：古典音乐评论家Alex Ross曾形容他是一个能够把爱乐乐团变成“一个明显不同、更有活力的组织”的人。</u>\n\n-**widely noted：** <u>被广泛注意到/被广为称道。</u>\n-**markedly different：** <u>显著的不同。</u>\n-**vibrant：** <u>充满活力的、生机勃勃的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut what will be the <font color=\"#ffff00\">nature of that difference</font>?\n翻译: <u>但这种不同的性质将是什么呢？</u>\n\n-<u>但是，那种<font color=\"#ffff00\">不同的本质</font>将会是什么呢？</u>\n\n---\n\nMerely expanding the orchestra’s repertoire will not be enough.\n翻译: <u>仅仅扩大乐团的曲目范围是不够的。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nIf Gilbert and the Philharmonic<font color=\"#ffff00\"> are to succeed</font>, they must first change the relationship between America’s oldest orchestra and the new audience <font color=\"#ffff00\">it hopes to attract</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果Gilbert和纽约爱乐乐团想要成功，他们必须首先改变美国最古老的管弦乐团与其希望吸引的新观众之间的关系。</u>\n\n-**be to succeed**：<u>这里的 `be to` 表示一种意图或未来的目标（If they want to succeed）。</u>\n-<u>省略了关系代词（that/whom）的定语从句，修饰 `audience`。</u>\n\n---\n\n\n\n第二篇阅读\n\n\nWhen Liam McGee <font color=\"#ffff00\">departed as</font> president of Bank of America in August, his explanation was surprisingly straight up.\n翻译: <u>8月，Liam McGee辞去美国银行总裁一职时，他的解释出人意料地坦率。</u>\n\n-**departed as：** <u>以……身份离职/离开。</u>\n\n---\n\nRather than cloaking his exit in the usual vague excuses, he came right out and said he was leaving “to pursue my goal of running a company.”\n翻译: <u>他没有用通常含糊的借口来掩饰自己的离职，而是直截了当地说，他离开是“为了追求我经营一家公司的目标”。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Broadcasting</font> his ambition was “<font color=\"#ffff00\">very much</font> my decision,” McGee says.\n翻译: <u>McGee说，公开表明自己的抱负“完全是我自己的决定”。</u>\n\n-**very much：** <u>程度副词，强调完全、非常。</u>\n-**Broadcasting：** <u>原意为“广播”，在这里指“向外界公开传播”或“散布”。</u>\n\n---\n\nWithin two weeks, he was talking for the first time with the board of Hartford Financial Services Group, which named him CEO and chairman on September 29.\n翻译: <u>不到两周，他便首次与Hartford Financial Services Group的董事会交谈；该公司于9月29日任命他为CEO兼董事长。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nMcGee says leaving without a position lined up gave him time to reflect on what kind of company he wanted to run.\n翻译: <u>McGee说，在没有安排好下一份职位的情况下离职，让他有时间思考自己想经营什么样的公司。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nIt also sent a clear message to the outside world about his <font color=\"#ffff00\">aspirations</font>.\n翻译: <u>这也向外界清楚地传达了他的抱负。</u>\n\n-**aspirations：** <u>抱负、渴望、志向（通常指长远且远大的目标）。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd McGee isn’t alone.\n翻译: <u>而McGee并非个例。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nIn recent weeks the <font color=\"#ffff00\">No.2 executives</font> at Avon and <font color=\"#ffff00\">American Express</font> quit with the explanation that they were looking for a CEO post.\n翻译: <u>最近几周，Avon和American Express的二号高管相继辞职，理由是他们正在寻找CEO职位。</u>\n\n-**No.2 executives：** <u>二号人物，通常指首席运营官（COO）或总裁，仅次于 CEO。</u>\n-<u>美国运通（American Express）</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAs boards <font color=\"#ffff00\">scrutinize </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">succession plans</font> in response to shareholder pressure, executives who don’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">get the nod</font> also may wish to <font color=\"#ffff00\">move on</font>.\n翻译: <u>随着董事会为回应股东压力而仔细审查继任计划，那些没有被选中的高管也可能希望另谋出路。</u>\n\n-**scrutinize：** <u>仔细检查、详尽审查（强调审查的严厉程度）。</u>\n-**succession plans：** <u>继任计划（即公司内部谁来接班 CEO 的安排）。</u>\n-**get the nod：** <u>这是一个关键的熟语，原意为“点头示意”，引申为“得到选中、获得认可、被钦点”。</u>\n-**move on：** <u>职场常用语，指离开当前职位，开启一段新的职业生涯或跳槽。</u>\n\n---\n\nA turbulent business environment also has<font color=\"#ffff00\"> senior managers </font>cautious of letting <font color=\"#ffff00\">vague pronouncements</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">cloud</font> their reputations.\n翻译: <u>动荡的商业环境也让高级管理人员谨慎起来，不愿让含糊的声明损害自己的声誉。</u>\n\n-**senior managers：** <u>高级管理人员。</u>\n-**vague pronouncements：** <u>模糊的声明/公告。指那些官方辞令，比如“因个人原因离职”。</u>\n-**cloud：** <u>动词，原意为“遮蔽”，引申为“污染、损害、使蒙上阴影”。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs the first signs of recovery begin to <font color=\"#ffff00\">take hold</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">deputy</font> chiefs may be more willing to make the jump <font color=\"#ffff00\">without a net</font>.\n翻译: <u>随着复苏的最初迹象开始站稳脚跟，副手们可能更愿意在没有保障的情况下跳槽。</u>\n\n-**take hold：** <u>变强、确立、生根。这里指经济复苏趋势变得明朗且稳定。</u>\n-**deputy：** <u>副职、代表。</u>\n-**without a net：** <u>原意指杂技演员在没有防护网的情况下表演高空动作。这里是一个生动的比喻，指**“裸辞”**，即在没有签好下一份工作合同（net）的情况下就放弃现有的职位。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the third quarter, CEO turnover was down 23% from a year ago as nervous boards <font color=\"#ffff00\">stuck with</font> the leaders they had, according to Liberum Research.\n翻译: <u>根据Liberum Research的数据，第三季度CEO更替率较一年前下降了23%，因为紧张不安的董事会坚持留用现有领导者。</u>\n\n-**stuck with：** <u>坚持、守着、不改变。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nAs the economy picks up, opportunities will <font color=\"#ffff00\">abound</font> for aspiring leaders.\n翻译: <u>随着经济好转，有抱负的领导者将会拥有大量机会。</u>\n\n-**abound：** <u>不及物动词，意为“大量存在、充满”。这个词比 `there will be many opportunities` 更有文学感和力量感。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe decision to quit a senior position to look for a better one is <font color=\"#ffff00\">unconventional.</font>\n翻译: <u>辞去高级职位去寻找一个更好的职位，这一决定并不合常规。</u>\n\n-**unconventional：** <u>反传统的、不按常理出牌的。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor years executives and headhunters have adhered to the rule that the most attractive CEO candidates are the ones who must be <font color=\"#ffff00\">poached</font>.\n翻译: <u>多年来，高管和猎头一直遵循这样一条规则：最有吸引力的CEO候选人，是那些必须被挖角的人。</u>\n\n-**poached：** <u>挖走、挖角（原意为偷猎）。</u>\n\n- <u>在猎头的逻辑里，正在职且被原公司重用的人才最有价值；而那些“失业”或“待业”的人常被怀疑是因为能力不足或被解雇。</u>\n\n---\n\nSays Korn/Ferry senior partner Dennis Carey: <font color=\"#ffff00\">“I can’t think of a single search</font> I’ve done where a board has not instructed me to look at sitting CEOs first.”\n翻译: <u>Korn/Ferry高级合伙人Dennis Carey说：“我想不出我做过的任何一次招聘中，董事会没有指示我先看在任CEO的。”</u>\n\n-<u>我无法想到任何一次（高管）搜寻任务，”</u>\n-**<u>地道意译：** 全球顶尖猎头公司光辉国际的高级合伙人丹尼斯·凯里表示：“在我经手的职业经理人搜寻案例中，几乎每一家董事会都会明确要求我：首选目标必须是那些正处于任期内的现任 CEO。”</u>\n\n---\n\nThose who jumped without a job haven’t always landed in top positions quickly.\n翻译: <u>那些在没有工作着落的情况下跳槽的人，并不总是能很快获得最高职位。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nEllen Marram quit as chief of Tropicana a decade ago, saying she wanted to be a CEO.\n翻译: <u>十年前，Ellen Marram辞去Tropicana负责人一职，称她想成为CEO。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It was a year before</font> she became head of a tiny Internet-based <font color=\"#ffff00\">commodities exchange</font>.\n翻译: <u>过了一年，她才成为一家小型互联网商品交易所的负责人。</u>\n\n-`It was + <u>时间段 + before...` 结构，意为“过了多久才……”。</u>\n-**commodities exchange：** <u>大宗商品交易所。</u>\n\n---\n\nRobert Willumstad left Citigroup in 2005 with ambitions to be a CEO.\n翻译: <u>Robert Willumstad于2005年离开Citigroup，怀有成为CEO的抱负。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nHe finally took that post at a major financial institution three years later.\n翻译: <u>三年后，他才终于在一家大型金融机构担任了那个职位。</u>\n\n( )\n\n---\n\nMany recruiters say the <font color=\"#ffff00\">old disgrace</font> is fading for top performers.\n翻译: <u>许多招聘人员说，对于表现优异者而言，过去那种丢脸的意味正在消退。</u>\n\n-**the old disgrace：** <u>旧有的耻辱。指代前文提到的观念：如果你离职时手里没有现成的 offer（即“裸辞”），大家会认为你是被开除的或者是没人要的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe financial crisis has made it more acceptable to <font color=\"#ffff00\">be between jobs </font>or to leave a bad one.\n翻译: <u>金融危机使得处于待业状态或离开一份糟糕的工作变得更容易被接受。</u>\n\n-**between jobs：** <u>这是一个非常委婉的地道表达，字面意思是在“两份工作之间”，实际指代“失业”或“待业状态”。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n“The traditional rule was it’s safer to stay where you are, but that’s been fundamentally<font color=\"#ffff00\"> inverted,</font>” says one headhunter.\n翻译: <u>一位猎头说：“传统规则是，留在原处更安全，但这一点已经被根本性地颠倒了。”</u>\n\n-- - **inverted：** <u>颠倒、倒置。这是一个强烈的词，意味着现在的逻辑和以前完全相反——现在的风险可能在于“不敢离开”。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The people who’ve been hurt the worst are those who’ve stayed too long.”\n翻译: <u>“受伤最严重的人，是那些待得太久的人。”</u>\n\n( )\n\n\n第三篇阅读\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">rough guide</font> to marketing success used to be that you got what you paid for.\n翻译: <u>过去，关于营销成功的粗略法则是：你花多少钱，就得到多少回报。</u>\n\n-**rough guide**：<u>粗略的指导、大致的准则。</u>\n\n---\n\nNo longer.\n翻译: <u>现在不再如此。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile traditional “paid” media – such as television commercials and print advertisements – still play a major role, companies today can exploit many alternative forms of media.\n翻译: <u>尽管电视广告和平面广告等传统“付费”媒体仍发挥着重要作用，但今天的公司可以利用许多替代性的媒体形式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nConsumers passionate about a product may create “earned” media by <font color=\"#ffff00\">willingly</font> promoting it to friends, and a company may leverage “owned” media by sending e-mail alerts about products and sales to customers registered with its Web site.\n翻译: <u>对某种产品充满热情的消费者可能会通过自愿向朋友推广它来创造“赢得”媒体，而公司也可以通过向在其网站注册的客户发送有关产品和促销的电子邮件提醒，来利用“自有”媒体。</u>\n\n-**willingly**：<u>自愿地、主动地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe way consumers now approach the process of making purchase decisions means that <font color=\"#ffff00\">marketing’s impact</font> stems from a broad range of factors beyond <font color=\"#ffff00\">conventional paid media</font>.\n翻译: <u>消费者如今进行购买决策的方式意味着，营销的影响来自一系列广泛因素，而不只是传统付费媒体。</u>\n\n-**marketing’s impact**：<u>营销的影响力。</u>\n-**conventional paid media**：<u>传统付费媒体。这是行业术语，指企业直接花钱购买的广告位，与社交媒体口碑、用户生成内容等新兴传播渠道相对。</u>\n\n---\n\nPaid and <font color=\"#ffff00\">owned media</font> are controlled by marketers promoting their own products.\n翻译: <u>付费媒体和自有媒体由营销人员控制，用来推广他们自己的产品。</u>\n\n-**Owned media（<u>自有媒体）**：指企业自己拥有的渠道（如官方网站、品牌博客、官方微信公众号）。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nFor earned media, such marketers act as the initiator for users’ responses.\n翻译: <u>对于赢得媒体而言，这些营销人员充当用户反应的发起者。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut in some cases, one marketer’s owned media become another marketer’s paid media – for instance, when an e-commerce retailer sells ad space on its Web site.\n翻译: <u>但在某些情况下，一个营销者的自有媒体会变成另一个营销者的付费媒体——例如，当一家电子商务零售商出售其网站上的广告空间时。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe define such sold media as owned media <font color=\"#ffff00\">whose traffic </font>is so strong that other organizations place their content or <font color=\"#ffff00\">e-commerce engines</font> within that environment.\n翻译: <u>我们将这种出售型媒体定义为一种自有媒体，其流量强大到其他组织会把自己的内容或电子商务引擎置于这一环境之中。</u>\n\n-**Whose traffic**：<u>指代“媒体的流量”。这里“流量”是自有媒体能够转变为“售出媒体”的资本。</u>\n-**E-commerce engines**：<u>电商引擎（如购物插件、支付接口、小程序商城）。这意味着这已经不仅仅是做广告，而是直接把销售终端搬进了别人的地盘。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis trend, which we believe is still<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in its infancy,</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">effectively</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">began with</font> retailers and travel providers such as airlines and hotels and will no doubt go further.\n翻译: <u>我们认为这一趋势仍处于初期阶段，它实际上始于零售商和航空公司、酒店等旅游服务提供商，并且无疑还会进一步发展。</u>\n\n-**in its infancy**：<u>处于婴儿期，意为“处于起步/初期阶段”。</u>\n-**effectively**：<u>实际上、事实上。</u>\n-**began with**：<u>从……开始。</u>\n\n---\n\nJohnson & Johnson, for example, has created BabyCenter, a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> stand-alone </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">media property</font> that promotes complementary and <font color=\"#ffff00\">even competitive products.</font>\n翻译: <u>例如，Johnson & Johnson创建了BabyCenter，这是一个独立的媒体资产，用来推广互补性产品，甚至是竞争性产品。</u>\n\n-**stand-alone**：<u>独立的、自成一体的。</u>\n-**media property**：<u>媒体资产/平台。</u>\n-**complementary and even competitive**：<u>互补的甚至竞争的（非常硬核的商业逻辑：不仅卖自己的东西，连竞品也可以在上面做广告）。</u>\n\n---\n\nBesides generating income, the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> presence</font> of other marketers makes the site seem objective, gives companies opportunities to learn valuable information about the <font color=\"#ffff00\">appeal </font>of other companies’ marketing, and may help expand user traffic for all companies <font color=\"#ffff00\">concerned</font>.\n翻译: <u>除了创造收入之外，其他营销者的存在会使该网站显得客观，给公司提供机会去了解其他公司营销吸引力方面的有价值信息，并可能帮助所有相关公司扩大用户流量。</u>\n\n-**Presence**：<u>指在场、存在。在营销语境下，它指的是允许同行在自己的平台上投放广告或展示内容。这是一个“开放”的动作。</u>\n-**Appeal**：<u>吸引力、卖点。</u>\n-**Concerned**：<u>后置定语，修饰 companies，意为“相关的”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The same</font> dramatic technological changes<font color=\"#ffff00\"> that</font> have provided marketers with more (and more diverse) communications choices have also increased the risk that passionate consumers will voice their opinions in quicker, more visible, and much more damaging ways.\n翻译: <u>那些为营销者提供了更多且更多样化传播选择的同样剧烈的技术变革，也增加了这样一种风险：充满热情的消费者会以更快、更显眼且破坏性大得多的方式表达他们的意见。</u>\n\n-**The same... that...**：<u>在这里意思是“正是这些……”，暗示技术变革是导致后续两种截然不同后果的共同根源。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nSuch hijacked media are the opposite of earned media: an asset or campaign <font color=\"#ffff00\">becomes hostage to</font> consumers, other stakeholders, or activists who make <font color=\"#ffff00\">negative allegations</font> about a brand or product.\n翻译: <u>这种被劫持的媒体是赢得媒体的反面：一项资产或一场活动会被消费者、其他利益相关者或活动人士所挟持，他们对某个品牌或产品提出负面指控。</u>\n\n-**Negative allegations**：<u>负面指控/断言。这是劫持发生的技术手段——通过发布负面信息来占据舆论高地，让大众误以为品牌有问题，从而“绑架”了品牌的公共声誉。</u>\n-<u>原本由品牌掌控的资产或营销活动，沦为了他人发泄不满的“人质”,人质就是这玩意儿在我手上,我随便怎么宰割,逼出你让利</u>\n\n---\n\nMembers of social networks, for instance, are learning that they can hijack media to apply pressure on the businesses that originally created them.\n翻译: <u>例如，社交网络成员正逐渐认识到，他们可以劫持媒体，对最初创建这些媒体的企业施加压力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIf that happens, passionate consumers would try to persuade others to boycott products, putting the reputation of the target company at risk.\n翻译: <u>如果这种情况发生，充满热情的消费者会试图说服其他人抵制产品，从而使目标公司的声誉面临风险。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn such a case, the company’s response may not be <font color=\"#ffff00\">sufficiently quick</font> or <font color=\"#ffff00\">thoughtful</font>, and the <font color=\"#ffff00\">learning curve</font> has been steep.\n翻译: <u>在这种情况下，公司的回应可能不够迅速或周全，而学习曲线一直很陡峭。</u>\n\n-- `sufficiently`：<u>修饰 `quick` 和 `thoughtful`，意为“足够地”。</u>\n    \n- `thoughtful`：<u>在此语境下不是指“体贴”，而是指“深思熟虑的”、“考虑周全的”。这是商业公关中非常重要的概念，指回应不仅要快，还要得体。</u>\n\n-<u>这是一句商业习语。`Learning curve`（学习曲线）描述从新手到专家的过程。</u>\n\n---\n\nToyota Motor, for example, alleviated some of the damage from its recall crisis earlier this year with a relatively quick and <font color=\"#ffff00\">well-orchestrated</font> social-media response campaign, which included efforts to engage with consumers directly on sites such as Twitter and the social-news site Digg.\n翻译: <u>例如，Toyota Motor在今年早些时候的召回危机中，通过一场相对迅速且组织良好的社交媒体回应活动，减轻了部分损害；该活动包括努力在Twitter和社交新闻网站Digg等网站上直接与消费者互动。</u>\n\n-`well-orchestrated`：<u>精心策划的/编排好的。形容组织工作做得非常到位，各部分协调一致。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n第四篇阅读\n\nIt’s no surprise that Jennifer Senior’s insightful, <font color=\"#ffff00\">provocative</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">magazine cover story</font>, “I love My Children, I Hate My Life, ” is arousing much chatter –<font color=\"#ffff00\"> nothing gets people talking like</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">suggestion</font> that child rearing is <font color=\"#ffff00\">anything less than</font> a completely fulfilling, life-enriching experience.\n翻译: <u>Jennifer Senior 那篇见解深刻、带有挑衅意味的杂志封面文章《I love My Children, I Hate My Life》引发大量议论，这并不令人意外；没有什么比“养育孩子并非完全令人满足、丰富人生的经历”这种说法更能让人们打开话匣子了。</u>\n\n-**provocative**: <u>煽动性的，引发争论的（常用来形容文章观点犀利）。</u>\n-**magazine cover story**: <u>杂志封面文章（通常指杂志的主打深度稿件）。</u>\n-<u>用否定表达最高级逻辑（Nothing... like... 表示“没有什么是比……更能……”）。没什么比……更能让人议论纷纷了。</u>\n-**suggestion:** <u>在此处译为“观点”、“暗示”或“说法”。</u>\n-**anything less than:** <u>一个非常重要的考研英语高频短语，意为“绝非”、“完全不是”（隐含了否定意味，即如果程度低于“完全满足”，那就是不好的）。</u>\n\n---\n\nRather than concluding that children make parents either happy or miserable, Senior suggests we need to redefine happiness: instead of thinking of it as something that can be measured by <font color=\"#ffff00\">moment-to-moment</font> joy, we should consider being happy as a <font color=\"#ffff00\">past-tense</font> condition.\n翻译: <u>Senior 并没有得出“孩子让父母要么快乐、要么痛苦”的结论，而是提出我们需要重新定义幸福：不要把它看作一种可以用每时每刻的快乐来衡量的东西，而应把幸福视为一种过去时的状态。</u>\n\n-**moment-to-moment joy:** <u>指瞬时的、即时的愉悦感（比如孩子笑了、孩子可爱的时候）。作者认为这就是大众通常对幸福的肤浅理解。</u>\n-**past-tense condition:** <u>这是全文的核心概念。作者认为幸福不是某种即时的、当下的感觉，而是一种当你回首往事时，对过去生活的一种整体性评价和感知。</u>\n\n---\n\nEven though the day-to-day experience of raising kids can be soul-crushingly hard, Senior writes that “<font color=\"#ffff00\">the very things</font> that<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in the moment</font> dampen our moods can later be sources of intense gratification and delight.”\n翻译: <u>Senior 写道，尽管养育孩子的日常经历可能艰难到令人心力交瘁，但“那些在当下压低我们情绪的事情，日后却可能成为强烈满足感和喜悦的来源”。</u>\n\n-- **the very things:** `very` <u>在此处用作强调，意为“恰恰是/正是这些事情”。</u>\n-**in the moment:** <u>这是一个关键的时间状语，强调“当下、身处其境的时候”</u>\n\n---\n\nThe magazine cover showing an attractive mother holding a cute baby <font color=\"#ffff00\">is hardly</font> the only Madonna-and-child image <font color=\"#ffff00\">on newsstands</font> this week.\n翻译: <u>杂志封面上那位有魅力的母亲抱着可爱婴儿的画面，绝不是本周报摊上唯一的圣母子形象。</u>\n\n-is hardly <u>绝非 / 根本不是。</u> \n-`on newsstands` (<u>在报刊亭)</u>\n\n---\n\nThere are also stories about newly adoptive – and newly single – mom Sandra Bullock, as well as the usual “Jennifer Aniston is pregnant” news.\n翻译: <u>还有关于刚刚成为养母、也刚刚恢复单身的 Sandra Bullock 的报道，以及一贯的“Jennifer Aniston 怀孕了”新闻。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Practically</font> every week <font color=\"#ffff00\">features</font> at least one celebrity mom, or mom-to-be, smiling on the newsstands.\n翻译: <u>几乎每一周，报摊上都会至少出现一位笑容满面的明星妈妈或准妈妈。</u>\n\n-**Practically:** <u>意为“几乎”、“实际上”，强调频率非常高。</u>\n-`Feature` <u>在这里是杂志或媒体语境下的常用词，意为“（重点）刊登、展示、报道”。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn a society that so persistently celebrates procreation, <font color=\"#ffff00\">is it any wonder that</font> admitting you regret having children is equivalent to admitting you support kitten-killing?\n翻译: <u>在一个如此持续不断地赞美生育的社会里，承认自己后悔生了孩子等同于承认自己支持杀小猫，这有什么可奇怪的吗？</u>\n\n-`is it any wonder...` <u>这是一个典型的反问句式 ……这难道还值得奇怪吗？（言下之意：这完全不奇怪。）</u>\n-<u>在一个如此执着地歌颂生育的社会里，承认你后悔生了孩子，这难道不就等同于承认你支持虐杀幼猫吗？（这有什么值得大惊小怪的呢？）</u>\n\n---\n\nIt doesn’t seem quite fair, <font color=\"#ffff00\">then</font>, to compare the regrets of parents to the regrets of the childless.\n翻译: <u>那么，把父母的遗憾同无子女者的遗憾相比，似乎就不太公平了。</u>\n\n-then <u>放在句子中间表示  那么</u>\n-<u>作者之所以说“不公平”，是因为父母因表达后悔而面临巨大的社会压力，而无子女者则不存在这种社会性惩罚，因此两者的“遗憾”在社会语境下是不具备可比性的。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnhappy parents rarely are <font color=\"#ffff00\">provoked to wonder</font> if they shouldn’t have had kids, but unhappy childless folks are bothered with the message that children are the single most important thing in the world: <font color=\"#ffff00\">obviously their misery must be a direct result of the gaping baby-size holes in their lives.</font>\n翻译: <u>不快乐的父母很少会被促使去想自己是否本不该要孩子；但不快乐的无子女者却总被这样一种信息困扰：孩子是世界上唯一最重要的东西；显然，他们的不幸一定是生活中那些婴儿大小的巨大空洞直接造成的。</u>\n\n-**provoked to wonder:** <u>被挑衅/激起去思考。暗示这种“怀疑自己生孩子是否正确”的想法通常不是父母自发的，而是受外部压力（provoked）产生的。</u>\n-obviously <u>这句在阴阳怪气</u>\n\n---\n\nOf course, the image of parenthood that celebrity magazines like Us Weekly and People present is hugely unrealistic, especially when the parents are single mothers like Bullock.\n翻译: <u>当然，像 Us Weekly 和 People 这样的明星杂志所呈现的为人父母形象极其不现实，尤其当这些父母是像 Bullock 这样的单身母亲时。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nAccording to several studies concluding that parents are less happy than childless couples, single parents are the least happy of all.\n翻译: <u>根据几项得出“有孩子的父母不如无子女夫妇快乐”这一结论的研究，单亲父母是所有人中最不快乐的。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nNo shock there, considering how much work it is to raise a kid without a partner to lean on; <font color=\"#ffff00\">yet</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">to hear</font> Sandra and Britney <font color=\"#ffff00\">tell it</font>, raising a kid on their “own” (read: with <font color=\"#ffff00\">round-the-clock</font> help) is a piece of cake.\n翻译: <u>这并不令人震惊，考虑到没有伴侣可以依靠而独自抚养孩子需要付出多少劳动；然而听 Sandra 和 Britney 的说法，靠她们“自己”（即：有全天候帮助）养孩子简直是小菜一碟。</u>\n\n-`yet` <u>表示转折，`to hear... tell it` 是一个习惯用语结构，表示“按照……的说法”。</u>\n-round-the-clock <u>全天候</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s hard to imagine that many people are dumb enough to want children just because Reese and Angelina make it look so glamorous: most adults understand that a baby is not a haircut.\n翻译: <u>很难想象会有很多人蠢到只是因为 Reese 和 Angelina 把有孩子这件事表现得如此光鲜就想要孩子：大多数成年人都明白，婴儿可不是一次发型。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nBut it’s interesting to <font color=\"#ffff00\">wonder if</font> the images we see every week of stress-free, happiness-enhancing parenthood<font color=\"#ffff00\"> aren’t </font>in some small,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> subconscious way</font> contributing to our own dissatisfactions with the actual experience, in the same way that a small part of us hoped getting “the Rachel” might make us look just a little bit like Jennifer Aniston.\n翻译: <u>但有趣的是，我们不妨想想：我们每周看到的那些毫无压力、提升幸福感的为人父母形象，是否在某种细微的、潜意识的层面上加剧了我们对真实体验的不满，就像我们内心有一小部分曾希望剪个“Rachel”发型也许能让自己看起来有那么一点像 Jennifer Aniston 一样。</u>\n\n-**subconscious way:** <u>潜意识层面。说明这种影响是隐蔽的，我们往往意识不到自己被这种“完美叙事”洗脑了。</u>\n-1<u>暗示作者的“倾向性”</u>\n\n<u>当你使用肯定形式 `wonder if they are...` 时，语气通常是**中立的**，表示你真的不知道答案，处于纯粹的好奇状态。</u>\n\n<u>但当作者使用否定形式 `wonder if they aren't...` 时，作者其实**心里已经有了答案**，甚至已经认定“它们确实在产生负面影响”。</u>\n\n\n\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2012","year":"2012","title":"2012 年英语一","fileName":"2012 年英语一.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2012 年英语一.md","content":"Come on – Everybody’s doing it.  \n翻译: <u>来吧，大家都这么做。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThat whispered message, half invitation and half forcing, is what most of us think of when we hear the words peer pressure.  \n翻译: <u>这种低声传来的信息，一半是邀请，一半是逼迫，就是我们大多数人在听到“同伴压力”这个词时想到的东西。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nIt usually leads to no good – drinking, drugs and casual sex.  \n翻译: <u>它通常不会带来什么好事：饮酒、吸毒和随意性行为。</u>\n\n-casual sex <u>随意性行为</u>\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nBut in her new book <font color=\"#00b050\">Join the Club</font>, Tina Rosenberg <font color=\"#00b050\">contends</font> that peer pressure can also be a positive force through what she calls the social cure, in which <font color=\"#00b050\">organizations and officials</font> use the power of group dynamics to help individuals improve their lives and possibly the world.  \n翻译: <u>但 Tina Rosenberg 在她的新书《Join the Club》中主张，同伴压力也可以通过她所谓的“社会疗法”成为一种积极力量；在这种方式中，组织和官员利用群体动力的力量来帮助个人改善生活，并且可能改善世界。</u>\n\n-**Join the Club** <u>是书名。</u> \n-**contend** <u>比 **say** 更正式，表示“提出观点、主张、论证”。</u> \n-**organizations and officials**：<u>组织和官员。</u> \n-\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nRosenberg, the<font color=\"#00b050\"> recipient</font> of a Pulitzer Prize, offers <font color=\"#00b050\">a host of</font> examples of the social cure <font color=\"#00b050\">in action</font>: In <font color=\"#00b050\">South Carolina</font>, a state-sponsored antismoking program called Rage Against the Haze <font color=\"#00b050\">sets out to</font> make cigarettes uncool.  \n翻译: <u>普利策奖得主 Rosenberg 提供了大量社会疗法实际运作的例子：在南卡罗来纳州，一个由州政府资助、名为 Rage Against the Haze 的反吸烟项目，旨在让香烟变得不酷。</u>\n\n-**recipient** <u>指“获得者”。</u>  \n-**a host of** <u>表示“大量、许多”。</u>  \n-**in action** <u>表示“在实际运作中、付诸实践时”。</u>  \n-south carolina <u>南卡罗来纳州</u>\n-**set out to do** <u>表示“开始着手做、旨在做”。</u>  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nIn South Africa, an HIV-prevention <font color=\"#00b050\">initiative</font> known as loveLife recruits young people to promote safe sex among their <font color=\"#00b050\">peers</font>.  \n翻译: <u>在南非，一项名为 loveLife 的 HIV 预防计划招募年轻人在同龄人中推广安全性行为。</u>\n\n-**initiative**：<u>倡议、项目、行动计划。</u>\n-**among their peers**：<u>在他们的同伴之间。</u>  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThe idea seems promising, and Rosenberg is a <font color=\"#00b050\">perceptive</font> observer.  \n翻译: <u>这个想法似乎很有前景，而 Rosenberg 也是一位敏锐的观察者。</u>\n\n-**perceptive** <u>表示“有洞察力的、敏锐的”。</u>  \n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nHer critique of the lameness of many public-health campaigns is <font color=\"#00b050\">spot-on</font>: they fail to <font color=\"#00b050\">mobilize</font> peer pressure for healthy habits, and they demonstrate a seriously flawed understanding of psychology.  \n翻译: <u>她对许多公共卫生宣传活动乏力无效的批评非常到位：它们未能调动同伴压力来促进健康习惯，而且显示出对心理学存在严重缺陷的理解。</u>\n\n-**spot-on** <u>是口语化表达，意思是“完全正确、非常精准”。</u>  \n-**mobilize**：<u>调动、动员。</u>\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\n“Dare to be different, please don’t smoke!” <font color=\"#00b050\">pleads</font> one billboard campaign aimed at reducing smoking among teenagers – teenagers, who desire nothing more than fitting in.  \n翻译: <u>“请勇于与众不同，不要吸烟！”一项旨在减少青少年吸烟的广告牌宣传这样恳求道；而青少年最渴望的，恰恰就是融入群体。</u>\n\n-<u>引语在前，谓语 **pleads** + 主语 **one billboard campaign** 在后。</u>\n-**plead** <u>表示“恳求、请求”。</u>  \n<u>这里用 **pleads** 带有讽刺感，因为广告牌当然不会真的“恳求”，这是拟人化表达。</u>  \n<u>作者暗示这个宣传口号显得软弱、幼稚。</u>\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nRosenberg argues <font color=\"#00b050\">convincingly</font> that public-health advocates <font color=\"#00b050\">ought to</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">take a page from</font> advertisers<font color=\"#00b050\">, </font>so skilled at applying peer pressure.  \n翻译: <u>Rosenberg 很有说服力地指出，公共卫生倡导者应当借鉴广告商的做法，因为广告商非常擅长运用同伴压力。</u>\n()\n-**convincingly** <u>表示“令人信服地”。</u>\n-**ought to**：<u>应该。</u>  \n-**take a page from…** <u>是习语，意思是“借鉴……的做法、向……学习”。</u>\n  -advertisers <u>后面的修饰 **advertisers**。 逗号很重要。逗号表示后面的内容是**补充说明**，不是必要限定。省略了 who are</u>\n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nBut on the <font color=\"#00b050\">general effectiveness</font> of the social cure, Rosenberg is less persuasive.  \n翻译: <u>但在社会疗法的总体有效性问题上，Rosenberg 的说服力就没那么强了。</u>\n-**general effectiveness**：<u>总体有效性。</u> \n-\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nJoin the Club is filled with too much irrelevant detail and not enough exploration of the social and biological factors that make peer pressure so powerful.  \n翻译: <u>《Join the Club》中充斥着太多无关细节，而对使同伴压力如此强大的社会因素和生物因素探讨不足。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThe most<font color=\"#00b050\"> glaring</font> flaw of the social cure <font color=\"#00b050\">as it’s presented here</font> is that it doesn’t work very well for very long.  \n翻译: <u>这里所呈现的社会疗法最明显的缺陷是：它并不能很好地、长期地发挥作用。</u>\n-**glaring**：<u>明显的、刺眼的。</u>  \n-**as it’s presented here**：<u>如本书中所呈现的那样。</u>  \n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nRage Against the Haze failed once state funding was cut.  \n翻译: <u>一旦州政府资金被削减，Rage Against the Haze 就失败了。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nEvidence that the loveLife program produces lasting changes is limited and <font color=\"#00b050\">mixed</font>.  \n翻译: <u>证明 loveLife 项目能产生持久改变的证据有限且结果不一。</u>\n\n-**mixed**：<u>混杂的、不一致的、有正有负的。</u> \n-<u>关于 loveLife 项目能够产生持久变化的证据是有限且混杂的。</u>\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThere’s no doubt that our peer groups <font color=\"#00b050\">exert </font>enormous <font color=\"#00b050\">influence on</font> our behavior.  \n翻译: <u>毫无疑问，我们的同伴群体对我们的行为有巨大影响。</u>\n-**exert influence on…**：<u>对……施加影响。</u>  \n-<u>同伴群体当然会强烈影响我们的行为，这一点没有疑问。</u>\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nAn <font color=\"#00b050\">emerging</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">body of research</font> shows that positive health habits – <font color=\"#00b050\">as well as </font>negative ones – spread through networks of friends via social communication.  \n翻译: <u>一批新兴研究表明，积极的健康习惯以及消极的健康习惯，都会通过社会交往在朋友网络中传播。</u>\n\n-**emerging**：<u>正在出现的、新兴的。</u>\n-a body of research**：<u>一批研究、一个研究领域的文献。</u>  \n-**as well as**：<u>以及、也包括。</u>\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThis is a subtle form of peer pressure: we unconsciously imitate the behavior we see every day.  \n翻译: <u>这是一种微妙形式的同伴压力：我们会无意识地模仿每天看到的行为。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Far less certain</font>, however, is <font color=\"#00b050\">how</font> successfully <font color=\"#00b050\">experts and bureaucrats</font> can select our peer groups and steer their activities in <font color=\"#00b050\">virtuous directions</font>.  \n翻译: <u>然而，专家和官僚能够在多大程度上成功地选择我们的同伴群体，并把他们的活动引向有益的方向，这一点远没有那么确定。</u>\n\n-Far less certain \n<u>然而，远不那么确定的是。</u>\n-**experts and bureaucrats**：<u>专家和官僚。</u>  \n-**virtuous directions**：<u>良善的方向、道德上积极的方向。</u>  \n-how <u>指的是 后面的事情 能做到什么程度.how 都是这样用的</u>\n⸻\n\n  \n\nIt’s like the teacher who <font color=\"#00b050\">breaks up</font> the troublemakers in the back row by <font color=\"#00b050\">pairing</font> them with better-behaved classmates.  \n翻译: <u>这就像老师把后排捣乱的学生拆开，让他们和表现更好的同学搭档。</u>\n\n-**break up**：<u>拆散、分开</u>\n-**pair A with B**：<u>把 A 和 B 配对。</u>  \n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nThe tactic never really works.  \n翻译: <u>这种策略从来并不真正奏效。</u>\n()\n\n  \n\n⸻\n\n  \n\nAnd that’s the problem with a social cure engineered from the outside: in the real world, as in school, we insist on choosing our own friends.  \n翻译: <u>这正是从外部设计出来的社会疗法的问题所在：在现实世界里，就像在学校里一样，我们坚持要自己选择朋友。</u>\n()\n\n#### 第二篇阅读\n\nA deal is a deal – except, apparently, when Entergy is involved.  \n翻译: <u>协议就是协议，除非，显然，牵涉到 Entergy。</u>\n-<u>说好了就该算数。可一旦牵涉到 Entergy，事情似乎就另当别论了。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe company, a major energy supplier in New England, provoked <font color=\"#00b050\">justified outrage</font> in Vermont last week when it announced it was<font color=\"#00b050\"> reneging on</font> a <font color=\"#00b050\">longstanding commitment</font> to abide by the state’s strict nuclear regulations.  \n翻译: <u>这家公司是新英格兰地区的一家主要能源供应商；上周它宣布将背弃一项长期承诺，不再遵守 Vermont 州严格的核能法规，此举在 Vermont 激起了理所当然的愤怒。</u>\n\n-**justified outrage**：<u>有正当理由的愤怒。</u> \n-**renege on**：<u>违背、背弃、食言。</u> \n-**a longstanding commitment**：<u>一项长期承诺。</u>\n-Entergy <u>是新英格兰地区的重要能源供应商。上周，它宣布不再履行长期以来遵守佛蒙特州严格核监管规定的承诺，由此在当地引发了理所当然的愤怒。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Instead</font>, the company has done <font color=\"#00b050\">precisely</font> what it had long promised it would not: challenge the <font color=\"#00b050\">constitutionality </font>of Vermont’s rules in the federal court, as part of a <font color=\"#00b050\">desperate effort</font> to keep its Vermont Yankee nuclear power plant running.  \n翻译: <u>相反，该公司做了它长期以来明确承诺不会做的事：作为竭力维持其 Vermont Yankee 核电站运行的一部分，它在联邦法院挑战 Vermont 州相关规定的合宪性。</u>\n-<u>相反 / 可结果却是。</u>\n-**precisely**：<u>正是、恰恰。</u>\n-<u>这里的 **would not** 后面省略了 **do**。</u>\n-**constitutionality**：<u>合宪性</u>\n-**desperate effort**：<u>拼命的努力、孤注一掷的努力。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt’s a stunning move.  \n翻译: <u>这是一个令人震惊的举动。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nThe conflict has <font color=\"#00b050\">been surfacing </font>since 2002, when the corporation bought Vermont’s only nuclear power plant, an <font color=\"#00b050\">aging</font> reactor in Vernon.  \n翻译: <u>这场冲突自 2002 年以来就一直在浮现，当时该公司收购了 Vermont 州唯一的核电站，一座位于 Vernon 的老旧反应堆。</u>\n\n-**has been surfacing**：<u>一直在浮现、逐渐显露。</u>  \n-**aging**：<u>老化的、老旧的。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">As a condition</font> of receiving state approval for the sale, the company agreed to seek permission from <font color=\"#00b050\">state regulators</font> to operate past 2012.  \n翻译: <u>作为获得州政府批准这笔出售交易的条件，该公司同意，如果要在 2012 年之后继续运营，须向州监管机构申请许可。</u>\n\n-**As + <u>名词短语** 作状语，表示“作为……的条件”。</u>\n-**state regulators**：<u>州监管机构。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nIn 2006, the state went a step further, requiring that <font color=\"#00b050\">any extension</font> of the plant’s license be subject to the Vermont legislature’s approval.  \n翻译: <u>2006 年，该州又进一步规定，该电站许可证的任何延长都必须经 Vermont 州议会批准。</u>\n\n-**any extension**：<u>任何延期。</u>\n-<u>到 2006 年，佛蒙特州又加强了一步监管：核电站许可证如果要延期，必须经过州议会批准。</u>\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Then, too</font>, the company <font color=\"#00b050\">went along</font>.  \n翻译: <u>当时，该公司也接受了。</u>\n-**go along**：<u>同意、配合、顺从。</u>\n-**Then**：<u>当时、那时。</u>  \n**too**：<u>也。   表示那个时候也同意了</u>\n\n---\n\nEither Entergy never really intended to<font color=\"#00b050\"> live by</font> those commitments, or it simply didn’t foresee what would happen next.  \n翻译: <u>要么 Entergy 从未真正打算遵守那些承诺，要么它只是没有预见到接下来会发生什么。</u>\n\n-**live by**：<u>遵守、按照……行事。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA string of accidents, including the partial collapse of a cooling tower in 2007 and the discovery of an underground pipe system leakage, <font color=\"#00b050\">raised serious questions</font> about both Vermont Yankee’s safety and Entergy’s management – especially after the company made <font color=\"#00b050\">misleading statements</font> about the pipe.  \n翻译: <u>一连串事故，包括 2007 年冷却塔部分坍塌以及地下管道系统泄漏被发现，使人们对 Vermont Yankee 的安全性和 Entergy 的管理都提出了严重质疑，尤其是在该公司就管道问题作出误导性陈述之后。</u>\n\n-**raise questions about**：<u>引发对……的质疑。</u>  \n-**both A and B**：<u>既……又……。   翻译的时候可以这样写</u>\n-**misleading statements**：<u>误导性陈述。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nEnraged by Entergy’s behavior, the Vermont Senate voted 26 to 4 last year against allowing an extension.  \n翻译: <u>Vermont 州参议院对 Entergy 的行为感到愤怒，去年以 26 票对 4 票否决了允许延期的提案。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nNow the company is suddenly claiming that the 2002 agreement is invalid because of the 2006 legislation, and that only the federal government has regulatory power over nuclear issues.  \n翻译: <u>现在，该公司突然声称，2002 年的协议因 2006 年的立法而无效，并且只有联邦政府对核问题拥有监管权。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nThe legal issues in the case are obscure: <font color=\"#00b050\">whereas</font> the <font color=\"#00b050\">Supreme Court</font> has ruled that states do have some regulatory authority over nuclear power, legal scholars say that Vermont case will offer a <font color=\"#00b050\">precedent-setting</font> test of how far those powers extend.  \n翻译: <u>此案中的法律问题晦涩复杂：尽管最高法院已经裁定各州确实对核电拥有某些监管权限，但法律学者表示，Vermont 案将提供一个确立先例的检验，以判断这些权力究竟能延伸多远。</u>\n-**whereas** <u>在这里表示“虽然、尽管、而”。**the Supreme Court**：最高法院。</u> \n-**precedent-setting**：<u>开创先例的、具有先例意义的。</u>  \n-<u>这个案件中的法律问题很晦涩：虽然最高法院已经裁定各州确实对核能拥有某些监管权，但法律学者说，佛蒙特案件将提供一个具有先例意义的测试，以检验这些权力到底延伸多远。</u>\n\n---\n\nCertainly, there are <font color=\"#00b050\">valid concerns</font> about the patchwork regulations that could result if every state sets its own rules.  \n翻译: <u>当然，如果每个州都制定自己的规则，可能产生拼凑式监管；对此存在合理担忧。</u>\n-**valid concerns**：<u>合理的担忧。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut had Entergy kept its word, that debate would be <font color=\"#00b050\">beside the point</font>.  \n翻译: <u>但如果 Entergy 信守承诺，那场争论就无关紧要了。</u>\n-**beside the point**：<u>不切题、无关紧要。</u>  \n-<u>这是 **省略 if 的倒装虚拟条件句** 看到句首是 had ➕ 主语➕过去分词,大概率就是倒装虚拟条件句,这个的正常语序是 if Entergy had kept its word</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe company <font color=\"#00b050\">seems to have concluded</font> that its reputation in Vermont is already so damaged that it has nothing left to lose by going to war with the state.  \n翻译: <u>该公司似乎已经认定，它在 Vermont 的声誉已经受损到如此程度，以至于同该州开战也没有什么可失去的了。</u>\n-**seems to have concluded**：<u>似乎已经认定/得出结论。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBut there should be consequences.  \n翻译: <u>但这应当产生后果。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nPermission to run a nuclear plant is a public trust.  \n翻译: <u>经营核电站的许可是一种公共信托。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nEntergy runs 11 other reactors in the United States, including Pilgrim Nuclear station in Plymouth.  \n翻译: <u>Entergy 在美国还运营着另外 11 座反应堆，其中包括位于 Plymouth 的 Pilgrim 核电站。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Pledging</font> to run Pilgrim safely, the company <font color=\"#00b050\">has applied for</font> federal permission to keep it open for another 20 years.  \n翻译: <u>该公司承诺安全运营 Pilgrim，并已向联邦政府申请许可，希望让其再运行 20 年。</u>\n-**pledging**：<u>承诺、保证。</u>  \n-**has applied for**：<u>已经申请</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBut as the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) <font color=\"#00b050\">reviews</font> the company’s application, it should keep in mind what promises from Entergy are worth.  \n翻译: <u>但是，当核管理委员会（NRC）审查该公司的申请时，它应当牢记 Entergy 的承诺究竟值什么。</u>\n-**reviews**：<u>审查。</u>  \n-**are worth**：<u>值多少、价值如何。</u>  \n\n\n第三篇阅读\n\n\nIn the idealized version of how science is done, facts about the world are waiting to be observed and collected by objective researchers who use the scientific method to carry out their work.  \n翻译: <u>在关于科学如何开展的理想化版本中，有关世界的事实正等待着客观研究者去观察和收集，而这些研究者使用科学方法来开展工作。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nBut in the everyday practice of science, discovery frequently follows an ambiguous and complicated route.  \n翻译: <u>但在科学的日常实践中，发现常常沿着一条含糊而复杂的路径展开。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nWe <font color=\"#00b050\">aim to</font> be objective, but we cannot escape the context of our unique life experiences.  \n翻译: <u>我们的目标是保持客观，但我们无法逃离自身独特生活经历所构成的背景。</u>\n\n-**aim to do**：<u>旨在做某事，努力做到某事。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nPrior knowledge and <font color=\"#00b050\">interests</font> influence what we experience, what we think our experiences mean, and the <font color=\"#00b050\">subsequent</font> actions we take.  \n翻译: <u>先前的知识和兴趣会影响我们经历什么、我们认为自己的经历意味着什么，以及我们随后采取的行动。</u>\n\n-**interests**：<u>兴趣、关注点。</u>  \n-**subsequent**：<u>随后的、后续的。</u>  \n\n\n\n---\n\nOpportunities for <font color=\"#00b050\">misinterpretation</font>, error, and <font color=\"#00b050\">self-deception</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">abound</font>.  \n翻译: <u>误解、错误和自我欺骗的机会比比皆是。</u>\n\n-**misinterpretation**：<u>误解、错误解读。</u>  \n-**self-deception**：<u>自我欺骗。</u>  \n-**abound**：<u>大量存在、充满。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nConsequently, <font color=\"#00b050\">discovery claims</font> should be thought of as <font color=\"#00b050\">protoscience</font>.  \n翻译: <u>因此，发现声明应当被看作原科学。</u>\n\n-discovery claims <u>发现声明 / 关于发现的主张。这里的 discovery 是形容词</u>\n-**protoscience**：<u>原科学、前科学。</u>  \n这里意思是：<u>发现声明只是科学知识形成的早期阶段，还需要进一步检验。</u>  \n\n\n\n---\n\nSimilar to <font color=\"#00b050\">newly staked</font> mining claims, they are full of potential.  \n翻译: <u>类似于新圈定的采矿权主张，它们充满潜力。</u>\n\n-**newly staked**：<u>新近圈定的、刚刚标定的。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBut it takes <font color=\"#00b050\">collective scrutiny</font> and acceptance to transform a discovery claim into a mature discovery.  \n翻译: <u>但要把一项发现声明转变为成熟的发现，需要集体的审查和认可。</u>\n\n-**collective scrutiny**：<u>集体审查、共同体的仔细审视。</u> \n\n\n---\n\nThis is the <font color=\"#00b050\">credibility process</font>, through which the individual researcher’s me, here, now becomes the community’s anyone, anywhere, anytime.  \n翻译: <u>这就是可信度过程；通过这一过程，个体研究者的“我、此地、此刻”变成了科学共同体的“任何人、任何地方、任何时候”。</u>\n\n-**credibility process**：<u>可信度过程，即科学主张变得可信的过程。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nObjective knowledge is the goal, not the <font color=\"#00b050\">starting point</font>.  \n翻译: <u>客观知识是目标，而不是起点。</u>\n\n-**starting point**：<u>起点。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOnce a discovery claim becomes public, the discoverer receives <font color=\"#00b050\">intellectual credit</font>.  \n翻译: <u>一旦发现声明公开，发现者就会获得智识上的荣誉。</u>\n-**receives intellectual credit**：<u>获得智识功劳、学术 credit。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nBut, unlike with mining claims, the community takes control of what happens next.  \n翻译: <u>但是，与采矿权主张不同，科学共同体会接管接下来发生的事情。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nWithin the complex social structure of the scientific community, researchers make discoveries; editors and reviewers act as gatekeepers by controlling the publication process; other scientists use the new finding to <font color=\"#00b050\">suit </font>their own purposes; and finally, the public (including other scientists) receives the new discovery and <font color=\"#00b050\">possibly accompanying technology</font>.  \n翻译: <u>在科学共同体复杂的社会结构中，研究人员作出发现；编辑和评审者通过控制发表过程来充当守门人；其他科学家利用新的发现来服务于自己的目的；最后，公众（包括其他科学家）接收这项新发现以及可能随之而来的技术。</u>\n-**to suit their own purposes**：<u>以符合他们自己的目的。</u>  \n-**possibly accompanying technology**：<u>可能伴随出现的技术。</u>  \n-<u>科学发现是在一个复杂共同体中流动的：研究者提出发现，编辑和审稿人决定它能否发表，其他科学家根据自己的研究需要使用它，最终公众和科学界更广泛成员接收这一发现及其可能带来的技术。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">As</font> a discovery claim <font color=\"#00b050\">works its way through</font> the community, the interaction and confrontation between <font color=\"#00b050\">shared</font> and <font color=\"#00b050\">competing beliefs</font> about the science and the technology involved transforms an individual’s discovery claim into the community’s credible discovery.  \n翻译: <u>当一项发现声明在共同体中逐步推进时，围绕相关科学和技术的共享信念与竞争性信念之间的互动和交锋，会把个人的发现声明转化为共同体可信的发现。</u>\n-As** <u>在这里表示“随着 / 当……过程中”。</u>  \n-**work its way through**：<u>逐步通过、艰难推进。</u>  \n-**shared beliefs**：<u>共同信念。</u>\n-**competing beliefs**：<u>竞争性信念、相互冲突的看法。</u>  \n\n---\n\nTwo paradoxes exist throughout this credibility process.  \n翻译: <u>在整个可信度过程中存在两个悖论。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nFirst, scientific work tends to focus on some aspect of <font color=\"#00b050\">prevailing knowledge</font> that is viewed as incomplete or incorrect.  \n翻译: <u>首先，科学工作往往聚焦于现有知识中被认为不完整或不正确的某个方面。</u>\n-prevailing knowledge <u>当前占主导地位的知识；也可译为“主流知识”或“被普遍接受的现有知识”。</u>\n\n---\n\nLittle reward accompanies <font color=\"#00b050\">duplication</font> and <font color=\"#00b050\">confirmation</font> of what is already known and believed.  \n翻译: <u>重复和确认已经为人所知并被相信的东西，几乎得不到什么奖励。</u>\n-**duplication**：<u>重复。</u>  \n**confirmation**：<u>确认。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe goal is new-search, not re-search.  \n翻译: <u>目标是 new-search，而不是 re-search。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nNot surprisingly, newly published discovery claims and credible discoveries that appear to be important and <font color=\"#00b050\">convincing</font> will always be open to <font color=\"#00b050\">challenge</font> and potential modification or <font color=\"#00b050\">refutation</font> by future researchers.  \n翻译: <u>毫不奇怪，新近发表的发现声明以及那些看似重要且令人信服的可信发现，将始终面临未来研究者的挑战，并可能被修改或驳倒。</u>\n-**convincing**：<u>有说服力的。</u>  \n-**challenge**：<u>挑战、质疑。</u>\n-refutation**：<u>反驳、推翻。</u>  \n()\n\n---\n\nSecond, novelty itself frequently <font color=\"#00b050\">provokes</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">disbelief</font>.  \n翻译: <u>其次，新颖性本身常常会引发怀疑。</u>\n-provoke**：<u>引发、激起。</u>  \n**disbelief**：<u>不信、怀疑。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Nobel Laureate</font> and physiologist Albert Szent-Györgyi once described discovery as “seeing what everybody has seen and thinking what nobody has thought.”  \n翻译: <u>诺贝尔奖获得者、生理学家 Albert Szent-Györgyi 曾把发现描述为“看到人人都看到过的东西，却想到无人曾想过的事情”。</u>\n-**Nobel Laureate**：<u>诺贝尔奖获得者。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nBut thinking what nobody else has thought and telling others what they have missed may not change their views.  \n翻译: <u>但是，想到别人从未想过的事情，并告诉别人他们遗漏了什么，未必会改变他们的看法。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nSometimes years are required for truly novel discovery claims to be accepted and appreciated.  \n翻译: <u>有时，真正新颖的发现声明需要数年时间才能被接受和赏识。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nIn the end, credibility “<font color=\"#00b050\">happens</font>” to a discovery claim – a process that <font color=\"#00b050\">corresponds to</font> what philosopher Annette Baier has described as the <font color=\"#00b050\">commons of the mind</font>.  \n翻译: <u>最终，可信度会“降临”到一项发现声明上——这一过程对应于哲学家 Annette Baier 所描述的心灵公地。</u>\n-<u>这里 **happens** 加引号，说明这是一种特殊用法：可信度不是个人直接制造出来的，而是在共同体互动过程中逐渐形成的。</u>  \n-**corresponds to**：<u>对应于、符合。</u>  \n-**the commons of the mind**：<u>心智的公共领域/思想共同体。</u>\n\n---\n\n“We reason together, challenge, revise, and complete each other’s reasoning and <font color=\"#00b050\">each other’s conceptions of reason</font>.”  \n翻译: <u>“我们共同推理，彼此质疑、修正并完善对方的推理和对理性的理解。”</u>\n-**each other’s conceptions of reason**：<u>彼此对“理性”的理解。</u>  \n-<u>第一个 reason 是推理 第二个reason 是理性</u>\n-**Enlightenment reason**  (<u>附加知识)</u>\n= <u>启蒙运动所强调的理性</u>\n\n\n\n第四篇阅读\n\nIf the <font color=\"#00b050\">trade unionist</font> Jimmy Hoffa were alive today, he would probably represent <font color=\"#00b050\">civil servants</font>.  \n翻译: <u>如果工会活动家 Jimmy Hoffa 今天还活着，他很可能会代表公务员。</u>\n-trade unionist  trade <u>本身有交易的意思,但是还有行业/职业/手艺的意思</u>\n<u>所以这里的意思是,trade unionist**：工会人士、工会领袖。</u>  \n-**civil servants**：<u>公务员、政府雇员。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhen Hoffa’s Teamsters were in their prime in 1960, only one in ten American government workers belonged to a union; now 36% do.  \n翻译: <u>1960年，当 Hoffa 的 Teamsters 工会处于鼎盛时期时，美国政府雇员中只有十分之一属于工会；如今这一比例为36%。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nIn 2009 the number of <font color=\"#00b050\">unionists</font> in America’s public sector passed that of their fellow members in the private sector.  \n翻译: <u>2009年，美国公共部门的工会会员人数超过了私营部门的工会会员人数。</u>\n()\n\n-**unionists**：<u>工会成员、工会主义者。</u>\n-<u>到 2009 年，美国公共部门的工会成员人数已经超过了私人部门的工会成员人数。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn Britain, more than half of public-sector workers but only about 15% of private-sector ones are unionized.  \n翻译: <u>在英国，超过一半的公共部门员工加入了工会，而私营部门员工中只有约15%加入工会。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nThere are three reasons for the public-sector unions’ thriving.  \n翻译: <u>公共部门工会的兴盛有三个原因。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nFirst, they can shut things down without suffering much <font color=\"#00b050\">in the way of </font>consequences.  \n翻译: <u>第一，它们可以让事情停摆，而几乎不用承受什么后果。</u>\n-in the way of <u>是固定表达，意思是“在……方面 / 关于……”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSecond, they are mostly <font color=\"#00b050\">bright</font> and well-educated.  \n翻译: <u>第二，它们大多聪明且受过良好教育。</u>\n-**bright**：<u>聪明的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA quarter of America’s public-sector workers have a university degree.  \n翻译: <u>美国公共部门员工中有四分之一拥有大学学位。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nThird, they now dominate <font color=\"#00b050\">left-of-centre politics</font>.  \n翻译: <u>第三，它们如今主导着中左翼政治。</u>\n-**left-of-centre politics**：<u>中左翼政治。</u>  \n<u>意思是公共部门工会在偏左政党和政策联盟中拥有很大影响力。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSome of their ties <font color=\"#00b050\">go back a long way</font>.  \n翻译: <u>它们的一些联系由来已久。</u>\n-**go back a long way**：<u>由来已久、历史悠久。</u> \n\n---\n\nBritain’s Labor Party, <font color=\"#00b050\">as its name implies</font>, has long been associated with trade unionism.  \n翻译: <u>英国工党，正如其名称所暗示的那样，长期以来一直与工会主义联系在一起。</u>\n-as：<u>正如。</u>  \n-**its name implies**：<u>它的名字暗示。</u> \n\n---\n\nIts current leader, Ed Miliband, <font color=\"#00b050\">owes his position to</font> votes from public-sector unions.  \n翻译: <u>其现任领导人 Ed Miliband 的职位得益于公共部门工会的选票。</u>\n-**owe his position to…**：<u>把自己的职位归功于……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nAt the <font color=\"#00b050\">state level</font> their influence can be even more fearsome.  \n翻译: <u>在州一级，它们的影响力甚至可能更加令人生畏。</u>\n-state level**：<u>州一级。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nMark Baldassare of the Public Policy Institute of California points out that much of the state’s budget is<font color=\"#00b050\"> patrolled by</font> unions.  \n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚公共政策研究所的 Mark Baldassare 指出，该州预算的很大一部分都受到工会的监控。</u>\n-**is patrolled by unions**：<u>被工会巡逻、看守。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe teachers’ unions <font color=\"#00b050\">keep an eye on</font> schools, the CCPOA on prisons and a variety of labor groups on health care.  \n翻译: <u>教师工会盯着学校，CCPOA 盯着监狱，各类劳工团体则盯着医疗保健。</u>\n-keep an eye on**：<u>密切关注、盯着。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn many rich countries average wages in the state sector are higher than in the private one.  \n翻译: <u>在许多富裕国家，国有部门的平均工资高于私营部门。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the real gains come in benefits and <font color=\"#00b050\">work practices</font>.  \n翻译: <u>但真正的收益体现在福利和工作惯例上。</u>\n-**work practices**：<u>工作惯例、工作制度，如岗位保护、晋升规则、工作安排。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPoliticians have repeatedly “backloaded” <font color=\"#00b050\">public-sector pay deals</font>, keeping the pay increases modest but adding to holidays and especially pensions that are already generous.  \n翻译: <u>政客们反复将公共部门的薪酬协议“后置化”，使工资涨幅保持温和，却增加假期，尤其是增加本已丰厚的养老金。</u>\n-**public-sector pay deals**：<u>公共部门薪酬协议。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nReform has been <font color=\"#00b050\">vigorously</font> opposed, perhaps most notoriously in education, where <font color=\"#00b050\">charter schools</font>, academies and <font color=\"#00b050\">merit pay</font> all faced <font color=\"#00b050\">drawn-out battles</font>.  \n翻译: <u>改革遭到了强烈反对，也许最臭名昭著的是在教育领域，特许学校、学院制学校和绩效工资都遭遇了旷日持久的斗争。</u>\n-**vigorously**：<u>强烈地、有力地。</u>  \n-**charter schools**：<u>特许学校。</u>  \n-**merit pay**：<u>绩效工资，根据表现支付薪酬。</u>  \n-**drawn-out battles**：<u>拖得很久的斗争、长期拉锯战。</u>  \n\n---\n\nEven though there is plenty of evidence that the quality of the teachers is the most important variable, teachers’ unions have fought against getting rid of bad ones and promoting good ones.  \n翻译: <u>尽管有大量证据表明教师质量是最重要的变量，教师工会却一直反对淘汰差教师、提拔好教师。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">As</font> the cost to everyone else has become clearer, politicians have begun to <font color=\"#00b050\">clamp down</font>.  \n翻译: <u>随着其他所有人所承担的成本变得更加清晰，政客们已开始采取压制措施。</u>\n-As<u>在这里主要是“随着”。</u>  \n-**clamp down**：<u>严厉打击、加强限制。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn Wisconsin the unions have <font color=\"#00b050\">rallied</font> thousands of supporters against Scott Walker, the <font color=\"#00b050\">hardline</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">Republican governor</font>.  \n翻译: <u>在 Wisconsin，工会动员了数千名支持者反对强硬派共和党州长 Scott Walker。</u>\n-rallied**：<u>召集、动员。</u>\n-**hardline**：<u>强硬路线的。</u>\n-**Republican governor**：<u>共和党州长。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut many <font color=\"#00b050\">within the public sector</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">suffer under</font> the current system, too.  \n翻译: <u>但公共部门内部也有许多人在当前制度下受苦。</u>\n\n-**within the public sector**：<u>在公共部门内部。</u>  \n-suffer under**：<u>在……下受苦、受损。</u>  \n\n---\n\nJohn Donahue at Harvard’s Kennedy School points out that the <font color=\"#00b050\">norms of culture</font> in <font color=\"#00b050\">Western civil services</font> suit those who want to <font color=\"#00b050\">stay put</font> but is bad for high achievers.  \n翻译: <u>哈佛 Kennedy School 的 John Donahue 指出，西方公务员体系中的文化规范适合那些想要原地不动的人，却不利于成就突出者。</u>\n\n-**norms of culture**：<u>文化规范、文化惯例。</u>  \n**Western civil services**：<u>西方公务员体系。</u>\n-**stay put**：<u>待在原地、不动、不求变化。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe only American public-sector <font color=\"#00b050\">workers</font> who earn well above $250,000 a year are university sports coaches and the president of the United States.  \n翻译: <u>美国公共部门员工中，唯一年收入远高于250,000美元的是大学体育教练和美国总统。</u>\n-workers <u>这里是复数 所以是指这一类 的很多人</u>\n\n---\n\nBankers’ <font color=\"#00b050\">fat pay packets</font> have attracted much criticism, but a public-sector system that does not reward high achievers may be a much bigger problem for America.  \n翻译: <u>银行家丰厚的薪酬待遇招致了许多批评，但一个不奖励高成就者的公共部门制度，对美国来说可能是一个大得多的问题。</u>\n-fat pay packets**：<u>丰厚薪酬、大额收入。</u>  \n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2013","year":"2013","title":"2013 年英语一","fileName":"2013 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2013 年英语 1.md","content":"#### 第一篇阅读\n\nIn the 2006 film version of The Devil Wears Prada, Miranda Priestly, played by Meryl Streep, scolds her unattractive assistant for imagining that high fashion <font color=\"#00b050\">doesn’t affect</font> her.  \n翻译: <u>在2006年电影版《The Devil Wears Prada》中，由 Meryl Streep 饰演的 Miranda Priestly 训斥她那位不出众的助理，因为她以为高级时装不会影响自己。</u>\n-**doesn’t affect her**：<u>不会影响她。   与她无关一样的意思</u>\n\n---\n\nPriestly explains how the deep blue color of the assistant’s sweater <font color=\"#00b050\">descended </font>over the years from fashion shows to department stores and to the <font color=\"#00b050\">bargain bin </font>in which the poor girl doubtless found her garment.  \n翻译: <u>Priestly 解释说，那位助理毛衣上的深蓝色，是如何多年来从时装秀流传到百货商店，再流传到折扣筐里的；那个可怜的女孩无疑就是在那里找到这件衣服的。</u>\n-**descended**：<u>下降、下移、流传下来。</u>  \n<u>这里不是物理下降，而是指颜色从高级时尚逐层传导到大众消费市场。</u> \n-**bargain bin**：<u>廉价处理货筐、打折货筐。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThis top-down <font color=\"#00b050\">conception</font> of the fashion business <font color=\"#00b050\">couldn’t be more</font> out of date or <font color=\"#00b050\">at odds with</font> the feverish world described in <font color=\"#00b050\">Overdressed</font>, Elizabeth Cline’s three-year indictment of “fast fashion”.  \n翻译: <u>这种对时装业自上而下的理解，已经过时得不能再过时，也与 Elizabeth Cline 在《Overdressed》中所描述的狂热世界格格不入；该书是她历时三年对“快时尚”的控诉。</u>\n-**conception**：<u>观念、理解。</u>  \n-**couldn’t be more…** <u>字面是“不可能更……”，实际表示“再……不过了 / 极其……”。</u>\n-**at odds with**：<u>与……不一致、相冲突。</u>  \n-Overdressed <u>首字母大写是个专有名词 老是忘记,注意英语里是没有书名号标记的</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the last decade or so, advances in technology have allowed mass-market labels such as Zara, H&M, and Uniqlo to react to trends more quickly and anticipate demand more precisely.  \n翻译: <u>在过去十年左右，技术进步使 Zara、H&M 和 Uniqlo 等大众市场品牌能够更快地回应潮流，并更精准地预判需求。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nQuicker <font color=\"#00b050\">turnarounds</font> mean <font color=\"#00b050\">less wasted inventory</font>, more frequent releases, and more profit.  \n翻译: <u>更快的周转意味着更少的库存浪费、更频繁的新品发布以及更多利润。</u>\n-**turnaround**：<u>周转、从设计到上架或从生产到销售的周期。</u>  \n-**less wasted inventory**：<u>更少浪费的库存。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese labels encourage style-conscious consumers to see clothes as disposable – meant to last only a wash or two, although they don’t advertise that – and to renew their wardrobe every few weeks.  \n翻译: <u>这些品牌鼓励注重风格的消费者把衣服看作一次性用品——只打算穿一两次水洗，尽管它们并不这样宣传——并且每隔几周就更新自己的衣橱。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nBy offering on-trend items at dirt-cheap prices, Cline argues, these brands have <font color=\"#00b050\">hijacked</font> fashion cycles, <font color=\"#00b050\">shaking</font> an industry <font color=\"#00b050\">long accustomed to</font> a <font color=\"#00b050\">seasonal pace</font>.  \n翻译: <u>Cline 认为，通过以极低价格提供紧跟潮流的商品，这些品牌劫持了时尚周期，动摇了一个长期习惯于季节性节奏的行业。</u>\n-**hijacked**：<u>劫持、强行夺取控制权。</u>\n-**shaking**：<u>撼动、震动。</u>\n-**long accustomed to**：<u>长期习惯于。</u>  \n-**a seasonal pace**：<u>季节性节奏。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe victims of this revolution, of course, are not limited to designers.  \n翻译: <u>当然，这场革命的受害者并不限于设计师。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">For H&M to offer</font> a $5.95 knit miniskirt in all its 2,300-plus stores around the world, it must rely on low-wage overseas labor, <font color=\"#00b050\">order in volumes</font> that <font color=\"#00b050\">strain natural resources</font>, and use massive amounts of harmful chemicals.  \n翻译: <u>为了让 H&M 能在其全球2,300多家门店中提供一条5.95美元的针织迷你裙，它必须依赖海外低薪劳动力，以使自然资源承压的规模下单，并使用大量有害化学品。</u>\n\n-**For H&M to offer…**：<u>为了使 H&M 能够提供……。</u>\n-**order in volumes**：<u>以大批量订货。</u> \n-**strain natural resources**：<u>使自然资源承压。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOverdressed is the fashion world’s <font color=\"#00b050\">answer</font> to <font color=\"#00b050\">consumer-activist</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">bestsellers</font> like Michael Pollan’s The Omnivore’s Dilemma.  \n翻译: <u>《Overdressed》是时尚界对 Michael Pollan 的《The Omnivore’s Dilemma》等消费者行动主义畅销书的回应。</u>\n\n-**the fashion world’s answer to…**：<u>时尚界对……的回应。</u>\n-**consumer-activist**：<u>消费者行动主义的，即通过消费选择推动社会或环境改变。</u>\n-**bestsellers**：<u>畅销书。</u>  \n-《Overdressed》<u>相当于时尚界版本的消费者行动主义畅销书，类似 Michael Pollan 批判食品系统的《杂食者的困境》。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Mass-produced clothing, like fast food, fills a hunger and need, <font color=\"#00b050\">yet</font> is non-durable and wasteful,” Cline argues.  \n翻译: <u>Cline 认为，“大规模生产的服装就像快餐一样，填补了饥饿和需求，却不耐用且造成浪费。”</u>\n-**yet**：<u>然而、但是。 但它不耐用且浪费。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nAmericans, she finds, buy roughly 20 billion garments a year – about 64 items per person – and no matter how much they <font color=\"#00b050\">give away</font>, this excess leads to waste.  \n翻译: <u>她发现，美国人每年大约购买200亿件衣服——人均约64件——而且无论他们捐出多少，这种过剩都会导致浪费。</u>\n-**give away**：<u>赠送、捐出。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Towards the end of</font> Overdressed, Cline introduced her ideal, a Brooklyn woman named Sarah Kate Beaumont, who since 2008 has made all of her own clothes – and beautifully.  \n翻译: <u>在《Overdressed》接近结尾处，Cline 介绍了她心目中的理想人物，一位名叫 Sarah Kate Beaumont 的布鲁克林女性；自2008年以来，她所有的衣服都由自己制作，而且做得很美。</u>\n\n-**Towards the end of…**：<u>在……接近结尾处。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut as Cline is<font color=\"#00b050\"> the first to note</font>, it took Beaumont decades to perfect her craft; her example can’t be<font color=\"#00b050\"> knocked off</font>.  \n翻译: <u>但正如 Cline 首先指出的那样，Beaumont 花了几十年才完善自己的手艺；她的范例无法被仿制。</u>\n\n-the first to note：<u>第一个指出、率先承认。</u> \n-**knock off**：<u>仿制、快速复制，也可指制造廉价仿品。</u> \n\n---\n\nThough several fast-fashion companies have made efforts to curb their impact on labor and the environment – including H&M, with its green Conscious Collection line – Cline believes<font color=\"#00b050\"> lasting change</font> can only be effected by the customer.  \n翻译: <u>尽管几家快时尚公司已努力遏制它们对劳工和环境的影响——包括 H&M 及其绿色的 Conscious Collection 系列——Cline 认为，持久的改变只能由顾客来实现。</u>\n\n-**lasting change**：<u>持久改变</u>\n\n---\n\nShe <font color=\"#00b050\">exhibits</font> the idealism <font color=\"#00b050\">common to</font> many advocates of sustainability, <font color=\"#00b050\">be it in </font>food <font color=\"#00b050\">or</font> in energy.  \n翻译: <u>她表现出许多可持续发展倡导者共有的理想主义，无论是在食品领域还是能源领域。</u>\n\n-**exhibits**：<u>表现出、显示出。</u>\n-**common to…**：<u>对……来说常见。</u>  \n-**be it…or…** <u>是固定结构，表示“无论是在……还是在……”。</u>\n**be it A or B** = **whether it is A or B**。 \n翻译: <u>**be it A or B** = **whether it is A or B**。</u>\n\n---\n\nVanity is a <font color=\"#00b050\">constant</font>; people will only start <font color=\"#00b050\">shopping more sustainably</font> when they <font color=\"#00b050\">can’t afford not to</font>.  \n翻译: <u>虚荣是一种常量；只有当人们承担不起不以更可持续方式购物的代价时，他们才会开始更可持续地购物。</u>\n\n-**constant**：<u>常量、不变因素。</u>  \n-**shopping more sustainably**：<u>以更可持续的方式购物。</u>  \n-**can’t afford not to** <u>是省略结构。完整理解是：</u>  \n**can’t afford not to shop more sustainably**  \n翻译: <u>**承担不起不以更可持续方式购物的代价**</u>\n= <u>承担不起不进行可持续购物的后果。</u>  \n<u>这不是单纯“买不起”，而是说只有当不可持续消费的经济、社会或环境代价变得无法承受时，人们才会改变。</u>  \n\n\n#### 第二篇阅读\n\nAn old saying <font color=\"#00b050\">has it</font> that half of all advertising budgets are wasted – the trouble is, no one knows which half.  \n翻译: <u>有句老话说，所有广告预算有一半都被浪费了——问题是，没人知道是哪一半。</u>\n\n-**has it that…** <u>是固定表达，意思是“据说 / 有说法认为”。</u>  \n<u>这里不是“拥有它”的意思，而是引出一句传统说法。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn the internet age, at least in theory, this fraction can be much reduced.  \n翻译: <u>在互联网时代，至少从理论上说，这一比例可以大大降低。</u>\n\n-**at least in theory** <u>表示作者谨慎表达,只是在理论上来说</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBy watching what people search for, click on and say online, companies can aim <font color=\"#00b050\">“behavioural” ads</font> at those most likely to buy.  \n翻译: <u>通过观察人们在网上搜索什么、点击什么以及说什么，公司可以把“行为”广告投向最有可能购买的人。</u>\n\n-**behavioural ads**：<u>行为广告，即根据用户行为数据定向投放的广告。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the past couple of weeks a quarrel has <font color=\"#00b050\">illustrated</font> the value to advertisers of such <font color=\"#00b050\">fine-grained information</font>: Should advertisers assume that people are happy to be tracked and sent behavioural ads?  \n翻译: <u>过去几周的一场争论说明了这种细粒度信息对广告商的价值：广告商是否应该假定人们乐于被追踪并接收行为广告？</u>\n\n-**illustrated**：<u>说明、展示。</u>\n-**fine-grained information**：<u>细粒度信息，指非常具体、精细的用户行为数据。</u>  \n-<u>过去几周的一场争论凸显了精细用户数据对广告商的价值：广告商能不能默认用户愿意被追踪，并愿意接收行为定向广告？</u>\n\n---\n\nOr should they have <font color=\"#00b050\">explicit permission</font>?  \n翻译: <u>还是说，他们应当获得明确许可？</u>\n\n-**explicit permission**：<u>明确许可、明示同意。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn December 2010 America’s Federal Trade Commission (FTC) proposed adding a “do not track” (DNT) option to internet browsers, so that users could tell advertisers that they did not want to be followed.  \n翻译: <u>2010年12月，美国联邦贸易委员会（FTC）提议在互联网浏览器中增加一个“do not track”（DNT）选项，以便用户可以告诉广告商他们不想被跟踪。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nMicrosoft’s Internet Explorer and Apple’s Safari both offer DNT; Google’s Chrome i<font color=\"#00b050\">s due to</font> do so this year.  \n翻译: <u>Microsoft 的 Internet Explorer 和 Apple 的 Safari 都提供 DNT；Google 的 Chrome 预计今年也会提供。</u>\n\n-**be due to do**：<u>预定、预计要做某事。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn February the FTC and the Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA) agreed that<font color=\"#00b050\"> the industry</font> would <font color=\"#00b050\">get cracking on</font> responding to DNT requests.  \n翻译: <u>2月，FTC 和数字广告联盟（DAA）达成一致，行业将立即着手回应 DNT 请求。</u>\n\n-**the industry**：<u>广告行业。</u>\n-**get cracking on**：<u>开始认真做、赶紧着手做。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOn May 31st Microsoft <font color=\"#00b050\">set off</font> the<font color=\"#00b050\"> row</font>.  \n翻译: <u>5月31日，Microsoft 引发了这场争端。</u>\n\n-**set off**：<u>引发、触发。</u>\n-**the row**：<u>这场争论、争吵。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt <font color=\"#00b050\">said</font> that Internet Explorer 10, the version <font color=\"#00b050\">due to appear</font> with Windows 8, would have DNT as a default.  \n翻译: <u>它表示，将随 Windows 8 推出的 Internet Explorer 10 会默认开启 DNT。</u>\n\n-**said**：<u>表示、称。</u>\n-**due to appear**：<u>预计推出、即将出现。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAdvertisers are horrified.  \n翻译: <u>广告商对此感到惊恐。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nHuman nature <font color=\"#00b050\">being what it is</font>, most people stick with default settings.  \n翻译: <u>人性如此，大多数人会沿用默认设置。</u>\n\n-**being what it is**：<u>既然就是这个样子。</u>  \n<u>人性既然如此，大多数人会坚持使用默认设置。</u>\n\n---\n\nFew switch DNT on now, but if tracking is off it will stay off.  \n翻译: <u>现在很少有人开启 DNT，但如果追踪被关闭，它就会一直关闭。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nBob Liodice, the chief executive of the Association of National Advertisers, says consumers will be <font color=\"#00b050\">worse off</font> if the industry cannot collect information about their preferences.  \n翻译: <u>全国广告商协会首席执行官 Bob Liodice 说，如果该行业无法收集有关消费者偏好的信息，消费者的处境会更糟。</u>\n\n-**worse off**：<u>处境更差、更不利。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nPeople will not get fewer ads, he says.  \n翻译: <u>他说，人们看到的广告不会减少。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n“They’ll get less meaningful, less targeted ads.”  \n翻译: <u>“他们会看到意义更少、针对性更弱的广告。”</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is not yet clear how <font color=\"#00b050\">advertisers</font> will respond.  \n翻译: <u>广告商将如何回应，目前尚不清楚。</u>\n\n-advertisers <u>广告商</u>\n\n---\n\nGetting a DNT signal does not <font color=\"#00b050\">oblige</font> anyone to stop tracking, although some companies have promised to do so.  \n翻译: <u>收到 DNT 信号并不迫使任何人停止追踪，尽管一些公司已经承诺会这样做。</u>\n\n**oblige sb to do**：<u>迫使/强制某人做某事。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Unable to tell</font> whether someone really <font color=\"#00b050\">objects to</font> behavioural ads or whether they are <font color=\"#00b050\">sticking with</font> Microsoft’s default, some may ignore a DNT signal and <font color=\"#00b050\">press on anyway</font>.  \n翻译: <u>由于无法判断某人是真的反对行为广告，还是只是沿用了 Microsoft 的默认设置，有些公司可能会无视 DNT 信号，继续照常推进。</u>\n\n-**Unable to tell**：<u>无法判断。</u> \n-**object to**：<u>反对。</u>\n-**stick with**：<u>沿用、坚持使用。</u>  \n-**press on anyway**：<u>不管怎样继续推进、照做不误。</u>  \n-<u>由于无法判断某人是真的反对行为广告，还是只是沿用了微软的默认设置，一些公司可能会忽略 DNT 信号并无论如何继续下去。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlso unclear is why Microsoft has <font color=\"#00b050\">gone it alone</font>.  \n翻译: <u>同样不清楚的是，为什么 Microsoft 要单独行动。</u>\n\n-**go it alone**：<u>单独行动、独自推进。</u> \n<u>同样不清楚的是，微软为什么单独行动。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">After all</font>, it has an ad business too, which it says will comply with DNT requests, though it is still <font color=\"#00b050\">working out</font> how.  \n翻译: <u>毕竟，它也有广告业务，并且它表示会遵守 DNT 请求，尽管它仍在研究如何做到这一点。</u>\n\n- after all <u>毕竟</u> \n- **working out**：<u>弄清楚、制定出。</u>\n- \n\n---\n\nIf it is trying to upset Google, which relies almost wholly on advertising, it has chosen an indirect method: <font color=\"#00b050\">there is no guarantee</font> that DNT by default will become the <font color=\"#00b050\">norm</font>.  \n翻译: <u>如果它是在试图激怒几乎完全依赖广告的 Google，那么它选择了一种间接方法：默认开启 DNT 并不一定会成为常规。</u>\n\n-there is no guarantee <u>并不能保证。</u>\n-**become the norm**：<u>成为常态、成为标准做法。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nDNT does not seem an obviously huge selling point for Windows 8 – though the firm has compared some of its other products favourably with <font color=\"#00b050\">Google’s</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">on that count</font> before.  \n翻译: <u>DNT 似乎并不是 Windows 8 一个显而易见的巨大卖点——尽管该公司此前曾在这一点上把自己的其他一些产品与 Google 的产品作过有利比较。</u>\n\n\n-**Google’s** <u>后面省略 **products**。</u>  \n-**on that count**：<u>在那一点上、就那个方面而言。这里指隐私保护或用户控制。</u>\n\n---\n\nBrendon Lynch, Microsoft’s chief privacy officer, blogged: “We believe consumers should have more control.”  \n翻译: <u>Microsoft 首席隐私官 Brendon Lynch 在博客中写道：“我们认为消费者应当拥有更多控制权。”</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nCould it really be that simple?  \n翻译: <u>事情真的会这么简单吗？</u>\n()\n\n\n#### 第三篇阅读\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Up until</font> a few decades ago, our visions of the future were largely – though <font color=\"#00b050\">by no means</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">uniformly</font> – glowingly positive.  \n翻译: <u>直到几十年前，我们对未来的设想在很大程度上——尽管绝非完全一致——都是光明而积极的。</u>\n\n-**up until**：<u>直到</u>\n-**by no means**：<u>绝不。</u>  \n-**uniformly**：<u>一致地、统一地。</u>\n-<u>直到几十年前，我们对未来的想象大体上是非常积极的，尽管绝不是完全一致地如此。</u>\n\n---\n\nScience and technology would cure all the ills of humanity, <font color=\"#00b050\">leading to</font> lives of fulfilment and opportunity for all.  \n翻译: <u>科学和技术将治愈人类的一切弊病，使所有人都过上充实且充满机会的生活。</u>\n\n-**leading to**：<u>导致、带来。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nNow utopia has grown unfashionable, as we have <font color=\"#00b050\">gained a deeper appreciation</font> of the range of threats facing us, from asteroid strike to epidemic flu and to climate change.  \n翻译: <u>如今，乌托邦已经变得不合时宜，因为我们对所面临的各种威胁有了更深的认识，从小行星撞击，到流行性流感，再到气候变化。</u>\n\n-**have gained a deeper appreciation of…**：<u>对……有了更深理解。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nYou might even<font color=\"#00b050\"> be tempted to</font> assume that humanity has little future to <font color=\"#00b050\">look forward to</font>.  \n翻译: <u>你甚至可能会忍不住假定，人类几乎没有什么未来可期待。</u>\n\n-**be tempted to do**：<u>忍不住想做某事、容易被诱使去做某事。</u> \n-**to look forward to**：<u>可以期待的。</u> \n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#00b050\">such gloominess</font> is<font color=\"#00b050\"> misplaced.  </font>\n翻译: <u>但这种悲观是错误的。</u>\n\n-**such gloominess**：<u>这种阴郁、悲观。</u>  \n-**misplaced**：<u>放错地方的、不合适的、判断不当的。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe fossil record shows that many species have endured for millions of years – so why shouldn’t we?  \n翻译: <u>化石记录显示，许多物种已经延续了数百万年——那么我们为什么不可以呢？</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nTake a broader look at our species’ place in the universe, and it becomes clear that we have an excellent chance of surviving <font color=\"#00b050\">for tens</font>, if not hundreds, <font color=\"#00b050\">of thousands of years.</font>  \n翻译: <u>从更广阔的角度审视我们这个物种在宇宙中的位置，就会清楚地看到，我们很有可能再存活数万年，甚至数十万年。</u>\n\n-**for tens of thousands of years**：<u>数万年。 中间的插入语可以不看</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Look up</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">Homo sapiens</font> in the “Red List” of threatened species of the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and you will read: “Listed as <font color=\"#00b050\">Least Concern</font> as the species is very widely distributed, adaptable, currently increasing, and there are no major threats resulting in an <font color=\"#00b050\">overall population decline</font>.”  \n翻译: <u>在国际自然保护联盟（IUCN）受威胁物种“红色名录”中查找 Homo sapiens，你会读到：“被列为无危，因为该物种分布非常广泛，适应性强，目前数量正在增加，并且不存在导致总体种群下降的重大威胁。”</u>\n\n-**Look up**：<u>查阅</u>\n-**Homo sapiens**：<u>智人，人类的学名。</u>  \n-**Least Concern**：<u>无危，IUCN 物种保护等级中风险最低的一类。</u>  \n-**overall population decline**：<u>总体人口下降。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSo what does our deep future <font color=\"#00b050\">hold</font>?  \n翻译: <u>那么，我们遥远的未来会是什么样子？</u>\n\n-**hold**：<u>包含、拥有、等待着。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA growing number of researchers and organisations are now thinking seriously about that question.  \n翻译: <u>如今，越来越多的研究人员和组织正在认真思考这个问题。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\nFor example, the Long Now Foundation <font color=\"#00b050\">has as its flagship project a mechanical clock</font> that is designed to <font color=\"#00b050\">still be marking time</font> thousands of years <font color=\"#00b050\">hence</font>.  \n翻译: <u>例如，Long Now Foundation 的旗舰项目是一座机械钟，其设计目标是在数千年后仍能记录时间。</u>\n\n-<u>正常语序可理解为：</u>  \n**has a mechanical clock as its flagship project**。\n翻译: <u>以一座机械钟作为其旗舰项目。</u>\n-mechanical clock <u>机械钟</u> \n-**still be marking time**：<u>仍在计时。</u>  \n-**hence** <u>在这里表示“从现在起之后”。</u> \n\n---\n\nPerhaps <font color=\"#00b050\">willfully</font>, it may be easier to think about <font color=\"#00b050\">such lengthy timescales</font> than about the more immediate future.  \n翻译: <u>或许是有意如此，相比更近的未来，思考如此漫长的时间尺度也许更容易。</u>\n\n-**willfully**：<u>有意地、故意地。</u>  \n-**such lengthy timescales**：<u>如此漫长的时间尺度。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe potential evolution of today’s technology, and its <font color=\"#00b050\">social consequences</font>, is dazzlingly complicated, and<font color=\"#00b050\"> it’s</font> perhaps best <font color=\"#00b050\">left to</font> science fiction writers and futurologists to explore the many possibilities we can envisage.  \n翻译: <u>当今技术的潜在演进及其社会后果极其复杂，而探索我们能够设想的诸多可能性，也许最好留给科幻作家和未来学家。</u>\n\n-**social consequences**：<u>社会后果。</u>  \n-**be left to sb**：<u>留给某人处理。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThat’s one reason why we have <font color=\"#00b050\">launched</font> Arc, a new publication <font color=\"#00b050\">dedicated to</font> the near future.  \n翻译: <u>这就是我们推出 Arc 的原因之一；Arc 是一份致力于近未来的新刊物。</u>\n\n-**launched**：<u>创办、推出。</u>  \n-**dedicated to**：<u>致力于、专注于。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut take a longer view and there is a surprising amount that we can say with considerable assurance.  \n翻译: <u>但如果把眼光放得更长远，我们就会发现，有相当多的事情是我们可以相当有把握地说出来的。</u>\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">As so often</font>, the past holds the key to the future: we have now identified enough of the long-term patterns <font color=\"#00b050\">shaping</font> the history of the planet, and our species, to make evidence-based forecasts/ about/of the situations/ in which our descendants will find themselves.  \n翻译: <u>一如既往，过去掌握着通往未来的钥匙：如今，我们已经识别出足够多塑造地球历史和我们这个物种历史的长期模式，从而能够基于证据，对我们的后代将置身其中的情境作出预测。</u>\n\n-**As so often** = as is so often the case。  \n意思是：<u>很多时候都是这样。  </u>\n-shaping<u>现在分词短语作后置定语，修饰 **patterns**。</u>\n-**in which our descendants will find themselves** =\nour descendants will find themselves in those situations。  \n翻译: <u>我们的后代将会发现自己处于那些情境之中。</u>\n-<u>和许多时候一样，理解过去是理解未来的关键。如今，我们已经识别出足够多影响地球和人类历史的长期规律，因此可以较有根据地预测我们的后代未来可能面对的处境。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThis <font color=\"#00b050\">long perspective</font> makes the pessimistic view of our prospects seem more likely to be a <font color=\"#00b050\">passing fad</font>.  \n翻译: <u>这种长远视角使得对我们前景的悲观看法更像是一时的风潮。</u>\n\n-**long perspective**：<u>长远视角。</u>  \n-**passing fad**：<u>一时风尚、短暂潮流。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">To be sure,</font> the future is not all <font color=\"#00b050\">rosy</font>.  \n翻译: <u>诚然，未来并非一片美好。</u>\n-to be sure <u>诚然 / 确实。</u>\n-**rosy**：<u>玫瑰色的、乐观美好的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut we are now knowledgeable enough to reduce many of the risks that threatened the existence of earlier humans, and to<font color=\"#00b050\"> improve the lot of</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">those to come</font>.  \n翻译: <u>但我们如今已经拥有足够的知识，可以减少许多曾威胁早期人类生存的风险，并改善后来者的处境。</u>\n-**improve the lot of…**：<u>改善……的命运/处境。</u>  \n-**those to come**：<u>后来的人、未来的人类。</u> \n\n#### 第四篇阅读\n\nOn a five to three vote, the Supreme Court <font color=\"#00b050\">knocked out</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">much of</font> Arizona’s immigration law Monday – a <font color=\"#00b050\">modest</font> policy victory for the<font color=\"#00b050\"> Obama Administration</font>.\n翻译: <u>周一，最高法院以五比三的投票结果推翻了亚利桑那州移民法的大部分内容，这对奥巴马政府而言是一次有限的政策胜利。</u>\n\n-**knocked out**：<u>谓语动词短语，原义为“击倒”，这里引申为“废除、推翻、判定无效”。</u>\n- **much of <u>大部分的</u>\n- -- **modest** <u>在这里不是“谦虚的”，而是“有限的、不大的”。</u>\n- Obama Administration** <u>奥巴马政府</u>\n\n---\n\nBut on the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">more important matter</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">of the Constitution</font>, the decision was an 8-0 defeat for the Administration’s effort to <font color=\"#9bbb59\">upset</font> the balance of power between the federal government and the states.\n翻译: <u>但在更重要的宪法问题上，这一裁决却以 8-0 的结果挫败了政府试图打破联邦政府与各州之间权力平衡的努力。</u>\n\n-- **on the matter of…** <u>表示“在……问题上”。of 后面的是修饰 matter 的</u>\n-**upset** <u>在这里不是“使难过”，而是“扰乱、打破”。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nIn Arizona v. United States,<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> the majority</font> overturned three of the four<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> contested </font><font color=\"#9bbb59\">provisions</font> of Arizona’s controversial plan to have state and local police enforce federal immigration law.\n翻译: <u>在 Arizona v. United States 一案中，多数法官推翻了亚利桑那州有争议计划中四项受质疑条款中的三项；该计划旨在让州和地方警察执行联邦移民法。</u>\n\n-**the majority** <u>指最高法院中的多数派大法官。</u>\n-- **contested** <u>表示“有争议的、受到质疑的”。</u>\n-**provisions** <u>指法律中的“条款”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">The Constitutiona</font>l principles that Washington<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> alone</font> has the power to “establish a uniform Rule of <font color=\"#9bbb59\">Naturalization</font> and that federal laws <font color=\"#9bbb59\">precede </font>state laws <font color=\"#9bbb59\">are noncontroversial.</font>\n翻译: <u>宪法原则认为，只有华盛顿才有权“制定统一的归化规则”，并且联邦法律优先于州法律；这些原则并无争议。</u>\n\n--**alone** <u>表示“单独、独自”，强调只有联邦政府有该权力。</u>\n-<u>逆天句子,句子的主干在最开头,和最后面</u>\n-**precede** <u>这里不是单纯时间上的“在……之前”，而是法律效力上的“优先于、高于”。</u>\n-**Naturalization** <u>指“归化”，即外国人成为美国公民的法律程序。</u>\n\n-<u>联邦政府独享归化规则制定权、联邦法律高于州法律，这些宪法原则本身并无争议。</u>\n\n---\n\nArizona <font color=\"#9bbb59\">had attempted</font> to <font color=\"#9bbb59\">fashion</font> state policies that ran parallel to the existing federal ones.\n翻译: <u>亚利桑那州曾试图制定与现有联邦政策并行的州政策。</u>\n\n- **had attempted** <u>是过去完成时，表示该尝试发生在最高法院裁决之前。</u>\n- **fashion** <u>这里不是“时尚”，而是动词，表示“制定、塑造、设计”。</u>\n\n<u>亚利桑那州原本试图设计一套州级政策，使其与现行联邦移民政策保持并行。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">Justice</font> Anthony Kennedy, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">joined by</font> Chief Justice John Roberts and the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">Court’s liberals</font>, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">ruled</font> that the state f<font color=\"#9bbb59\">lew too close to the federal sun</font>.\n翻译: <u>Anthony Kennedy 大法官在首席大法官 John Roberts 和法院自由派法官的支持下裁定，该州飞得离联邦这轮太阳太近了。</u>\n\n\n- **Justice** <u>在这里指“美国最高法院大法官”。</u>\n- **rule** <u>在法律语境中是动词，表示“裁定、判决”。</u>\n- **the Court’s liberals** <u>指最高法院中的自由派大法官。</u>\n- joined by <u>其实是省略了 核心是 who was joined by</u>\n- <u>这里的 join 的意思是**支持其判决意见 / 加入其意见 / 与其形成多数意见**</u>\n- lew too close to the federal sun** <u>是比喻表达。</u>\n- <u>该表达借用了希腊神话中伊卡洛斯飞得太靠近太阳而坠落的意象。政策过度接近甚至侵犯了联邦政府的专属权力</u>\n\n<u>肯尼迪大法官在罗伯茨首席大法官和自由派大法官支持下裁定，亚利桑那州的做法过度触及了联邦政府的权力范围。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">On</font> the overturned provisions <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the majority held</font><font color=\"#9bbb59\"> Congress </font>had deliberately “occupied the field” and Arizona had <font color=\"#9bbb59\">thus</font> intruded on the federal’s privileged powers.\n翻译: <u>对于被推翻的条款，多数法官认为，国会已刻意“占据了该领域”，因此亚利桑那州侵犯了联邦的专属权力。</u>\n\n-**on** <u>在这里表示“关于、就……而言”。</u>\n-- **the majority** <u>指最高法院多数派。</u>\n- **held** <u>在法律语境中表示“认为、裁定”。</u>\n- held <u>后面是一个省略 that 的从句,动词后面没有说 that 直接开始一个句子 就是省略从句</u> \n- <u>一句话里省略了两个 that 真畜生</u>\n- **Congress** <u>指美国国会。</u>\n- - **thus** <u>表示“因此”，说明逻辑结果。</u>\n- <u>对于被判无效的条款，最高法院多数派认为，国会已经对相关领域作出充分规制，所以亚利桑那州的做法侵犯了联邦政府的专属权力。</u>\n\n---\n\nHowever, the Justices said that Arizona police would be allowed to verify<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> the legal status of people</font> who <font color=\"#9bbb59\">come in contact with</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">law enforcement.</font>\n翻译: <u>不过，大法官们表示，亚利桑那州警察将被允许核实与执法机关接触人员的合法身份。</u>\n\n- **the legal status** <u>指“法律身份”，在这里具体指移民身份是否合法。</u>\n- **come in contact with** <u>是固定搭配，表示“与……接触”</u>\n- **law enforcement** <u>指“执法机关、执法部门、执法活动”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat’s because Congress has always envisioned joint <font color=\"#9bbb59\">federal-state</font> immigration enforcement and <font color=\"#9bbb59\">explicitly encourages</font> state officers to share information and cooperate with federal colleagues.\n翻译: <u>这是因为国会一直设想联邦与各州共同执行移民法，并明确鼓励州官员分享信息、与联邦同僚合作。</u>\n\n-**joint federal-state** <u>表示“联邦与州共同的”。</u>\n-explicitly encourages <u>明确鼓励</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nTwo of the three<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> objecting Justices</font> – Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas – agreed with this Constitutional logic but disagreed about <font color=\"#9bbb59\">which</font> Arizona rules conflicted with the federal statute.\n翻译: <u>三位持异议的大法官中有两位——Samuel Alito 和 Clarence Thomas——同意这一宪法逻辑，但不同意哪些亚利桑那州规则与联邦法规相冲突。</u>\n\n-**objecting Justices** <u>指“提出反对意见的大法官”。</u>\n-**which Arizona rules** <u>表示“哪些亚利桑那州规则”。这里 **which 修饰 Arizona rules**，表示“哪些规则”。</u>\n<u>在三位反对的大法官中，阿利托和托马斯赞同这一宪法推理，但他们对哪些亚利桑那州条款真正与联邦法冲突持不同看法。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe only major objection came from Justice Antonin Scalia, who offered an even more robust defense of state privileges<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> going back to</font> the<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> Alien and Sedition Acts</font>.\n翻译: <u>唯一重大的反对意见来自大法官 Antonin Scalia，他提出了对州权更有力的辩护，并把这种辩护追溯到《外国人与煽动叛乱法》。</u>\n\n- **going back to…** <u>表示“追溯到……”。</u>\n-  Alien and Sedition Acts <u>专有名词不用管</u>\n\n---\n\nThe 8-0 objection <font color=\"#9bbb59\">to President Obama</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">turns on</font> what Justice Samuel Alito describes in his objection as “a shocking assertion of federal executive power”.\n翻译: <u>对奥巴马总统的 8-0 反对，关键在于 Samuel Alito 大法官在其异议中所称的“一种令人震惊的联邦行政权力主张”。</u>\n\n- **to President Obama** <u>表示反对对象是奥巴马总统或奥巴马政府的主张。</u>\n- **turn on** <u>是固定搭配，在这里不是“打开”，而是“取决于、以……为关键”。</u>\n- <u>最高法院八比零反对奥巴马政府的关键，在于阿利托大法官所说的那种“令人震惊的联邦行政权扩张主张”。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe White House argued that Arizona’s laws conflicted with its<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> enforcement priorities</font>, even if state laws complied with federal statutes <font color=\"#9bbb59\">to the letter</font>.\n翻译: <u>白宫辩称，亚利桑那州的法律与其执法优先事项相冲突，即便州法律在字面上符合联邦法规。</u>\n\n-**enforcement priorities** <u>指“执法优先事项”，即行政部门决定优先执行哪些法律、重点处理哪些案件。</u>\n-o the letter** <u>是固定短语，表示“严格按照字面规定、一丝不苟地”。</u>\n-\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">In effect</font>, the White House claimed that it could invalidate any <font color=\"#9bbb59\">otherwise </font>legitimate state law that it disagrees with.\n翻译: <u>实际上，白宫声称，它可以使任何它不同意的、在其他方面合法的州法律失效。</u>\n\n- **in effect** <u>是固定短语，表示“实际上、实质上”。</u>\n- <u><font color=\"#9bbb59\">换言之</font>，白宫实际上是在主张：只要它不同意，即使一项州法本来合法，它也可以将其否定。</u>\n- in effect <u>不是一个完全没用的词,而是对之前内容的总结.</u>\n- otherwise <u>本来的意思是否则,但是作为一个副词放在形容词legitimate(合法的)前,otherwise + 形容词 **本来是……的 / 在其他方面是……的**</u>\n- an otherwise good plan <u>一个本来不错的计划</u>\n\n---\n\nSome powers do belong exclusively to the federal government, and control of citizenship and the borders is among them.\n翻译: <u>有些权力确实完全属于联邦政府，控制公民身份和边境便是其中之一。</u>\n\n-<u>有些权力确实专属于联邦政府，而公民身份和边境的控制就在这些权力之中。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut if Congress wanted to prevent states from using their own resources to check immigration status, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">it could.</font>\n翻译: <u>但是，如果国会想阻止各州使用自身资源来核查移民身份，它本可以这样做。</u>\n\n-it could <u>它本来完全可以这么做</u>\n\n---\n\nIt never did so.\n翻译: <u>它从未这样做。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe Administration was in essence asserting that because it didn’t want to carry out Congress’s immigration wishes, no state should be allowed to do so <font color=\"#9bbb59\">either</font>.\n翻译: <u>政府实质上是在声称，因为它不想执行国会在移民问题上的意愿，所以任何州也都不应被允许这样做。</u>\n\n-**either** <u>用于否定句末，表示“也”。</u>\n\n---\n\nEvery Justice <font color=\"#9bbb59\">rightly</font> rejected this remarkable claim.\n翻译: <u>每一位大法官都正确地驳回了这一非同寻常的主张。</u>\n\n-**rightly** <u>是副词，修饰 **rejected**，表示“正确地、理所当然地”。</u>\n\n\t()\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2014","year":"2014","title":"2014 年英语一","fileName":"2014 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2014 年英语 1.md","content":"In order to “change lives for the better” and reduce “dependency”, George Osborne, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">Chancellor of the Exchequer</font>, introduced the “upfront work search” <font color=\"#9bbb59\">scheme</font>.\n翻译: <u>为了“让生活变得更好”并减少“依赖”，财政大臣 George Osborne 推出了“预先求职”计划。</u>\n\n-**Chancellor of the Exchequer**：<u>英国财政大臣。</u>\n-- **scheme**：<u>在英式英语中常指“计划、方案、制度安排”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">Only if</font> the jobless arrive at the jobcentre with a <font color=\"#9bbb59\">CV</font>, register for online job search, and start looking for work <font color=\"#9bbb59\">will they</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">be eligible for</font> benefit – and then they should report weekly rather than fortnightly.\n翻译: <u>只有当失业者带着简历来到就业中心，注册在线求职，并开始找工作时，他们才有资格领取救济金；而且随后他们应每周报到，而不是每两周报到一次。</u>\n\n- **Only if**：<u>表示“只有在……条件下才……”</u>\n- **with a CV**：<u>介词短语作伴随状语，表示“带着简历”。</u>\n- will they <u>倒装 因为前面是 only if</u> \n- **be eligible for**：<u>固定搭配，意思是“有资格获得……”。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat <font color=\"#9bbb59\">could be</font> more reasonable?\n翻译: <u>还有什么能比这更合理呢？</u>\n\n-**could be**：<u>情态动词 **could** 加动词原形 **be**，表示一种设问语气。</u>\n-<u>这句话表面是疑问句，实际带有反问意味，暗示“这看起来非常合理”。</u>\n\n---\n\nMore <font color=\"#9bbb59\">apparent</font><font color=\"#9bbb59\"> reasonableness</font> followed.\n翻译: <u>随后又出现了更多表面上的合理之处。</u>\n\n- **reasonableness**：<u>合理性。</u>\n- **apparent**：<u>表面上的、看似的。这个词很关键，说明作者认为这种合理性只是表象。</u>\n- <u>更多表面上的合理性随后出现了。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere will now be a seven-day wait for the jobseeker’s<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> allowance.</font>\n翻译: <u>如今，领取求职者津贴将有七天的等待期。</u>\n\n-**jobseeker’s allowance**：<u>英国的“求职者津贴”，即失业福利的一种。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Those first few days should be spent looking for work, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">not looking to</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">sign on</font>,” he claimed.\n翻译: <u>他声称：“最初的几天应该用来找工作，而不是想着登记领取救济。”</u>\n\n-look to do something <u>打算做某事 / 试图做某事 / 指望做某事</u>\n-**sign on**：<u>英式英语短语，指“登记领取失业救济”。</u>\n\n\n---\n\n“We’re doing these things because we know they help people stay off benefits and help those on benefits get into work faster.”\n翻译: <u>“我们做这些事，是因为我们知道它们有助于人们不再依赖福利，也有助于正在领取福利的人更快进入工作。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHelp?\n\n()\n\n---\n\nReally?\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOn first hearing, this was the socially concerned chancellor, trying to change lives for the better, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">complete with</font> “reforms” to an obviously<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> indulgent system </font>that demands too little effort from <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the newly unemployed</font> to find work, and <font color=\"#9bbb59\">subsidises laziness</font>.\n翻译: <u>乍一听，这是位关心社会的财政大臣，试图让生活变得更好，并对一个显然过于宽纵的制度进行“改革”；这个制度对新近失业者找工作的努力要求太少，并补贴懒惰。</u>\n\n-  **complete with**：<u>固定搭配，意思是“配有、包括、连同……一起”。</u>\n- **obviously indulgent system**：<u>明显过于纵容的制度。</u>\n- **the newly unemployed**：<u>新近失业者；“the + 形容词/分词”表示一类人。</u>\n- **subsidises laziness**：<u>补贴懒惰，带有强烈价值判断色彩。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat motivated him, we <font color=\"#9bbb59\">were to</font> understand, was his zeal for “<font color=\"#9bbb59\">fundamental fairness</font>” – protecting the taxpayer, controlling spending and ensuring that only the most deserving claimants received their benefits.\n翻译: <u>我们理应理解，他的动机是他对“根本公平”的热忱——保护纳税人、控制支出，并确保只有最应得的申请者才能领取福利。</u>\n\n-- **be to do**：<u>表示安排、要求、预期或命令。“我们被要求这样理解 / 我们应该这样理解。”</u>\n-- **for “fundamental fairness”**：<u>对“根本公平”的追求</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nLosing a job is hurting: you don’t<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> skip down to</font> the jobcentre with a song in your heart, delighted at the prospect of doubling your income from the generous state.\n翻译: <u>失业是痛苦的：你不会心中唱着歌、蹦蹦跳跳地去就业中心，并为有望从慷慨的国家那里使收入翻倍而欣喜。</u>\n\n- **don’t skip down to**：<u>不会蹦蹦跳跳地去。</u>\n- **skip**：<u>这里不是“跳过”，而是“蹦跳着走”。</u>\n- \n\n---\n\nIt is financially terrifying, psychologically embarrassing and you know that support is minimal and extraordinarily hard to get.\n翻译: <u>这在财务上令人恐惧，在心理上令人尴尬，而且你知道，支持微乎其微且极难获得。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYou are now<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> not wanted</font>; you are now excluded from the work environment that offers<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> purpose</font> and<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> structure</font> in your life.\n翻译: <u>你如今不再被需要；你如今被排除在那个为你生活提供目标和结构的工作环境之外。</u>\n\n- **not wanted**：<u>不被需要，不受欢迎。</u>\n- **purpose**：<u>目标、意义。</u>\n- **structure**：<u>结构、秩序、日常安排。</u>\n\n---\n\nWorse, the crucial income to feed yourself and your family and pay the bills has disappeared.\n翻译: <u>更糟的是，用来养活自己和家人并支付账单的关键收入已经消失。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAsk anyone newly unemployed what they want and the answer is always: a job.\n翻译: <u>问任何一个新近失业的人他们想要什么，答案总是：一份工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut in Osborneland, your<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> first instinc</font>t is to fall into dependency – permanent dependency if you can get it – supported by a state only too ready to indulge your falsehood.\n翻译: <u>但在 Osborne 的世界里，你的第一本能就是陷入依赖——如果可以的话，就是永久依赖——由一个过于乐意纵容你谎言的国家来支撑。</u>\n\n- **first instinct**：<u>第一反应、本能。</u>\n- \n\n---\n\nIt is<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> as though</font> 20 years of <font color=\"#9bbb59\">ever-tougher</font> reforms of the job search and<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> benefit administration system</font> never happened.\n翻译: <u>这就好像 20 年来对求职和福利管理制度日益严厉的改革从未发生过一样。</u>\n\n- **as though**：<u>好像，仿佛。</u>\n-  **ever-tougher**：<u>越来越严格的。</u>\n- - **benefit administration system**：<u>福利管理制度。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe principle of British welfare is no longer that you can insure yourself against the risk of unemployment and receive unconditional payments if the disaster happens.\n翻译: <u>英国福利的原则不再是：你可以为失业风险给自己投保，并在灾难发生时获得无条件付款。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> the very phrase</font> “jobseeker’s allowance” is about redefining the unemployed as a “jobseeker” who had no fundamental right to a benefit he or she has earned through making national insurance contributions.\n翻译: <u>甚至“求职者津贴”这个短语本身，就是在把失业者重新定义为“求职者”，而不是一个通过缴纳国民保险费赚得福利、因而对福利拥有基本权利的人。</u>\n\n- **the very phrase**：<u>这个词语本身。**very** 在这里不是“非常”，而是“正是这个、本身这个”</u>\n- <u>连“求职者津贴”这个名称本身都在改变福利逻辑：它把失业者说成“求职者”，从而削弱了他们基于国民保险缴费本应享有的福利权利。</u>\n\n---\n\nInstead, the claimant receives a time-limited “allowance,” <font color=\"#9bbb59\">conditional on</font> actively seeking a job; no <font color=\"#9bbb59\">entitlement</font> and no <font color=\"#9bbb59\">insurance</font>, at £71.70 a week, one of the least generous in the EU.\n翻译: <u>相反，申请者领取的是有时间限制的“津贴”，条件是积极寻找工作；没有权利，也没有保险，每周 £71.70，是欧盟中最不慷慨的福利之一。</u>\n\n-**conditional on sth. / doing sth.**：<u>以……为条件。</u>\n-- **entitlement**：<u>应得权利、法定权利。</u>\n- **insurance**：<u>保险保障。</u>\n\n第二篇\nAll around the world, lawyers generate more hostility than the members of any other profession – with the possible exception of journalism.\n翻译: <u>在世界各地，律师招致的敌意都超过任何其他职业的成员——新闻业或许除外。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut there are few places where clients have more<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> grounds for</font> complaint than America.\n翻译: <u>但很少有地方的客户比美国客户更有理由抱怨。</u>\n\n-**grounds for complaint**：<u>抱怨的理由，投诉的根据。</u>\n\n---\n\nDuring the decade before the economic crisis, spending on legal services in America grew <font color=\"#9bbb59\">twice as fast as inflation.</font>\n翻译: <u>在经济危机前的十年里，美国法律服务支出的增长速度是通货膨胀的两倍。</u>\n\n-**twice as fast as inflation**：<u>速度是通货膨胀的两倍。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe best lawyers made skyscrapers-full of money, tempting ever more students to pile into law schools.\n翻译: <u>最优秀的律师赚得盆满钵满，诱使越来越多的学生涌入法学院。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut most law graduates never get <font color=\"#9bbb59\">a big-firm job</font>.\n翻译: <u>但大多数法学院毕业生从未得到大型律所的工作。</u>\n\n- **a big-firm job**：<u>大型律师事务所的工作，通常意味着高薪、体面、竞争激烈。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nMany of them <font color=\"#9bbb59\">instead</font> become the kind of<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> nuisance</font>-lawsuit <font color=\"#9bbb59\">filer</font> that makes the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">tort system</font> a costly nightmare.\n翻译: <u>他们中的许多人反而成了那种提起滋扰性诉讼的人，使侵权制度变成一场代价高昂的噩梦。</u>\n\n- instead**：<u>反而，代替原本期待的大所职业道路。</u>\n- **nuisance-lawsuit filer**：<u>烦扰性诉讼/滥诉的提起者。</u>\n- **the tort system**：<u>侵权法/侵权诉讼体系。</u>\n- <u>许多人进不了大律所，反而转向提起各种骚扰性诉讼，结果让侵权诉讼体系变得成本高昂、令人头疼。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThere are many reasons for this.\n翻译: <u>造成这种情况有很多原因。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOne is the excessive costs of a legal education.\n翻译: <u>其中一个原因是法律教育成本过高。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere is just one path for a lawyer in most American states: a four-year undergraduate degree in some unrelated subject, then a three-year law degree at one of 200 law schools authorized by the American Bar Association and an expensive preparation for the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">bar exam</font>.\n翻译: <u>在美国大多数州，成为律师只有一条路：先在某个不相关的学科取得四年制本科学位，然后在美国律师协会授权的 200 所法学院之一攻读三年法律学位，并为律师资格考试进行昂贵的备考。</u>\n\n-**the bar exam**：<u>律师资格考试。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis leaves today’s average law-school graduate with $100,000 of debt on top of undergraduate debts.\n翻译: <u>这使得如今普通法学院毕业生在本科债务之外，又背负了 $100,000 的债务。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nLaw-school debt means that they have to work fearsomely hard.\n翻译: <u>法学院债务意味着他们不得不极其拼命地工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nReforming the system would help both lawyers and their customers.\n翻译: <u>改革这一制度将有助于律师和他们的客户。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">Sensible ideas</font> have<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> been around</font> for a long time, but the state-level <font color=\"#9bbb59\">bodies</font> that <font color=\"#9bbb59\">govern</font> the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">profession</font> have been too conservative to implement them.\n翻译: <u>合理的想法早已存在，但管理这一行业的州级机构过于保守，未能实施这些想法。</u>\n\n-  **Sensible ideas**：<u>合理的想法，明智的方案。</u>\n- **have been around**：<u>已经存在，早就有。</u>\n- **bodies**：<u>机构，组织。</u>\n- **govern**：<u>管理，监管。</u>\n- **the profession**：<u>这个职业，指法律职业。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nOne idea is to allow people to study law as an undergraduate degree.\n翻译: <u>一个想法是允许人们在本科阶段学习法律。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnother is to let students <font color=\"#9bbb59\">sit for</font> the bar after only two years of law school.\n翻译: <u>另一个想法是让学生只读两年法学院后就参加律师资格考试。</u>\n\n\n-**sit for the bar**：<u>参加律师资格考试。sit for 专门指参加考试</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIf the bar exam is truly a stern enough test for a would-be lawyer, those who can sit it earlier should be allowed to do so.\n翻译: <u>如果律师资格考试确实足够严格，足以检验一个想成为律师的人，那么那些能够更早参加考试的人就应被允许这样做。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nStudents who do not need the extra training could cut their debt mountain by <font color=\"#9bbb59\">a third</font>.\n翻译: <u>不需要额外培训的学生可以把他们的债务高山削减三分之一。</u>\n\n-**by a third**：<u>减少三分之一。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe other reason why costs are so high is the restrictive <font color=\"#9bbb59\">guild-like</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">ownership structure</font> of the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">business</font>.\n翻译: <u>成本如此之高的另一个原因，是这一行业限制性的、类似行会的所有权结构。</u>\n\n- **guild-like**：<u>像行会一样的。</u>\n-  ownership structure：<u>所有权结构。</u>\n- **of the business**：<u>这个行业的，指法律服务行业。</u>\n\n---\n\nExcept in the District of Columbia, non-lawyers <font color=\"#9bbb59\">may not</font> own any share of a law firm.\n翻译: <u>除哥伦比亚特区外，非律师不得拥有律师事务所的任何股份。</u>\n\n-**may not**：<u>不得，不被允许。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis keeps fees high and innovation slow.\n翻译: <u>这使费用居高不下，创新进展缓慢。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere is pressure for change <font color=\"#9bbb59\">from within the profession</font>, but <font color=\"#9bbb59\">opponents of change</font> among the regulators insist that keeping outsiders out of a law firm isolates lawyers from the pressure to make money <font color=\"#9bbb59\">rather than</font> serve clients <font color=\"#9bbb59\">ethically</font>.\n翻译: <u>行业内部存在变革压力，但监管者中的变革反对者坚持认为，将外部人士排除在律师事务所之外，可以使律师免受赚钱压力的影响，从而以合乎伦理的方式服务客户。</u>\n\n- ** from within the profession**：<u>来自这个职业内部。这里的 within 特指,内部的</u>\n- **opponents of change**：<u>改革的反对者。</u>\n- **serve clients ethically**：<u>以合乎职业伦理的方式服务客户。</u>\n- rather than <u>而不是 后面的是不是的部分</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIn fact, allowing non-lawyers to own shares in law firms would reduce costs and improve services to customers, by encouraging law firms to use technology and to employ professional managers to focus on improving firms’ efficiency.\n翻译: <u>事实上，允许非律师持有律师事务所股份，将通过鼓励律所使用技术并雇用职业经理人专注于提高律所效率，来降低成本并改善对客户的服务。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">After all</font>, other countries, such as Australia and Britain, have started liberalizing their legal professions.\n翻译: <u>毕竟，澳大利亚和英国等其他国家已经开始放宽对法律职业的限制。</u>\n\n-**After all**：<u>毕竟，归根结底。 **After all** 常用来引出一个“支持前文判断的理由”。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmerica should follow.\n翻译: <u>美国应当效仿。</u>\n\n()\n\n\n\n第三篇\n\n<u>心得:</u>\n- <u>这篇虽然全对了但是只是看懂了百分之 80 以上</u>\n- <u>一定要有根据,但是依照英语 1的难度,不可能是原原本本的根据,一定是某个别的词,根据<font color=\"#9bbb59\">逻辑推理</font>可以推出来这个结论</u>\n- <u>之前写的确实有点浪费了,但是也没啥,做个 5-6 年 熟悉一下模式,反正后面的题也没做,自己做一遍,然后再去读,印象会更深</u>\n\nThe US$3-million Fundamental Physics Prize is <font color=\"#9bbb59\">indeed</font> an interesting experiment, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">as</font> Alexander Polyakov said when he accepted this year’s award in March.\n翻译: <u>正如 Alexander Polyakov 在今年 3 月接受该奖项时所说，300 万美元的 Fundamental Physics Prize 的确是一项有趣的实验。</u>\n\n- **indeed**：<u>副词，表示“确实、的确”，加强判断语气。</u>\n- **as**：<u>正如</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd it is <font color=\"#9bbb59\">far from</font> the only one of<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> its type</font>.\n翻译: <u>而且它远非同类中唯一的一项。</u>\n\n- **far from**：<u>远非，绝不是。</u>\n- **of its type**：<u>同类型的。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs a <font color=\"#9bbb59\">News Feature article</font> in Nature discusses, a string of lucrative awards for researchers have<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> joined the Nobel Prizes </font>in recent years.\n翻译: <u>正如 Nature 的一篇新闻特写文章所讨论的那样，近年来，一连串为研究人员设立的丰厚奖项加入了诺贝尔奖的行列。</u>\n\n-**a News Feature article**：<u>一篇新闻特写文章。</u>\n-<u>这里的 joined 不是加入了诺贝尔奖 而是说 加入了这种和诺贝尔奖一样的竞争层级</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">Many,</font> like the Fundamental Physics Prize, are funded from the telephone-number-sized bank accounts of Internet entrepreneurs.\n翻译: <u>其中许多奖项像 Fundamental Physics Prize 一样，资金来自互联网企业家那些数额像电话号码一样长的银行账户。</u>\n\n-**Many** <u>指代前一句中的 **a string of lucrative awards**，即“一系列奖金丰厚的奖项”中的许多</u>\n\n---\n\nThese benefactors have succeeded in their chosen fields, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">they say</font>, and they want to use their wealth to draw attention to those who have succeeded in science.\n翻译: <u>这些赞助者说，他们已经在自己选择的领域取得成功，并希望利用自己的财富来吸引人们关注那些在科学领域取得成功的人。</u>\n\n-<u>这个插入语很关键，暗示作者与这些资助者的说法保持一定距离，不完全替他们背书。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">What’s not to like?</font>\n翻译: <u>有什么不讨人喜欢的呢？</u>\n\n-<u>实际意思是“这听起来不是挺好吗？”</u>\n\n---\n\nQuite a lot, according to <font color=\"#9bbb59\">a handful of</font> scientists quoted in the News Feature.\n翻译: <u>据《新闻特写》中引用的几位科学家说，不讨人喜欢的地方相当多。</u>\n\n-**a handful of** <u>暗示人数不多，也可能降低这些批评声音的代表性。</u>\n\n---\n\nYou cannot buy <font color=\"#9bbb59\">class</font>, as the old saying goes, and these <font color=\"#9bbb59\">upstart</font> entrepreneurs cannot buy their prizes the prestige of the Nobels.\n翻译: <u>俗话说，品位是买不来的，而这些新贵企业家也无法用钱为他们的奖项买来诺贝尔奖那样的声望。</u>\n\n-**class**：<u>格调、品位、体面、真正的尊贵感。</u>\n-**upstart** <u>带有贬义，指突然发财、地位新近上升但缺乏传统声望的人。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe new awards <font color=\"#9bbb59\">are an exercise in</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">self-promotion</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">for those behind them</font>, say scientists.\n翻译: <u>科学家们说，这些新奖项是其幕后人士的一种自我宣传。</u>\n\n-**are an exercise in…**：<u>是一种……行为 / 做法。</u>\n-**self-promotion**：<u>自我宣传</u>\n-**for those behind them**：<u>对那些在背后推动这些奖项的人来说。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey could distort the achievement-based system of peer-review-led research.\n翻译: <u>它们可能扭曲由同行评议主导、以成就为基础的研究体系。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey could cement <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the status quo</font> of peer-reviewed research.\n翻译: <u>它们可能巩固同行评议研究的现状。</u>\n\n- **the status quo**：<u>现状，已有格局。 组合起来的 quo 一般不单独出现</u>\n- <u>这些奖项也可能进一步固化学术界原有的权力结构和评价格局。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey do not fund peer-reviewed research.\n翻译: <u>它们并不资助经过同行评议的研究。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey perpetuate the myth of <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the lone genius</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们延续了孤独天才的神话。</u>\n\n- the lone genius**：<u>孤独天才，指一个人凭借天赋独自完成伟大发现的形象。</u>\n- <u>批评点在于：现代科研往往是团队合作，而奖项却容易突出个人英雄。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe goals of the prize-givers seem <font color=\"#9bbb59\">as scattered as</font> the criticism.\n翻译: <u>颁奖者的目标似乎和批评意见一样分散。</u>\n\n-**as scattered as…**：<u>和……一样分散 / 零散。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome want to <font color=\"#9bbb59\">shock</font>, others to draw people into science, or to better reward those who have <font color=\"#9bbb59\">made their careers in research</font>.\n翻译: <u>有些人想制造震动，另一些人则想吸引人们进入科学领域，或更好地奖励那些把职业生涯投入研究的人。</u>\n\n- **want to shock**：<u>想要震动公众、制造冲击效果。</u>\n- **have made their careers in research**：<u>把科研作为职业生涯的人。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs Nature has pointed out before, there are some <font color=\"#9bbb59\">legitimate concerns</font> about how science prizes – both new and old – are distributed.\n翻译: <u>正如《Nature》此前指出的，对于科学奖项——无论新旧——如何分配，确实存在一些合理的担忧。</u>\n\n-**some legitimate concerns**：<u>一些合理的担忧。</u>\n-<u>不要被这两个横杠给迷惑了,前后连起来就好说了 how science prizes are distributed.</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">launched</font> this year, takes an <font color=\"#9bbb59\">unrepresentative</font> view of what the life sciences include.\n翻译: <u>今年设立的生命科学突破奖，对生命科学所涵盖的内容采取了一种不具代表性的看法。</u>\n\n- **launched**：<u>被推出、被设立。</u>\n- **unrepresentative**：<u>不具代表性的，不能反映整体情况的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the Nobel Foundation’s limit of three recipients per prize, each of whom must still be living, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">has long been outgrown</font> by <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the collaborative nature of modern research</font> – as will be <font color=\"#9bbb59\">demonstrated</font> by the inevitable <font color=\"#9bbb59\">row</font> over who is ignored when it comes to acknowledging the discovery of the Higgs boson.\n翻译: <u>但诺贝尔基金会规定每个奖项最多三名获奖者且每个人都必须仍然在世，这一限制早已不适应现代研究的合作性质——这一点将会由在承认希格斯玻色子发现时，围绕谁被忽略而不可避免爆发的争论来证明。</u>\n\n- **has long been outgrown**：<u>早已被超越，已经不合时宜。</u>\n- **by the collaborative nature of modern research**：<u>被现代科研的合作性质所超越。</u>\n- **as will be demonstrated**：<u>正如将会被证明。</u>\n- **row** <u>在英式英语中常指“争吵、争议”。</u>\n- <u>不过，诺贝尔奖每项最多三人且必须授予在世者的规定，早已不适应现代科研高度协作的现实。希格斯玻色子发现的归属问题势必引发争议，也正会说明这一点。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Nobels were, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">of course</font>, themselves set up by a very rich individual who had decided what he wanted to do with his own money.\n翻译: <u>当然，诺贝尔奖本身也是由一位非常富有的个人设立的，他决定了自己想如何处置自己的钱。</u>\n\n-of course <u>不是白插入的  **of course 的核心作用：把信息标成“常识性提醒”**</u>\n\n<u>所以它的语气不是：我告诉你一个新事实。</u>\n<u>而是：别忘了，诺贝尔奖自己也一样。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nTime, rather than intention, has given them<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> legitimacy</font>.\n翻译: <u>赋予它们合法性的，是时间，而非初衷。</u>\n\n- **legitimacy**：<u>合法性、正当性、权威性。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#9bbb59\">As much as</font> some scientists may complain about the new awards, two things seem clear.\n翻译: <u>尽管一些科学家可能会抱怨这些新奖项，但有两件事似乎很清楚。</u>\n\n- **As much as…**：<u>尽管……，虽然……很大程度上。</u>\n\n---\n\nFirst, most researchers would accept such a prize if they were offered one.\n翻译: <u>第一，如果获得提名，大多数研究人员都会接受这样的奖项。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSecond, it is surely a good thing that the money and attention come to science rather than go elsewhere.\n翻译: <u>第二，金钱和关注流向科学而不是流向别处，这无疑是一件好事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is <font color=\"#9bbb59\">fair</font> to criticize and question the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">mechanism</font> – that is the culture of research, <font color=\"#9bbb59\">after all</font> – but it is the prize-givers’ money to do with as they please.\n翻译: <u>批评和质疑其机制是合理的——毕竟这正是研究文化的一部分——但那是颁奖者的钱，他们可以按自己的意愿支配。</u>\n\n-   **It is fair to…**：<u>做……是合理的。</u>\n-  **the mechanism**：<u>这种机制，即奖项设立、评选和分配机制。</u>\n- **after all**：<u>毕竟。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is wise to take such gifts with gratitude and grace.\n翻译: <u>以感激和体面之态接受这样的馈赠，是明智的。</u>\n\n()\n\n\n第四篇\n- <u>分析文章的时候,一定要搞清楚主语,不要误判动作</u>\n- <u>文章很多时候在陈述某些人或者观点的时候,那些人/观点本身就是偏激的,所以分析答案的时候,不要自己先主观预设一个中性立场,需要忠实于原文</u>\n- <u>遇到那种,句子特长的 一定要注意核心结构 treat xx as 有时候这两个部分之间会隔非常远</u>\n\n“The Heart of the Matter,” the just-released report by the American Academy of Arts and Sciences (AAAS), deserves praise for affirming the importance of the humanities and social sciences <font color=\"#9bbb59\">to</font> the prosperity and security of liberal democracy in America.\n翻译: <u>美国艺术与科学院（AAAS）刚刚发布的报告《问题的核心》，因肯定人文学科和社会科学对于美国自由民主的繁荣与安全的重要性而值得赞扬。</u>\n\n-<u>介词 to 引出“重要性所指向的对象”。  核心是 the importance to</u>\n\n\n---\n\nRegrettably, however, the report’s <font color=\"#9bbb59\">failure to</font> address the true nature of the crisis facing liberal education may cause more harm than good.\n翻译: <u>然而令人遗憾的是，该报告未能触及自由教育所面临危机的真实本质，可能弊大于利。</u>\n\n-failure to do <u>表示“未能做某事”。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nIn 2010, leading congressional Democrats and Republicans sent letters to the AAAS <font color=\"#9bbb59\">asking that</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">it identify actions</font> that could be taken by “federal, state and local governments, universities, foundations, educators, individual benefactors and others” to “maintain national excellence in humanities and social scientific <font color=\"#9bbb59\">scholarship</font> and education.”\n翻译: <u>2010年，国会中民主党和共和党的主要成员致信AAAS，要求其确定“联邦、州和地方政府，大学，基金会，教育工作者，个人捐助者以及其他方面”可以采取哪些行动，以“保持国家在人文学科和社会科学学术与教育方面的卓越水平”。</u>\n\n-**ask that + <u>主语 + 动词原形** 要求……做某事 it 指代 AAAS</u>\n-scholarship <u>指学术研究。</u>  \n2010 <u>年，国会两党重要成员要求 AAAS 提出行动建议，说明政府、大学、基金会和社会各方应如何维护美国人文社科研究与教育的领先地位。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nIn response, the American Academy formed the Commission on the Humanities and Social Sciences.\n翻译: <u>作为回应，美国艺术与科学院成立了人文学科与社会科学委员会。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAmong the commission’s 51 members are top-tier-university presidents, scholars, lawyers, judges, and business executives,<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> as well as</font> <font color=\"#9bbb59\">prominent figures</font> from diplomacy, filmmaking, music and journalism.\n翻译: <u>该委员会的51名成员包括顶尖大学校长、学者、律师、法官和企业高管，也包括来自外交、电影制作、音乐和新闻领域的杰出人物。</u>\n\n-prominent figures <u>指“知名人物、重要人物”。</u>  \n-as well as <u>连接补充成分。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe goals <font color=\"#9bbb59\">identified</font> in the report are <font color=\"#9bbb59\">generally</font> admirable.\n翻译: <u>报告中确定的目标总体上令人钦佩。</u>\n\n-identified <u>表示“被确定、被提出”。</u>  \n-generally <u>表示“总体而言”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBecause representative government <font color=\"#9bbb59\">presupposes</font> an <font color=\"#9bbb59\">informed citizenry</font>, the report supports <font color=\"#9bbb59\">full literacy</font>; stresses the study of history and government, particularly American history and American government; and encourages the use of new digital technologies.\n翻译: <u>由于代议制政府以知情的公民为前提，该报告支持全面读写能力；强调历史和政府研究，尤其是美国历史和美国政府研究；并鼓励使用新的数字技术。</u>\n\n-presupposes <u>表示“以……为前提”。</u>\n-an informed citizenry <u>指“有知识、有判断力的公民群体”。</u>  \n-full literacy <u>不只是识字，也可理解为充分的读写与理解能力。</u>  \n<u>这是报告提出的第一个教育目标。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo encourage innovation and competition, the report calls for increased investment in research, the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">crafting</font> of <font color=\"#9bbb59\">coherent curricula</font> that improve students’ ability to solve problems and communicate effectively in the 21st century, increased funding for teachers and the encouragement of scholars to <font color=\"#9bbb59\">bring their learning to bear </font>on the great challenges of the day.\n翻译: <u>为鼓励创新和竞争，该报告呼吁增加研究投资，制定连贯的课程体系以提高学生在21世纪解决问题和有效沟通的能力，增加教师经费，并鼓励学者运用其学识来应对当今的重大挑战。</u>\n\n-crafting <u>表示“精心设计、制定”。</u> \n-coherent curricula <u>指“连贯一致的课程体系”。</u>\n-bring A to bear on B <u>是固定表达，意为“把 A 应用于 B”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe report also advocates greater study of foreign languages, international affairs and the expansion of study abroad programs.\n翻译: <u>该报告还主张加强外语、国际事务的学习，并扩大海外学习项目。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, despite <font color=\"#9bbb59\">2 1/2 years in the making,</font> “The Heart of the Matter” never gets to the heart of the matter: the illiberal nature of liberal education at our leading colleges and universities.\n翻译: <u>不幸的是，尽管历时2年半才完成，《问题的核心》却从未触及问题的核心：我们顶尖学院和大学中自由教育的非自由性质。</u>\n\n-2 1/2 years in the making <u>表示“历时两年半制作”。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe commission ignores that for several decades America’s colleges and universities have produced graduates who don’t know the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">content</font> and <font color=\"#9bbb59\">characte</font>r of liberal education and are thus deprived of its benefits.\n翻译: <u>委员会忽视了这样一个事实：几十年来，美国的学院和大学培养出的毕业生并不了解自由教育的内容和性质，因此被剥夺了其益处。</u>\n\n-content <u>指具体内容。</u>  \n-character <u>指性质、精神、特征。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSadly, the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">spirit of inquiry</font> once <font color=\"#9bbb59\">at home on campus</font> has been replaced by<font color=\"#9bbb59\"> the use of</font> the humanities and social sciences <font color=\"#9bbb59\">as</font> vehicles for publicizing “progressive,” or left-liberal propaganda.\n翻译: <u>令人悲哀的是，曾经在校园中自在存在的探究精神，已被把人文学科和社会科学用作宣传“进步主义”或左翼自由主义宣传工具的做法所取代。</u>\n\n-the spirit of inquiry <u>指探究精神、求知精神。</u>  \n-at home on campus <u>表示“在校园中自在存在、原本属于校园”。</u>  \n-the use of…as… <u>表示“把……用作……”。</u>  \n\n\n\n---\n\nToday, professors routinely treat <font color=\"#9bbb59\">the progressive interpretation </font>of history and progressive public policy as the <font color=\"#9bbb59\">proper </font>subject of study <font color=\"#9bbb59\">while </font>portraying conservative or classical liberal ideas – such as free markets and self-reliance – <font color=\"#9bbb59\">as falling outside</font> the boundaries of routine, and <font color=\"#9bbb59\">sometimes</font> legitimate, intellectual investigation.\n翻译: <u>如今，教授们通常把对历史的进步主义解读和进步主义公共政策当作适当的研究对象，同时把保守主义或古典自由主义观念——如自由市场和自力更生——描述为处于常规的、有时甚至是合法的智识探究范围之外。</u>\n\n-the progressive interpretation of history <u>指进步主义对历史的解释。</u>  \n-the proper subject of study <u>指合适的、正当的研究对象。</u>\n-while <u>在这里不是单纯表示“当……时候”，而是表示“然而、与此同时却”。</u> \n-sometime <u>后面省略了 <font color=\"#9bbb59\">as falling outside</font> 实际上是,这个对理解大关键,因为看起来句子成分很缺失,就要考虑,是不是省略了什么部分</u>\nas falling outside the boundaries of **routine intellectual investigation**, and sometimes **outside the boundaries of legitimate intellectual investigation**\n翻译: <u>处于**常规智识探究**的范围之外，有时甚至处于**合法智识探究**的范围之外</u>\n-<u>地道意译：作者批评说，当今大学教师往往把进步主义观点视为正常研究内容，却把自由市场、自立等保守或古典自由主义思想排除在严肃学术讨论之外。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe AAAS displays great enthusiasm for liberal education.\n翻译: <u>AAAS对自由教育表现出极大的热情。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYet its report <font color=\"#9bbb59\">may well</font> set back reform by <font color=\"#9bbb59\">obscuring</font> the depth and breadth of the challenge that Congress asked it to illuminate.\n翻译: <u>然而，其报告通过掩盖国会要求它阐明的挑战的深度和广度，很可能阻碍改革。</u>\n\n-may well <u>表示“很可能”。</u>  \n-obscuring <u>表示“遮蔽、模糊、使不清楚”。</u>  \n\n<u>直译：然而，它的报告很可能通过遮蔽国会要求它阐明的挑战的深度和广度，从而阻碍改革。</u>  \n\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2015","year":"2015","title":"2015 年英语一","fileName":"2015 年英语 一.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2015 年英语 一.md","content":"第一篇\n\n\nKing Juan Carlos of Spain <font color=\"#00b050\">once</font> insisted “kings don’t <font color=\"#00b050\">abdicate</font>, they die in their sleep.”\n翻译: <u>西班牙国王Juan Carlos曾坚持说，“国王不会退位，他们会在睡梦中死去。”</u>\n\n-**once** <u>表示“过去某个时候”。这里暗示他说过这句话，但后来情况发生了变化。</u>\n-**abdicate**：<u>退位，放弃王位。</u> \n\n---\n\nBut embarrassing scandals and <font color=\"#00b050\">the popularity of the republican</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">left</font> in the recent Euro-elections have forced him to eat his words and <font color=\"#00b050\">stand down.</font>\n翻译: <u>但令人尴尬的丑闻以及共和派左翼在最近欧洲选举中的受欢迎程度，迫使他收回前言并退位。</u>\n\n-**the popularity of the republican left**：<u>共和派左翼的受欢迎程度。</u>  \n-**stand down** <u>指从职位上退下来。这里对应前一句的 **abdicate**，即“退位”。</u>\n\n---\n\nSo, does the Spanish crisis suggest that monarchy is <font color=\"#00b050\">seeing its last days</font>?\n翻译: <u>那么，西班牙危机是否表明君主制正在走向末日？</u>\n\n-**see one’s last days**：<u>经历最后的日子，即“走到尽头”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nDoes that mean the writing is on the wall for all European royals, with their magnificent uniforms and majestic lifestyles?\n翻译: <u>这是否意味着，所有穿着华丽制服、过着威严生活方式的欧洲王室都大势已去？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe Spanish case<font color=\"#00b050\"> provides arguments</font> both for and against monarchy.\n翻译: <u>西班牙的例子为支持和反对君主制都提供了论据。</u>\n\n-**provide arguments**：<u>提供论点、理由、论据。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">When</font> public opinion is particularly <font color=\"#00b050\">polarised</font>, <font color=\"#00b050\">as it was</font> following the end of the Franco regime, monarchs can rise above <font color=\"#00b050\">“mere”</font> politics and <font color=\"#00b050\">“embody”</font> a spirit of national unity.\n翻译: <u>当公众意见尤其两极分化时，正如Franco政权结束后那样，君主可以超越“单纯的”政治，并“体现”一种民族团结精神。</u>\n\n-<u>这个 when 是引导了个从句,强调了背景,还蛮重要的</u>\n-**polarised**：<u>两极化的，严重分裂的。</u>  \n-**as it was** <u>中的 **it** 指 **public opinion**。</u>\n-<u>正如佛朗哥政权结束后那样。</u>\n-**mere politics**：<u>所谓的普通政治、狭义政治。</u>  \n<u>引号中的 **“mere”** 带有轻微讽刺或保留态度，表示作者不完全接受这种说法。</u>\n-**embody**：<u>体现、代表、化身为。</u> \n-<u>在民意高度撕裂的时期，比如佛朗哥政权结束后的西班牙，君主往往可以被塑造成超越党派政治、象征国家团结的人物。</u>\n-\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">It is</font> this<font color=\"#00b050\"> apparent</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">transcendence</font> of politics <font color=\"#00b050\">that</font> explains<font color=\"#00b050\"> monarchs’</font> continuing popularity as heads of state.\n翻译: <u>正是这种表面上的超越政治，解释了君主作为国家元首持续受欢迎的原因。</u>\n\n-<u>这里用 **It is…that…** 强调原因。</u>\n-**apparent**：<u>表面上的、看起来的。</u>  \n-**transcendence of politics**：<u>超越政治。</u>\n-**monarchs’** <u>是所有格，表示“君主们的”。</u>\n-<u>君主之所以还能作为国家元首受到欢迎，正是因为他们看起来能够超越日常政治纷争。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nAnd so, the <font color=\"#00b050\">Middle East excepted</font>, Europe is the most monarch-<font color=\"#00b050\">infested</font> region in the world, <font color=\"#00b050\">with</font> 10 kingdoms, not counting <font color=\"#00b050\">Vatican City</font> and Andorra.\n翻译: <u>因此，除中东外，欧洲是世界上君主制最泛滥的地区，拥有10个王国，还不包括梵蒂冈城和安道尔。</u>\n\n-**if the Middle East is excepted**  <u>即“如果把中东排除在外”。</u>\n-**infested** <u>常用于“害虫、问题大量滋生”，如 rat-infested。</u>  \n-**with** <u>在这里表示“具有、拥有”</u>\n-**Vatican City**：<u>梵蒂冈城国。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut unlike their absolutist counterparts in the Gulf and Asia, most royal families <font color=\"#00b050\">have survived</font> because they allow voters to avoid the difficult search for a non-controversial but respected public figure.\n翻译: <u>但与海湾地区和亚洲的专制君主不同，大多数王室之所以得以存续，是因为它们让选民避免了艰难地寻找一位无争议但受尊敬的公众人物。</u>\n\n-**have survived** <u>表示这些王室从过去延续到现在。</u>  \n<u>这里的 survive 不只是“活下来”，而是“制度上继续存在”。</u>\n-<u>地道意译：不过，欧洲王室不同于海湾和亚洲那些掌握实权的专制君主。它们能保留下来，很大程度上是因为它们替选民省去了一个麻烦：不用再费力寻找一位既不惹争议、又能受人尊敬的国家象征。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Even so</font>, kings and queens undoubtedly have a downside.\n翻译: <u>即便如此，国王和女王无疑也有不利的一面。</u>\n\n-**Even so** <u>表示“尽管前面说了君主制有好处，但仍然……”。</u>  \n<u>它引出君主制的问题。</u>\n\n---\n\nSymbolic of national unity <font color=\"#00b050\">as</font> they claim to be, their <font color=\"#00b050\">very</font> history — and sometimes the way they behave today — embodies outdated and indefensible privileges and inequalities.\n翻译: <u>尽管他们自称象征民族团结，但他们自身的历史——有时还有他们今天的行为方式——体现了过时且站不住脚的特权和不平等。</u>\n\n-**as** <u>在这里相当于“尽管”。</u>\n-**very** <u>在这里不是“非常”，而是“正是的、恰恰是的”。</u>  \n**their very history**：<u>他们那一整套历史本身。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">At a time when</font> Thomas Piketty and other economists are warning of rising inequality and the increasing power of inherited wealth, it is <font color=\"#00b050\">bizarre</font> that wealthy aristocratic families <font color=\"#00b050\">should still be</font> the symbolic heart of modern democratic states.\n翻译: <u>在Thomas Piketty和其他经济学家警告不平等加剧以及继承财富的力量日益增强之际，富有的贵族家庭仍然是现代民主国家的象征核心，这很荒谬。</u>\n\n-**At a time when…**：<u>在一个……的时代。</u>  \n-**bizarre**：<u>奇怪的、荒谬的、不可思议的。</u>\n-**should still be** <u>中的 **should** 带有惊讶、不可思议的语气，不是“应该”</u>\n\n---\n\nThe most successful monarchies strive to abandon or hide their old aristocratic <font color=\"#00b050\">ways</font>.\n翻译: <u>最成功的君主制努力抛弃或隐藏其旧式贵族做派。</u>\n\n-**ways**：<u>方式、作风。</u> \n\n\n---\n\nPrinces and princesses have day-jobs and ride bicycles, not horses or helicopters.\n翻译: <u>王子和公主有日常工作，骑自行车，而不是骑马或乘直升机。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven so, these are wealthy families who <font color=\"#00b050\">party with </font>the international 1%, and <font color=\"#00b050\">media intrusiveness</font> makes it increasingly difficult to maintain the <font color=\"#00b050\">right image</font>.\n翻译: <u>即便如此，这些仍是与国际1%精英一起聚会的富裕家庭，而媒体的侵扰使保持正确形象变得越来越困难。</u>\n\n-**party with**：<u>和……一起参加派对。</u> \n-**intrusiveness** <u>来自 intrusive，意思是“侵入性的、打扰性的”。</u>  \n<u>指媒体不断曝光王室私生活。</u>\n-**the right image**：<u>合适的公众形象，即亲民、普通、节制的形象。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile Europe’s monarchies will no doubt be smart enough to survive <font color=\"#00b050\">for some time to come</font>, it is the British royals who have most to fear from the Spanish example.\n翻译: <u>虽然欧洲的君主制无疑会足够聪明，在未来一段时间内继续存续，但从西班牙的例子中最应感到担忧的是英国王室。</u>\n\n-**for some time to come**：<u>在未来一段时间内。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is only the Queen who has preserved the monarchy’s reputation with her <font color=\"#00b050\">rather ordinary</font>, if <font color=\"#00b050\">well-heeled</font>, granny style.\n翻译: <u>正是女王凭借她相当普通、尽管富裕的祖母式风格，维护了君主制的声誉。</u>\n\n-**rather ordinary**：<u>相当普通、朴素。</u>  \n-**if well-heeled**：<u>尽管很富裕。</u>  \n**well-heeled**：<u>富有的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe danger will come with Charles, who has both an expensive taste of lifestyle and a pretty hierarchical view of the world.\n翻译: <u>危险将随着Charles而来，他既有昂贵的生活品味，又有相当等级化的世界观。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHe has failed to understand that monarchies have <font color=\"#00b050\">largely</font> survived because they provide a service — as non-controversial and non-political heads of state.\n翻译: <u>他未能理解，君主制之所以在很大程度上得以存续，是因为它提供了一项服务——充当无争议、非政治性的国家元首。</u>\n\n-**largely**：<u>很大程度上。</u>  \n\n---\n\nCharles<font color=\"#00b050\"> ought to</font> know that, as English history shows, it is kings, not republicans, who are the monarchy’s worst enemies.\n翻译: <u>Charles应该知道，正如英国历史所显示的，君主制最大的敌人是国王，而不是共和主义者。</u>\n\n-**ought to** <u>表示“应该”，语气比 should 更正式，也带有道义或理性上的责任感。</u>\n\n\n第二篇\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Just how much</font> does the Constitution protect your digital data?\n翻译: <u>宪法究竟在多大程度上保护你的数字数据？</u>\n\n-**how much**：<u>多少、多大程度。</u>  \n-**just** <u>在这里不是“刚刚”，而是加强语气，相当于“究竟、到底”。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nThe Supreme Court <font color=\"#00b050\">will now consider</font> whether police can search <font color=\"#00b050\">the contents of a mobile phone</font> without a warrant if the phone is on or around a person during an arrest.\n翻译: <u>最高法院现在将考虑，如果手机在逮捕过程中位于某人身上或其周围，警察是否可以在没有搜查令的情况下搜查手机内容。</u>\n\n-**will now consider**：<u>现在将审议、考虑。</u>  \n-**the contents of a mobile phone**：<u>手机里的内容，不只是手机这个物品本身。到时候后面的题目里只出现了个 phone 就不是一个东西</u>\n\n---\n\nCalifornia has asked the justices to <font color=\"#00b050\">refrain from</font> a sweeping ruling, <font color=\"#00b050\">particularly </font><font color=\"#00b050\">one</font> that upsets the old assumption that authorities may search through the possessions of suspects at the time of their arrest.\n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚州已请求大法官们避免作出范围广泛的裁决，尤其是避免作出会推翻一种旧有假设的裁决，即当局可以在逮捕嫌疑人时搜查其随身物品。</u>\n\n-**refrain from**：<u>克制不做、避免做。</u>  \n-**one** = **a sweeping ruling**。   \n-**particularly** <u>表示“尤其”。</u>  \n-<u>加州方面请求最高法院不要作出过于宽泛的判决，特别是不要推翻一个长期存在的规则：警方在逮捕嫌疑人时，可以搜查其随身物品。</u>\n\n-<u>这一句的理解有一个非常关键的地方,particularly one 指代的是前面的sweeping ruling** 也就是说 不要推翻这个 upset 旧惯例的(即搜查) 也就是说它不要推翻搜查,加州想要搜查</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is hard, <font color=\"#00b050\">the state</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">argues</font>, for judges to assess the implications of new and rapidly changing technologies.\n翻译: <u>该州辩称，法官很难评估新的且迅速变化的技术所带来的影响。</u>\n\n-**the state** <u>指加利福尼亚州。</u>  \n**argues** <u>在法律语境中常表示“主张、辩称”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe court would be <font color=\"#00b050\">recklessly</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">modest</font> if it followed California’s advice.\n翻译: <u>如果法院采纳加利福尼亚州的建议，那将是一种鲁莽的克制。</u>\n\n-- **modest** <u>本来是谨慎、谦逊；</u>\n- **recklessly** <u>是鲁莽地。</u>  \n    合起来意思是：<u>法院若太不愿意表态，反而是一种不负责任的谨慎。</u>\n\n- <u>这道题考察的就是能不能读懂作者的意思,用比较不那么容易的句子去表现他的态度</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Enough of</font> the implications are <font color=\"#00b050\">discernable</font>, <font color=\"#00b050\">even obvious,</font> so that the justices <font color=\"#00b050\">can and should</font> provide updated guidelines to police, lawyers and defendants.\n翻译: <u>足够多的影响已经可以看清，甚至显而易见，因此大法官们能够也应该为警察、律师和被告提供更新后的指导原则。</u>\n\n-**enough of…**：……<u>中足够多的一部分。</u>  \n-**discernable**：<u>可辨认的、可看出的。</u>  \n-**even obvious**：<u>甚至是显而易见的。</u>  \n-**can and should**：<u>不仅能够，而且应该。  非常坚决的语气</u>\n\n-<u>新技术带来的许多法律后果已经足够清楚了，甚至相当明显。因此，最高法院完全有能力，也有责任为警察、律师和被告制定新的规则。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#00b050\">should start by</font> discarding California’s <font color=\"#00b050\">lame argument</font> that exploring the contents of a smartphone — a <font color=\"#00b050\">vast </font>storehouse of digital information — is similar to,<font color=\"#00b050\"> say,</font> going through a suspect’s purse.\n翻译: <u>他们应首先摒弃加利福尼亚州那个站不住脚的论点，即查看智能手机——一个庞大的数字信息仓库——的内容，类似于比如翻查嫌疑人的钱包。</u>\n\n-**should start by doing**：<u>应该从做某事开始。</u>\n-**lame argument**：<u>无力的、牵强的论点。</u>  \n-**vast**：<u>巨大的。</u> \n-**say** <u>在这里是插入语，相当于“比如说”。</u>\n\n-<u>大法官们首先应当否定加州那个站不住脚的说法：查看智能手机内容，就像翻一翻嫌疑人的钱包一样。手机其实是一个巨大的数字信息仓库，二者根本不能类比。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe court has ruled that police don’t violate the <font color=\"#00b050\">Fourth Amendmen</font>t when they go through the wallet or <font color=\"#00b050\">pocketbook</font> of an arrestee without a warrant.\n翻译: <u>法院曾裁定，警察在没有搜查令的情况下翻查被逮捕者的钱包或手提包，并不违反第四修正案。</u>\n\n-**the Fourth Amendment**：<u>美国宪法第四修正案，保护公民免受不合理搜查和扣押。</u>  \n-**pocketbook**：<u>手提包、钱包。</u>  \n<u>地道意译：最高法院过去已经认定，警方逮捕某人时，即使没有搜查令，也可以翻查其钱包或手提包，这并不违反第四修正案。</u>\n-\n---\n\nBut exploring one’s smartphone is more like entering his or her home.\n翻译: <u>但查看一个人的智能手机更像是进入他或她的家。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA smartphone may contain an arrestee’s reading history, financial history, medical history and <font color=\"#00b050\">comprehensive records</font> of <font color=\"#00b050\">recent correspondence</font>.\n翻译: <u>一部智能手机可能包含被逮捕者的阅读历史、财务历史、医疗历史以及近期通信的完整记录。</u>\n\n-**comprehensive records**：<u>全面记录。</u>\n-**recent correspondence**：<u>最近的通信往来</u>\n\n---\n\nThe development of “cloud computing”, meanwhile, has made that exploration so much the easier.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，“云计算”的发展使这种查看变得容易得多。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAmericans should take steps to protect their digital privacy.\n翻译: <u>美国人应采取措施保护自己的数字隐私。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut keeping sensitive information on these devices is increasingly a requirement of normal life.\n翻译: <u>但把敏感信息保存在这些设备上，正日益成为正常生活的一项要求。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCitizens still have a right to expect private documents to remain private and protected by the <font color=\"#00b050\">Constitution’s prohibition</font> on unreasonable searches.\n翻译: <u>公民仍有权期待私人文件保持私密，并受到宪法禁止不合理搜查规定的保护。</u>\n\n-**the Constitution’s prohibition**：<u>宪法的禁止性规定。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">As so often is the case</font>, <font color=\"#00b050\">stating</font> that principle doesn’t ease the challenge of<font color=\"#00b050\"> line-drawing.</font>\n翻译: <u>正如常常出现的情况一样，陈述这一原则并不会减轻划定界限的挑战。</u>\n\n-**As is so often the case**  \n<u>意思是“情况常常如此”。</u>\n-**stating**：<u>陈述、说明。</u>  \n-**line-drawing**：<u>划线、划边界。</u>  \n<u>在法律语境中指制定明确界限：哪些情况可以搜，哪些情况必须先拿搜查令。</u>\n\n<u>不过，问题常常就在这里：原则说清楚了，并不代表边界就容易划清。</u>\n-\n---\n\nIn many cases, it would not be overly burdensome for authorities to obtain a warrant to search through phone contents.\n翻译: <u>在许多情况下，当局获取搜查令以搜查手机内容并不会过于繁琐。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey could still invalidate Fourth Amendment protections when facing severe, urgent circumstances, and they could take reasonable measures to ensure that phone data are not erased or altered while waiting for a warrant.\n翻译: <u>在面临严重、紧急情况时，他们仍可使第四修正案的保护失效，而且他们可以采取合理措施，确保在等待搜查令期间手机数据不被删除或更改。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe court, <font color=\"#00b050\">though</font>, may want to allow room for police to <font color=\"#00b050\">cite</font> situations where they are entitled to more freedom.\n翻译: <u>不过，法院可能希望为警察援引他们有权享有更大自由的情形留出空间。</u>\n\n-**though** <u>放在句中，表示轻微转折，相当于“不过”。</u>  \n<u>它承接前文：虽然一般应要求搜查令，但法院可能需要留下例外空间。</u>\n-**cite**：<u>引用、援引、提出作为理由。</u>  \n-<u>不过，最高法院也许会保留一些弹性，让警方在特殊情况下主张自己需要更大的执法自由。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the justices <font color=\"#00b050\">should not swallow</font> California’s argument whole.\n翻译: <u>但大法官们不应全盘接受加利福尼亚州的论点。</u>\n\n-**swallow** <u>字面意思是“吞下”。</u>  \n<u>在这里是比喻：不加质疑地接受。**whole**：整个地、完整地。</u>  \n\n---\n\nNew, disruptive technology sometimes demands <font color=\"#00b050\">novel applications</font> of the Constitution’s protections.\n翻译: <u>新的、具有颠覆性的技术有时要求以新颖方式适用宪法的保护。</u>\n\n-**novel applications**：<u>新的应用方式、新的适用方法。</u> \n\n---\n\nOrin Kerr, a law professor, compares the explosion and accessibility of digital information in the 21st century with the <font color=\"#00b050\">establishment</font> of <font color=\"#00b050\">automobile use</font> as a <font color=\"#00b050\">virtual necessity</font> of life in the 20th.\n翻译: <u>法学教授Orin Kerr将21世纪数字信息的爆炸式增长及其可获取性，与20世纪汽车使用成为生活中实际必需品的确立相比较。</u>\n\n-**establishment**：<u>确立、形成。</u>  \n-**automobile use**：<u>汽车使用。</u>\n-**as a virtual necessity of life**：<u>作为实际上的生活必需。</u>  \n**virtual** <u>在这里不是“虚拟的”，而是“实际上的、几乎等同于”</u>\n\n---\n\nThe justices had to specify <font color=\"#00b050\">novel rules</font> for the new personal domain of the <font color=\"#00b050\">passenger car</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">then</font>; they must <font color=\"#00b050\">sort out</font> how the Fourth Amendment applies to digital information <font color=\"#00b050\">now</font>.\n翻译: <u>当时，大法官们不得不为乘用车这一新的个人领域规定新规则；如今，他们必须理清第四修正案如何适用于数字信息。</u>\n\n-**novel rules**：<u>新的规则。</u>  \n-**passenger car**：<u>乘用车、私家车。</u>  \n-hen** <u>指 20 世纪汽车成为生活必需品之后的那个历史阶段。</u>  \n<u>它与后面的 **now** 形成对比。</u>\n-**sort out**：<u>理清、解决、弄明白。</u>\n\n\n第三篇\nThe journal Science is adding an extra round of statistical checks to its peer-review process, editor-in-chief Marcia McNutt announced today.\n翻译: <u>《Science》杂志主编Marcia McNutt今天宣布，该刊将在其同行评议流程中增加一轮额外的统计检查。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe policy follows similar efforts from other journals, after widespread concern that basic mistakes in data analysis are contributing to the<font color=\"#00b050\"> irreproducibility</font> of many published research findings.\n翻译: <u>此前，由于人们普遍担心数据分析中的基本错误正在导致许多已发表研究结果无法复现，其他期刊也采取了类似举措，这项政策正是随之而来。</u>\n\n-**irreproducibility**：<u>不可复现性，即别人按照同样方法无法得到相同结果。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\n“Readers must have confidence in the conclusions published in our journal,” writes McNutt in an <font color=\"#00b050\">editorial.</font>\n翻译: <u>McNutt 在一篇社论中写道：“读者必须对我们期刊上发表的结论有信心。”</u>\n\n-**editorial**：<u>社论、评论文章。</u>\n-<u>直译：“读者必须对我们期刊发表的结论有信心，”麦克纳特在一篇社论中写道。</u>  \n<u>地道意译：麦克纳特在社论中表示：“读者必须能够信任我们期刊发表的研究结论。”</u>\n\n---\n\nWorking with the American Statistical Association, the journal has appointed seven experts to a statistics <font color=\"#00b050\">board</font> of <font color=\"#00b050\">reviewing editors</font> (SBoRE).\n翻译: <u>该期刊与 American Statistical Association 合作，已任命七名专家组成一个统计学审稿编辑委员会（SBoRE）。</u>\n\n-**statistics board**：<u>统计委员会。</u>\n-**reviewing editors**：<u>评审编辑。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Manuscripts</font> will be flagged up for additional scrutiny by the journal’s internal editors, or by its existing Board of Reviewing Editors or by outside peer reviewers.\n翻译: <u>稿件将由该期刊的内部编辑、其现有的审稿编辑委员会或外部同行评审者标记出来，以接受额外审查。</u>\n\n-**manuscripts** <u>指投稿给期刊、尚未正式发表的论文稿件。</u>\n-**flag up**：<u>标出、提醒注意。 这他妈是 flag 这都能认不出来当时,别以为猜词都是很生僻的词</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThe SBoRE panel will then find external statisticians to review these manuscripts.\n翻译: <u>随后，SBoRE 小组将寻找外部统计学家来审查这些稿件。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Asked</font> whether <font color=\"#00b050\">any particular papers</font> had <font color=\"#00b050\">impelled the change</font>, McNutt said: “The creation of the ‘statistics board’ was motivated by <font color=\"#00b050\">concerns broadly with</font> the application of statistics and data analysis in scientific research and is part of Science’s <font color=\"#00b050\">overall drive</font> to increase reproducibility in the research we publish.”\n翻译: <u>当被问及是否有某些特定论文促成了这一改变时，McNutt 说：“设立‘统计学委员会’的动因，是对科学研究中统计学和数据分析应用的广泛担忧，也是 Science 为提高我们所发表研究的可重复性而进行的整体努力的一部分。”</u>\n\n-**Asked** <u>是被动意义，因为 McNutt 是“被问到”</u>\n-**any particular papers**：<u>某些具体论文。</u>\n-**had impelled**：<u>过去完成时，表示在这项改变之前已经推动了它。</u>  \n<u>问题是在问：是不是某篇或某几篇论文出了问题，才导致 Science 改革？-</u>\n-**concerns broadly with…**：<u>广泛涉及……的担忧。</u>  \n-**overall drive**：<u>整体推动、整体努力。</u>  \n-<u>当被问及是否因为某些具体论文才作出这一改革时，麦克纳特表示，设立统计委员会并非针对个别论文，而是源于对科研中统计和数据分析使用问题的广泛担忧，也是《科学》提升论文可复现性整体改革的一环。</u>\n\n---\n\nGiovanni Parmigiani, a biostatistician at the Harvard School of Public Health, a member of the SBoRE group, says he expects the board to “play primarily an <font color=\"#00b050\">advisory role.</font>”\n翻译: <u>Harvard School of Public Health 的生物统计学家、SBoRE 小组成员 Giovanni Parmigiani 表示，他预计该委员会将“主要发挥咨询作用”。</u>\n\n-**advisory role**：<u>咨询性角色。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHe agreed to join because he “<font color=\"#00b050\">found</font> the <font color=\"#00b050\">foresight</font> behind the establishment of the SBoRE <font color=\"#00b050\">to be</font> novel, unique and likely to have a lasting impact.”\n翻译: <u>他同意加入，是因为他“认为设立 SBoRE 背后的远见是新颖、独特的，并且可能产生持久影响”。</u>\n\n-**found** <u>在这里不是“发现某物”，而是“认为、觉得”。</u>  \n<u>结构可以理解为：</u>  \n**found X to be Y** = <u>认为 X 是 Y。</u>\n-**foresight**：<u>远见、预见力。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis impact will not only be through the publications in Science itself, but <font color=\"#00b050\">hopefully</font> through a larger group of publishing places that may want to model their approach after Science.\n翻译: <u>这种影响不仅会通过 Science 本身的出版物体现出来，而且有望通过更大范围的出版机构体现出来，这些机构可能希望仿效 Science 的做法。</u>\n\n-**hopefully**：<u>希望如此。</u>  \n\n---\n\nJohn Ioannidis, a physician who studies research methodology, says that the policy is “a <font color=\"#00b050\">most</font> welcome step forward” and “<font color=\"#00b050\">long overdue</font>”.\n翻译: <u>研究科研方法论的医生 John Ioannidis 表示，这项政策是“非常受欢迎的进步”，并且“早该如此”。</u>\n\n-**most** <u>在这里不是“最”，而是非常正式的加强语气，相当于 **very**。</u> \n-**long overdue**：<u>早该发生但迟迟未发生。</u>  \n\n---\n\n“Most journals are weak in statistical review, and this damages the quality of what they publish.”\n翻译: <u>“大多数期刊在统计审查方面薄弱，而这损害了它们所发表内容的质量。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I think that, for the majority of scientific papers nowadays, statistical review is more essential than expert review,” he says, but he noted that biomedical journals such as Annals of Internal Medicine, the Journal of the American Medical Association and The Lancet pay strong attention to statistical review.\n翻译: <u>他说：“我认为，对于如今大多数科学论文来说，统计审查比专家审查更为必要。”但他指出，Annals of Internal Medicine、Journal of the American Medical Association 和 The Lancet 等生物医学期刊非常重视统计审查。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nProfessional scientists<font color=\"#00b050\"> are expected to</font> know how to analyse data, but statistical errors are <font color=\"#00b050\">alarmingly</font> common in published research, according to David Vaux, a cell biologist.\n翻译: <u>细胞生物学家 David Vaux 表示，职业科学家理应知道如何分析数据，但已发表研究中的统计错误普遍得令人担忧。</u>\n\n-**are expected to**：<u>被认为应该、理应。</u>  \n-**alarmingly**：<u>令人担忧地、令人震惊地。</u>  \n\n---\n\nResearchers should improve their standards, he wrote in 2012, but journals should also <font color=\"#00b050\">take a tougher line</font>, “<font color=\"#00b050\">engaging</font> reviewers who are statistically literate and editors who can verify the process”.\n翻译: <u>他在 2012 年写道，研究人员应提高自身标准，但期刊也应采取更强硬的立场，“聘用具备统计素养的审稿人，以及能够核查这一过程的编辑”。</u>\n\n-**take a tougher line**：<u>采取更强硬、更严格的立场。</u>  \n-**engaging**：<u>聘用、邀请、安排参与。</u>\n\n---\n\nVaux says that Science’s idea to<font color=\"#00b050\"> pass some papers to statisticians</font> “has some <font color=\"#00b050\">merit</font>, but a weakness is that it relies on the board of reviewing editors to identify ‘the papers that need scrutiny’ <font color=\"#00b050\">in the first place</font>”.\n翻译: <u>Vaux 表示，Science 将部分论文交给统计学家的想法“有一定可取之处，但一个弱点是，它首先依赖审稿编辑委员会来识别‘需要审查的论文’”。</u>\n\n-**to pass some papers to statisticians** <u>是不定式短语，修饰 idea，说明这个想法的内容。**pass A to B**：把 A 交给 B。</u>\n-**merit**：<u>优点、价值、可取之处。</u>\n-**in the first place**：<u>首先、从一开始。</u>  \n\n-Vaux <u>认为，《科学》把部分论文交由统计学家审查的做法有价值，但问题在于：它首先要靠评审编辑委员会发现哪些论文需要额外统计审查；如果第一步识别不到位，后面的统计审查就无从开始。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2016","year":"2016","title":"2016 年英语一","fileName":"2016 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2016 年英语 1.md","content":"第一篇\nFrance, which prides itself as the global innovator of fashion, has decided its fashion industry has lost an absolute right to define physical beauty for women.\n翻译: <u>法国自诩为全球时尚创新者，如今已认定其时尚产业失去了界定女性身体美的绝对权利。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nIts lawmakers gave <font color=\"#00b050\">preliminary approval </font>last week to a law that would make it a crime to employ ultra-thin models on runways.\n翻译: <u>法国立法者上周初步批准了一项法律，该法律将把在时装秀上雇用超瘦模特定为犯罪。</u>\n\n-**preliminary approval**：<u>初步批准。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe parliament also agreed to ban websites that “<font color=\"#00b050\">incite</font> excessive thinness” by <font color=\"#00b050\">promoting</font> extreme dieting.\n翻译: <u>议会还同意禁止通过鼓励极端节食来“煽动过度消瘦”的网站。</u>\n\n-**incite**：<u>煽动、鼓动。</u>  \n-**promote**：<u>推广、宣扬。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSuch measures have <font color=\"#00b050\">a couple of</font> uplifting <font color=\"#00b050\">motives</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些措施有几个令人振奋的动机。</u>\n\n-**a couple of**：<u>几个、两个左右。</u>  \n-**motives**：<u>动机。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey suggest beauty should not be defined by looks that end up impinging on health.\n翻译: <u>它们表明，美不应由最终损害健康的外貌来定义。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat’s a start.\n翻译: <u>这是一个开端。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd the ban on ultra-thin models seems to go beyond protecting models from starving themselves to death — as some have done.\n翻译: <u>而对超瘦模特的禁令似乎超出了保护模特免于把自己饿死的范围——正如有些人已经这样做了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt <font color=\"#00b050\">tells</font> the fashion industry that it must take responsibility for the signal it sends women, especially teenage girls, about the social <font color=\"#00b050\">tape-measure</font> they must use to determine their individual worth.\n翻译: <u>它告诉时尚产业，它必须对自己向女性，尤其是少女，发出的信号负责，即她们必须用怎样的社会衡量标准来判定自己的个人价值。</u>\n\n-**tell** <u>在这里不是简单“告知”，而是“向……传达一个要求”。</u>\n-**tape-measure** <u>是卷尺，用来量尺寸。</u>  \n<u>这里比喻社会用某种标准“测量”一个人的价值，尤其是用身材来衡量女性价值。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nThe bans,<font color=\"#00b050\"> if fully enforced</font>, would suggest to women and many men that they should not let others be arbiters of their beauty.\n翻译: <u>这些禁令如果得到全面执行，将会向女性以及许多男性表明，他们不应让他人成为自己美的裁判者。</u>\n\n-**if they are fully enforced**。  \n**enforced**：<u>被执行。</u>  \n<u>作者暗示：政策效果取决于是否真正执行。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd perhaps<font color=\"#00b050\"> faintly</font>, they hint that people should look to intangible qualities like <font color=\"#00b050\">character</font> and intellect rather than dieting their way to size zero or wasp-waist physiques.\n翻译: <u>也许它们还隐约暗示，人们应当看重品格和才智等无形品质，而不是通过节食来追求零号尺码或蜂腰体型。</u>\n\n-**faintly**：<u>微弱地、隐约地。  作者语气很谨慎：这些禁令也许只是稍微暗示了更深层的审美转向。</u>\n-**character**：<u>品格、人格。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe French measures, <font color=\"#00b050\">however</font>, rely too much on severe punishment to change a culture that still regards beauty as skin-deep — and bone-showing.\n翻译: <u>然而，法国的这些措施过于依赖严厉惩罚，来改变一种仍把美视为肤浅外表——甚至瘦到露骨——的文化。</u>\n\n-however    <u>作者前面肯定其动机，现在开始批评方法。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnder the law, using a fashion model that does not meet a government-defined <font color=\"#00b050\">index of body mass</font> could result in a $85,000 fine and six months in prison.\n翻译: <u>根据该法律，使用不符合政府规定体重指数的时装模特，可能导致 85,000 美元罚款和六个月监禁。</u>\n\n-**index of body mass**：<u>身体质量指数，即 BMI 一类指标。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThe fashion industry knows it has an <font color=\"#00b050\">inherent problem</font> in focusing on <font color=\"#00b050\">material adornment</font> and idealized body types.\n翻译: <u>时尚产业知道，它在聚焦物质装饰和理想化体型方面存在固有问题。</u>\n\n-**inherent problem**：<u>内在问题、固有问题。</u>\n-**material adornment**：<u>物质装饰，比如衣服、配饰、外在打扮。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn Denmark, the United States, and a few other countries, it is trying to set <font color=\"#00b050\">voluntary standards</font> for models and fashion images that rely more on <font color=\"#00b050\">peer pressure</font> for enforcement.\n翻译: <u>在丹麦、美国和其他少数国家，它正试图为模特和时尚形象制定自愿性标准，这些标准更多依靠同侪压力来执行。</u>\n\n-**voluntary standards**：<u>自愿性标准，不是政府强制法律。</u>  \n-**peer pressure**：<u>同伴压力、同行压力。</u>  \n-<u>地道意译：在丹麦、美国等国家，时尚行业尝试用自律标准来规范模特和时尚影像，并主要依靠行业内部压力来推动执行。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn contrast to France’s actions, Denmark’s fashion industry agreed last month on rules and sanctions regarding the age, health, and other characteristics of models.\n翻译: <u>与法国的行动相比，丹麦时尚产业上个月就有关模特年龄、健康和其他特征的规则与制裁达成了一致。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe newly revised Danish Fashion Ethical Charter clearly states: “We are aware of and take responsibility for the impact the fashion industry has on <font color=\"#00b050\">body ideals,</font> especially on young people.”\n翻译: <u>新修订的 Danish Fashion Ethical Charter 明确声明：“我们意识到并承担时尚产业对身体理想的影响，尤其是对年轻人的影响。”</u>\n\n-**body ideals**：<u>身体理想、理想身材标准。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe charter’s main tool of enforcement is to deny access for designers and modeling <font color=\"#00b050\">agencies</font> to Copenhagen Fashion Week (CFW), which is run by the Danish Fashion Institute.\n翻译: <u>该章程的主要执行手段，是拒绝设计师和模特经纪公司进入由 Danish Fashion Institute 运营的 Copenhagen Fashion Week（CFW）。</u>\n\n-**modeling agencies**：<u>模特经纪公司。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#00b050\">in general</font> it relies on a <font color=\"#00b050\">name-and-shame</font> method of <font color=\"#00b050\">compliance</font>.\n翻译: <u>但总体而言，它依靠一种点名羞辱的合规方法。</u>\n\n-**in general**：<u>一般而言、总体上。</u>  \n-**name-and-shame**：<u>公开点名并羞辱，即公布违规者，让其承受声誉压力。</u>  \n<u>这是一种非法律强制的执行方式。</u>\n-**compliance**：<u>遵守、合规。</u>  \n-\n---\n\nRelying on ethical persuasion rather than law to address the misuse of body ideals may be the best step.\n翻译: <u>依靠伦理劝导而非法律来处理身体理想被滥用的问题，或许是最佳的一步。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Even better</font> would be to help elevate notions of beauty beyond the material standards of a particular industry.\n翻译: <u>更好的做法是帮助把美的观念提升到某一特定行业的物质标准之外。</u>\n\n-**To help elevate notions of beauty beyond the material standards of a particular industry would be even better.**<u>作者把 **Even better** 放在句首，强调更理想的方案。</u>\n\n<u>直译：更好的做法将是帮助把美的观念提升到某个特定行业的物质标准之外。</u>  \n<u>地道意译：更理想的是，我们应帮助社会重新理解美，让美超越时尚行业那些外在、物质化的标准。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\nFor the first time in history more people live in towns than in the country.\n翻译: <u>历史上第一次，居住在城镇中的人口超过了居住在乡村中的人口。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn Britain this has had a <font color=\"#00b050\">curious result</font>.\n翻译: <u>在英国，这产生了一个奇特的结果。</u>\n\n-curious result <u>奇妙的结果</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile polls show Britons <font color=\"#00b050\">rate</font> “the countryside” <font color=\"#00b050\">alongside</font> the royal family, Shakespeare and the National Health Service (NHS) <font color=\"#00b050\">as</font> what makes them proudest of their country, this has limited political support.\n翻译: <u>尽管民调显示，英国人把“乡村”与王室、Shakespeare 和 National Health Service（NHS）并列，视为最令他们为自己的国家感到自豪的事物，但这在政治上得到的支持有限。</u>\n\n-**rate A alongside B**：<u>把 A 与 B 并列评价 / 放在同一等级。</u>  \n-as + <u>名词性从句，作宾语补足语。把它们视为最让自己为国家感到自豪的东西。</u>\n-<u>地道意译：民调显示，英国人把乡村看得和王室、莎士比亚、NHS 一样重要，是国家自豪感的来源；可在政治层面，保护乡村却并没有得到多少支持。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nA century ago Octavia Hill launched the National Trust not to rescue <font color=\"#00b050\">stylish houses</font> but to save “the beauty of natural places for everyone forever.”\n翻译: <u>一个世纪前，Octavia Hill 发起 National Trust，并不是为了拯救有格调的住宅，而是为了保存“自然场所之美，让每个人永远享有”。</u>\n\n-**stylish houses**：<u>有风格的房屋、漂亮宅邸。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nIt was specifically to provide city dwellers with spaces for leisure where they could experience “a refreshing air.”\n翻译: <u>其明确目的，是为城市居民提供休闲空间，让他们能够体验“一股清新的空气”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHill’s pressure <font color=\"#00b050\">later</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">led to</font> the creation of national parks and green belts.\n翻译: <u>Hill 的施压后来促成了国家公园和绿化带的建立。</u>\n\n-later  <u>后来</u>\n-**lead to**：<u>导致、促成。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#00b050\">don’t make</font> countryside <font color=\"#00b050\">any more</font>, and every year concrete <font color=\"#00b050\">consumes </font>more of it.\n翻译: <u>乡村不会再被制造出来，而每年混凝土都吞噬着更多乡村。</u>\n\n-**don’t make…any more**：<u>不再制造……。</u>  \n-**consume**：<u>消耗、吞噬。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt needs constant guardianship.\n翻译: <u>它需要持续的守护。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt the next election none of the big parties seem likely to endorse this <font color=\"#00b050\">sentiment</font>.\n翻译: <u>在下一次选举中，似乎没有一个大党可能支持这种情感。</u>\n\n-**this sentiment** <u>指前面“乡村需要持续守护”的情感或立场。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">The Conservatives’</font> planning reform <font color=\"#00b050\">explicitly</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">gives</font> rural development <font color=\"#00b050\">priority </font><font color=\"#00b050\">over</font> conservation, even <font color=\"#00b050\">authorising</font> “off-plan” building where local people might object.\n翻译: <u>Conservatives 的规划改革明确赋予乡村开发优先于保护的地位，甚至授权在当地人可能反对的地方进行“规划外”建设。</u>\n\n-**The Conservatives**：<u>英国保守党。</u>\n-**explicitly**：<u>明确地。</u>  \n-**give A priority over B**：<u>让 A 优先于 B。</u>\n-<u>这里有个很有意思的点 conservative-保守党  conservation-保护</u>\n-**authorising**：<u>授权、允许。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe concept of sustainable development has <font color=\"#00b050\">been defined as</font> profitable.\n翻译: <u>可持续发展的概念已被定义为有利可图。</u>\n\n-**has been defined**：<u>已经被定义。</u> \n\n---\n\nLabour likewise wants to <font color=\"#00b050\">discontinue</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">local planning</font> where councils <font color=\"#00b050\">oppose development</font>.\n翻译: <u>Labour 同样希望在地方议会反对开发时中止地方规划。</u>\n\n-**discontinue**：<u>停止、终止。</u> \n-**oppose development**：<u>反对开发。</u> \n-local planning  <u>地方规划 这个很重要</u>\n\n-<u>直译：工党同样想在地方议会反对开发的地方终止地方规划。</u>  \n**<u>工党也差不多：只要地方政府挡了开发项目的路，它就想把地方规划权拿掉。**</u>\n\n-**council**：<u>地方议会   **parliament**：国会  **council 一般没有“国会”的意思。**</u>\n \n\n---\n\nThe Liberal Democrats are silent.\n翻译: <u>Liberal Democrats 则保持沉默。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOnly Ukip, sensing its chance, has <font color=\"#00b050\">sided with</font> those pleading for a <font color=\"#00b050\">more considered approach</font> to using green land.\n翻译: <u>只有 Ukip 察觉到自己的机会，站到了那些恳求以更审慎方式使用绿地的人一边。</u>\n\n-**side with**：<u>支持、站在……一边。</u>  \n-**a more considered approach**：<u>更审慎、更深思熟虑的方法。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIts Campaign to Protect Rural England struck terror into many local Conservative parties.\n翻译: <u>它的 Campaign to Protect Rural England 让许多地方 Conservative 党组织感到恐惧。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#00b050\">sensible</font> place to build new houses, factories and offices is <font color=\"#00b050\">where people are</font>, in cities and towns where infrastructure is in place.\n翻译: <u>建造新住宅、工厂和办公室的合理地点，是人们所在的地方，即基础设施已经到位的城市和城镇。</u>\n\n-**sensible**：<u>明智的、合理的。</u>  \n-**where people are**：<u>人们已经所在的地方。</u>  \n-**in place**：<u>已经到位、已经存在。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe London <font color=\"#00b050\">agents</font> Stirling Ackroyd recently<font color=\"#00b050\"> identified</font> enough sites for<font color=\"#00b050\"> half a million</font> houses in the London area <font color=\"#00b050\">alone</font>, with no intrusion on green belt.\n翻译: <u>伦敦地产代理公司 Stirling Ackroyd 最近仅在伦敦地区就找出了足够建造 50 万套住房的地块，而且不侵占绿化带。</u>\n\n-**agents** <u>在这里指房地产代理/地产机构</u>\n-**identify**：<u>识别、找出。</u>  \n-**half a million**：<u>五十万。</u>  \n-**alone**：<u>仅仅、单是。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">What is true of</font> London is <font color=\"#00b050\">even</font> truer of the <font color=\"#00b050\">provinces</font>.\n翻译: <u>适用于伦敦的情况，在外省地区更加适用。</u>\n\n-**what is true of…**：<u>对……成立的情况 / 适用于……的事实。</u>  \n-**the provinces**：<u>外省地区、伦敦以外的地区。</u>  \n-even <u>更加</u>\n-<u>地道意译：伦敦尚且如此，英国其他地区就更是如此了。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe idea that “housing crisis” equals “<font color=\"#00b050\">concreted meadows</font>” is pure <font color=\"#00b050\">lobby talk</font>.\n翻译: <u>认为“住房危机”等同于“被混凝土覆盖的草地”，纯粹是游说说辞。</u>\n\n-**concreted meadows**：<u>被混凝土覆盖的草地。</u>  \n-**lobby talk**：<u>游说集团的话术、利益集团宣传。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">The issue</font> is not the need for more houses but, <font color=\"#00b050\">as always</font>, where to put them.\n翻译: <u>问题不在于是否需要更多住房，而是一如既往，在于把它们建在哪里。</u>\n\n-**the issue**：<u>问题的关键。</u>\n-**as is always the case**。    <u>一如既往。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nUnder lobby pressure, George Osborne favours rural new-build <font color=\"#00b050\">against </font>urban renovation and renewal.\n翻译: <u>在游说压力下，George Osborne 支持乡村新建项目，而不是城市修缮和更新。</u>\n\n-**against** <u>在这里表示“相比于 / 而不是”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHe favours out-of-town shopping sites against high streets.\n翻译: <u>他支持城外购物场所，而不是商业街。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis is not a free market but a <font color=\"#00b050\">biased one</font>.\n翻译: <u>这不是自由市场，而是一个带有偏向的市场。</u>\n\n-**biased one**：<u>有偏见/有倾向的市场。</u>  \n-<u>作者反驳“开发是市场自然选择”的说法，认为政策本身在偏袒某些开发模式。</u>\n\n---\n\nRural towns and villages have grown and will always grow.\n翻译: <u>乡村城镇和村庄已经发展，并且将永远发展。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#00b050\">do so</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">best</font> where building sticks to <font color=\"#00b050\">their edges</font> and respects their <font color=\"#00b050\">character</font>.\n翻译: <u>当建设贴着它们的边缘进行并尊重其特色时，它们发展得最好。</u>\n\n-**do so** <u>指上一句的 **grow**，即“发展、扩展”。</u>  \n-**best**：<u>最好地。</u>  \n-**their edges**：<u>它们的边缘，即城镇和村庄已有边界。</u>\n-**character**：<u>特色、风貌、地方性格。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWe <font color=\"#00b050\">do not ruin</font> urban conservation areas.\n翻译: <u>我们不会毁坏城市保护区。</u>\n\n-**do not ruin**：<u>不毁坏。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhy ruin rural ones?\n翻译: <u>为什么要毁坏乡村保护区呢？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDevelopment should be planned, not let rip.\n翻译: <u>开发应当经过规划，而不是任其失控。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">After</font> the Netherlands, Britain is Europe’s most crowded country.\n翻译: <u>除荷兰之外，英国是欧洲最拥挤的国家。</u>\n\n-**after** <u>在这里表示排名次序，即“排在……之后”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHalf a century of <font color=\"#00b050\">town and country planning</font> has enabled it to retain an <font color=\"#00b050\">enviable </font><font color=\"#00b050\">rural coherence</font>, while still permitting low-density urban living.\n翻译: <u>半个世纪的城乡规划使它得以保留一种令人羡慕的乡村整体性，同时仍允许低密度的城市生活。</u>\n\n-**town and country planning**：<u>城乡规划。</u>  \n-**enviable**：<u>令人羡慕的。</u>  \n-**rural coherence**：<u>乡村整体性、乡村景观的连贯完整。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThere is no doubt of <font color=\"#00b050\">the alternative</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">—</font> the corrupted landscapes of southern Portugal, Spain or Ireland.\n翻译: <u>替代方案毫无疑问——就是葡萄牙南部、西班牙或爱尔兰那些被破坏的景观。</u>\n\n-**the alternative** <u>这里指如果不进行规划保护，会走向什么结果。</u>\n-    —**<u>破折号解释 alternative**</u>\n\n\n---\n\nAvoiding this rather than promoting it should unite the <font color=\"#00b050\">left and right</font> of the <font color=\"#00b050\">political spectrum</font>.\n翻译: <u>避免这种情况，而不是推动它，应当把政治光谱的左翼和右翼团结起来。</u>\n\n-**the left and right**：<u>左翼和右翼。</u>  \n-**political spectrum**：<u>政治光谱。</u>  \n\n---\n\n第三篇\n“There is one and only one social responsibility of business,” wrote Milton Friedman, a Nobel prize-winning economist, “<font color=\"#00b0f0\">That is</font>, to use its resources and <font color=\"#00b050\">engage in</font> activities designed to increase its profits.”\n翻译: <u>诺贝尔奖得主、经济学家 Milton Friedman 写道：“企业有且只有一种社会责任，那就是利用其资源并从事旨在增加其利润的活动。”</u>\n\n-that is <u>也就是说。</u>\n-**engage in**：<u>从事、参与。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#00b050\">even if </font>you accept Friedman’s premise and regard corporate social responsibility (CSR) policies as a waste of shareholders’ money, things may not be <font color=\"#00b050\">absolutely</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">clear-cut.</font>\n翻译: <u>但即便你接受 Friedman 的前提，并把企业社会责任（CSR）政策视为对股东资金的浪费，事情也未必绝对界限分明。</u>\n\n-**even if**：<u>即使。</u> \n-**clear-cut**：<u>清楚明确的、界限分明的。</u> \n-**absolutely** <u>加强语气。</u>  \n\n---\n\nNew research suggests that CSR may create monetary value for companies – at least when they <font color=\"#00b050\">are prosecuted for</font> corruption.\n翻译: <u>新研究表明，CSR 可能为公司创造货币价值——至少在它们因腐败而被起诉时是如此。</u>\n\n-**be prosecuted for corruption**：<u>因腐败被起诉。  for 后面表示原因,因 xx 被 xx</u>\n\n---\n\nThe largest firms in America and Britain <font color=\"#00b050\">together </font>spend more than $15 billion a year on CSR, according to an estimate by EPG, a consulting firm.\n翻译: <u>据咨询公司 EPG 估算，美国和英国最大的公司合计每年在 CSR 上花费超过 150 亿美元。</u>\n\n-**together** <u>是总计的意思 不是共同的意思</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThis could add value to their businesses in three ways.\n翻译: <u>这可能通过三种方式为它们的业务增加价值。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFirst, consumers may take CSR spending as a “signal” that a company’s products are of high quality.\n翻译: <u>首先，消费者可能把 CSR 支出视为一种“信号”，表明一家公司的产品质量很高。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSecond, customers may be willing to buy a company’s products as an indirect way to donate to the <font color=\"#00b050\">good causes</font><font color=\"#00b050\"> it helps</font>.\n翻译: <u>其次，顾客可能愿意购买一家公司的产品，作为一种间接向其所帮助的公益事业捐赠的方式。</u>\n\n-**good causes**：<u>公益事业、善因。</u> \n-**it** <u>指 a company。</u>  \n<u>意思是公司通过 CSR 支持的公益项目，比如环保、教育、扶贫等。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd third, through a more <font color=\"#00b050\">diffuse</font> “<font color=\"#00b050\">halo effect,</font>” <font color=\"#00b050\">whereby</font> its good deeds earn it greater consideration from consumers and others.\n翻译: <u>第三，通过一种更为分散的“光环效应”，即它的善行使其从消费者和其他人那里获得更多体谅。</u>\n\n-**diffuse**：<u>分散的、不那么直接的。</u>  \n-**halo effect**：<u>光环效应，即某方面的好印象会影响人们对整体的评价。</u>\n-**whereby**：<u>借此、通过这种方式。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPrevious studies on CSR have had trouble <font color=\"#00b050\">differentiating</font> these effects because consumers can be affected by all three.\n翻译: <u>以往关于 CSR 的研究难以区分这些效应，因为消费者可能同时受到三者影响。</u>\n\n-**differentiating**：<u>区分。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA recent study attempts to separate them by <font color=\"#00b050\">looking at</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">bribery prosecutions </font>under America’s Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA).\n翻译: <u>一项近期研究试图通过考察美国 Foreign Corrupt Practices Act（FCPA）下的贿赂起诉来区分它们。</u>\n\n-**looking at**：<u>研究、考察。</u>  \n-**bribery prosecutions**：<u>贿赂起诉案件。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt argues that <font color=\"#00b050\">since</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">prosecutors </font>do not consume a company’s products as part of their investigations, they could be influenced only by the halo effect.\n翻译: <u>该研究认为，由于检察官在调查过程中并不消费公司的产品，他们只能受到光环效应的影响。</u>\n\n-**since** <u>在这里不是“自从”，而是“因为”。</u>\n-**prosecutors**：<u>检察官。</u>  \n\n<u>地道意译：研究认为，检察官办案时不会购买被调查公司的产品，因此不可能受到“产品质量信号”或“购买即捐赠”的影响；如果 CSR 影响他们，那只能是光环效应在起作用。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe study found that, among prosecuted firms, those with the most <font color=\"#00b050\">comprehensive</font> CSR programmes tended to get more lenient penalties.\n翻译: <u>研究发现，在被起诉的公司中，那些拥有最全面 CSR 项目的公司往往受到更宽大的处罚。</u>\n\n-**comprehensive**：<u>全面的、覆盖广泛的。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nTheir analysis <font color=\"#00b050\">ruled out </font>the possibility that it was firms’ political influence, rather than <font color=\"#00b050\">their CSR stand</font>, that accounted for the leniency: Companies that <font color=\"#00b050\">contributed </font>more <font color=\"#00b050\">to</font> political campaigns did not receive lower fines.\n翻译: <u>他们的分析排除了这样一种可能性：宽大处理是由公司的政治影响力，而不是其 CSR 立场所造成的；向政治竞选捐款更多的公司并未获得更低罚款。</u>\n\n-**rule out**：<u>排除。</u> \n-**their CSR stand**：<u>公司的 CSR 立场/表现。</u>\n-**contribute to**：<u>向……捐款、贡献。</u>  \n\n-<u>地道意译：研究者还排除了“政治关系导致从轻处罚”的解释。因为那些给政治竞选捐款更多的公司，并没有因此获得更低罚款。</u>\n\n-\n---\n\nIn all, the study concludes that <font color=\"#00b050\">whereas</font> prosecutors should only evaluate a case <font color=\"#00b050\">based on its merits</font>, they do seem to be influenced by a company’s record in CSR.\n翻译: <u>总体而言，该研究得出结论：尽管检察官本应只根据案件本身的是非曲直来评估案件，但他们似乎确实会受到公司 CSR 记录的影响。</u>\n\n-**whereas**：<u>然而、尽管、鉴于。</u>  \n-**based on its merits**：<u>基于案件本身事实和法律依据。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n“We estimate that <font color=\"#00b050\">either</font> eliminating a <font color=\"#00b050\">substantial</font> labour-rights <font color=\"#00b050\">concern</font>, such as child labour, <font color=\"#00b050\">or</font> increasing <font color=\"#00b050\">corporate giving</font> by about 20% <font color=\"#00b050\">results in</font> fines that generally are 40% lower than the typical punishment for bribing foreign officials,” says one researcher.\n翻译: <u>一位研究人员说：“我们估计，消除一个重大的劳工权利问题，比如童工，或者将企业捐赠增加约20%，都会使罚款通常比贿赂外国官员的典型处罚低40%。”</u>\n\n-**either…or…**：<u>或者……或者……。</u>  \n-**substantial**：<u>重大的、实质性的。</u>\n-**labour-rights concern**：<u>劳工权利方面的问题。</u>  \n-**corporate giving**：<u>企业捐赠、企业慈善支出。</u>  \n-**result in**：<u>导致、造成。</u>  \n\n<u>地道意译：一位研究者表示：“我们的估算显示，如果企业消除童工等重大劳工权利问题，或将企业捐赠增加约 20%，其罚款通常会比外国贿赂案件的典型处罚低 40%。”</u>\n\n---\n\nResearchers admit that their study does not answer the question of how much businesses <font color=\"#00b050\">ought to</font> spend on CSR.\n翻译: <u>研究人员承认，他们的研究并没有回答企业应当在企业社会责任（CSR）上花多少钱这个问题。</u>\n\n-**ought to**：<u>应该，带有规范或责任意味。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Nor does it</font> reveal <font color=\"#00b050\">how much</font> companies are <font color=\"#00b050\">banking on</font> the halo effect, rather than the other possible benefits, when they decide their <font color=\"#00b050\">do-gooding</font> policies.\n翻译: <u>它也没有揭示，当公司决定其行善政策时，它们在多大程度上指望的是光环效应，而不是其他可能的好处。</u>\n\n-<u>否定副词 **Nor** 置于句首，引起部分倒装。</u>\n-**how much** <u>在这里不是问具体钱数，而是“多大程度上”。</u>  \n-**bank on**：<u>指望、依赖、押注。</u>\n-**do-gooding policies**：<u>行善政策、公益政策。</u> \n\n---\n\nBut at least they have <font color=\"#00b050\">demonstrated that</font> when companies get into trouble with the law, evidence of good character can win them a less costly punishment.\n翻译: <u>但至少他们已经证明，当公司惹上法律麻烦时，良好品格的证据可以为它们赢得代价较低的处罚。</u>\n\n-**have demonstrated**：<u>已经证明、展示出。</u>  \n\n第四篇\n\n-There will eventually come a day when The New York Times ceases to publish <font color=\"#00b050\">stories</font> on <font color=\"#00b050\">newsprint.</font>\n\n-**newsprint**：<u>新闻纸，指印刷报纸所用纸张。</u>  \n-**publish stories**：<u>刊登新闻报道。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Exactly when</font> that day will be is a matter of debate.\n翻译: <u>那一天究竟何时到来，仍是一个有争议的问题。</u>\n\n-**Exactly when…**：<u>究竟什么时候。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Sometime in the future,” the paper’s <font color=\"#00b050\">publisher</font> said back in 2010.\n翻译: <u>该报的出版商早在2010年就说：“未来的某个时候。”</u>\n\n-**publisher**：<u>出版人、发行人，这里是报社高层负责人。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Nostalgia</font> for ink on paper and the<font color=\"#00b050\"> rustle of pages</font><font color=\"#00b050\"> aside</font>, there’s plenty of <font color=\"#00b050\">incentive</font> to ditch print.\n翻译: <u>撇开对纸上油墨和翻页沙沙声的怀旧不谈，放弃印刷版有很多动因。</u>\n\n-**nostalgia for…**：<u>对……的怀旧。</u>  \n-**the rustle of pages**：<u>纸页翻动的沙沙声。</u>  \n-**aside**：<u>放到一边、不谈。</u> \n-**incentive**：<u>动机、刺激因素、诱因。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe infrastructure required to make a <font color=\"#00b050\">physical</font> newspaper — <font color=\"#00b050\">printing presses</font>, delivery trucks — isn’t<font color=\"#00b050\"> just</font> expensive; it’s <font color=\"#00b050\">excessive</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">at a time when</font> online-only competitors don’t have the same set of financial constraints.\n翻译: <u>制作实体报纸所需的基础设施——印刷机、送货卡车——不仅昂贵；在纯在线竞争者不受同样财务约束的时代，它还显得过度。</u>\n\n-physical <u>实体的</u>\n-**printing presses**：<u>印刷机。</u> \n-**isn’t just expensive** <u>暗示后面还要进一步说明：问题不只是贵，而是在当下显得过度、不合时宜。</u>\n-**excessive**：<u>过度的、超出必要的。</u> \n-**at a time when…**：<u>在……的时代。</u>\n\n---\n\nReaders are <font color=\"#00b050\">migrating away</font> from print anyway.\n翻译: <u>无论如何，读者正在离开印刷版。</u>\n\n-**migrate away from…**：<u>从……迁移出去、逐渐离开……。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnd though print ad sales still <font color=\"#00b050\">dwarf</font> their online and mobile counterparts, <font color=\"#00b050\">revenue from print</font> is still declining.\n翻译: <u>而且，尽管纸媒广告销售额仍远远超过在线和移动端广告销售额，来自纸媒的收入仍在下降。</u>\n\n-**dwarf** <u>原意是“使显得矮小”，这里作动词表示“远远超过、使……相形见绌”。</u>\n-**revenue from print**：<u>来自纸质业务的收入。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#00b050\">Overhead</font> may be high and <font color=\"#00b050\">circulation</font> lower, but <font color=\"#00b050\">rushing to</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">eliminate</font> its print edition would be a mistake, says BuzzFeed CEO Jonah Peretti.\n翻译: <u>BuzzFeed首席执行官Jonah Peretti说，管理费用可能很高，发行量也较低，但急于取消其印刷版将是一个错误。</u>\n\n-**overhead**：<u>运营间接成本、固定成本，比如印刷、配送、管理成本。</u>\n-**circulation**：<u>发行量。</u> \n-**rushing to do**：<u>仓促做某事。</u>\n-**eliminate**：<u>取消、淘汰。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPeretti says the Times shouldn’t waste time getting out of the print business, but only if they <font color=\"#00b050\">go about doing </font>it the right way.\n翻译: <u>Peretti说，Times不应该浪费时间退出印刷业务，但前提是他们要以正确的方式去做。</u>\n\n-**go about doing it** <u>强调“采取什么路径、怎样推进”。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Figuring out a way to accelerate <font color=\"#00b050\">that transition</font> would <font color=\"#00b050\">make sense</font> for them,” he said, “but if you discontinue it, you’re going to have your <font color=\"#00b050\">most loyal customers </font>really upset with you.”\n翻译: <u>他说：“想出一种办法来加快这种转型，对他们来说是有意义的；但如果你停止它，你会让你最忠实的客户对你非常不满。”</u>\n\n-**that transition**：<u>那种转型，指从纸质业务转向数字业务。</u>\n-**make sense**：<u>有道理、合理。</u>  \n-**most loyal customers**：<u>最忠诚的顾客。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nSometimes that’s worth making a change anyway.\n翻译: <u>有时候，即便如此，做出改变也是值得的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPeretti gives the example of Netflix discontinuing its DVD-mailing service to focus on streaming.\n翻译: <u>Peretti举了Netflix停止其DVD邮寄服务、转而专注于流媒体的例子。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It was seen as a <font color=\"#00b050\">blunder</font>,” he said.\n翻译: <u>他说：“当时这被视为一个失误。”</u>\n\n-**blunder**：<u>大错、愚蠢错误。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThe move turned out to be <font color=\"#00b050\">foresighted</font>.\n翻译: <u>这一举措后来证明是有先见之明的。</u>\n\n-**foresighted**：<u>有远见的、具有前瞻性的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#00b050\">if</font> Peretti <font color=\"#00b050\">were</font> in charge at the Times?\n翻译: <u>那么，如果Peretti掌管Times呢？</u>\n\n-**if** <u>引导虚拟条件。**were** 用虚拟语气，因为 Peretti 实际上并不掌管《纽约时报》。**in charge**：负责、掌管。</u>\n\n---\n\n“I wouldn’t pick a year to end print,” he said.\n翻译: <u>他说：“我不会选定某一年终止印刷版。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I would raise prices and make it into <font color=\"#00b050\">more of a</font> <font color=\"#00b050\">legacy product</font>.”\n翻译: <u>“我会提高价格，把它更多地变成一种传统产品。”</u>\n\n-**more of a…** <u>表示“更像是……”。</u>\n-**legacy product**：<u>传统遗留产品、经典保留产品。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe most loyal customers would still get the product they favor, <font color=\"#00b050\">the idea goes,</font> and they’d feel like they were helping sustain the quality of something they believe in.\n翻译: <u>这种想法是，最忠实的客户仍会得到他们偏爱的产品，而且他们会觉得自己是在帮助维持某种他们所信仰之物的质量。</u>\n\n-**the idea goes** <u>类似 **the argument goes**，意思是“这个想法的逻辑是”。</u> \n\n---\n\n“So if you’re overpaying for print, you could feel like you were helping,” Peretti said.\n翻译: <u>Peretti说：“所以，如果你为印刷版支付了过高的费用，你可能会觉得自己是在帮忙。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Then increase it at a higher rate each year and essentially try to generate additional revenue.”\n翻译: <u>“然后每年以更高的幅度提高价格，本质上是努力创造额外收入。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn other words, if you’re going to make a print product, make it for the people who are already obsessed with it.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，如果你要做一种印刷产品，就为那些已经对它着迷的人去做。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhich may be what the Times is doing already.\n翻译: <u>这也许正是Times已经在做的事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nGetting the print edition seven days a week costs nearly $500 a year — more than twice as much as a digital-only subscription.\n翻译: <u>每周七天获取印刷版一年花费近500美元——是纯数字订阅费用的两倍多。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It’s a really hard thing to do and it’s a tremendous luxury that <font color=\"#00b050\">BuzzFeed </font>doesn’t have a <font color=\"#00b050\">legacy business</font>,” Peretti remarked.\n翻译: <u>Peretti评论说：“这是一件非常难做的事，而BuzzFeed没有传统业务，这是一个巨大的奢侈条件。”</u>\n\n-BuzzFeed <u>是数字媒体，没有类似沉重的纸质业务。</u>\n-**legacy business**：<u>传统遗留业务、历史业务包袱。</u>  \n\n---\n\n“But we’re going to have questions like that where we have things we’re doing that <font color=\"#00b050\">don’t make sense</font> when the market changes and the world changes.”\n翻译: <u>“但我们也会遇到类似的问题：当市场变化、世界变化时，我们正在做的一些事情就不再合理。”</u>\n\n-**don’t make sense**：<u>不再合理、不再有意义。</u>  \n-<u>他说：“不过，BuzzFeed 以后也会遇到类似问题：有些现在还在做的事，等市场和世界变了，可能就不再合理了。”</u>\n\n\n---\n\n“In those situations, it’s better to be more <font color=\"#00b050\">aggressive</font> than less aggressive.”\n翻译: <u>“在那些情况下，采取更积极的做法比不那么积极要好。”</u>\n\n-**aggressive** <u>在商业语境中不是“攻击性强”，而是“积极果断、大胆”。</u>  \n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2017","year":"2017","title":"2017 年英语一","fileName":"2017 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2017 年英语 1.md","content":"第一篇\n\nFirst two hours, now three hours — this is how far in advance authorities are recommending people show up to catch a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> domestic flight</font>, at least at some major U.S. airports with increasingly massive security lines.\n翻译: <u>先是提前两个小时，现在是三个小时——这就是当局建议人们提前多久到机场赶国内航班的程度，至少在一些安检队伍日益庞大的美国主要机场是这样。</u>\n\n-**domestic flight**：<u>国内航班。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAmericans are willing to tolerate <font color=\"#ffff00\">time-consuming</font> security procedures in return for increased safety.\n翻译: <u>美国人愿意忍受耗时的安检程序，以换取更高的安全性。</u>\n\n-**time-consuming**：<u>耗费时间的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe crash of EgyptAir Flight 804, which terrorists <font color=\"#ffff00\">may have downed</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> over the Mediterranean Sea</font>, provides another tragic reminder of why.\n翻译: <u>埃及航空804号航班的坠毁事件——恐怖分子可能在地中海上空将其击落——又一次以悲剧方式提醒人们为什么要这样做。</u>\n\n-**may have done** <u>表示对过去事情的不确定推测。</u>\n-**over the Mediterranean Sea**：<u>在地中海上空。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">demanding too much of air travelers</font> or providing too little security in return undermines public support for<font color=\"#ffff00\"> the process.</font>\n翻译: <u>但是，对航空旅客要求过多，或者作为回报提供的安全保障太少，都会削弱公众对这一流程的支持。</u>\n\n-**demand too much of someone**：<u>对某人要求过多。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">it should</font>: <font color=\"#ffff00\">Wasted time</font> is a drag on Americans’ economic and private lives, <font color=\"#ffff00\">not to mention</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">infuriating</font>.\n翻译: <u>而且也应该如此：浪费的时间拖累着美国人的经济生活和私人生活，更不用说还令人恼火了。</u>\n\n-**should** <u>这里表示“应该会 / 理应会”。</u>  \n-**wasted time**：<u>浪费掉的时间。</u>  \n-**not to mention…**：<u>更不用说……。</u>  \n-**infuriating**：<u>令人愤怒的、让人火大的。</u>  \n-<u>公众支持被削弱也很正常：浪费时间不仅影响美国人的工作和私人生活，还非常让人恼火。</u>\n\n---\n\nLast year, the Transportation Security Administration (TSA) found in a <font color=\"#ffff00\">secret check</font> that<font color=\"#ffff00\"> undercover</font> investigators were able to sneak weapons — <font color=\"#ffff00\">both fake and real</font> — past airport security nearly every time they tried.\n翻译: <u>去年，美国运输安全管理局（TSA）在一次秘密检查中发现，卧底调查人员几乎每次尝试都能把武器——假的和真的都有——偷偷带过机场安检。</u>\n\n-**secret check**：<u>秘密检查、暗访测试。</u>  \n-**undercover**：<u>卧底的、秘密身份的。</u>  \n-both  a and b <u>既有---也有---</u>\n\n\n---\n\nEnhanced security measures since then, <font color=\"#ffff00\">combined with</font> a rise in airline travel due to the improving economy and low oil prices, have resulted in long waits at major airports such as Chicago’s O’Hare International.\n翻译: <u>自那以后加强的安保措施，加上经济好转和低油价导致航空旅行增加，使芝加哥奥黑尔国际机场等主要机场出现了长时间等待。</u>\n\n-**combined with…**：<u>与……结合起来 / 再加上……。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt is <font color=\"#ffff00\">not yet</font> clear how much more effective airline security has become — but the lines are obvious.\n翻译: <u>航空安检变得更有效的程度目前尚不清楚——但排队的队伍显而易见。</u>\n\n-**not yet**：<u>尚未。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nPart of the issue is that the government did not anticipate the steep increase in airline travel, so the TSA<font color=\"#ffff00\"> is now rushing to</font> get new <font color=\"#ffff00\">screeners</font> on the line.\n翻译: <u>问题的一部分在于，政府没有预料到航空旅行会急剧增加，因此TSA现在正匆忙让新的安检员上岗。</u>\n\n-**is now rushing to do**：<u>现在正急着做某事。</u>  \n-**screeners**：<u>安检员，负责检查旅客和行李。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Part of </font>the issue is that airports <font color=\"#ffff00\">have only so much room</font> for screening lanes.\n翻译: <u>问题的一部分在于，机场用于安检通道的空间只有这么多。</u>\n\n-Part of   <u>问题的另一部分在于。与上一句重复 **Part of the issue is that…**，列举第二个原因。</u>\n-**only so much** <u>是常见表达，意思是“只有这么多，不能无限增加”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnother factor may be that more people are trying to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> overpack</font> their<font color=\"#ffff00\"> carry-on bags</font> to avoid <font color=\"#ffff00\">checked-baggage</font> fees, though the airlines <font color=\"#ffff00\">strongly dispute</font> this.\n翻译: <u>另一个因素可能是，更多人为了避免托运行李费而试图把随身行李塞得过满，尽管航空公司强烈反驳这一点。</u>\n\n-**overpack**：<u>过度打包、塞得太满。</u>\n-carry-on bags**：<u>随身行李、登机箱。</u>  \n-**checked-baggage fees**：<u>托运行李费。</u>  \n-**strongly dispute**：<u>强烈反驳、强烈否认。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is one step</font> the TSA could take that would not require <font color=\"#ffff00\">remodeling airport</font>s or rushing to hire: Enroll more people in the PreCheck program.\n翻译: <u>TSA可以采取一个不需要改造机场或匆忙招聘的步骤：让更多人加入PreCheck计划。</u>\n\n-There be <u>句型。 有一个步骤 / 有一个办法。</u>\n-**remodeling airports**：<u>改造机场。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPreCheck is supposed to be a win-win for travelers and the TSA.\n翻译: <u>PreCheck本应对旅客和TSA来说是双赢。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPassengers who pass a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> background chec</font>k are eligible to use <font color=\"#ffff00\">expedited </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">screening lanes</font>.\n翻译: <u>通过背景审查的乘客有资格使用快速安检通道。</u>\n\n-**background check**：<u>背景审查，比如身份、犯罪记录、安全风险等检查。</u>\n-**expedited**：<u>加快的、快速处理的。</u>  \n-**screening lanes**：<u>安检通道。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis allows the TSA to focus on travelers who are higher risk, saving time for everyone involved.\n翻译: <u>这使TSA能够把注意力集中在风险更高的旅客身上，从而为所有相关人员节省时间。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe TSA wants to <font color=\"#ffff00\">enroll</font> 25 million people in PreCheck.\n翻译: <u>TSA希望让2500万人加入PreCheck。</u>\n\n-**want to enroll**：<u>想让人注册加入。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt has <font color=\"#ffff00\">not</font> gotten <font color=\"#ffff00\">anywhere close</font> to that, and one big reason is<font color=\"#ffff00\"> sticker shock</font>: Passengers must pay $85 every five years to <font color=\"#ffff00\">process </font>their background checks.\n翻译: <u>它离这个目标还差得很远，一个重要原因是价格令人咋舌：乘客必须每五年支付85美元来处理他们的背景审查。</u>\n\n-**not anywhere close**：<u>完全没接近、差得远。</u>  \n-**sticker shock**：<u>看到价格标签后感到震惊，指价格让人望而却步。</u>  \n-**process**：<u>处理、办理。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSince the beginning, this price tag has been PreCheck’s<font color=\"#ffff00\"> fatal flaw.</font>\n翻译: <u>从一开始，这个价格标签就是PreCheck的致命缺陷。</u>\n\n-**fatal flaw**：<u>致命缺陷。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Upcoming</font> reforms might bring the price to a more reasonable level.\n翻译: <u>即将到来的改革可能会把价格降到更合理的水平。</u>\n\n-**upcoming**：<u>即将到来的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut Congress should<font color=\"#ffff00\"> look into</font> doing so directly, by helping to <font color=\"#ffff00\">finance</font> PreCheck enrollment or to cut costs in other ways.\n翻译: <u>但国会应该考虑直接这样做，通过帮助资助PreCheck注册或以其他方式削减成本。</u>\n\n-**look into**：<u>调查、研究、考虑。</u>  \n-**finance**：<u>资助、提供资金。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe TSA cannot continue<font color=\"#ffff00\"> diverting resources</font> into <font color=\"#ffff00\">underused</font> PreCheck lanes <font color=\"#ffff00\">while</font> most of the traveling public suffers in unnecessary lines.\n翻译: <u>TSA不能继续把资源转移到使用不足的PreCheck通道上，而让大多数旅行公众在不必要的队伍中受苦。</u>\n\n-**divert resources**：<u>转移资源、调配资源。</u>  \n-**underused**：<u>未被充分使用的、使用率低的。</u>  \n-**while** <u>在这里强调对比：一边资源投入到用不满的快速通道，一边普通旅客排长队。</u>  \n-TSA <u>不能一边把资源投向没充分利用的 PreCheck 通道，一边让大多数旅客继续在本可避免的长队中苦等。</u>\n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It is long past time</font> to make the program work.\n翻译: <u>早就该让这个项目发挥作用了。</u>\n\n-ong past time** <u>是固定表达，意思是“早已过了该做某事的时候”，即“早该做了”。</u>  \n<u>语气比 **it is time** 更强。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇阅读\n\n\n“The ancient Hawaiians were <font color=\"#ffff00\">astronomers,</font>” wrote Queen Liliuokalani, Hawaii’s last <font color=\"#ffff00\">reigning monarch</font>, in 1897.\n翻译: <u>“古代夏威夷人是天文学家，”夏威夷最后一位在位君主Liliuokalani女王在1897年写道。</u>\n\n-**were astronomers**：<u>是天文学家。</u> \n-**reigning monarch**：<u>在位君主。</u>  \n\n---\n\nStar watchers were among the <font color=\"#ffff00\">most esteemed</font> members of Hawaiian society.\n翻译: <u>观星者曾是夏威夷社会中最受尊敬的成员之一。</u>\n\n-**the most esteemed members**：<u>最受尊敬的成员。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSadly,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> all is not well with</font> astronomy in Hawaii today.\n翻译: <u>遗憾的是，如今夏威夷的天文学状况并不顺利。</u>\n\n-**all is not well with…** <u>是习惯表达，意思是“……情况并不好 / 出了问题”。</u>  \n<u>不是字面上的“所有都不好”，而是“事情不太妙”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Protests</font> have <font color=\"#ffff00\">erupted</font> over construction of the Thirty Meter Telescope (TMT), a giant <font color=\"#ffff00\">observatory</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">promises to </font>revolutionize humanity’s view of the cosmos.\n翻译: <u>围绕三十米望远镜（TMT）的建设爆发了抗议；这是一座巨型天文台，有望彻底改变人类对宇宙的认识。</u>\n\n-**protests**：<u>抗议活动。</u> \n-**have erupted**：<u>爆发。</u> \n-**observatory**：<u>天文台、观测站。</u>  \n-**promise to do**：<u>有望做某事。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">At issue</font> is the TMT’s planned location on Mauna Kea, a dormant volcano <font color=\"#ffff00\">worshiped</font> by some Hawaiians as the piko, that connects the Hawaiian Islands to the heavens.\n翻译: <u>争议的焦点是TMT计划建在Mauna Kea上；这是一座休眠火山，一些夏威夷人将其作为piko来崇拜，认为它把夏威夷群岛与天界相连。</u>\n\n-**at issue**：<u>处于争议中的、问题焦点所在的。</u> \n-**worshiped**：<u>被崇拜、被敬奉。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut Mauna Kea is also home to some of the world’s most powerful telescopes.\n翻译: <u>但Mauna Kea也是世界上一些最强大望远镜的所在地。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Rested in</font> the Pacific Ocean, Mauna Kea’s peak <font color=\"#ffff00\">rises above</font> the bulk of our planet’s dense atmosphere, where conditions allow telescopes to obtain images of unsurpassed clarity.\n翻译: <u>坐落于太平洋中，Mauna Kea的峰顶高出地球大部分厚重的大气层，在那里，条件使望远镜能够获得清晰度无与伦比的图像。</u>\n\n-Rested in  <u>坐落在</u>\n-**rises above**：<u>升到……之上。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Opposition</font> to telescopes on Mauna Kea is <font color=\"#ffff00\">nothing new.</font>\n翻译: <u>反对在Mauna Kea上建望远镜并不是什么新鲜事。</u>\n\n \n-**opposition to…**：<u>对……的反对。</u>  \n-**nothing new**：<u>不新鲜、早已有之。</u>\n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">small but vocal</font> group of Hawaiians and environmentalists have long viewed <font color=\"#ffff00\">their presence</font> as disrespect for <font color=\"#ffff00\">sacred land</font> and a painful reminder of the occupation of what <font color=\"#ffff00\">was once</font> a <font color=\"#ffff00\">sovereign nation</font>.\n翻译: <u>一小群但声音响亮的夏威夷人和环保主义者长期以来一直把这些望远镜的存在视为对圣地的不敬，也是对这个曾经主权国家被占领的痛苦提醒。</u>\n\n-**small but vocal**：<u>人数不多但发声积极、声音响亮。</u>  \n-**their presence** <u>指望远镜在 Mauna Kea 上的存在。</u>\n-**sacred land**：<u>神圣土地。</u> \n-**was once**：<u>曾经是。</u>  \n-**a sovereign nation**：<u>一个主权国家。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Some blame</font> for the current controversy belongs to astronomers.\n翻译: <u>当前争议的部分责任在天文学家。</u>\n\n-**some blame**：<u>一些责任。</u>  \n-<u>当前这场争议，天文学家也应承担部分责任。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn their eagerness to build bigger telescopes, they forgot that science is not the only way of understanding the world.\n翻译: <u>在他们急切地建造更大望远镜的过程中，他们忘记了科学并不是理解世界的唯一方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#ffff00\">did not always</font> prioritize the protection of Mauna Kea’s fragile ecosystems or its <font color=\"#ffff00\">holiness</font> to the island’s inhabitants.\n翻译: <u>他们并不总是优先保护Mauna Kea脆弱的生态系统，也没有总是优先考虑它对岛上居民而言的神圣性。</u>\n\n-**did not always**：<u>并非总是。</u>  \n-**holiness**：<u>神圣性。</u> \n\n---\n\nHawaiian culture is not a relic of the past; it is a living culture undergoing a <font color=\"#ffff00\">renaissance</font> today.\n翻译: <u>夏威夷文化并不是过去的遗物；它是一种如今正在经历复兴的活态文化。</u>\n\n-**renaissance**：<u>复兴、再生。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Yet</font> science has a cultural history, too, with roots going back to the dawn of civilization.\n翻译: <u>然而，科学也有其文化史，其根源可以追溯到文明的黎明。</u>\n\n-yet <u>然而 / 不过</u>\n\n---\n\nThe same curiosity to find <font color=\"#ffff00\">what lies beyond the horizon</font> that first brought early Polynesians to Hawaii’s<font color=\"#ffff00\"> shores</font> inspires astronomers today to explore the heavens.\n翻译: <u>正是那种想要发现地平线之外有什么的好奇心，最初把早期波利尼西亚人带到了夏威夷海岸；这种好奇心今天也激励着天文学家探索天界。</u>\n\n-**what lies beyond the horizon**：<u>地平线之外有什么。</u>  \n-**Hawaii’s shores**：<u>夏威夷海岸。</u>  \n-\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Calls to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">disassemble</font> all telescopes on Mauna Kea or to ban future development there ignore the reality that astronomy and Hawaiian culture both seek to answer big questions about who we are, where we come from and where we are going.\n翻译: <u>呼吁拆除Mauna Kea上的所有望远镜，或禁止那里未来的发展，忽视了这样一个现实：天文学和夏威夷文化都在试图回答关于我们是谁、我们从哪里来以及我们将去向何方的重大问题。</u>\n\n-**calls to do**：<u>要求做某事的呼声。</u>  \n-**disassemble**：<u>拆除、拆解。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPerhaps that is why we explore the starry skies, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as if</font> answering a <font color=\"#ffff00\">primal</font> calling to know ourselves and our<font color=\"#ffff00\"> true ancestral</font> homes.\n翻译: <u>也许这就是我们探索星空的原因，仿佛是在回应一种原始的召唤，去认识我们自己和我们真正的祖先家园。</u>\n\n-**as if we are answering a primal calling**。   <u>仿佛是在回应一种原始召唤。</u>\n-**true ancestral homes**：<u>真正的祖先家园。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">astronomy community</font> is making <font color=\"#ffff00\">compromises</font> to change its use of Mauna Kea.\n翻译: <u>天文学界正在作出妥协，以改变其对Mauna Kea的使用方式。</u>\n\n-**community** <u>在这里不是居民社区，而是“共同体、群体”。</u>  \n-**make compromises**：<u>作出妥协。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe TMT site was chosen to minimize the telescope’s visibility around the island and to avoid archaeological and environmental impact.\n翻译: <u>TMT的选址是为了尽量减少该望远镜在岛上各处的可见度，并避免考古和环境影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTo limit the number of telescopes on Mauna Kea, old ones will be removed at the end of their lifetimes and their <font color=\"#ffff00\">sites</font> returned to a <font color=\"#ffff00\">natural state.</font>\n翻译: <u>为了限制Mauna Kea上的望远镜数量，旧望远镜将在其寿命结束时被拆除，其所在地将恢复为自然状态。</u>\n\n-**sites**：<u>地点、场址。</u>  \n-**returned to a natural state**：<u>恢复为自然状态。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There is no reason why </font>everyone <font color=\"#ffff00\">cannot</font> be welcomed on Mauna Kea to embrace their cultural heritage and to study the stars.\n翻译: <u>没有理由不能欢迎每个人来到Mauna Kea，拥抱他们的文化遗产并研究星辰。</u>\n\n-**There is no reason why…**：<u>没有理由说……不能。  这是一种强调“完全可以”的表达。</u>\n\n<u>没有理由说“不能”</u>  \n= <u>没理由不能</u>  \n= <u>可以</u>\n\n**There is no reason why X cannot do Y** \n翻译: <u>**没有理由说明X不能做Y**</u>\n**X <u>完全可以做 Y。**</u>\n\n-<u>没有理由说 Mauna Kea 不能同时欢迎不同的人：有人来珍视文化遗产，也有人来研究星空。</u>\n\n---\n21. The author’s attitude toward choosing Mauna Kea as the TMT site is one of  \n\n[A] severe criticism.\n\n[B] passive acceptance.\n\n[C] slight hesitancy.\n\n[D] full approval.\n\n<u>又犯了同样的错误 文章问作者的意思 文章可以不是中立的 有立场的,选 c 完全是预设了话不说满的原则</u>\n\n\n第三篇\nRobert F. Kennedy once said that a country’s GDP measures “everything except that which makes life worthwhile.”\n翻译: <u>Robert F. Kennedy曾说，一个国家的GDP衡量的是“除那些使生活有价值的东西之外的一切”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">With</font> Britain voting to leave the European Union, and GDP already <font color=\"#ffff00\">predicted to </font>slow <font color=\"#ffff00\">as a result</font>, it is now a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> timely</font> moment to assess what he was referring to.\n翻译: <u>随着英国投票决定离开欧盟，而GDP已被预测会因此放缓，现在正是评估他所指之事的合适时机。</u>\n\n-with + <u>名词 + 现在分词，作背景状语。</u>\n-**predicted to slow**：<u>被预测会放缓。</u>  \n-**as a result**：<u>因此，指由于英国脱欧。</u>\n-**timely**：<u>及时的、正合时宜的。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe question of GDP and its usefulness has annoyed policymakers for over half a century.\n翻译: <u>GDP及其有用性这一问题已经困扰政策制定者半个多世纪。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMany argue that it is a flawed concept.\n翻译: <u>许多人认为它是一个有缺陷的概念。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt measures things that <font color=\"#ffff00\">do not matter</font> and misses things <font color=\"#ffff00\">that do</font>.\n翻译: <u>它衡量了不重要的东西，却遗漏了重要的东西。</u>\n\n-**do not matter**：<u>并不真正重要。</u>  \n-**that do** = **that do matter**。  \n<u>英语中用 **do** 避免重复 **matter**。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBy most recent <font color=\"#ffff00\">measures</font>, the UK’s GDP has been the envy of the Western world, with record low unemployment and<font color=\"#ffff00\"> high growth figures</font>.\n翻译: <u>按照最近的大多数衡量标准，英国的GDP一直令西方世界羡慕，失业率创历史新低，增长数据也很高。</u>\n\n-**most recent measures**：<u>最近的大多数指标。</u>  \n-**high growth figures**：<u>高增长数字。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIf everything was going so well, then why did over 17 million people vote for Brexit, <font color=\"#ffff00\">despite</font> the warnings about what it could do to their country’s economic prospects?\n翻译: <u>如果一切都进展得如此顺利，那么为什么仍有超过1700万人投票支持Brexit，尽管有警告称这可能会影响他们国家的经济前景？</u>\n\n-**despite**：<u>尽管。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA recent <font color=\"#ffff00\">annual</font> study of countries and their ability to convert growth into well-being <font color=\"#ffff00\">sheds some light on</font> that question.\n翻译: <u>最近一项关于各国及其将增长转化为福祉的能力的年度研究，对这个问题提供了一些启示。</u>\n\n-**recent annual study**：<u>最近的一项年度研究。</u> \n-**shed light on**：<u>阐明、帮助理解。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Across</font> the 163 countries measured, the UK is one of the poorest performers in ensuring that economic growth is translated into meaningful improvements for its citizens.\n翻译: <u>在被衡量的163个国家中，英国是在确保经济增长转化为公民有意义的改善方面表现最差的国家之一。</u>\n\n-**across**：<u>在……范围内。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Rather than</font> just focusing on GDP, over 40 different <font color=\"#ffff00\">sets of criteria</font> from health, education and <font color=\"#ffff00\">civil society engagement</font> have been measured to get a <font color=\"#ffff00\">more rounded assessment</font> of how countries are performing.\n翻译: <u>为了对各国表现作出更全面的评估，衡量的不是仅仅聚焦于GDP，而是来自健康、教育和公民社会参与等方面的40多组不同标准。</u>\n\n-Rather than <u>不是只关注 GDP。</u>\n-**sets of criteria**：<u>几组/几套标准。</u>  \n-**civil society engagement**：<u>公民社会参与，</u>\n-**more rounded**：<u>更全面、更完整，而不是单一维度。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile all of these countries face their own challenges, there are a number of <font color=\"#ffff00\">consistent themes</font>.\n翻译: <u>尽管所有这些国家都面临各自的挑战，但存在若干一贯的主题。</u>\n\n-**consistent themes**：<u>一致的主题、反复出现的规律。</u>  \n\n---\n\nYes, there has been a <font color=\"#ffff00\">budding </font>economic recovery since the 2008 global crash, but in<font color=\"#ffff00\"> key indicators</font> in areas such as health and education, major economies have continued to decline.\n翻译: <u>是的，自2008年全球崩盘以来，经济复苏已初露端倪，但在健康和教育等领域的关键指标上，主要经济体仍在持续下滑。</u>\n\n-**budding**：<u>萌芽中的、初步的。</u>  \n-**key indicators**：<u>关键指标。</u>  \n\n---\n\nYet this isn’t the case with all countries.\n翻译: <u>然而，并非所有国家都是这种情况。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome <font color=\"#ffff00\">relatively poor</font> European countries have seen huge improvements across measures including civil society, income equality and the environment.\n翻译: <u>一些相对贫穷的欧洲国家在包括公民社会、收入平等和环境在内的各项指标上都取得了巨大改善。</u>\n\n-**relatively poor**：<u>相对贫穷的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThis is a lesson that rich countries can learn: When GDP is no longer regarded as the sole measure of a country’s success, the world looks very different.\n翻译: <u>这是富裕国家可以学习的一课：当GDP不再被视为衡量一个国家成功的唯一标准时，世界看起来就大不相同。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSo, what Kennedy was referring to was that while GDP has been the most common method for measuring the economic activity of nations, as a measure, it is no longer enough.\n翻译: <u>因此，Kennedy所指的是，尽管GDP一直是衡量各国经济活动最常用的方法，但作为一种衡量标准，它已不再足够。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt does not include <font color=\"#ffff00\">important factors</font> such as environmental quality or <font color=\"#ffff00\">education outcomes</font> — all things that contribute to a person’s sense of well-being.\n翻译: <u>它不包括环境质量或教育成果等重要因素，而这些都是有助于形成个人福祉感的事物。</u>\n\n-**important factors**：<u>重要因素。</u>\n-**education outcomes**：<u>教育结果、教育成效。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe sharp hit to growth<font color=\"#ffff00\"> predicted</font> around the world and in the UK could lead to a decline in the everyday services we depend on for our well-being and for growth.\n翻译: <u>预计全球和英国的增长将遭受严重打击，这可能导致我们日常依赖的服务减少，而这些服务关系到我们的福祉和增长。</u>\n\n-predicted <u>类似这种非谓语现在看的不是很熟练,chat gpt 练练</u>\n<u>非常好的长难句训练,再难的难句,划分好成分也是很 easy 的</u>\n-<u>地道意译：如果英国和全球经济增长如预测般受到重创，日常公共服务可能会恶化，而这些服务正是我们生活福祉和未来增长所依赖的基础。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut policymakers who refocus efforts on improving well-being rather than simply worrying about GDP figures could avoid the forecasted doom and <font color=\"#ffff00\">may even</font> see progress.\n翻译: <u>但是，如果政策制定者重新把努力集中在改善福祉上，而不是仅仅担忧GDP数字，他们就可能避开预测中的厄运，甚至可能看到进展。</u>\n\n-**may even**：<u>甚至可能。</u>  \n\n---\n\n21. Robert F. Kennedy is cited because he   \n\n[A] praised the UK for its GDP.\n\n[B] identified GDP with happiness.\n\n[C] misinterpreted the role of GDP.\n\n[D] had a low opinion of GDP.\n\n<u>依旧是人物主观意图填,大胆肯定它的想法,出题人就怕你不敢选</u>\n\n第四篇\n\nIn a rare <font color=\"#ffff00\">unanimous</font> ruling, the US Supreme Court has overturned the <font color=\"#ffff00\">corruption conviction</font> of a former Virginia governor, Robert McDonnell.\n翻译: <u>在一次罕见的一致裁决中，美国最高法院推翻了弗吉尼亚州前州长Robert McDonnell的腐败定罪。</u>\n\n-**unanimous**：<u>一致同意的、全体一致的。</u> \n-**corruption conviction**：<u>腐败罪定罪。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut it did so while <font color=\"#ffff00\">holding its nose at</font> the ethics of his conduct, which included accepting gifts such as a Rolex watch and a Ferrari automobile from a company seeking access to government.\n翻译: <u>但法院这样做时，对其行为的伦理性仍感厌恶；他的行为包括从一家寻求接触政府的公司接受Rolex手表和Ferrari汽车等礼物。</u>\n\n-**hold one’s nose at…** <u>字面是“捏住鼻子”，比喻“觉得恶心、反感、嫌弃”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe high court’s decision said the judge in Mr. McDonnell’s trial failed to tell <font color=\"#ffff00\">a </font>jury that it must look only at his “<font color=\"#ffff00\">official acts</font>,” <font color=\"#ffff00\">or</font> the former governor’s decisions on “<font color=\"#ffff00\">specific</font>” and “<font color=\"#ffff00\">unsettled</font>” issues <font color=\"#ffff00\">related to his duties</font>.\n翻译: <u>最高法院的判决称，McDonnell先生庭审中的法官未能告知陪审团，它必须只考察他的“官方行为”，即这位前州长就与其职责相关的“具体”且“未决”的问题所作的决定。</u>\n\n-**official acts**：<u>官方行为、公职行为。</u>  \n-<u>这里 **or** 不是“或者”，而是“也就是、换言之”。</u> \n-**specific issues**：<u>具体事项。</u>  \n-**unsettled issues**：<u>尚未定论、尚待处理的问题。</u>  \n-**related to his duties**：<u>与其职责相关。</u>  \n-jury <u>前面的a 因为是文章第一次提到，所以用 **a**。 不然用 the</u>\n\n<u>最高法院认为，原审法官没有正确指导陪审团：判断腐败时，只能看 McDonnell 是否作出了真正的“官方行为”，也就是是否在其职责范围内对具体、尚未解决的事项作出决定。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Merely</font> helping a gift-giver gain access to other officials, unless done with clear intent to pressure those officials, is not corruption, the justices <font color=\"#ffff00\">found</font>.\n翻译: <u>大法官们认定，仅仅帮助送礼者接触其他官员，除非是带着明确意图向那些官员施压，否则并不构成腐败。</u>\n\n-**merely**：<u>仅仅。</u>  \n- <u>这里 unless 插在中间 作为引导从句 比较少见 但是要习惯 **unless it is done with clear intent to pressure those officials**。</u>  \n- -**found** <u>在法律语境中是“认定、认为”。</u>\n-<u>地道意译：最高法院认为，单纯帮送礼者牵线接触其他官员，并不等于腐败；只有在明确意图施压那些官员时，才可能构成犯罪。</u>\n---\n\nThe court did suggest that accepting favors in return for opening doors is “distasteful” and “nasty.”\n翻译: <u>法院确实暗示，接受好处以换取开门牵线是“令人反感的”和“恶劣的”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut under anti-bribery laws, proof must be made of <font color=\"#ffff00\">concrete</font> benefits, such as approval of a contract or <font color=\"#ffff00\">regulation</font>.\n翻译: <u>但根据反贿赂法，必须证明存在具体利益，例如批准一份合同或一项监管规定。</u>\n\n-**concrete benefits**：<u>具体利益、实质好处。</u>\n-**regulation**：<u>规章、监管规定。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSimply arranging a meeting, making a phone call, or <font color=\"#ffff00\">hosting an event</font> is not an “official act”.\n翻译: <u>仅仅安排一次会面、打一通电话或主办一场活动，并不是一种“官方行为”。</u>\n\n-**hosting an event**：<u>主持/举办一个活动。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe court’s ruling is <font color=\"#ffff00\">legally sound</font> in defining a kind of <font color=\"#ffff00\">favoritism</font> that is not criminal.\n翻译: <u>法院的裁决在界定一种不构成犯罪的偏袒行为方面，在法律上是合理的。</u>\n\n-**legally sound**：<u>法律上合理、合法理上稳固。</u>  \n-**favoritism**：<u>偏袒、徇私。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Elected leaders</font> must be allowed to help supporters deal with bureaucratic problems without <font color=\"#ffff00\">fear of prosecution</font> for bribery.\n翻译: <u>必须允许民选领导人帮助支持者处理官僚问题，而不必担心因贿赂而被起诉。</u>\n\n-**elected leaders**：<u>民选领导人。</u> \n-**fear of prosecution**：<u>害怕被起诉。</u>  \n-<u>民选官员应当可以帮助支持者解决行政难题，而不能因为这种正常政治服务就担心被控受贿。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The <font color=\"#ffff00\">basic compact</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">underlying</font> representative government,” wrote Chief Justice John Roberts for the court, “<font color=\"#ffff00\">assumes that </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">public officials</font> will hear from their <font color=\"#ffff00\">constituents</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">act on their concerns.</font>”\n翻译: <u>首席大法官John Roberts代表法院写道：“代议制政府所依据的基本契约”假定“公职人员会听取选民的意见，并回应他们的关切。”</u>\n\n-**basic compact**：<u>基本契约、基本约定。</u>  \n-**underlying**：<u>构成基础的、位于背后的。</u>  \n-**assume**：<u>假定、以……为前提。</u>\n-**public officials**：<u>公职人员。</u>\n-**constituents**：<u>选区选民。</u>\n-**act on their concerns**：<u>根据他们的关切采取行动。</u>  \n-<u>中间谁谁说的 作为了一个插入语,前后的话实际上是连起来的</u>\n-<u>首席大法官 Roberts 在法院意见中写道：代议制政府的基本前提，就是官员会听取选民声音，并回应他们关心的问题。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nBut the ruling reinforces<font color=\"#ffff00\"> the need</font> for citizens and their <font color=\"#ffff00\">elected representatives</font>, not the courts, to <font color=\"#ffff00\">ensure equality of access to government</font>.\n翻译: <u>但这一裁决强化了这样一种必要性：确保平等接触政府的，应是公民及其民选代表，而不是法院。</u>\n\n-**the need**：<u>必要性。</u>  \n-**elected representatives**：<u>民选代表。</u>  \n-**ensure equality of access to government**：<u>确保接触政府资源/官员的机会平等。</u> \n\n---\n\nOfficials must not be allowed to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> play favorites</font> in providing information or in arranging meetings simply because an individual or group provides a <font color=\"#ffff00\">campaign donation</font> or a personal gift.\n翻译: <u>官员不得仅仅因为某个个人或团体提供了竞选捐款或个人礼物，就在提供信息或安排会面时偏袒一方。</u>\n\n-**play favorites**：<u>偏袒、厚此薄彼。</u>\n-**campaign donation**：<u>竞选捐款。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">This type of integrity</font> requires well-enforced laws in government transparency, such as records of official meetings, <font color=\"#ffff00\">rules on lobbying</font>, and information about each elected leader’s source of wealth.\n翻译: <u>这种廉洁性需要政府透明度方面得到良好执行的法律，例如官方会议记录、游说规则，以及关于每位民选领导人财富来源的信息。</u>\n\n-**this type of integrity**：<u>这种廉洁性、这种公共诚信。</u>  \n-**rules on lobbying**：<u>关于游说的规则。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Favoritism</font> in official access can <font color=\"#ffff00\">fan</font> public <font color=\"#ffff00\">perceptions of corruption.</font>\n翻译: <u>官方接触渠道中的偏袒会煽动公众对腐败的观感。</u>\n\n-**favoritism**：<u>偏袒。</u>  \n-**fan** <u>字面是“扇风”，这里比喻“助长、煽动、加剧”。</u>  \n-**public perceptions**：<u>公众看法、公众认知。</u>  \n<u>偏袒会让公众更觉得政府腐败。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut it is not always corruption.\n翻译: <u>但它并不总是腐败。</u>\n\n-<u>但这种偏袒并不一定都构成法律意义上的腐败。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Rather</font> officials must avoid double standards, <font color=\"#ffff00\">or</font> different types of access for average people and the wealthy.\n翻译: <u>相反，官员必须避免双重标准，或避免让普通人与富人享有不同类型的接触渠道。</u>\n\n-**Rather** <u>在这里不是“相当”，而是“而是、确切地说”。</u>  \n-<u>这里 **or** 不是“或者”，而是“也就是说”  **or** 就是起到**补充说明 / 解释说明**的作用。也</u>\n<u>可以翻译成就是说  换言之  或者说  即</u>\n\n---\n\nIf <font color=\"#ffff00\">connections</font> can be bought, a basic premise of democratic society — that all are <font color=\"#ffff00\">equal in treatment</font> by government — is undermined.\n翻译: <u>如果关系可以买到，那么民主社会的一个基本前提——所有人在政府对待中都是平等的——就会被削弱。</u>\n\n-**connections**：<u>关系、人脉、接触渠道。</u>  \n-**equal in treatment**：<u>在待遇上平等。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Good governance</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">rests on</font> an understanding of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">inherent worth</font> of each individual.\n翻译: <u>良好治理建立在对每个人内在价值的理解之上。</u>\n\n-**good governance**：<u>良好治理、良政。</u>  \n-**rest on**：<u>建立在……基础上，依赖于……。</u>  \n-**inherent worth**：<u>内在价值、固有尊严。</u>  \n<u>直译：良好治理建立在对每个人内在价值的理解之上。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe court’s ruling is a step forward <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the struggle against</font> both corruption and official favoritism.\n翻译: <u>法院的裁决是在反对腐败和官方偏袒的斗争中迈出的一步。</u>\n\n-**struggle against…**：<u>反对……的斗争。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n<u>做下来感觉,阅读题无非就是把文章里的东西,放到选项里,换了一个说法,用另外的单词和惯用法表达同一种意思让人选</u>\n<u>最大的要求就是能看懂就行,能细心,要小心<font color=\"#ffff00\">偷换主语</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\">定位原文错误</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\">没有根据直接选</font>,有一点根据,但不是完全确定,<font color=\"#ffff00\">其它的相比于它更可靠</font>,还是得选其它的.</u>\n\n\n21. According to Paragraph 4, an official act is deemed corruptive only if it involves   \n\n[A] leaking secrets intentionally. \n\n[B] sizable gains in the form of gifts.\n\n[C] concrete returns for gift-givers.\n\n[D] breaking contracts officially.\n\n<u>第 4 段说，反贿赂法下必须证明有 **concrete benefits**，比如批准合同或法规。也就是说，只有礼物给予者获得了具体回报，才可能构成腐败。</u>  \n<u>所以应选 **C concrete returns for gift-givers**。</u>  \n<u>你选的 **D breaking contracts officially** 不对，文中说的是 “approval of a contract or regulation”，不是“违反合同”。</u>\n\n<u>选 D</u>\n\n\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2018","year":"2018","title":"2018 年英语一","fileName":"2018.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2018.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIt is <font color=\"#ffff00\">curious</font> that Stephen Koziatek feels almost <font color=\"#ffff00\">as though</font> he has to <font color=\"#ffff00\">justify</font> his efforts to give his students a better future.\n翻译: <u>令人奇怪的是，Stephen Koziatek几乎觉得自己必须为努力给学生一个更好的未来而辩解。</u>\n\n-**curious** <u>在这里不是“好奇的”，而是“奇怪的、耐人寻味的”。</u>  \n-**as though**：<u>好像、仿佛。</u>\n-**justify**：<u>证明……是合理的、为……辩解。</u>  \n-Stephen Koziatek <u>明明是在努力帮助学生拥有更好的未来，却似乎还得为自己的做法辩护，这实在有些奇怪。</u>\n\n---\n\nMr. Koziatek is part of <font color=\"#ffff00\">something pioneering.</font>\n翻译: <u>Koziatek先生是某种开创性事物的一部分。</u>\n\n-**something pioneering**：<u>某种开创性的东西。</u>\n\n---\n\nHe is a teacher at a New Hampshire high school where learning is not something of books and tests and mechanical memorization, but practical.\n翻译: <u>他是New Hampshire一所高中的教师，在那里，学习不是关于书本、考试和机械记忆的东西，而是实践性的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen did it become <font color=\"#ffff00\">accepted wisdom</font> that students should be able to name the 13th president of the United States but be utterly overwhelmed by a broken bike chain?\n翻译: <u>从什么时候起，学生应该能够说出美国第13任总统的名字，却会被一条断掉的自行车链弄得完全不知所措，成了公认的看法？</u>\n\n-**accepted wisdom**：<u>公认的看法、普遍接受的观点。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">As</font> Koziatek knows, there is learning in just about everything.\n翻译: <u>正如Koziatek所知道的，几乎所有事情中都有学习。</u>\n\n-**as**：<u>正如。</u>  \n<u>这部分引出 Koziatek 的教育理念。</u>\n\n---\n\nNothing is <font color=\"#ffff00\">necessarily</font> gained by forcing students to <font color=\"#ffff00\">learn geometry</font> at a graffitied desk <font color=\"#ffff00\">stuck with</font> generations of discarded chewing gum.\n翻译: <u>强迫学生在一张涂满涂鸦、粘着几代人丢弃口香糖的课桌前学习几何，并不一定能带来什么收获。</u>\n\n-**necessarily**：<u>必然地、一定。</u>  \n-**learn geometry**：<u>学习几何。</u>  \n-**stuck with…**：<u>粘着……。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey can also learn geometry by assembling a bicycle.\n翻译: <u>他们也可以通过组装一辆自行车来学习几何。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut he’s also found a kind of insidious prejudice.\n翻译: <u>但他也发现了一种隐蔽的偏见。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWorking with your hands is seen as almost a mark of <font color=\"#ffff00\">inferiority</font>.\n翻译: <u>用双手劳动被视为几乎是一种低人一等的标志。</u>\n\n-**inferiority**：<u>低等、劣等。</u>\n\n---\n\nSchools <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the family of</font> vocational education “have that stereotype…that it’s for kids who can’t make it <font color=\"#ffff00\">academically,</font>” he says.\n翻译: <u>他说，职业教育这一类学校“带有那种刻板印象……认为它是给那些在学业上撑不下去的孩子上的”。</u>\n\n-**in the family of vocational education**：<u>属于职业教育这一类的学校。</u>\n-**make it academically**：<u>在学业上成功、适应学术道路。</u> \n\n---\n\nOn one hand, that viewpoint is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">logical product</font> of America’s evolution.\n翻译: <u>一方面，这种观点是美国演变过程的一个合乎逻辑的产物。</u>\n\n-**logical product**：<u>合乎逻辑的产物。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Manufacturing</font> is not the economic engine that it once was.\n翻译: <u>制造业已不再是它曾经那样的经济引擎。</u>\n\n-**manufacturing**：<u>制造业。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">job security</font> that the US economy once offered to high school graduates has largely evaporated.\n翻译: <u>美国经济曾经为高中毕业生提供的就业保障，在很大程度上已经消失。</u>\n\n-**job security**：<u>工作稳定性、职业保障。</u>  \n\n---\n\nMore education is the new principle.\n翻译: <u>接受更多教育是新的原则。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe want more for our kids, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">rightfully so</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们希望孩子们拥有更多，这也理所当然。</u>\n\n-**rightfully so**：<u>理所当然地、合理地。</u>  \n-<u>我们当然希望孩子拥有更多机会，这本身并没有错。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the <font color=\"#ffff00\">headlong</font> push into bachelor’s degrees <font color=\"#ffff00\">for all</font> — and the subtle <font color=\"#ffff00\">devaluing</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">anything less</font> — misses an important point: That’s not the only thing the American economy needs.\n翻译: <u>但是，向人人都拿学士学位的方向仓促推进，并微妙地贬低任何低于学士学位的东西，忽视了一个重要问题：那并不是美国经济唯一需要的东西。</u>\n\n-**headlong**：<u>仓促的、鲁莽向前的、不顾后果的。</u>  \n-**for all**：<u>给所有人。</u>  \n-**devaluing**：<u>贬低、降低价值。</u>  \n-**anything less**：<u>任何低于本科学位的教育或资格，比如职业证书、技术培训、副学士等。</u>  \n\n---\n\nYes, a bachelor’s degree opens more doors.\n翻译: <u>是的，学士学位会打开更多门路。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">even now</font>, 54 percent of the jobs in the country are middle-skill jobs, such as construction and <font color=\"#ffff00\">high-skill manufacturing</font>.\n翻译: <u>但即使在现在，美国54%的工作仍是中等技能工作，例如建筑业和高技能制造业。</u>\n\n-**even now**：<u>即使在今天。</u>  \n-**high-skill manufacturing**：<u>高技能制造业。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut only 44 percent of workers are adequately trained.\n翻译: <u>但只有44%的工人受过充分培训。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn other words, at a time when the working class has <font color=\"#ffff00\">turned the country on its political head</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">frustrated</font> that the opportunity that once defined America is vanishing, one obvious solution is <font color=\"#ffff00\">staring us in the face</font>.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，在工人阶级因曾经定义美国的机会正在消失而感到沮丧、并使这个国家的政治格局发生颠覆之时，一个显而易见的解决办法正摆在我们面前。</u>\n\n-**turn the country on its political head**：<u>让国家政治天翻地覆。</u>  \n<u>这个表达比喻政治秩序被颠倒、被震动。   很多这种比喻的,大概感受一下意思就行.不可能是拿来背的,背是背不完的</u>\n-**frustrated**：<u>沮丧的、受挫的。</u>  \n-**stare someone in the face**：<u>明摆在某人面前、显而易见。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThere is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">gap</font> in working-class jobs, but the workers who need those jobs most <font color=\"#ffff00\">aren’t equipped to do</font> them.\n翻译: <u>工人阶级岗位存在缺口，但最需要这些岗位的工人却没有能力胜任它们。</u>\n\n-**gap**：<u>缺口、差距。</u>  \n-**be equipped to do**：<u>具备做某事的能力、技能或准备。</u>  \n\n---\n\nKoziatek’s Manchester School of Technology High School is trying to fill that gap.\n翻译: <u>Koziatek的Manchester School of Technology High School正试图填补这一缺口。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nKoziatek’s school is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">wake-up call</font>.\n翻译: <u>Koziatek的学校是一个警醒。</u>\n\n-**wake-up call**：<u>警钟、提醒人醒悟的信号。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhen education becomes <font color=\"#ffff00\">one-size-fits-all</font>, it risks <font color=\"#ffff00\">overlooking</font> a nation’s diversity of <font color=\"#ffff00\">gifts</font>.\n翻译: <u>当教育变成一刀切时，它就有可能忽视一个国家才能的多样性。</u>\n\n-**one-size-fits-all**：<u>一刀切的、统一规格适用于所有人的</u>\n-**overlook**：<u>忽视、忽略。</u>\n-**gifts**：<u>天赋、才能。</u>  \n\n---\n\n\n第二篇\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">While</font> fossil fuels — coal, oil, gas — still generate roughly 85 percent of the world’s energy supply, it’s clearer than ever that the future belongs to renewable sources such as wind and solar.\n翻译: <u>尽管化石燃料——煤、石油、天然气——仍提供着全球约85%的能源供应，但比以往任何时候都更清楚的是，未来属于风能和太阳能等可再生能源。</u>\n\n-**while** <u>在这里不是“当……时候”，而是“尽管”。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">move to</font> renewables is <font color=\"#ffff00\">picking up momentum</font> around the world: They now <font color=\"#ffff00\">account for</font> more than half of new power sources<font color=\"#ffff00\"> going on line</font>.\n翻译: <u>向可再生能源的转变正在世界各地加速推进：它们如今占新上线电力来源的一半以上。</u>\n\n\n-**the move to renewables**：<u>向可再生能源的转变。</u>  \n-**pick up momentum**：<u>积聚势头、加速发展。</u>  \n-**account for**：<u>占据、占……比例。</u> \n-**go on line**：<u>上线、投入运行、接入电网。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome growth stems from a <font color=\"#ffff00\">commitment</font> by governments and<font color=\"#ffff00\"> farsighted </font>businesses to <font color=\"#ffff00\">fund</font> cleaner energy sources.\n翻译: <u>部分增长源于各国政府和有远见的企业为更清洁能源提供资金的承诺。</u>\n\n-**commitment**：<u>承诺、投入。</u>  \n-**farsighted**：<u>有远见的。</u>  \n-**fund**：<u>资助、投入资金。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">increasingly</font> the story is about the <font color=\"#ffff00\">plummeting prices</font> of renewables, especially wind and solar.\n翻译: <u>但越来越多地，这个故事关乎可再生能源价格的暴跌，尤其是风能和太阳能。</u>\n\n-**increasingly**：<u>越来越。</u> \n-**plummeting prices**：<u>急剧下降的价格。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe cost of solar panels has dropped by 80 percent and the cost of <font color=\"#ffff00\">wind turbines</font> by <font color=\"#ffff00\">close to one-third</font> in the past eight years.\n翻译: <u>在过去八年中，太阳能电池板的成本下降了80%，风力涡轮机的成本下降了近三分之一。</u>\n\n-**wind turbines**：<u>风力涡轮机。</u>  \n-**close to one-third**：<u>接近三分之一。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn many parts of the world renewable energy is already a <font color=\"#ffff00\">principal</font> energy source.\n翻译: <u>在世界许多地区，可再生能源已经是一种主要能源来源。</u>\n\n-**principal**：<u>主要的、重要的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn Scotland, for example, wind turbines provide enough electricity to power 95 percent of homes.\n翻译: <u>例如在Scotland，风力涡轮机提供的电力足以供95%的家庭使用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the rest of the world takes the lead, notably China and Europe, the United States is also <font color=\"#ffff00\">seeing a remarkable shift</font>.\n翻译: <u>在世界其他地区，尤其是中国和欧洲处于领先之际，美国也正在经历一场显著转变。</u>\n\n-**see a shift**：<u>经历变化、出现转变。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIn March, for the first time, wind and solar power accounted for more than 10 percent of the power generated in the US, reported the US Energy Information Administration.\n翻译: <u>美国能源信息署报告称，3月份，风能和太阳能发电首次占美国发电量的10%以上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPresident Trump has <font color=\"#ffff00\">underlined</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">fossil fuels</font> — especially coal — as the path to economic growth.\n翻译: <u>Trump总统强调，化石燃料——尤其是煤炭——是通往经济增长的道路。</u>\n\n-**underline**：<u>强调、突出。</u>  \n-**fossil fuels**：<u>化石燃料。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a recent speech in Iowa, he <font color=\"#ffff00\">dismissed</font> wind power <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> an unreliable energy source.\n翻译: <u>在最近于Iowa的一次演讲中，他把风能斥为一种不可靠的能源来源。</u>\n\n-**dismiss A as B**：<u>把 A 轻描淡写地否定为 B / 不屑地称 A 为 B。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut that message <font color=\"#ffff00\">did not play well</font> with many in Iowa, where wind turbines dot the fields and provide 36 percent of the state’s electricity generation — and where tech giants like Microsoft are being attracted by the availability of clean energy to power their data centers.\n翻译: <u>但这一信息并未得到Iowa许多人的认同；在那里，风力涡轮机点缀着田野，并提供该州36%的发电量，而Microsoft等科技巨头也正因可用于为其数据中心供电的清洁能源而被吸引到这里。</u>\n\n-**did not play well**：<u>反响不好。</u>  \n-**dot the fields**：<u>点缀田野、散布在田野中。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe question “what happens when the wind doesn’t blow or the sun doesn’t shine?” has provided a quick <font color=\"#ffff00\">put-down</font> for <font color=\"#ffff00\">skeptics</font>.\n翻译: <u>“当风不吹或太阳不照时会发生什么？”这个问题，为怀疑者提供了一句迅速的贬低之词。</u>\n\n-**put-down**：<u>贬低的话、挖苦、反驳。</u>  \n-**skeptics**：<u>怀疑者。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut a boost in the storage capacity of batteries is making their ability to keep power flowing <font color=\"#ffff00\">around the clock</font> more likely.\n翻译: <u>但电池储能能力的提升，正在使它们全天候保持电力流动的能力变得更有可能。</u>\n\n-\n-**around the clock**：<u>全天候、昼夜不停。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The advance</font> is driven <font color=\"#ffff00\">in part</font> by vehicle manufacturers, who are <font color=\"#ffff00\">placing big bets</font> on battery-powered electric vehicles.\n翻译: <u>这一进展部分由汽车制造商推动，他们正在对电池驱动的电动汽车下大赌注。</u>\n\n-**The advance** <u>指电池储能能力的提升</u>\n-**in part**：<u>部分地。</u>  \n-**place big bets on…**：<u>大举押注、投入重注。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAlthough electric cars are still a <font color=\"#ffff00\">rarity</font> on roads now, this massive investment could change the picture rapidly in coming years.\n翻译: <u>尽管电动汽车现在在道路上仍很少见，但这项大规模投资可能在未来几年迅速改变局面。</u>\n\n-**rarity**：<u>罕见之物。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nWhile there’s a long way to go, the trend lines for renewables are <font color=\"#ffff00\">spiking</font>.\n翻译: <u>尽管还有很长的路要走，可再生能源的趋势线正在急剧上升。</u>\n\n-**spike**：<u>急剧上升、猛增。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe pace of change in energy sources appears to be speeding up — perhaps <font color=\"#ffff00\">just in time</font> to have <font color=\"#ffff00\">a meaningful effect</font> in slowing climate change.\n翻译: <u>能源来源变化的步伐似乎正在加快——也许正好来得及对减缓气候变化产生有意义的影响。</u>\n\n-**just in time**：<u>刚好及时。</u>  \n-**have a meaningful effect**：<u>产生有意义的影响。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhat Washington does — or doesn’t do — to promote alternative energy may mean less and less at a time of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">global shift in thought</font>.\n翻译: <u>在全球思想转变之时，Washington为促进替代能源所做或不做的事情，可能会变得越来越不重要。</u>\n\n-**global shift in thought**：<u>全球思想/观念转变。</u>\n-<u>在全球能源观念已经转向的大背景下，美国联邦政府是否推动替代能源，影响可能会越来越小。</u>\n\n\n21. Which of the following is true about clean energy according to Paragraphs 5&6？B\n\nA. Its application has boosted battery storage.x\n\nB. It is commonly used in car manufacturing.\n\nC. Its continuous supply is <font color=\"#ffff00\">becoming</font> a reality.x\n\nD. Its sustainable exploitation will remain difficult.x\n<u>人家也是进行时啊,因为原文进行时不选.....</u>\n\n\n21. It can be inferred from the last paragraph that renewable energy  . A \n\nA. will bring the US closer to other countries\n\nB. will accelerate global environmental change x\n\nC. is not really encouraged by the US governmentx\n\nD. is not competitive enough with regard to its costx\n\n\n\n第三篇 \n\nThe power and ambition of the giants of the digital economy is <font color=\"#ffff00\">astonishing</font>.\n翻译: <u>数字经济巨头的力量和雄心令人震惊。</u>\n\n-**astonishing**：<u>令人惊讶的、惊人的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAmazon has just announced the <font color=\"#ffff00\">purchase</font> of the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> upmarket</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">grocery chain</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">Whole Foods</font> for $13.5bn, but two years ago Facebook paid even more than that to <font color=\"#ffff00\">acquire</font> the WhatsApp messaging service, which doesn’t have any physical product at all.\n翻译: <u>Amazon刚刚宣布以135亿美元收购高端食品杂货连锁店Whole Foods，但两年前，Facebook为收购WhatsApp即时通讯服务支付了比这还多的钱，而后者根本没有任何实体产品。</u>\n\n-**purchase**：<u>购买、收购。</u>  \n-**upmarket**：<u>高端的、面向较富裕消费者的。</u>  \n-**grocery chain**：<u>食品杂货连锁店。</u>  \n-**Whole Foods**：<u>全食超市。</u>\n-**acquire**：<u>收购。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhat WhatsApp offered Facebook was an<font color=\"#ffff00\"> intricate</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">finely detailed</font> web of its users’ friendships and social lives.\n翻译: <u>WhatsApp提供给Facebook的，是一张错综复杂且极其细致的用户友谊和社交生活网络。</u>\n\n-**intricate**：<u>复杂精细的。</u>  \n-**finely detailed**：<u>细节非常丰富的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nFacebook promised the European Commission <font color=\"#ffff00\">then</font> that it would not link phone numbers to <font color=\"#ffff00\">Facebook identities</font>, but it broke the promise almost as soon as the deal <font color=\"#ffff00\">went through</font>.\n翻译: <u>Facebook当时向European Commission承诺，它不会把电话号码与Facebook身份关联起来，但交易一完成，它几乎立刻就违背了这一承诺。</u>\n\n-**then**：<u>当时，指收购 WhatsApp 的时候。</u>\n-**Facebook identities**：Facebook <u>身份/账号身份。</u>  \n-**the deal went through**：<u>交易完成、交易获批并生效。</u>  \n\n---\n\nEven without knowing what was in the messages,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> the knowledge of </font>who sent them and to whom was <font color=\"#ffff00\">enormously</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">revealing</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">still could be</font>.\n翻译: <u>即便不知道信息中的内容，知道是谁发送了信息以及发给了谁，也具有极大的揭示性，而且现在仍可能如此。</u>\n\n-**the knowledge of…**：<u>关于……的信息。</u>  \n-**enormously**：<u>极其、非常。</u>  \n-**revealing**：<u>揭示性的、透露大量信息的。</u>  \n-still could be **<u>至今仍可能非常敏感**</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat political journalist, what <font color=\"#ffff00\">party whip</font>, would not want to know the makeup of the WhatsApp groups in which Theresa May’s enemies are currently plotting?\n翻译: <u>哪一位政治记者，哪一位党鞭，不想知道Theresa May的敌人们目前正在其中密谋的WhatsApp群组的构成呢？</u>\n\n-**what party whip**：<u>哪个党鞭/政党督导员。</u>  \nwhat <u>引导的从句</u>\n-<u>哪个政治记者或党内负责人不想知道 Theresa May 的反对者们到底在哪些 WhatsApp 群里密谋、群里都有谁呢？</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It may be that </font>the value of Whole Foods to Amazon is not so much the 460 shops it owns, but the records of which customers have purchased what.\n翻译: <u>Whole Foods 对 Amazon 的价值可能并不在于它拥有的那 460 家门店，而在于关于哪些顾客购买了什么商品的记录。</u>\n\n-<u>也许情况是…… it may be that</u> \n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Competition law</font> appears to be the only way to address these imbalances of power.\n翻译: <u>竞争法似乎是解决这些权力失衡的唯一途径。</u>\n\n-**competition law**：<u>竞争法、反垄断法。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut it is <font color=\"#ffff00\">clumsy</font>.\n翻译: <u>但它很笨拙。</u>\n\n-**clumsy**：<u>笨拙的、不灵活的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For one thing</font>, it is very slow compared to the pace of change within the digital economy.\n翻译: <u>一方面，与数字经济内部变化的速度相比，它非常缓慢。</u>\n\n-**for one thing**：<u>首先、一方面。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBy the time a problem has been addressed and remedied it may have vanished in the marketplace, to be replaced by new <font color=\"#ffff00\">abuses of power.</font>\n翻译: <u>等到一个问题得到处理和补救时，它可能已经在市场中消失了，并被新的权力滥用所取代。</u>\n\n-**new abuses of power**：<u>新的权力滥用。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut there is a deeper conceptual problem, too.\n翻译: <u>但还有一个更深层的概念问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCompetition law as <font color=\"#ffff00\">presently interpreted</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">deals with</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">financial disadvantage</font> to consumers and this is not obvious when the users of these services don’t pay for them.\n翻译: <u>按目前的解释，竞争法处理的是消费者在经济上的不利处境；而当这些服务的用户并不为服务付费时，这一点并不明显。</u>\n\n-**as presently interpreted**：<u>按照目前的解释方式。</u>  \n-**deal with**：<u>处理。</u>  \n-**financial disadvantage**：<u>金钱上的不利、经济损害。</u>  \n<u>现行竞争法主要关注消费者是否在金钱上受损；但在 Facebook、Google 这类免费服务中，用户并不直接付钱，因此这种损害很难按传统方式看出来。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe users of their services are not their customers.\n翻译: <u>这些服务的用户并不是它们的客户。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat <font color=\"#ffff00\">would be</font> the people who buy advertising from them — and Facebook and Google, the two virtual giants, dominate digital advertising <font color=\"#ffff00\">to the disadvantage </font>of all other media and entertainment companies.\n翻译: <u>它们的客户应当是那些从它们那里购买广告的人，而 Facebook 和 Google 这两大虚拟巨头主导着数字广告，使所有其他媒体和娱乐公司处于不利地位。</u>\n\n-**would be** <u>在这里带有解释/判断语气：真正客户是……**the people** 后面定语从句说明是哪类人。</u>\n-**to the disadvantage of…**：<u>对……不利、损害……。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe product they’re selling is data, and we, the users, convert our lives to data <font color=\"#ffff00\">for the benefit of the digital giants.</font>\n翻译: <u>它们出售的产品是数据，而我们这些用户，则为了数字巨头的利益，把自己的生活转化为数据。</u>\n\n-for the benefit of…**：<u>为了……的利益。</u>  \n<u>这些平台真正卖的是数据；而我们用户则不断把自己的生活变成数据，供数字巨头获利。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Just as</font> some ants <font color=\"#ffff00\">farm</font> the bugs called aphids for the honeydew they produce when they <font color=\"#ffff00\">feed</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">so</font> Google farms us for the data that our digital lives yield.\n翻译: <u>正如有些蚂蚁饲养名为蚜虫的昆虫，以获取它们进食时产生的蜜露一样，Google 也饲养着我们，以获取我们的数字生活所产出的数据。</u>\n\n-**Just as…so…**：<u>正如……一样，……也……。</u>\n-**farm** <u>在这里作动词，意思是“饲养、养殖”。</u>\n-**they** <u>指 aphids。**feed**：进食。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnts keep <font color=\"#ffff00\">predatory insects</font> away from where their aphids feed; Gmail keeps the <font color=\"#ffff00\">spammers</font> out of our inboxes.\n翻译: <u>蚂蚁会把捕食性昆虫赶离蚜虫取食的地方；Gmail 则把垃圾邮件发送者挡在我们的收件箱之外。</u>\n\n-**predatory insects**：<u>捕食性昆虫。</u>  \n-**spammers**：<u>垃圾邮件发送者。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt doesn’t feel like a <font color=\"#ffff00\">human</font> or democratic relationship, even if <font color=\"#ffff00\">both sides</font> benefit.\n翻译: <u>即便双方都受益，这也不像是一种人性化或民主的关系。</u>\n\n-**human relationship**：<u>人性化关系。</u>  \n-**both sides**：<u>双方，即平台和用户。</u>  \n\n---\n\n\n第四篇\n\n\nThe U.S. <font color=\"#ffff00\">Postal Service</font> (USPS) continues to bleed red ink.\n翻译: <u>美国邮政署（USPS）继续出现大量赤字。</u>\n\n-Postal Service (USPS)**：<u>美国邮政署。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt reported a net loss of $5.6 billion for fiscal 2016, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">10th straight year</font> its expenses have exceeded revenue.\n翻译: <u>它报告称，2016 财年净亏损 56 亿美元，这是其支出连续第 10 年超过收入。</u>\n\n-**the 10th straight year**：<u>连续第十年。</u>  \n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, it has more than $120 billion in <font color=\"#ffff00\">unfunded liabilities</font>, mostly for employee health and retirement costs.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，它还有超过 1200 亿美元的无资金准备负债，其中大部分用于员工医疗和退休成本。</u>\n\n-**unfunded liabilities**：<u>没有相应资金覆盖的债务/负债。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThere are many reasons this<font color=\"#ffff00\"> formerly stable</font> federal institution finds itself at the brink of bankruptcy.\n翻译: <u>这个曾经稳定的联邦机构如今发现自己濒临破产，原因有很多。</u>\n\n-**formerly stable**：<u>过去稳定的。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Fundamentally,</font> the USPS is in a historic squeeze between technological change that has permanently decreased demand for its <font color=\"#ffff00\">bread-and-butter product</font>, first-class mail, and a <font color=\"#ffff00\">regulatory structure</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">denies</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">management</font> the flexibility to <font color=\"#ffff00\">adjust its operations</font> to the new reality.\n翻译: <u>从根本上说，USPS 正处于一种历史性的挤压之中：一边是技术变革永久性地减少了对其核心产品一等邮件的需求，另一边是监管结构剥夺了管理层调整运营以适应新现实的灵活性。</u>\n\n-**Fundamentally** <u>引出最核心、最根本的原因。</u>\n-**bread-and-butter product**：<u>赖以生存的核心产品 / 主要收入来源。</u>  \n-**regulatory structure**：<u>监管结构、监管制度。</u>  \n-**deny someone something**：<u>不给某人某物。</u>  \n-**management**：<u>管理层。</u> \n-**adjust its operations**：<u>调整运营方式。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">interest groups</font> ranging from postal unions to <font color=\"#ffff00\">greeting-card makers </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">exert </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">self-interested</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">pressure</font> on the USPS’s<font color=\"#ffff00\"> ultimate overseer</font> — Congress — <font color=\"#ffff00\">insisting</font> that whatever else happens to the Postal Service, <font color=\"#ffff00\">aspects of the status quo</font> they depend on get protected.\n翻译: <u>而从邮政工会到贺卡制造商等各类利益集团，都向 USPS 的最终监管者国会施加出于自身利益的压力，坚称无论邮政署发生什么，它们所依赖的现状中的某些方面都必须得到保护。</u>\n\n-**interest groups**：<u>利益集团。</u>\n-**greeting-card makers**：<u>贺卡制造商。</u>  \n-**self-interested**：<u>出于自身利益的。</u>  \n-**exert pressure on…**：<u>对……施加压力。</u>  \n-**ultimate overseer**：<u>最终监管者、最高监督者。</u>  \n-insisting <u>这里是动名词 重新开的一个从句 所以翻译的时候 可以在前面多加一个并</u>\n<u>并坚持认为</u>\n-**aspects of the status quo**：<u>现状中的某些方面。</u>  \n-<u>与此同时，从邮政工会到贺卡制造商，各种利益集团都向国会施压，要求无论 USPS 怎么改革，它们赖以获益的现有安排都不能被动。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThis is why <font color=\"#ffff00\">repeated attempts</font> at<font color=\"#ffff00\"> reform legislation</font> have failed in recent years, leaving the Postal Service unable to pay its bills<font color=\"#ffff00\"> except by</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">deferring</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">vital modernization.</font>\n翻译: <u>这就是近年来改革立法的反复尝试为何失败，使邮政署除了推迟关键现代化建设外无力支付账单。</u>\n\n-**repeated attempts**：<u>反复尝试。</u>  \n-**reform legislation**：<u>改革立法。</u>  \n-**except by…**：<u>除了通过……之外没有办法。</u>  \n-**defer**：<u>推迟。</u>  \n-**vital modernization**：<u>关键现代化升级，比如车辆、设备、系统更新。</u>  \n\n---\n\nNow comes <font color=\"#ffff00\">word</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">everyone involved</font> — Democrats, Republicans, the Postal Service, the unions and the system’s heaviest users — has finally agreed on a plan to fix the system.\n翻译: <u>如今传来消息，所有相关方，包括民主党人、共和党人、邮政署、工会以及该系统最大的用户，终于就一项修复该系统的计划达成一致。</u>\n\n-**word** <u>在这里不是“单词”，而是“消息、传闻、报道”。</u>  \n-**everyone involved**：<u>所有相关方。</u>  \n\n---\n\nLegislation <font color=\"#ffff00\">is moving through</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">House</font> that would save USPS <font color=\"#ffff00\">an estimated $28.6 billion</font> over five years, which could help pay for new vehicles, <font color=\"#ffff00\">among other</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">survival measures</font>.\n翻译: <u>一项立法正在众议院推进，该立法预计将在五年内为 USPS 节省 286 亿美元，这些资金可用于购买新车辆以及其他生存措施。</u>\n\n-**is moving through**：<u>正在通过、正在推进。</u> \n-**the House**：<u>美国众议院。</u> \n-**an estimated $28.6 billion**：<u>估计 286 亿美元。</u>  \n-**among other…**：<u>除了……之外还有其他。</u>  \n-**survival measures**：<u>维持生存的措施。</u>  \n-\n---\n\nMost of the money would come from a <font color=\"#ffff00\">penny-per-letter</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">permanent rate increase</font> and from <font color=\"#ffff00\">shifting</font> postal retirees<font color=\"#ffff00\"> into</font> Medicare.\n翻译: <u>大部分资金将来自每封信永久涨价 1 美分，以及将邮政退休人员转入 Medicare。</u>\n\n-**penny-per-letter**：<u>每封信一美分。</u>  \n-**permanent rate increase**：<u>永久性费率上涨。</u>  \n-**shift A into B**：<u>把 A 转入 B。</u> \n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">latter</font> step would largely offset the financial burden of annually <font color=\"#ffff00\">pre-funding </font>retiree health care, <font color=\"#ffff00\">thus</font> addressing a long-standing complaint by the USPS and its unions.\n翻译: <u>后一步将在很大程度上抵消每年为退休人员医疗保健预先筹资所带来的财务负担，从而回应 USPS 及其工会长期以来的一项抱怨。</u>\n\n-**latter**：<u>后者。</u>\n-**pre-funding**：<u>预先筹资、提前拨备资金。</u>  \n-**thus**：<u>因此、从而。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIf it <font color=\"#ffff00\">clears the House</font>, this measure would <font color=\"#ffff00\">still have to</font> get through the Senate — where someone is bound to point out that it<font color=\"#ffff00\"> amounts to</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">bare, bare minimum</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">necessary to </font>keep the Postal Service afloat, not <font color=\"#ffff00\">comprehensive reform</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果该措施在众议院获得通过，它仍必须通过参议院；在那里一定会有人指出，它只相当于维持邮政署运转所必需的最低限度，而不是全面改革。</u>\n\n-**clear the House**：<u>通过众议院。</u>  \n-**still have to**：<u>仍然必须。</u>\n-**amount to**：<u>等同于、实际上是。</u>  \n-**bare, bare minimum**：<u>最低限度中的最低限度，重复 bare 强调非常少。</u>  \n-**not comprehensive reform**：<u>不是全面改革。</u>  \n-**necessary to do**：<u>为了做某事所必需的。</u>  \n-<u>即便法案通过众议院，还得过参议院；而参议院肯定会有人指出，这不过是让 USPS 勉强活下去的最低限度措施，并不是真正全面改革。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere’s no change to <font color=\"#ffff00\">collective bargaining</font> at the USPS, a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> major omission </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">considering</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">personnel</font> accounts for 80 percent of the agency’s costs.\n翻译: <u>该方案没有改变 USPS 的集体谈判制度；考虑到人员成本占该机构成本的 80%，这是一个重大遗漏。</u>\n\n-**collective bargaining**：<u>集体谈判，指工会与雇主就工资、福利、工作条件等谈判。</u>  \n-**major omission**：<u>重大遗漏。</u>  \n-**considering that…**：<u>考虑到……。</u>  \n-**personnel**：<u>人员、人事，这里指员工工资福利等人力成本。</u>  \n-<u>法案没有改革 USPS 的集体谈判制度，而员工成本占总成本 80%，所以这是一个很大的缺失。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlso missing is any discussion of eliminating Saturday letter delivery.\n翻译: <u>其中也没有任何关于取消周六信件投递的讨论。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat <font color=\"#ffff00\">common-sense</font> change <font color=\"#ffff00\">enjoys</font> wide public support and would save the USPS $2 billion per year.\n翻译: <u>这一符合常识的改变获得了广泛的公众支持，并且每年可为 USPS 节省 20 亿美元。</u>\n\n-**common-sense**：<u>合乎常识的、明显合理的。</u>  \n-**enjoy support**：<u>获得支持。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut postal <font color=\"#ffff00\">special-interest groups</font> seem to have killed it, at least in the House.\n翻译: <u>但邮政特殊利益集团似乎已经扼杀了它，至少在众议院是如此。</u>\n\n-**special-interest groups**：<u>特殊利益集团。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nThe<font color=\"#ffff00\"> emerging</font> consensus around the bill is a sign that legislators are getting frightened about a <font color=\"#ffff00\">politically embarrassing</font> short-term collapse at the USPS.\n翻译: <u>围绕该法案正在形成的共识表明，立法者开始担心 USPS 出现政治上令人难堪的短期崩溃。</u>\n\n-**emerging**：<u>正在出现的、逐渐形成的。</u>  \n-**politically embarrassing**：<u>政治上令人难堪的。   这个整体作为一个副词 修饰 collapse 后面的 short-term 作为形容词 同样修饰 cllapse 所以看起来很长</u>\n\n<u>各方围绕这项法案形成共识，并不说明他们真正想改革，而是说明议员们害怕 USPS 突然崩溃，造成政治难堪。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is not, however, a sign that they’re <font color=\"#ffff00\">getting serious about</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">transforming</font> the postal system for the 21st century.\n翻译: <u>然而，这并不表明他们开始认真对待为 21 世纪改造邮政系统。</u>\n\n-**get serious about…**：<u>认真对待……。</u>  \n-**transforming**：<u>转型、改造。</u>  \n\n-<u>然而，这并不是一个迹象，表明他们正在认真对待把邮政系统转型为适应 21 世纪的体系。</u>  \n\n---\n\n21. Which of the following would be the best title for the text? C\n\n[A] The USPS Starts to Miss Its Good Old Days.X\n\n[B] The Postal Service: Keep Away from My Cheese.X\n\n[C] The USPS: Chronic Illness Requires a Quick Cure.  \n\n[D] The Postal Service Needs More Than a <font color=\"#ffff00\">Band-Aid.</font>\n\n<u>创口贴式的补救</u>\n\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2019","year":"2019","title":"2019 年英语一","fileName":"2019 英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2019 英语 1.md","content":"<font color=\"#ffff00\">Financial regulators</font> in Britain have imposed a rather unusual rule on the bosses of big banks.\n翻译: <u>英国的金融监管机构对大型银行的老板们实施了一项颇不寻常的规定。</u>\n\n\n-**financial regulators**：<u>金融监管机构 / 金融监管者。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\nStarting next year, any <font color=\"#ffff00\">guaranteed bonus</font> of top executives could be delayed 10 years if their banks are under investigation for wrongdoing.\n翻译: <u>从明年开始，如果银行因不当行为受到调查，高管的任何保底奖金都可能被推迟 10 年发放。</u>\n\n-**guaranteed bonus**：<u>保证奖金，即不完全取决于业绩、承诺会给的奖金。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nThe main purpose of this <font color=\"#ffff00\">“clawback” </font>rule is to <font color=\"#ffff00\">hold bankers accountable</font> for harmful risk-taking and to restore public trust in financial institutions.\n翻译: <u>这项“追回”规则的主要目的是让银行家为有害的冒险行为负责，并恢复公众对金融机构的信任。</u>\n\n-**clawback rule**：<u>追回规则，指公司或监管机构可以收回、扣留或延迟高管奖金。</u>\n-**hold someone accountable**：<u>让某人负责、追究某人责任。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet officials also hope for a much larger benefit: more long-term decisionmaking, not only by banks but by all corporations, to build a stronger economy for future generations.\n翻译: <u>然而，官员们也希望获得更大的收益：促使不仅银行而且所有公司都做出更多长期决策，为后代建设更强大的经济。</u>\n\n()\n\n\n\n“Short-termism” or the desire for quick profits, has worsened in <font color=\"#ffff00\">publicly traded companies</font>, says the Bank of England’s top economist, Andrew Haldane.\n翻译: <u>英格兰银行首席经济学家 Andrew Haldane 表示，“短期主义”，即追求快速利润的欲望，在上市公司中已经恶化。</u>\n\n-**publicly traded companies**：<u>公开交易的公司，即上市公司。</u>\n\n---\n\nHe quotes a <font color=\"#ffff00\">giant</font> of classical economics, Alfred Marshall, in <font color=\"#ffff00\">describing</font> this financial <font color=\"#ffff00\">impatience</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> acting like “children who pick the plums out of their pudding to eat them at once” rather than putting them aside to be eaten last.\n翻译: <u>在描述这种金融上的急躁时，他引用了古典经济学巨擘 Alfred Marshall 的话，称其行为就像“把布丁里的李子挑出来立刻吃掉的孩子”，而不是把它们留到最后再吃。</u>\n\n\n-**a giant of classical economics**：<u>古典经济学巨匠。</u>  \n-**describing A as B**：<u>把 A 描述为 B。</u>  \n-**financial impatience**：<u>金融上的急躁，指投资者或公司急着获取短期收益。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe average time for holding a stock in both the United States and Britain, he notes, has dropped from seven years to seven months in recent decades.\n翻译: <u>他指出，近几十年来，在美国和英国，持有一只股票的平均时间都已从 7 年降至 7 个月。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTransient investors, who demand high quarterly profits from companies, can hinder a firm’s efforts to invest in long-term research or to build up customer loyalty.\n翻译: <u>要求公司获得高额季度利润的短期投资者，可能会阻碍公司投资长期研究或建立客户忠诚度的努力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis has been <font color=\"#ffff00\">dubbed</font> “quarterly capitalism.”\n翻译: <u>这被称为“季度资本主义”。</u>\n\n-**dub**：<u>称为、给……起名。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn addition, new digital technologies have allowed more rapid trading of <font color=\"#ffff00\">equities</font>, quicker use of information, and thus shorter attention spans in financial markets.\n翻译: <u>此外，新的数字技术使股票交易更迅速、信息使用更快捷，因此金融市场的注意力持续时间也更短。</u>\n\n-**equities**：<u>股票、股权证券。</u>\n\n---\n\n“There seems to be a predominance of short-term thinking <font color=\"#ffff00\">at the expense of </font>long-term investing,” said Commissioner Daniel Gallagher of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">US Securities and Exchange Commission</font> in a speech this week.\n翻译: <u>美国证券交易委员会委员 Daniel Gallagher 在本周的一次演讲中说：“似乎存在一种短期思维占主导、以牺牲长期投资为代价的情况。”</u>\n\n-**at the expense of…**：<u>以……为代价。</u>  \n-**US Securities and Exchange Commission**：<u>美国证券交易委员会，简称 SEC。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the US, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 has pushed most public companies to defer <font color=\"#ffff00\">performance bonuses</font> for <font color=\"#ffff00\">senior executives</font> by about a year, slightly helping reduce “short-termism.”\n翻译: <u>在美国，2002 年的 Sarbanes-Oxley Act 促使大多数上市公司将高级管理人员的绩效奖金推迟大约一年发放，这在一定程度上有助于减少“短期主义”。</u>\n\n-**performance bonuses**：<u>绩效奖金。</u>  \n-**senior executives**：<u>高级管理人员。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn its latest survey of<font color=\"#ffff00\"> CEO pay</font>, The Wall Street <font color=\"#ffff00\">Journal </font>finds that “a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> substantial part</font>” of executive pay is now tied to performance.\n翻译: <u>《华尔街日报》在其最新的 CEO 薪酬调查中发现，如今高管薪酬中“相当大一部分”与业绩挂钩。</u>\n\n-**CEO pay**：CEO <u>薪酬。</u>\n-journal. <u>日报 华尔街日报</u>\n-**a substantial part**：<u>相当大的一部分。</u>\n\n---\n\nMuch more could be done to encourage “long-termism,” such as changes in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">tax code</font> and quicker disclosure of <font color=\"#ffff00\">stock acquisitions</font>.\n翻译: <u>还可以采取更多措施来鼓励“长期主义”，例如修改税法以及更快披露股票收购情况。</u>\n\n-**tax code**：<u>税法、税收制度。</u>  \n-**stock acquisitions**：<u>股票收购、购入股票。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn France, shareholders who hold onto a company investment for at least two years can sometimes earn more voting rights in a company.\n翻译: <u>在法国，持有某家公司投资至少两年的股东，有时可以在公司中获得更多投票权。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Within companies</font>, the right <font color=\"#ffff00\">compensation design</font> can provide incentives for executives to think beyond their own time at the company and on behalf of all stakeholders.\n翻译: <u>在公司内部，合理的薪酬设计可以激励高管超越自己在公司任职期间来思考，并代表所有利益相关者行事。</u>\n\n-Within companies <u>在公司的内部</u> \n-**compensation design**：<u>薪酬设计，即工资、奖金、股权、延期支付等安排。</u>\n\n---\n\nBritain’s new rule is a reminder to bankers that society <font color=\"#ffff00\">has an interest in</font> their performance, not just for the short term but for the long term.\n翻译: <u>英国的新规则提醒银行家，社会关心他们的表现，不仅是短期表现，也包括长期表现。</u>\n\n-**has an interest in…**：<u>对……有利害关系 / 关心……。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇阅读\n\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Grade inflation</font> — the gradual increase in average GPAs, or grade-point averages, over the past few decades — is often considered a product of a consumer era in higher education, in which students are treated like customers to be pleased.\n翻译: <u>成绩膨胀，即过去几十年平均 GPA 或平均绩点的逐步上升，常被认为是高等教育消费时代的产物；在这个时代，学生被当作需要取悦的顾客。</u>\n\n-Grade inflation <u>成绩通胀</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBut another, <font color=\"#ffff00\">related force</font> — a policy often buried deep in course catalogs called “grade forgiveness” — is helping raise GPAs.\n翻译: <u>但另一股相关力量，即一种常被深埋在课程目录中的政策，名为“成绩宽恕”，也在帮助提高 GPA。</u>\n\n-**related**：<u>相关的。</u>  \n-**force**：<u>力量、因素。</u>\n\n---\n\nGrade forgiveness allows students to retake a course in which they received a low grade, and the most recent grade or the highest grade is the only one that counts in calculating a student’s overall GPA.\n翻译: <u>成绩宽恕允许学生重修一门曾取得低分的课程，而在计算学生总体 GPA 时，只计入最近一次成绩或最高成绩。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe use of this little-known practice has accelerated in recent years, as colleges continue to do their utmost to keep students in school and paying tuition and improve their graduation rates.\n翻译: <u>近年来，随着大学继续竭尽全力让学生留在学校并缴纳学费，同时提高毕业率，这种鲜为人知的做法使用得越来越快。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen this practice first started decades ago, it was usually limited to freshmen, to give them a second chance to take a class in their first year if they struggled in their transition to college-level courses.\n翻译: <u>几十年前这种做法刚开始时，通常仅限于大一学生，目的是在他们适应大学水平课程的过程中遇到困难时，给他们在第一年重修课程的第二次机会。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut now most colleges, <font color=\"#ffff00\">save for</font> many <font color=\"#ffff00\">selective campuses</font>, allow all undergraduates, and even graduate students, to get their low grades forgiven.\n翻译: <u>但现在，除许多选拔性很强的校园外，大多数大学都允许所有本科生，甚至研究生，让自己的低分得到宽恕。</u>\n\n-**save for**：<u>除了，等于 **except for**。</u>  \n-**selective campuses**：<u>录取选择性强的学校/校区，通常指更精英、更难进的学校。</u>\n\n---\n\nCollege officials tend to emphasize that the goal of grade forgiveness is less about the grade itself and more about encouraging students to retake courses <font color=\"#ffff00\">critical to </font>their degree program and graduation without <font color=\"#ffff00\">incurring</font> a big penalty.\n翻译: <u>大学官员往往强调，成绩宽恕的目标与其说是成绩本身，不如说是鼓励学生重修对其学位项目和毕业至关重要的课程，而不必承受重大惩罚。</u>\n\n-**critical to…**：<u>对……至关重要。</u>  \n-**incur**：<u>招致、遭受，常用于费用、损失、惩罚等。</u>  \n-：<u>学校管理者通常会说，成绩宽恕并不是为了美化分数，而是为了鼓励学生重修那些对专业和毕业很重要的课程，同时不让一次低分对他们造成过大惩罚。</u>\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">Ultimately,</font>” said Jack Miner, Ohio State University’s registrar, “we see students achieve more success because they retake a course and do better in subsequent courses or master the content that allows them to graduate on time.”\n翻译: <u>Ohio State University 的注册主任 Jack Miner 说：“最终，我们看到学生取得了更多成功，因为他们重修了一门课程，并在后续课程中表现更好，或者掌握了使他们能够按时毕业的内容。”</u>\n\n-**Ultimately**：<u>最终、归根结底。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">That said</font>, there is a way in which grade forgiveness satisfies colleges’ own needs as well.\n翻译: <u>话虽如此，成绩宽恕也在某种程度上满足了大学自身的需求。</u>\n\n-**That said** = **Having said that**。  \n意思是：<u>承认上一段说法有道理，但接下来要补充另一面。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor <font color=\"#ffff00\">public institutions</font>, state funds are sometimes tied partly to their success on <font color=\"#ffff00\">metrics </font>such as graduation rates and student retention — so better grades can, by boosting figures like those, mean more money.\n翻译: <u>对公立机构而言，州政府资金有时部分与它们在毕业率和学生留校率等指标上的成功挂钩；因此，更好的成绩通过提高这类数据，可能意味着更多资金。</u>\n\n-**public institutions**：<u>公立高校。</u>  \n-**metrics**：<u>指标。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd anything that raises GPAs <font color=\"#ffff00\">will likely</font> make students — who,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> at the end of the day</font>, are paying the bill — feel they’ve gotten a better value for their tuition dollars, which is another big concern for colleges.\n翻译: <u>而任何提高 GPA 的做法，都可能让学生，也就是归根结底在支付账单的人，觉得他们的学费花得更值；这也是大学的另一大关切。</u>\n\n-**will likely**：<u>很可能会。</u>  \n-**at the end of the day**：<u>归根结底、说到底。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Indeed</font>, grade forgiveness is just another way that universities are responding to consumers’ expectations for higher education.\n翻译: <u>事实上，成绩宽恕只是大学回应消费者对高等教育期望的又一种方式。</u>\n\n-**Indeed** <u>用来强调总结前文：成绩宽恕体现了大学迎合消费者期待。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Since</font> students and parents expect a college degree to lead to a job, it is<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in the best interest of</font> a school to turn out graduates who are as qualified as possible — or at least appear to be.\n翻译: <u>既然学生和家长期望大学学位能带来工作，那么培养出尽可能合格，或至少看起来合格的毕业生，就符合学校的最大利益。</u>\n\n-**since** <u>在这里是“既然、由于”，不是“自从”</u>\n-**in the best interest of…**：<u>符合……的最大利益。</u>\n\n---\n\nOn this, students’ and colleges’ incentives seem to be aligned.\n翻译: <u>在这一点上，学生和大学的激励似乎是一致的。</u>\n\n()\n\n\n第三篇阅读\n\n\nThis year <font color=\"#ffff00\">marks</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">exactly</font> two centuries since the publication of “Frankenstein; or, The <font color=\"#ffff00\">Modern Prometheus</font>,” by Mary Shelley.\n翻译: <u>今年正值 Mary Shelley 的《Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus》出版整整两个世纪。</u>\n\n-**marks**：<u>标志着。</u>  \n-exactly <u>正好</u>\n-Modern Prometheus <u>依旧书名不用看</u>\n\n---\n\nEven before the invention of the electric light bulb, the author produced a remarkable work of <font color=\"#ffff00\">speculative fiction</font> that would <font color=\"#ffff00\">foreshadow</font> many ethical questions to be raised by technologies <font color=\"#ffff00\">yet to come</font>.\n翻译: <u>甚至在电灯泡发明之前，这位作者就创作出了一部非凡的推想小说作品，它预示了许多将由未来技术提出的伦理问题。</u>\n\n-**speculative fiction**：<u>思辨小说 / 科幻式想象文学，</u>\n-**would foreshadow**：<u>将会预示、预先暗示。</u>  \n-**yet to come**：<u>还未到来的。</u>\n<u>在 **yet to do / yet to come / yet to be seen** 这种结构里，**yet** 表示“仍然尚未，但预期以后会”</u>\n\n---\n\nToday the rapid growth of artificial intelligence, or AI, raises fundamental questions: “What is intelligence, <font color=\"#ffff00\">identity</font>, or <font color=\"#ffff00\">consciousness</font>?”\n翻译: <u>如今，人工智能，即 AI 的快速发展，提出了一些根本问题：“什么是智能、身份或意识？”</u>\n\n-**identity**：<u>身份、自我认同。</u>  \n-**consciousness**：<u>意识。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat makes humans humans?\n翻译: <u>是什么使人类成为人类？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">What is being called </font>artificial general intelligence, machines that would imitate the way humans think, continues to <font color=\"#ffff00\">evade scientists</font>.\n翻译: <u>被称为通用人工智能的东西，即会模仿人类思维方式的机器，仍然让科学家难以实现。</u>\n\n-**What is being called…**：<u>正在被称为……的东西 / 所谓……。</u>  \n-**evade**：<u>逃避、避开；这里引申为“仍然难以掌握 / 难以实现”。   也是一种比喻的说法</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Yet</font> humans remain fascinated by the idea of robots that would look, move, and respond like humans, similar to those recently depicted on popular sci-fi TV series such as “Westworld” and “Humans.”\n翻译: <u>然而，人类仍然迷恋于这样一种机器人：它们会像人类一样看起来、移动和回应，类似于最近在“Westworld”和“Humans”等热门科幻电视剧中描绘的那些机器人。</u>\n\n- yet <u>这就离就是然而</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Just</font> how people think is still far too complex to be understood, let alone reproduced, says David Eagleman, a Stanford University neuroscientist.\n翻译: <u>Stanford University 神经科学家 David Eagleman 表示，人们究竟如何思考仍然过于复杂，尚无法被理解，更不用说被复制了。</u>\n\n-just <u>起强调作用 **just how…**：究竟如何……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n“We are just in a situation where there are no good theories explaining what consciousness actually is and how you could ever build a machine to <font color=\"#ffff00\">get there</font>.”\n翻译: <u>“我们现在所处的情况是，还没有好的理论能够解释意识究竟是什么，以及你如何可能制造出一台机器来达到那种状态。”</u>\n\n-**get there**：<u>达到那种状态。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut that doesn’t mean crucial ethical issues involving AI aren’t at hand.\n翻译: <u>但这并不意味着涉及 AI 的关键伦理问题尚未迫在眉睫。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe coming use of autonomous vehicles, for example, <font color=\"#ffff00\">poses </font>thorny ethical questions.\n翻译: <u>例如，即将到来的自动驾驶车辆使用，就提出了棘手的伦理问题。</u>\n\n-**pose questions**：<u>提出问题、造成问题。</u>\n\n---\n\nHuman drivers sometimes must make <font color=\"#ffff00\">split-second</font> decisions.\n翻译: <u>人类驾驶员有时必须在瞬间作出决定。</u>\n\n-**split-second**：<u>瞬间的、极短时间内的。 其实也算是一种比喻类型,不可能背完所有比喻 只能去感受</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir reactions may be a complex combination of <font color=\"#ffff00\">instant reflexes</font>, input from past driving experiences, and what their eyes and ears tell them in that moment.\n翻译: <u>他们的反应可能是即时反射、过去驾驶经验的输入，以及当时眼睛和耳朵所传递信息的复杂组合。</u>\n\n-**instant reflexes**：<u>瞬间反射、本能反应。</u>\n\n---\n\nAI “vision” today is <font color=\"#ffff00\">not nearly as</font> sophisticated <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> that of humans.\n翻译: <u>如今 AI 的“视觉”远没有人类的视觉那么复杂精细。</u>\n\n-**not nearly as…as…**：<u>远远没有……那么……。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd to anticipate every imaginable driving situation is a difficult programming problem.\n翻译: <u>而预判每一种可以想象的驾驶情境，是一个困难的编程问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhenever decisions are based on masses of data, “you quickly get into a lot of ethical questions,” notes Tan Kiat How, chief executive of a Singapore-based <font color=\"#ffff00\">agency</font> that is helping the government develop a <font color=\"#ffff00\">voluntary code</font> for the ethical use of AI.\n翻译: <u>新加坡一个帮助政府制定 AI 伦理使用自愿准则的机构的首席执行官 Tan Kiat How 指出，每当决策基于大量数据时，“你很快就会进入许多伦理问题之中”。</u>\n\n-**Singapore-based agency**：<u>总部位于新加坡的机构。</u>\n-**voluntary code**：<u>自愿准则，不是强制法律。</u>\n\n-**voluntary** = <u>自愿的，非强制的**vulnerable** = 脆弱的，易受伤害的，易受攻击的，处于弱势的 这两个老是容易混</u>\n**voluntary** <u>来自 **volunteer**，和“自愿”有关。</u>\n<u>而 **vulnerable** 和“受伤、容易被伤害”有关：</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Along with</font> Singapore, other governments and <font color=\"#ffff00\">mega</font>-corporations are beginning to establish their own guidelines.\n翻译: <u>除了新加坡，其他政府和大型企业也开始制定自己的准则。</u>\n\n-**along with…**：<u>与……一起；除了……之外还有。</u>  \n-**mega-corporations**：<u>超大型公司。</u>\n\n---\n\nBritain is setting up a data ethics center.\n翻译: <u>英国正在设立一个数据伦理中心。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIndia released its AI ethics strategy this spring.\n翻译: <u>印度今年春天发布了其 AI 伦理战略。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOn June 7 Google pledged not to “design or deploy AI” that would cause “overall harm,” or to develop AI-directed weapons or use AI for <font color=\"#ffff00\">surveillance</font> that would violate international norms.\n翻译: <u>6月7日，Google 承诺不会“设计或部署”会造成“整体伤害”的 AI，也不会开发由 AI 指挥的武器，或将 AI 用于会违反国际规范的监控。</u>\n\n-**surveillance**：<u>监控、监视。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt also pledged not to deploy AI whose use would violate international laws or human rights.\n翻译: <u>它还承诺不会部署其使用会违反国际法律或人权的 AI。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the statement is vague, it represents one starting point.\n翻译: <u>尽管这一声明含糊不清，但它代表了一个起点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">So does </font>the idea that decisions made by AI systems should be explainable, transparent, and fair.\n翻译: <u>AI 系统所作出的决策应当可解释、透明且公平，这一理念同样如此。</u>\n\n-so does <u>同样地</u>\n-<u>同样，另一个重要起点是：AI 作出的决策应当能够被解释、保持透明，并且符合公平原则。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">To put it another way</font>: How can we <font color=\"#ffff00\">make sure</font> that the thinking of intelligent machines reflects humanity’s highest values?\n翻译: <u>换句话说：我们如何确保智能机器的思维反映人类最高的价值观？</u>\n\n-**put it another way**：<u>换一种说法。</u>  \n-**make sure that…**：<u>确保……。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Only then</font> will they be useful servants and not Frankenstein’s out-of-control monster.\n翻译: <u>只有到那时，它们才会成为有用的仆人，而不是 Frankenstein 那失控的怪物。</u>\n\n-：Only + <u>状语置于句首，引起部分倒装。 只有到那时</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇阅读\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 53 -->\nStates will be able to force more people to pay <font color=\"#ffff00\">sales tax</font> when they make online purchases <font color=\"#ffff00\">under</font> a Supreme Court decision Thursday that will leave shoppers with lighter wallets but is a big financial win for states.\n翻译: <u>根据最高法院周四的一项裁决，各州将能够迫使更多人在网上购物时缴纳销售税；这将使购物者的钱包变瘪，但对各州来说却是一项重大的财政胜利。</u>\n\n-`sales tax` <u>指消费税/销售税。</u>\n-`under`：<u>依据、根据（法案、判决等）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 54 -->\nThe Supreme Court’s opinion Thursday <font color=\"#ffff00\">overruled</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">a pair of</font> decades-old decisions that states said <font color=\"#ffff00\">cost them</font> billions of dollars in lost revenue annually.\n翻译: <u>最高法院周四的意见推翻了两项已有数十年历史的裁决，各州称这些裁决每年使它们损失数十亿美元收入。</u>\n\n-`overruled`：<u>推翻、否定（先前的判例）。</u>\n-`a pair of`：<u>一对、两项。</u>\n-`cost them...`：<u>让它们（各州）付出……的代价。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 55 -->\nThe decisions made it more difficult for states to <font color=\"#ffff00\">collect sales tax</font> on <font color=\"#ffff00\">certain </font>online purchases.\n翻译: <u>这些裁决使各州更难对某些网上购物征收销售税。</u>\n\n-`collect sales tax`：<u>征收销售税。</u>\n-`certain`：<u>特定的、某些。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 56 -->\nThe cases the court overturned said that if a business was shipping a customer’s purchase to a state where the business didn’t have a <font color=\"#ffff00\">physical presence</font> such as a warehouse or office, the business didn’t have to collect sales tax for the state.\n翻译: <u>法院推翻的那些案件曾判定，如果一家企业把顾客购买的商品运往某个州，而该企业在该州没有仓库或办公室等实体存在，那么该企业就不必为该州代收销售税。</u>\n\n-`physical presence`：<u>实体存在、实体店铺/设施。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 57 -->\nCustomers were generally responsible for paying the sales tax to the state themselves if they weren’t charged it, but most didn’t realize they owed it and few paid.\n翻译: <u>如果顾客没有被收取销售税，他们通常有责任自行向州政府缴纳，但大多数人并未意识到自己欠税，缴纳的人也很少。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 58 -->\nJustice Anthony Kennedy wrote that the <font color=\"#ffff00\">previous decisions</font> were flawed.\n翻译: <u>大法官 Anthony Kennedy 写道，先前的裁决是有缺陷的。</u>\n\n-`previous decisions`：<u>先前的裁决。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 59 -->\n“Each year the physical presence rule becomes <font color=\"#ffff00\">further removed from</font> economic reality and results in significant revenue losses to the States,” he wrote in an opinion j<font color=\"#ffff00\">oined by four other justices</font>.\n翻译: <u>他在一份有另外四名大法官加入的意见书中写道：“实体存在规则每年都更加脱离经济现实，并导致各州遭受重大收入损失。”</u>\n\n- `be removed from`：<u>远离、与……脱节。</u>\n- `joined by four other justices`：<u>得到了另外四名大法官的加入/支持。美国最高法院共9人，5人赞成即通过。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 60 -->\nKennedy wrote that the rule “limited states’ ability to seek long-term prosperity and has prevented market participants from competing on an even playing field.”\n翻译: <u>Kennedy 写道，该规则“限制了各州追求长期繁荣的能力，并阻碍了市场参与者在公平的竞争环境中竞争”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 61 -->\nThe ruling is a victory for big chains with a presence in many states,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> since</font> they usually collect sales tax on online purchases already.\n翻译: <u>这一裁决对在许多州都有实体存在的大型连锁企业来说是一场胜利，因为它们通常已经对网上购物征收销售税。</u>\n\n-`since`：<u>既然、因为。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 62 -->\nNow, rivals will be charging sales tax where they hadn’t before.\n翻译: <u>现在，竞争对手将在以前没有征收销售税的地方开始征收。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 63 -->\nBig chains <font color=\"#ffff00\">have been collecting </font>sales tax nationwide because they <font color=\"#ffff00\">typically </font>have physical stores in whatever state a purchase is being shipped to.\n翻译: <u>大型连锁企业一直在全国范围内征收销售税，因为它们通常在购买商品被运往的任何州都有实体店。</u>\n\n-- `have been collecting`：<u>一直以来都在征收（强调动作的持续）。</u>\n-- `typically`：<u>典型地、通常。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 64 -->\nAmazon.com, with its network of warehouses, also collects sales tax in every state that charges it, though <font color=\"#ffff00\">third-party sellers</font> who use the site don’t have to.\n翻译: <u>Amazon.com 凭借其仓库网络，也在每个征收销售税的州收取销售税，尽管使用该网站的第三方卖家不必这样做。</u>\n\n-`third-party sellers`：<u>第三方卖家（指借用亚马逊平台卖自己货的人）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 65 -->\nUntil now, many sellers that have a physical presence in only a single state or a few states have been able to avoid charging sales taxes when they ship to addresses outside those states.\n翻译: <u>到目前为止，许多只在一个州或少数几个州有实体存在的卖家，在把商品运往这些州以外的地址时，一直能够避免收取销售税。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 66 -->\nSellers that use eBay and Etsy, which <font color=\"#ffff00\">provide platforms for</font> smaller sellers, also haven’t been collecting sales tax nationwide.\n翻译: <u>使用 eBay 和 Etsy 的卖家也尚未在全国范围内征收销售税，这两个网站为较小的卖家提供平台。</u>\n\n-`provide platforms for`：<u>为……提供平台。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 67 -->\nUnder the ruling Thursday, states can pass laws requiring out-of-state sellers to collect the state’s sales tax from customers and send it to the state.\n翻译: <u>根据周四的裁决，各州可以通过法律，要求州外卖家向顾客收取该州的销售税并上缴给州政府。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 68 -->\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Retail trade groups</font> praised the ruling, saying it <font color=\"#ffff00\">levels the playing field</font> for local and online businesses.\n翻译: <u>零售行业组织称赞了这一裁决，称它为本地企业和线上企业创造了公平的竞争环境。</u>\n\n-`Retail trade groups`：<u>零售行业协会、贸易组织。</u>\n-`levels the playing field`：<u>抹平游戏场、提供公平竞争的环境（非常地道的商业习语）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 69 -->\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">losers</font>, said retail analyst Neil Saunders, are online-only retailers, especially smaller ones.\n翻译: <u>零售分析师 Neil Saunders 说，输家是纯线上零售商，尤其是较小的零售商。</u>\n\n-`losers`：<u>失败者、受害者。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 70 -->\nThose retailers may face headaches <font color=\"#ffff00\">complying with</font> various state sales tax laws.\n翻译: <u>这些零售商在遵守各州不同的销售税法律时可能会面临麻烦。</u>\n\n-`complying with`：<u>顺应、遵守、符合（法律、法规）。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 71 -->\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">Small Business & Entrepreneurship Council</font> advocacy group said in a statement, “Small businesses and internet entrepreneurs are not well served at all by this decision.”\n翻译: <u>倡议组织 Small Business & Entrepreneurship Council 在一份声明中说：“小企业和互联网创业者根本没有从这一裁决中受益。”</u>\n\n-- `Small Business & Entrepreneurship Council`：<u>小企业与创业理事会（美国一个保护小企业利益的组织）。</u>\n\n---\n\n21. In dealing with the Supreme Court decision Thursday, the author D\n\n[A] gives a factual account of it and discusses its consequences.\n\n[B] describes the long and complicated process of its making.\n\n[C] presents its main points with conflicting views on them.\n\n[D] cites some cases related to it and analyzes their implications.\n\n答案选 A\n\n**<u>作者是怎样处理/展开这篇文章内容的？**</u>\n**<u>在论述星期四最高法院这个判决时，作者采取了什么写法？**</u>\n<u>它不是问判决内容本身，而是问**文章的写作方式 / 行文思路**。</u>\n\n<u>前面说：最高法院做了什么判决，推翻了什么旧规定。</u>  \n<u>后面说：这个判决会影响谁，比如州政府、大型连锁店、Amazon、eBay/Etsy 小卖家、在线零售商等。</u>\n\n<u>这种题确实有点难度,因为推翻每个选项所需要的信息源(量)是文章的结构,不是某一句话.这种题的难点在于，错误选项往往会抓住文章里出现过的一点点内容来迷惑你。</u> \n\n<u>其实也不难,它经常都是无中生有,搞出一个莫须有的内容,说文章是这样叙述的</u>\n\n<u>而错误选项常见问题是：</u>\n\n- <u>把<font color=\"#ffff00\">局部内容</font>说成全文重点</u>\n- <u>说文章做了但<font color=\"#ffff00\">其实没做</font>的事</u>\n- <u><font color=\"#ffff00\">语气过重</font>，比如 complicated、conflicting、long process</u>\n- <u><font color=\"#ffff00\">偷换对象</font>，比如分析“案例”而不是分析“判决影响”</u>\n\n**B. describes the long and complicated process of its making**  \n翻译: <u>**B. 描述其形成的漫长而复杂的过程**</u>\n意思是：<u>描述这个判决形成的漫长复杂过程。</u>  \n<u>不对。文章没有讲最高法院内部怎么审理、怎么投票、案件经历了哪些阶段，只是说了**判决结果和影响**。</u>\n\n**C. presents its main points with conflicting views on them**  \n翻译: <u>**C. 呈现其要点以及围绕这些要点的相互冲突的观点**</u>\n意思是：<u>介绍判决要点，并呈现对这些要点的冲突观点。</u>  \n<u>不太对。文章确实有不同人的反应，比如零售贸易组织赞成，小企业组织不满，但文章重点不是“双方围绕判决要点激烈争论”。它主要是在说明**谁受益、谁受损**。</u>\n\n**D. cites some <font color=\"#ffff00\">cases</font> related to it and analyzes their implications**  \n翻译: <u>**D. 引用一些与之相关的案例并分析其影响**</u>\n意思是：<u>引用一些相关案例，并分析这些案例的含义。</u>  \n<u>不对。文章只提到最高法院推翻了过去的两个旧判例，但没有具体展开这些案例的案情、判决逻辑或影响。文章<font color=\"#ffff00\">重点不是“分析案例”，而是**介绍这次判决及其后果**。</font></u>\n\n**A. gives a factual account of it and discusses its consequences**  \n翻译: <u>**A. 对其作出事实性叙述并讨论其后果**</u>\n意思是：<u>客观介绍这个判决，并讨论它的后果。</u>  \n\n<u>这个最中性</u>\n\n<u>这最符合全文：前半部分讲判决内容，后半部分讲影响——州政府受益、大型连锁店受益、网购消费者多交税、小型线上卖家负担变重。</u>"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2020","year":"2020","title":"2020 年英语一","fileName":"2020 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2020 年英语 1.md","content":"A group of <font color=\"#ffff00\">Labour MPs</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">among them</font> Yvette Cooper, are <font color=\"#ffff00\">bringing in</font> the new year with a call to <font color=\"#ffff00\">institute</font> a UK “town of culture” award.\n翻译: <u>一群工党议员，其中包括 Yvette Cooper，以呼吁设立英国“文化城镇”奖来迎接新年。</u>\n\n-**Labour MPs**：<u>英国工党议员。</u>  \n**MPs** = Members of Parliament，<u>国会议员。</u>  \n-including Yvette Cooper**。  \n<u>这里用 **among them…**，带有新闻写作的简洁风格。</u>\n-**bring in the new year**：<u>迎接新年。</u>  \n-**institute**：<u>设立、建立。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe proposal is that it should <font color=\"#ffff00\">sit alongside</font> the existing city of culture title, which was held by Hull in 2017, and has <font color=\"#ffff00\">been awarded to</font> Coventry for 2021.\n翻译: <u>该提议是，这一奖项应与现有的“文化城市”称号并行；Hull 曾在 2017 年获得该称号，Coventry 则已被授予 2021 年的称号。</u>\n\n-**sit alongside**：<u>与……并列、并存。</u>  \n-**has been awarded to…**：<u>已被授予……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nCooper and her colleagues argue that the success of <font color=\"#ffff00\">the crown for </font>Hull, where it brought in £220m of investment and an avalanche of arts, ought not to <font color=\"#ffff00\">be confined to</font> cities.\n翻译: <u>Cooper 和她的同事们认为，Hull 获得这一桂冠所带来的成功——它带来了 2.2 亿英镑投资和大量艺术活动——不应局限于城市。</u>\n\n-**has been awarded to…**：<u>已被授予……。</u>  \n-**be confined to…**：<u>被限制在……范围内。</u>  \nCooper <u>等人认为，Hull 获得“文化之城”称号后吸引了 2.2 亿英镑投资和大量艺术活动，这样的成功不应只属于城市，城镇也应该分享。</u>\n\n---\n\nBritain’s towns,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> it is true</font>, are not prevented from applying, but they generally lack the resources to <font color=\"#ffff00\">put together</font> a bid to beat their bigger competitors.\n翻译: <u>诚然，英国的城镇并未被禁止申请，但它们通常缺乏资源来组织申报，以击败更大的竞争者。</u>\n\n-**it is true**：<u>诚然、确实。</u>  \n<u>插入语表示作者承认一个事实：城镇并没有被正式禁止申请。</u>\n-**put together**：<u>组织、拼凑、准备。</u>\n\n---\n\nA town of culture award could, <font color=\"#ffff00\">it is argued</font>, become an annual event, <font color=\"#ffff00\">attracting funding</font> and creating jobs.\n翻译: <u>有人认为，“文化城镇”奖可以成为一项年度活动，吸引资金并创造就业。</u>\n\n-**it is argued**：<u>有人认为、论者认为。</u>  \n**attract funding**：<u>吸引资金。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome might see the proposal as a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> booby prize</font> for the fact that Britain is no longer able to apply for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">much more prestigious title</font> of European capital of culture, a <font color=\"#ffff00\">sought-after</font> award<font color=\"#ffff00\"> bagged</font> by Glasgow in 1990 and Liverpool in 2008.\n翻译: <u>有些人可能会把这一提议视为一种安慰奖，因为英国已无法再申请声望高得多的“欧洲文化之都”称号；这是一个备受追捧的奖项，Glasgow 于 1990 年、Liverpool 于 2008 年曾获得该称号。</u>\n\n-**booby prize**：<u>安慰奖、最差奖、带有讽刺意味的补偿奖。</u>  \n-**much more prestigious**：<u>声望高得多的。</u>  \n-**sought-after**：<u>抢手的、受追捧的。   名词短语作同位语，解释 European capital of culture。</u>\n-**bagged**：<u>拿到、赢得，口语化表达。</u>  \n-<u>有人可能会嘲讽说，“文化之镇”不过是个安慰奖，因为英国已无法再申请更有分量的“欧洲文化之都”称号——这个备受追捧的奖项曾由格拉斯哥和利物浦赢得。</u>\n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">cynic</font> might speculate that the UK is on the verge of disappearing into an endless fever of <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-celebration</font> in its desperation to <font color=\"#ffff00\">reinvent itself</font> for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">post-Brexit</font> world: after town of culture, who knows what will follow — village of culture?\n翻译: <u>愤世嫉俗者也许会猜测，英国为了在后 Brexit 世界中重塑自身，正处在陷入无休止自我庆祝狂热的边缘：在“文化城镇”之后，谁知道还会有什么——文化村庄？</u>\n\n-**cynic**：<u>愤世嫉俗者、冷嘲热讽的人。</u>\n-**self-celebration**：<u>自我庆祝。</u>\n-**reinvent itself**：<u>重塑自身。</u> \n-**post-Brexit world**：<u>脱欧后的世界。</u>\n\n---\n\nSuburb of culture?\n翻译: <u>文化郊区？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Hamlet </font>of culture?\n翻译: <u>文化小村？</u>\n\n-**hamlet**：<u>小村庄、村落，比 village 还小。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is also wise to <font color=\"#ffff00\">recal</font>l that such titles are not a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> cure-all</font>.\n翻译: <u>同样明智的是要记住，这类称号并非包治百病的灵药。</u>\n\n-**recall**：<u>回想起、记住。</u>  \n-**cure-all**：<u>万能药、包治百病的办法。</u>\n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">badly run</font> “year of culture” <font color=\"#ffff00\">washes in and out</font> of a place like the tide, bringing <font color=\"#ffff00\">prominence</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> for a spell</font> but leaving no lasting benefits to the community.\n翻译: <u>一个运作不善的“文化年”会像潮水一样在一个地方涌入又退去，带来一时的知名度，却不给当地社区留下持久的好处。</u>\n\n-**badly run**：<u>管理/运作糟糕的。</u>  \n-**wash in and out**：<u>涌进又退走。</u>  \n-**prominence**：<u>知名度、关注度。</u>  \n-**for a spell**：<u>一小段时间、短暂地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe really successful <font color=\"#ffff00\">holders</font> of such titles are those that do <font color=\"#ffff00\">a great deal more than</font> fill hotel bedrooms and bring in high-profile arts events and <font color=\"#ffff00\">good press</font> for a year.\n翻译: <u>真正成功拥有这类称号的地方，所做的远不止是让酒店客房住满、带来高知名度的艺术活动和一年的好媒体报道。</u>\n\n-**holders of such titles**：<u>这些称号的获得者。</u>  \n-**a great deal more than…**：<u>远远不止……。</u>  \n-**good press**：<u>媒体好评、正面报道。</u>  \n\n<u>这-些称号真正成功的持有者，是那些做的远远超过填满酒店客房、引入高调艺术活动和带来一年好媒体报道的地方。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey transform the <font color=\"#ffff00\">aspirations</font> of the people who live there; they <font color=\"#ffff00\">nudge</font> the self-image of the city into a <font color=\"#ffff00\">bolder</font> and more optimistic light.\n翻译: <u>它们改变居住在那里的人们的抱负；它们把城市的自我形象推向更大胆、更乐观的光亮之中。</u>\n\n-**aspirations**：<u>抱负、愿望、向往。</u>\n-**nudge**：<u>轻推、推动。</u>  \n<u>这里不是剧烈改变，而是逐渐推动城市看待自己的方式发生变化。</u>  \n-**bolder**：<u>更大胆的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is hard to <font color=\"#ffff00\">get right</font>, and requires a remarkable <font color=\"#ffff00\">degree of vision</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as well as </font>cooperation between city authorities, the private sector, community groups and cultural organisations.\n翻译: <u>要把这件事做好很难，需要非凡程度的远见，也需要城市当局、私营部门、社区团体和文化组织之间的合作。</u>\n\n-**get right**：<u>把……做对、做好。</u>  \n-**degree of vision**：<u>远见程度。</u>  \n-**as well as**：<u>以及。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut it <font color=\"#ffff00\">can be done</font>: Glasgow’s year as European capital of culture can certainly be seen as <font color=\"#ffff00\">one of a complex series of factors</font> that have turned the city into the <font color=\"#ffff00\">powerhouse</font> of art, music and theatre that it remains today.\n翻译: <u>但这是可以做到的：Glasgow 作为欧洲文化之都的那一年，当然可以被视为一系列复杂因素之一，这些因素把这座城市变成了今天依然保持的艺术、音乐和戏剧重镇。</u>\n\n-**can be done**：<u>可以被做到。</u> \n-**one of a complex series of factors**：<u>一系列复杂因素中的一个。</u>  \n-**powerhouse**：<u>强大中心、重镇。</u>\n\n---\n\nA “town of culture” could be not just about the arts but about honouring a town’s peculiarities — helping sustain its <font color=\"#ffff00\">high street</font>, supporting <font color=\"#ffff00\">local facilities</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">above all</font> celebrating its people.\n翻译: <u>一个“文化城镇”可以不仅关乎艺术，还关乎表彰一个城镇的独特性——帮助维持其商业街，支持当地设施，最重要的是赞美其人民。</u>\n\n-**high street**：<u>英国城镇里的主要商业街/市中心商业区。</u>  \n-**local facilities**：<u>本地设施，比如图书馆、社区中心、剧场、体育馆、公共空间等。</u>  \n-**above all**：<u>最重要的是。</u>\n\n---\n\nJeremy Wright, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">culture secretary</font>, should welcome this positive, hope-filled proposal, and turn it into action.\n翻译: <u>文化大臣 Jeremy Wright 应当欢迎这一积极、充满希望的提议，并将其付诸行动。</u>\n\n-**the culture secretary**：<u>文化大臣。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇阅读\n\nScientific publishing has long been a licence to print money.\n翻译: <u>科学出版长期以来一直是一门稳赚大钱的生意。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nScientists need journals in which to publish their research, so they will <font color=\"#ffff00\">supply the articles</font> without monetary reward.\n翻译: <u>科学家需要期刊来发表他们的研究，因此他们会无偿提供文章。</u>\n\n-**supply the articles**：<u>提供文章。</u>\n\n---\n\nOther scientists <font color=\"#ffff00\">perform</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">specialised work</font> of peer review also for free, because it is a central element in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">acquisition of status</font> and the production of scientific knowledge.\n翻译: <u>其他科学家也免费从事同行评议这一专业工作，因为它是获得地位和生产科学知识的核心要素。</u>\n\n-**perform**：<u>执行、完成。</u>  \n-**specialised work**：<u>专业化工作。</u>  \n-**acquisition of status**：<u>获得地位、取得学术声望。</u>\n\n---\n\nWith the content of papers <font color=\"#ffff00\">secured</font> for free, the publisher needs only to find a market for its journal.\n翻译: <u>既然论文内容已免费获得，出版商只需要为其期刊找到市场。</u>\n\n-**secured**：<u>获得、确保到手。</u>  \n-<u>直译：在论文内容已经免费获得的情况下，出版商只需为它的期刊找到市场。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Until this century</font>, university libraries were not very price sensitive.\n翻译: <u>直到本世纪以前，大学图书馆对价格并不十分敏感。</u>\n\n-Until this century <u>直到本世纪之前。</u>\n\n---\n\nScientific publishers <font color=\"#ffff00\">routinely</font> report <font color=\"#ffff00\">profit margins</font> approaching 40% on their <font color=\"#ffff00\">operations</font>, at a time when the rest of the publishing industry is in an existential crisis.\n翻译: <u>在出版业其他领域正处于生存危机之际，科学出版商经常报告其业务利润率接近 40%。</u>\n\n-**routinely**：<u>经常、通常。</u>  \n-**report profit margins**：<u>报告利润率。</u>  \n**profit** = <u>利润</u>\n**margin** = <u>幅度、差额、边际</u>\n**profit margin** = <u>利润率  也就是 利润占收入的比例</u>\n-**operations**：<u>经营活动、运营业务。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">Dutch</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">giant</font> Elsevier, which claims to publish 25% of the scientific papers produced in the world, made profits of more than £900m last year, while UK universities alone spent more than £210m in 2016 to enable researchers to access <font color=\"#ffff00\">their own publicly funded research</font>.\n翻译: <u>荷兰巨头 Elsevier 声称发表了全球 25% 的科学论文，去年盈利超过 9 亿英镑；与此同时，仅英国大学在 2016 年就花费了超过 2.1 亿英镑，使研究人员能够访问他们自己由公共资金资助的研究。</u>\n\n-**Dutch**：<u>荷兰的。</u> \n-**giant**：<u>巨头、大公司。</u>  \n-**their own publicly funded research**：<u>他们自己由公共资金资助的研究。</u>\n\n---\n\nBoth figures seem to rise unstoppably despite increasingly desperate efforts to change them.\n翻译: <u>尽管改变这些数字的努力越来越近乎绝望，这两个数字似乎仍在不可阻挡地上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe most <font color=\"#ffff00\">drastic</font>, and<font color=\"#ffff00\"> thoroughly illegal</font>, reaction has been the emergence of Sci-Hub, a kind of <font color=\"#ffff00\">global photocopier</font> for scientific papers, set up in 2012, which now <font color=\"#ffff00\">claims to offer</font> access to every paywalled article published since 2015.\n翻译: <u>最激烈且完全非法的反应，是 Sci-Hub 的出现；它是一种科学论文的全球复印机，成立于 2012 年，现在声称可以提供自 2015 年以来发表的每一篇付费墙文章的访问权限。</u>\n\n-**drastic**：<u>激烈的、极端的。</u>  \n-**thoroughly illegal**：<u>彻底非法的。</u> \n-**global photocopier**：<u>全球复印机，比喻它复制并传播论文。</u> \n-**claims to offer access to…**：<u>声称提供对……的访问。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe success of Sci-Hub, which relies on researchers passing on copies they have themselves legally accessed, shows the legal ecosystem has lost legitimacy among its users and must be transformed so that it works for <font color=\"#ffff00\">all participants</font>.\n翻译: <u>Sci-Hub 的成功依赖研究人员传递他们自己合法获取的副本，这表明法律生态系统在其用户中已经失去合法性，必须被改造，以便为所有参与者服务。</u>\n\n-**all participants**：<u>所有参与者，包括作者、审稿人、大学、读者、资助者和出版商。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn Britain the move towards open access publishing has been driven by funding bodies.\n翻译: <u>在英国，向开放获取出版转变一直由资助机构推动。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn some ways it has been very successful.\n翻译: <u>在某些方面，它非常成功。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMore than half of all British scientific research is now published under open access terms: either freely available from the moment of publication, or paywalled for a year or more so that the publishers can make a profit before being placed on <font color=\"#ffff00\">general release.</font>\n翻译: <u>如今，超过一半的英国科学研究是在开放获取条款下发表的：要么从发表之时起即可免费获取，要么被置于付费墙后一年或更久，以便出版商在公开发布之前能够获利。</u>\n\n-**general release**：<u>公开发行、普遍开放。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet the new system has not worked out any cheaper for the universities.\n翻译: <u>然而，对大学来说，新体系并没有变得更便宜。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPublishers have responded to the demand that they make their product free to readers by charging their writers fees to cover the costs of preparing an article.\n翻译: <u>出版商面对让其产品对读者免费的要求，作出的回应是向作者收费，以支付准备一篇文章的成本。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThese range from around £500 to $5,000.\n翻译: <u>这些费用从约 500 英镑到 5,000 美元不等。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA report last year pointed out that the costs both of subscriptions and of these “article preparation costs” had been steadily rising at a rate above inflation.\n翻译: <u>去年的一份报告指出，订阅费用和这些“文章准备费用”的成本都一直以高于通胀的速度稳步上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn some ways the scientific publishing model <font color=\"#ffff00\">resembles</font> the economy of the social internet: labour is provided free in exchange for the hope of status, while huge profits are made by a few big firms who run the market places.\n翻译: <u>在某些方面，科学出版模式类似于社交互联网经济：劳动被免费提供，以换取获得地位的希望，而巨额利润则由少数经营市场的大公司赚取。</u>\n\n-**resemble**：<u>类似、相似。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn both cases, we need a rebalancing of power.\n翻译: <u>在这两种情况下，我们都需要重新平衡权力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Progressives</font> often support diversity <font color=\"#ffff00\">mandates</font> as a path to equality and a way to level the playing field.\n翻译: <u>进步派常常支持多样性强制规定，将其作为通往平等的路径和创造公平竞争环境的方式。</u>\n\n--**progressives**：<u>进步派、自由派改革者。</u>  \n-**mandate** <u>指官方要求、强制规定。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">all too often</font> such policies are an insincere form of <font color=\"#ffff00\">virtue-signaling</font> that benefits only the most privileged and does little to help average people.\n翻译: <u>但这类政策往往是一种不真诚的美德展示，只让最享有特权的人受益，对普通人帮助甚微。</u>\n\n-**all too often**：<u>太经常、常常令人遗憾地。</u> \n-**virtue-signaling**：<u>美德信号、道德姿态展示。  意思是某些人推出政策主要是为了显得自己站在道德高地，而不是实际解决问题。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">A pair of bills</font> sponsored by Massachusetts state Senator Jason Lewis and <font color=\"#ffff00\">House Speaker Pro Tempore</font> Patricia Haddad, to ensure <font color=\"#ffff00\">“gender parity</font>” on <font color=\"#ffff00\">boards and commissions</font>, provide <font color=\"#ffff00\">a case in point</font>.\n翻译: <u>由 Massachusetts 州参议员 Jason Lewis 和众议院临时议长 Patricia Haddad 发起的两项法案，旨在确保委员会和理事会中的“性别均等”，就是一个恰当的例子。</u>\n\n-**a pair of bills**：<u>两项法案。</u>\n-**House Speaker Pro Tempore**：<u>众议院临时议长 / 代理议长职位。</u> \n-**gender parity**：<u>性别平等 / 性别比例均衡。</u>  \n-**boards and commissions**：<u>董事会、委员会、政府委员会等决策机构。</u> \n-**a case in point**：<u>一个恰当例子、一个现成例证。</u>\n\n---\n\nHaddad and Lewis <font color=\"#ffff00\">are concerned that</font> more than half the state-government boards are less than 40 percent female.\n翻译: <u>Haddad 和 Lewis 担心，州政府委员会中有一半以上女性比例低于 40%。</u>\n\n-**be concerned that…**：<u>担心……，关注……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nIn order to ensure that elite women have more such opportunities, they have proposed imposing government <font color=\"#ffff00\">quotas</font>.\n翻译: <u>为了确保精英女性拥有更多这样的机会，他们提议实施政府配额。</u>\n\n**quota**：<u>配额、比例要求。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nIf the <font color=\"#ffff00\">bills become law</font>, state boards and commissions will be required to <font color=\"#ffff00\">set aside</font> 50 percent of board seats for women by 2022.\n翻译: <u>如果这些法案成为法律，到 2022 年，州理事会和委员会将被要求为女性预留 50% 的席位。</u>\n\n-bill become law <u>法案是法案,法律是法律</u>\n-**set aside**：<u>预留、留出。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe bills are similar to a <font color=\"#ffff00\">measure</font> recently adopted in California, which last year became the first state to require gender quotas for private companies.\n翻译: <u>这些法案类似于 California 最近通过的一项措施；该州去年成为第一个要求私营公司实行性别配额的州。</u>\n\n-**measure**：<u>措施、法案、政策。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In </font>signing the measure, California Governor Jerry Brown admitted that the law, which <font color=\"#ffff00\">expressly</font> classifies people on the basis of sex, is probably <font color=\"#ffff00\">unconstitutional</font>.\n翻译: <u>在签署该措施时，California 州长 Jerry Brown 承认，这项明确根据性别对人进行分类的法律很可能违宪。</u>\n\n-in + <u>动名词短语，作时间/背景状语。 在签署这项措施时。</u>\n-**expressly**：<u>明确地、明文地。</u>  \n-**unconstitutional**：<u>违宪的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe US Supreme Court <font color=\"#ffff00\">frowns on</font> sex-based classifications unless they are designed to address an “important” <font color=\"#ffff00\">policy interest</font>.\n翻译: <u>美国最高法院通常不赞成基于性别的分类，除非这些分类旨在回应一项“重要的”政策利益。</u>\n\n-**frown on**：<u>不赞成、不认可。</u>  \n-**important policy interest**：<u>重要政策利益。</u>\n\n---\n\nBecause the California law applies to all boards, even where there is no history of prior discrimination, courts are likely to rule that the law violates the constitutional guarantee of “equal protection”.\n翻译: <u>由于 California 法律适用于所有董事会，即使在没有既往歧视历史的地方也适用，法院很可能裁定该法律违反“平等保护”的宪法保障。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut are such government mandates even necessary?\n翻译: <u>但这类政府强制规定真的有必要吗？</u>\n\n-<u>但问题是，这样的政府配额要求真的有必要吗？</u>\n\n---\n\nFemale participation on <font color=\"#ffff00\">corporate boards</font> may not currently mirror the percentage of women in the general population, <font color=\"#ffff00\">but so what</font>?\n翻译: <u>女性在公司董事会中的参与度目前也许并未反映女性在总人口中的比例，但那又怎样呢？</u>\n\n-**corporate boards**：<u>公司董事会。</u>  \n-<u>公司董事会上的女性参与度目前可能并不反映总人口中女性比例，<font color=\"#ffff00\">但那又怎样？</font></u>\n\n---\n\nThe number of women on corporate boards has been steadily increasing without government interference.\n翻译: <u>在没有政府干预的情况下，公司董事会中女性的人数一直在稳步增加。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAccording to a study by Catalyst, between 2010 and 2015 <font color=\"#ffff00\">the share of women</font> on the boards of global corporations increased by 54 percent.\n翻译: <u>根据 Catalyst 的一项研究，2010 年至 2015 年间，全球公司董事会中女性所占比例增加了 54%。</u>\n\n-**the share of women**：<u>女性比例。</u>\n\n---\n\nRequiring companies to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> make</font> gender the primary qualification for board membership will inevitably lead to less experienced private sector boards.\n翻译: <u>要求公司把性别作为董事会成员资格的首要条件，将不可避免地导致私营部门董事会经验更少。</u>\n\n-**make A B**：<u>使 A 成为 B。</u>  \n-<u>作者认为，如果强制公司按性别配额选董事，性别就会压过经验成为首要条件，最终会让私营企业董事会整体经验不足。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat is exactly what happened when <font color=\"#ffff00\">Norway</font> adopted a nationwide corporate gender quota.\n翻译: <u>当挪威采用全国性的企业性别配额时，发生的正是这种情况。</u>\n\n-**Norway**：<u>挪威。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nWriting in The New Republic, Alice Lee notes that increasing the number of opportunities for board membership without increasing the <font color=\"#ffff00\">pool </font>of qualified women to <font color=\"#ffff00\">serve on such boards</font> has led to a “golden skirt” phenomenon, where the s<font color=\"#ffff00\">ame elite women</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">scoop up</font> multiple seats on a variety of boards.\n翻译: <u>Alice Lee 在《新共和》上撰文指出，在没有扩大有资格担任董事会成员的女性人才库的情况下增加董事会成员机会，已经导致了一种“金裙子”现象，即同一批精英女性在各种董事会中揽获多个席位。</u>\n\n-**pool**：<u>人才池、候选人群体。</u>\n-**to serve on such boards**：<u>在这些董事会任职。</u>  \n-**the same elite women**：<u>同一批精英女性。</u>  \n-**scoop up**：<u>迅速获得、抢占。</u>  \n<u>地道意译：Alice Lee 指出，如果只是硬性增加女性董事席位，却没有培养和扩大合格女性候选人群体，结果可能只是少数精英女性同时占据多个董事会席位，这就是所谓“金裙子”现象。</u>\n\n---\n\nNext time somebody pushes corporate quotas as a way to promote gender equity, remember that such policies are largely <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-serving</font> measures that make their sponsors feel good but do little to help average women.\n翻译: <u>下次有人把企业配额作为促进性别平等的方式来推动时，请记住，这类政策在很大程度上是自利性措施，让其倡导者自我感觉良好，却几乎无助于普通女性。</u>\n\n-**self-serving**：<u>自利的、服务自身利益的。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇阅读\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 54 -->\nLast Thursday, the French Senate passed a digital services tax, which would impose an entirely new tax on large <font color=\"#ffff00\">multinationals</font> that provide digital services to consumers or users in France.\n翻译: <u>上周四，法国参议院通过了一项数字服务税，该税将对向法国消费者或用户提供数字服务的大型跨国公司征收一种全新的税。</u>\n\n-multinationals：<u>跨国公司。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 55 -->\nDigital services include everything from providing a platform for selling goods and services online to targeting advertising based on user data, and the tax <font color=\"#ffff00\">applies to </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">gross revenue</font> from such services.\n翻译: <u>数字服务包括从提供在线销售商品和服务的平台，到基于用户数据定向投放广告等各种内容，而该税适用于此类服务产生的总收入。</u>\n\n-apply to：<u>适用于、针对。</u>\n-gross revenue：<u>总收入、毛收入（不扣除成本的营利总额）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 56 -->\nMany French politicians and <font color=\"#ffff00\">media outlets</font> have <font color=\"#ffff00\">referred to this as</font> a “GAFA tax,” meaning that it is designed to apply <font color=\"#ffff00\">primarily</font> to companies such as Google, Apple, Facebook and Amazon—in other words, multinational tech companies based in the United States.\n翻译: <u>许多法国政治人物和媒体机构将其称为“GAFA tax”，意思是它主要旨在适用于 Google、Apple、Facebook 和 Amazon 等公司，换言之，就是总部设在美国的跨国科技公司。</u>\n\n-media outlets：<u>媒体机构、新闻媒体。</u>\n-refer to A as B：<u>把A称作B。</u>\n-primarily：<u>主要地、首要地。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 57 -->\nThe digital services tax now awaits the signature of President Emmanuel Macron, who has expressed support for the measure, and it could go into effect within the next few weeks.\n翻译: <u>数字服务税现在正等待 Emmanuel Macron 总统签署，他已表示支持这项措施，而该税可能在未来几周内生效。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 58 -->\nBut it has already <font color=\"#ffff00\">sparked</font> significant controversy, with the United States trade representative opening an investigation into whether the tax discriminates against American companies, which <font color=\"#ffff00\">in turn</font> could lead to trade sanctions against France.\n翻译: <u>但它已经引发了重大争议，美国贸易代表已启动调查，以确定该税是否歧视美国公司，而这反过来可能导致美国对法国实施贸易制裁。</u>\n\n-sparked：<u>引发、触发（原意为产生火花）。</u>\n-in turn：<u>反过来、转而。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 59 -->\nThe French tax is not just a unilateral move by one country in need of revenue.\n翻译: <u>法国的这项税并不只是一个需要收入的国家采取的单边行动。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 60 -->\nInstead, the digital services tax is part of a much larger trend, with countries over the past few years proposing or <font color=\"#ffff00\">putting in place</font> an alphabet soup of new international <font color=\"#ffff00\">tax provisions</font>.\n翻译: <u>相反，数字服务税是一种更大趋势的一部分，过去几年中，各国提出或实施了一连串名目繁多的新的国际税收条款。</u>\n\n-putting in place：<u>落实、实施、使生效。</u>\n-tax provisions：<u>税收条款/规定。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 61 -->\nThese have included Britain’s DPT (<font color=\"#ffff00\">diverted profits tax</font>), Australia’s MAAL (<font color=\"#ffff00\">multinational antiavoidance law</font>), and India’s SEP (significant economic presence) test,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> to name but a few.</font>\n翻译: <u>这些包括英国的 DPT（转移利润税）、澳大利亚的 MAAL（跨国反避税法）以及印度的 SEP（重大经济存在）测试，仅举数例。</u>\n\n-diverted profits tax：<u>转移利润税</u>\n--multinational antiavoidance law：<u>跨国反避税法。</u>\n-to name but a few：<u>仅举几例（固定用法，放在句尾）。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 62 -->\nAt the same time, the European Union, Spain, Britain and several other countries have all seriously contemplated digital services taxes.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，欧盟、西班牙、英国以及其他几个国家都认真考虑过数字服务税。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 63 -->\nThese unilateral developments differ in their specifics, but they are all designed to tax multinationals on <font color=\"#ffff00\">income and revenue</font> that countries believe they should have a right to tax, even if international tax rules do not grant them that right.\n翻译: <u>这些单边发展在具体细节上有所不同，但它们都旨在对跨国公司的收入和营收征税，因为各国认为自己应当有权对其征税，即便国际税收规则并未赋予它们这种权利。</u>\n\n-income and revenue <u>收入和利润</u>\n-\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 64 -->\nIn other words, they all share a view that the international tax system has failed to keep up with the current economy.\n翻译: <u>换言之，它们都持有一种共同看法，即国际税收体系未能跟上当前经济的发展。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 65 -->\nIn response to these many unilateral measures, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) is currently working with 131 countries to reach a consensus by the end of 2020 on an international solution.\n翻译: <u>为回应这些众多单边措施，经济合作与发展组织（OECD）目前正与 131 个国家合作，力争在 2020 年底前就一项国际解决方案达成共识。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 66 -->\nBoth France and the United States are involved in the organization's work, but France's digital services tax and the American response raise questions about <font color=\"#ffff00\">what the future holds for </font>the international tax system.\n翻译: <u>法国和美国都参与了该组织的工作，但法国的数字服务税以及美国的回应，引发了关于国际税收体系未来将走向何方的问题。</u>\n\n-what the future holds for...：……<u>的未来会怎样（地道表达，直译是“未来为某物保留了什么”）。</u>\n-<u>尽管法国和美国都参与了经合组织的这项协调工作，但法国强推数字服务税以及美国做出的激烈反击，不禁让人对国际税收体系的未来命运打上了一个大大的问号。</u>\n\n---\n\n<!-- card-id: 67 -->\nFrance’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">planned tax</font> is a clear warning: Unless a broad consensus can be reached on reforming the international tax system, other nations are likely to <font color=\"#ffff00\">follow suit</font>, and American companies will face a cascade of different taxes from dozens of nations that will prove burdensome and costly.\n翻译: <u>法国计划中的这项税是一个明确警告：除非能够就改革国际税收体系达成广泛共识，否则其他国家很可能效仿，而美国公司将面临来自数十个国家的一连串不同税收，这将被证明既繁重又代价高昂。</u>\n\n-planned tax：<u>计划实施的税收。</u>\n-follow suit：<u>效仿、跟风（源自打牌跟牌的牌术用语）。</u>"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2021","year":"2021","title":"2021 年英语一","fileName":"2021 年英语 1.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2021 年英语 1.md","content":"<font color=\"#ffff00\">How can</font> Britain’s train operators <font color=\"#ffff00\">possibly</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">justify</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">yet another</font> increase to rail passenger fares?\n翻译: <u>英国的火车运营商怎么可能为铁路乘客票价又一次上涨作出合理解释呢？</u>\n\n-**How can…justify…?**：<u>怎么能证明……合理？</u>  \n-**possibly**：<u>到底、究竟、怎么可能。这里加强质疑语气。</u>  \n-**yet another**：<u>又一个、又一次，带有不满语气。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt has become a <font color=\"#ffff00\">grimly</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">reliable</font> annual ritual: every January the cost of travelling by train rises, imposing a significant extra burden on those who have no option but to use the rail network to get to work <font color=\"#ffff00\">or otherwise.</font>\n翻译: <u>这已经变成一种令人沮丧却可靠上演的年度惯例：每年一月，乘火车出行的成本都会上涨，给那些别无选择、只能利用铁路网络上下班或进行其他出行的人施加一笔显著的额外负担。</u>\n\n-**grimly**：<u>令人沮丧地、严峻地。</u>  \n-**reliable**：<u>可靠的、准时发生的。</u>  \n-**or otherwise**：<u>或出于其他原因。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nThis year’s rise, an average of 2.7 per cent, may be <font color=\"#ffff00\">a fraction lowe</font>r than last year’s, but it is still <font color=\"#ffff00\">well above</font> the official Consumer Price Index (CPI) <font color=\"#ffff00\">measure of inflation.</font>\n翻译: <u>今年的涨幅平均为 2.7%，或许比去年的涨幅略低一点，但仍远高于官方消费者价格指数（CPI）衡量的通货膨胀率。</u>\n\n-**a fraction lower**：<u>略低一点点。</u>  \n-**well above**：<u>远高于。</u>  \n-**measure of inflation**：<u>通货膨胀指标。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Successive governments</font> have permitted such increases <font color=\"#ffff00\">on the grounds that</font> the cost of investing in and running the rail network should <font color=\"#ffff00\">be borne</font> by those who use it, rather than the general taxpayer.\n翻译: <u>历届政府都允许这类涨价，理由是投资和运营铁路网络的成本应由使用者承担，而不是由普通纳税人承担。</u>\n\n-**successive governments**：<u>一届又一届政府、历届政府。</u>  \n-**on the grounds that…**：<u>基于……理由。</u>  \n-**be borne by…**：<u>由……承担。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhy, the argument goes, should a car-driving <font color=\"#ffff00\">pensioner </font>from Lincolnshire have to <font color=\"#ffff00\">subsidise</font> the daily commute of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">stockbroker</font> from Surrey?\n翻译: <u>这种论点认为，为什么一位来自 Lincolnshire、开车出行的养老金领取者要补贴一位来自 Surrey 的股票经纪人的日常通勤呢？</u>\n\n-**car-driving pensioner**：<u>开车的退休老人。</u>  \n-**have to subsidise**：<u>必须补贴。</u>  \n-**stockbroker**：<u>股票经纪人。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Equally</font>, there is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">sense that</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">travails</font> of commuters in the South East, many of whom will face among the biggest rises, have received too much attention compared to those who must endure the relatively poor infrastructure of the Midlands and the North.\n翻译: <u>同样，也有一种看法认为，英格兰东南部通勤者的困境受到了过多关注，其中许多人将面临最大幅度的涨价之一，而相比之下，那些必须忍受 Midlands 和北部相对落后基础设施的人受到的关注较少。</u>\n\n-**Equally** <u>表示提出另一个相关观点。</u>  \n-**there is a sense that…**：<u>人们有一种感觉认为……。</u>  \n-**travails**：<u>艰辛、苦恼、折磨。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHowever, over the past 12 months, those commuters have also experienced some of the worst rail strikes in years.\n翻译: <u>然而，在过去 12 个月里，这些通勤者也经历了多年来最严重的一些铁路罢工。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It is all very well</font> train operators <font color=\"#ffff00\">trumpeting</font> the improvements they are making to the network, <font color=\"#ffff00\">but</font> passengers should be able to expect a basic level of service for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">substantial sums</font> they are now paying to travel.\n翻译: <u>火车运营商大肆宣扬他们正在对铁路网络进行的改进固然不错，但乘客既然如今为出行支付了相当可观的费用，就应当能够期待基本水平的服务。</u>\n\n-**It is all very well…but…**：……<u>固然不错 / ……说得好听，但……。</u>  \n-**trumpeting**：<u>大肆宣扬、吹嘘。</u>  \n-**substantial sums**：<u>相当大的金额。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe responsibility for the latest wave of strikes <font color=\"#ffff00\">rests on</font> the unions.\n翻译: <u>最近这一波罢工的责任在工会。</u>\n\n-**rest on**：<u>落在……身上、由……承担。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">However</font>, there is <font color=\"#ffff00\">a strong case</font> that those who have been worst affected by <font color=\"#ffff00\">industrial action</font> should receive compensation for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">disruption</font> they have suffered.\n翻译: <u>然而，有充分理由认为，那些受劳工行动影响最严重的人应当就他们遭受的干扰获得补偿。</u>\n\n-<u>前一句说罢工责任在工会；这里转向乘客补偿：无论责任在谁，受害最严重的乘客应得到补偿。</u>\n-**a strong case**：<u>有力理由、充分论据。</u>  \n-**industrial action**：<u>劳工行动，通常指罢工、怠工等工会行动。</u>  \n-**disruption**：<u>扰乱、中断、不便。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe Government has pledged to change the law to introduce a <font color=\"#ffff00\">minimum service requirement</font> so that, even when strikes occur, services can continue to operate.\n翻译: <u>政府已承诺修改法律，引入最低服务要求，以便即使发生罢工，服务也能继续运行。</u>\n\n-**minimum service requirement**：<u>最低服务要求。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThis should form part of a wider package of measures to address the long-running problems on Britain’s railways.\n翻译: <u>这应当成为一揽子更广泛措施的一部分，以解决英国铁路长期存在的问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYes, more investment is needed, but passengers will not be willing to pay more indefinitely if they must also endure <font color=\"#ffff00\">cramped</font>, unreliable services, interrupted by regular chaos when <font color=\"#ffff00\">timetables</font> are changed, or planned maintenance is <font color=\"#ffff00\">managed incompetently</font>.\n翻译: <u>是的，需要更多投资，但如果乘客还必须忍受拥挤、不可靠的服务，忍受时刻表变更时经常出现的混乱，或计划内维护管理不善造成的中断，他们就不会愿意无限期地支付更多费用。</u>\n\n-**cramped**：<u>拥挤狭窄的。</u>  \n-**timetables**：<u>列车时刻表。</u>  \n-**managed incompetently**：<u>被无能地管理。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe threat of <font color=\"#ffff00\">nationalisation</font> may have been <font color=\"#ffff00\">seen off </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">for now</font>, but it will <font color=\"#ffff00\">return with a vengeance</font> if the<font color=\"#ffff00\"> justified anger</font> of passengers is not addressed<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in short order</font>.\n翻译: <u>国有化的威胁眼下或许已经被挡了回去，但如果乘客有正当理由的愤怒不能尽快得到处理，它将以更猛烈的势头卷土重来。</u>\n\n-**nationalisation**：<u>国有化，即把铁路运营重新交由国家控制。</u>  \n-**see off**：<u>击退、赶走、暂时化解。</u>  \n-**for now**：<u>目前、暂时。</u>  \n-return with a vengeance**：<u>猛烈回归、以更强烈形式卷土重来。</u>  \n-**justified anger**：<u>合理的愤怒、有正当理由的愤怒。</u>  \n-**in short order**：<u>很快、迅速。</u>  \n\n-\n\n\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\n\nLast year marked the <font color=\"#ffff00\">third year in a row</font> that Indonesia’s bleak rate of deforestation has slowed in pace.\n翻译: <u>去年标志着印度尼西亚严峻的森林砍伐速度连续第三年放缓。</u>\n\n-**the third year in a row**：<u>连续第三年。</u>\n<u>去年标志着印尼严峻的森林砍伐率放缓速度的连续第三年。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOne reason for the turnaround may be the country’s antipoverty program.\n翻译: <u>出现这一转变的一个原因可能是该国的反贫困项目。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn 2007, Indonesia started <font color=\"#ffff00\">phasing in</font> a program that gives money to its poorest residents under certain conditions, such as requiring people to keep kids in school or get regular medical care.\n翻译: <u>2007 年，印度尼西亚开始逐步推行一项项目，在某些条件下向最贫困居民发放现金，例如要求人们让孩子继续上学或定期接受医疗护理。</u>\n\n-**phase in**：<u>逐步引入、分阶段实施。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Called</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">conditional</font> cash transfers or CCTs, these social assistance programs are designed to reduce inequality and break the cycle of poverty.\n翻译: <u>这些社会援助项目被称为有条件现金转移支付，即 CCTs，旨在减少不平等并打破贫困循环。</u>\n\n-**Called…** = **These programs are called…**。  \n-**conditional cash transfers**：<u>有条件现金转移。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey’re already used in dozens of countries worldwide.\n翻译: <u>它们已经在全球数十个国家使用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn Indonesia, the program has provided enough food and medicine to <font color=\"#ffff00\">substantially</font> reduce severe growth problems among children.\n翻译: <u>在印度尼西亚，该项目提供了足够的食物和药品，从而大幅减少了儿童严重生长问题。</u>\n\n-**substantially**：<u>大幅地、显著地。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut CCT programs don’t generally consider effects on the environment.\n翻译: <u>但 CCT 项目通常并不考虑其对环境的影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn fact, poverty alleviation and environmental protection are often viewed as conflicting goals, says Paul Ferraro, an economist at Johns Hopkins University.\n翻译: <u>事实上，减贫和环境保护常常被视为相互冲突的目标，Johns Hopkins University 的经济学家 Paul Ferraro 说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat’s because economic growth can be correlated with environmental degradation, <font color=\"#ffff00\">while</font> protecting the environment is sometimes correlated with greater poverty.\n翻译: <u>这是因为经济增长可能与环境退化相关，而保护环境有时又与更严重的贫困相关。</u>\n\n-**while** <u>在这里表示对比 翻译成而</u>\n\n---\n\nHowever, those correlations don’t prove cause and effect.\n翻译: <u>然而，这些相关性并不能证明因果关系。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nThe only previous study analyzing <font color=\"#ffff00\">causality</font>, based on an area in Mexico that <font color=\"#ffff00\">had instituted</font> CCTs, supported the traditional view.\n翻译: <u>此前唯一一项分析因果关系的研究，基于墨西哥一个已实施 CCTs 的地区，支持了传统观点。</u>\n\n-**analyzing causality**：<u>分析因果关系的。</u>\n**causality** <u>里面有 **cause**，所以和“原因、导致”有关。  **靠-ZA-li-ti**</u>\n**casualty** <u>常出现在 **war / accident / disaster** 语境里，表示“伤亡”。**开-柔-ə-ti**</u>\n-**had instituted**：<u>已经实施、建立。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">There,</font> as people got more money, some of them may have more <font color=\"#ffff00\">cleared land </font>for cattle to raise for meat, Ferraro says.\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 说，在那里，随着人们获得更多钱，其中一些人可能清理了更多土地，用来饲养供食肉的牛。</u>\n\n-There <u>在那里。</u>\n-**cleared land**：<u>清理土地，通常指砍伐森林、开辟牧场。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSuch programs <font color=\"#ffff00\">do not have to</font> negatively affect the environment, <font color=\"#ffff00\">though</font>.\n翻译: <u>不过，这类项目并不一定会对环境产生负面影响。</u>\n\n-**do not have to**：<u>不必然、不一定。</u>  \n-**though** <u>放句末，表示转折，“不过”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nFerraro <font color=\"#ffff00\">wanted to see</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">if </font>Indonesia’s poverty-alleviation program was affecting deforestation.\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 想看看印度尼西亚的减贫项目是否正在影响森林砍伐。</u>\n\n-**wanted to see**：<u>想要弄清楚、想看看。</u>  \n-<u>这里 **if** 不是条件“如果”，而是“是否”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIndonesia has the third-largest area of tropical forest in the world and one of the highest deforestation rates.\n翻译: <u>印度尼西亚拥有世界第三大热带森林面积，同时也是森林砍伐率最高的国家之一。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFerraro analyzed satellite data showing annual forest loss from 2008 to 2012 — including during Indonesia’s phase-in of the antipoverty program — in 7,468 forested villages across 15 provinces.\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 分析了 2008 年至 2012 年的卫星数据，这些数据显示了 15 个省 7,468 个森林村庄的年度森林损失情况，其中包括印度尼西亚逐步推行反贫困项目期间的数据。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We see that the program is associated with a 30 percent reduction in deforestation,” Ferraro says.\n翻译: <u>“我们看到，该项目与森林砍伐减少 30% 有关，”Ferraro 说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat’s likely because the rural poor are using the money as <font color=\"#ffff00\">makeshift</font> insurance policies against <font color=\"#ffff00\">inclement weather,</font> Ferraro says.\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 说，这很可能是因为农村贫困人口把这些钱当作应对恶劣天气的临时保险。</u>\n\n-**makeshift**：<u>临时替代的、权宜的。</u> \n-**inclement weather**：<u>恶劣天气，比如雨季延迟、干旱、洪水等。</u>  \nFerraro <u>认为，原因可能在于农村贫困家庭把现金补助当成一种临时保险，用来应对天气不好造成的收成风险。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Typically</font>, if rains are delayed, people may clear land to plant more rice to <font color=\"#ffff00\">supplement</font> their harvests.\n翻译: <u>通常情况下，如果降雨推迟，人们可能会清理土地，种植更多水稻来补充收成。</u>\n\n-**Typically**：<u>通常、一般来说。</u>  \n-**supplement**：<u>补充。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWith the CCTs, individuals instead can use the money to supplement their harvests.\n翻译: <u>有了 CCTs，个人则可以用这笔钱来补充收成。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhether this research <font color=\"#ffff00\">translates elsewhere</font> is <font color=\"#ffff00\">anybody’s guess.</font>\n翻译: <u>这项研究能否适用于其他地方，谁也说不准。</u>\n\n-**translates elsewhere**：<u>迁移到其他地方、在其他地方也适用。</u>\n-**anybody’s guess**：<u>谁都可以猜、无法确定。</u>  \n\n---\n\nFerraro suggests the results may transfer to other parts of Asia, due to <font color=\"#ffff00\">commonalities</font> such as the importance of growing rice and <font color=\"#ffff00\">market access</font>.\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 认为，由于存在一些共通点，比如水稻种植的重要性和市场准入，研究结果可能适用于亚洲其他地区。</u>\n\n-**commonalities**：<u>共同点。</u>  \n-**market access**：<u>市场准入、进入市场的能力。</u> \n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">regardless of </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">transferability</font>, the study shows that what’s good for people may also be good for the environment.\n翻译: <u>而且无论其可迁移性如何，该研究都表明，对人有益的东西也可能对环境有益。</u>\n\n-**regardless of…**：<u>不管、无论。</u>  \n-**transferability**：<u>可迁移性、可推广性。</u> \n\n---\n\nEven if this program didn’t reduce poverty, Ferraro says, “the value of the avoided deforestation just for carbon dioxide emissions alone is more than the program costs.”\n翻译: <u>Ferraro 说，即使这个项目没有减少贫困，“仅就二氧化碳排放而言，避免森林砍伐所带来的价值就超过了该项目的成本。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nAs a historian who’s always searching for the text or the image that makes us re-evaluate the past, I’ve <font color=\"#ffff00\">become preoccupied with</font> looking for photographs that show our Victorian ancestors smiling.\n翻译: <u>作为一名总是在寻找能让我们重新评价过去的文本或图像的历史学家，我开始格外专注于寻找那些展现我们维多利亚时代祖先微笑的照片。</u>\n\n-**become preoccupied with…**：<u>变得全神贯注于……，心里一直想着……。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">What better way</font> to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> shatter</font> the image of <font color=\"#ffff00\">19th-century prudery</font>?\n翻译: <u>还有什么更好的方式来打破 19 世纪拘谨守礼的形象呢？</u>\n\n-<u>完整版是 **What better way is there to shatter…?**</u>  \n<u>没有比这更好的方式了。</u>  \n<u>这是一种反问，表达强烈肯定。</u>\n-**shatter**：<u>打碎、彻底打破。</u>  \n-**19th-century prudery**：19 <u>世纪的道德拘谨、假正经、过分保守。</u>  \n\n---\n\nI’ve found <font color=\"#ffff00\">quite a few</font>, and — since I started posting them on Twitter — they have been causing <font color=\"#ffff00\">quite a stir</font>.\n翻译: <u>我已经找到了不少，而且自从我开始在 Twitter 上发布它们以来，它们已经引起了相当大的轰动。</u>\n\n-**quite a few**：<u>相当多、不少。</u>\n-**quite a stir**：<u>很大反响、轰动、热议。</u>  \n\n---\n\nPeople have been surprised to see evidence that Victorians had fun and could, <font color=\"#ffff00\">and did, laugh.</font>\n翻译: <u>人们惊讶地看到证据表明，维多利亚时代的人也会享乐，也能够并且确实会大笑。</u>\n\n-**and did laugh**：<u>而且确实笑了。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey are <font color=\"#ffff00\">noting</font> that the Victorians suddenly seem to become <font color=\"#ffff00\">more human</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">as </font>the hundred-or-so years/that separate us /fade away /through our common experience of laughter.\n翻译: <u>他们注意到，随着把我们隔开的约一百年岁月通过共同的笑声体验逐渐消退，维多利亚时代的人似乎突然变得更有人情味了。</u>\n\n-**note**：<u>注意到、指出。  noting 看起来有点不好辨认</u>\n-**more human**：<u>更有人性、更真实、更亲近。</u>  \n-**as**：<u>随着。</u>  \n<u>看到这些笑容后，人们发现维多利亚人一下子变得更真实、更亲近；笑这种共同体验让我们和他们之间一百多年的距离仿佛消失了。</u>\n\n\n---\n\nOf course, I need to <font color=\"#ffff00\">concede</font> that my collection of “Smiling Victorians”<font color=\"#ffff00\"> makes up</font> only a tiny percentage of the vast catalogue of <font color=\"#ffff00\">photographic portraiture</font> created between 1840 and 1900.\n翻译: <u>当然，我需要承认，我收集的“微笑的维多利亚人”只占 1840 年至 1900 年间创作的庞大摄影肖像目录中的极小一部分。</u>\n\n-**concede**：<u>承认，尤其是承认对自己观点不利或需要补充的事实。</u>  \n-**make up**：<u>构成、占。</u>  \n-**photographic portraiture**：<u>摄影肖像作品。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe majority of which show sitters posing miserably and stiffly in front of painted backdrops, or <font color=\"#ffff00\">staring</font> absently into the <font color=\"#ffff00\">middle distance</font>.\n翻译: <u>其中大多数照片显示，入镜者在绘制的背景前痛苦而僵硬地摆姿势，或者茫然地望向中景。</u>\n\n-**staring**：<u>凝视。</u>  \n-**middle distance**：<u>中景距离，不是看镜头，也不是看远方，而是目光空洞地看向某处。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHow do we explain this trend?\n翻译: <u>我们如何解释这种趋势呢？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDuring the 1840s and 1850s, in the early days of photography, <font color=\"#ffff00\">exposure times </font>were notoriously long.\n翻译: <u>在 1840 年代和 1850 年代，也就是摄影术早期，曝光时间是出了名地长。</u>\n\n-**exposure times**：<u>曝光时间。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe daguerreotype photographic method, producing an image on a silvered copper plate, could take several minutes to complete, resulting in blurred images as sitters shifted position or adjusted their limbs.\n翻译: <u>银版摄影法会在镀银铜板上生成图像，可能需要数分钟才能完成，结果当入镜者改变姿势或调整四肢时，图像就会变得模糊。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe thought of holding a fixed grin /as the camera performed /its magical duties/ was <font color=\"#ffff00\">too much to contemplate</font>, and so a <font color=\"#ffff00\">non-committal</font> blank stare became the <font color=\"#ffff00\">norm</font>.\n翻译: <u>想到要在相机执行其神奇职责时一直保持固定的咧嘴笑，实在令人难以承受，于是一种不表态的空洞凝视便成为常态。</u>\n\n-**too much to contemplate**：<u>让人不愿考虑、难以想象、负担太大。</u>  \n-**non-committal**：<u>不表态的、不明确表达情绪的。</u>  \n-**became the norm**：<u>成为常态。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut exposure times were much quicker by the 1880s, and the introduction of the Box Brownie and other portable cameras meant that, <font color=\"#ffff00\">(though slow by today’s digital standards,) </font>the exposure was almost instantaneous.\n翻译: <u>但到 1880 年代，曝光时间已经快得多，而 Box Brownie 及其他便携式相机的引入意味着，尽管按今天的数字标准来看仍然很慢，曝光几乎已经是瞬间完成的。</u>\n\n-<u>这种前后都有逗号的插入语最烦,直接忽略,不要影响到前后链接</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Spontaneous smiles</font> were relatively easy to capture by the 1890s, so we must look elsewhere for an explanation of why Victorians still hesitated to smile.\n翻译: <u>到 1890 年代，自然流露的微笑已相对容易捕捉，因此我们必须从别处寻找维多利亚时代的人仍然迟疑于微笑的原因。</u>\n\n-**spontaneous smiles**：<u>自然的、自发的微笑。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOne explanation might be the l<font color=\"#ffff00\">oss of dignity</font> displayed through a<font color=\"#ffff00\"> cheesy grin.</font>\n翻译: <u>一种解释可能是，露出俗气的咧嘴笑会有失尊严。</u>\n\n-**loss of dignity**：<u>尊严的丧失。   这里翻译成庄重</u>\n-**cheesy grin**：<u>傻笑、夸张而不自然的咧嘴笑。</u>  \n\n---\n\n“Nature gave us lips to conceal our teeth,” <font color=\"#ffff00\">ran</font> one popular Victorian saying, alluding to the fact that before the birth of <font color=\"#ffff00\">proper dentistry,</font> mouths were often in a shocking state of hygiene.\n翻译: <u>“大自然赐予我们嘴唇，是为了遮住我们的牙齿，”维多利亚时代一句流行说法这样说，它暗指在真正牙科诞生之前，口腔卫生状况常常令人震惊。</u>\n\n-**ran** <u>在这里不是“跑”，而是“写道、说道、措辞是”。</u>  \n<u>类似：**The saying ran…**</u>  \n-**before the birth of proper dentistry**：<u>在正规牙科诞生之前。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">flashing</font> set of healthy and clean, regular “pearly whites” was a rare sight in Victorian society, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">preserve</font> of the super-rich.\n翻译: <u>在维多利亚社会中，一口健康、洁净、整齐而闪亮的“珍珠白”牙齿很少见，是超级富人的专属。</u>\n\n-fashing**：<u>闪亮显露的。</u>  \n-**preserve** <u>在这里不是“保护区”的普通意思，而是“专属领域、只有某类人享有的东西”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">even then</font>, dental hygiene was not guaranteed.\n翻译: <u>即便如此，牙齿卫生也无法保证。</u>\n\n-**even then**：<u>即使在那种情况下。</u>  \n-<u>即使是富人，也不一定能拥有良好的牙齿卫生。</u>\n\n---\n\nA toothy grin, especially when there were gaps or blackened teeth, <font color=\"#ffff00\">lacked class</font>.\n翻译: <u>露齿而笑，尤其是在有牙缝或牙齿发黑的情况下，显得缺乏体面。</u>\n\n-**lack**：<u>缺乏。</u>  \n**class**：<u>格调、体面、上流气质。  缺乏格调</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Drunks</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">tramps</font> and music hall performers might gurn and grin with a smile as wide as Lewis Carroll’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">gum-exposing</font> Cheshire Cat, but it was not a <font color=\"#ffff00\">becoming </font>look for <font color=\"#ffff00\">properly bred persons</font>.\n翻译: <u>醉汉、流浪汉和音乐厅演员也许会像 Lewis Carroll 笔下露出牙龈的 Cheshire Cat 那样，做鬼脸并咧嘴大笑，但这对出身良好的人来说并不是得体的样子。</u>\n\n-**drunks**：<u>醉汉。</u>  \n-**tramps**：<u>流浪汉。</u>\n-**gum-exposing**：<u>露出牙龈的。</u>  \n-**becoming**：<u>合适的、得体的、好看的。</u>  \n-**properly bred persons**：<u>有良好教养的人、出身体面的人。</u>  \n\n---\n\nEven Mark Twain, a man who enjoyed a hearty laugh, said that when it came to photographic portraits there could be “nothing more <font color=\"#ffff00\">damning</font> than a silly, foolish smile fixed forever”.\n翻译: <u>即便是喜欢开怀大笑的 Mark Twain 也说，当涉及摄影肖像时，可能“没有什么比一个愚蠢、傻气的微笑被永远定格更具毁灭性了”。</u>\n\n-**damning**：<u>毁灭性的、极其不利的。</u>  \n\n---\n\n第四篇阅读\n\nFrom the early days of broadband, <font color=\"#ffff00\">advocates for consumers</font> and web-based companies worried that the cable and phone companies selling broadband connections had the power and <font color=\"#ffff00\">incentive</font> to favor affiliated websites over their rivals’.\n翻译: <u>从宽带早期开始，消费者权益倡导者和网络公司就担心，销售宽带连接的有线电视公司和电话公司拥有权力和动机去偏袒关联网站，而不是其竞争对手的网站。</u>\n\n-**advocates for consumers**：<u>消费者权益倡导者。  for 表示补充说明,构成一个完整的成分 容易忽略掉</u> \n-**incentive**：<u>动机、利益驱动。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nThat’s why there has been such a strong demand for rules that would prevent broadband providers from picking winners and losers online,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> preserving</font> the freedom and innovation that have been the lifeblood of the Internet.\n翻译: <u>这就是为什么人们一直强烈要求制定规则，以防止宽带提供商在网上挑选赢家和输家，从而维护一直是互联网命脉的自由与创新。</u>\n\n-**preserve**：<u>保护、维护。</u>  \n\n---\n\nYet that demand has been almost impossible to fill — in part because of <font color=\"#ffff00\">pushback</font> from broadband providers, <font color=\"#ffff00\">anti-regulatory conservatives</font> and the courts.\n翻译: <u>然而，这种需求几乎不可能得到满足，部分原因在于宽带提供商、反监管保守派以及法院的阻力。</u>\n\n-**pushback**：<u>反对、抵制、阻力。</u>  \n-**anti-regulatory conservatives**：<u>反监管的保守派人士。</u>  \n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal appeals court</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">weighed in</font> again Tuesday, but instead of providing a badly needed <font color=\"#ffff00\">resolution</font>, it only <font color=\"#ffff00\">prolonged</font> the fight.\n翻译: <u>一家联邦上诉法院周二再次介入此事，但它没有提供迫切需要的解决方案，反而只是延长了这场争斗。</u>\n\n-**federal appeals court**：<u>联邦上诉法院。</u>  \n-**weigh in**：<u>发表意见、介入争论、作出判断。</u>  \n-**provide a resolution**：<u>提供解决方案。</u>\n-prolonged <u>延长</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">At issue</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">before the U.S. Court</font> of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit was the <font color=\"#ffff00\">latest take</font> of the Federal Communications Commission, or FCC, on net neutrality, adopted on a <font color=\"#ffff00\">party-line vote</font> in 2017.\n翻译: <u>摆在美国哥伦比亚特区巡回上诉法院面前的问题，是联邦通信委员会（FCC）关于网络中立性的最新方案，该方案于 2017 年按党派路线投票通过。</u>\n\n-**At issue**：<u>争议焦点是、问题所在是。</u>  \n-**before the court**：<u>在法院面前，也就是由法院审理。</u>  \n-**U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit**：<u>美国哥伦比亚特区巡回上诉法院。   for 表示补充说明非常常见 用来**补充说明/限定名称、身份、职责范围或所属对象**。</u>\n-**latest take**：<u>最新看法、最新立场、最新方案。</u>\n-**net neutrality**：<u>网络中立。</u>\n-**party-line vote**：<u>按党派立场投票，即共和党和民主党基本按党派分裂投票。</u>\n<u>直译：摆在美国哥伦比亚特区巡回上诉法院面前的问题，是联邦通信委员会 FCC 对网络中立的最新立场，该立场于 2017 年按党派路线投票通过。</u>  \n\n\n<u>其它介词也有这种情况 比如</u>\nto\n<u>不一定是“到”，也可以表示“针对、对于、与……相配”</u>\n\nin\n<u>不一定是“在……里面”，也可以表示领域、状态、方面</u>\nprogress in science\n翻译: <u>科学的进步</u>\n<u>科学领域的进展</u>\n\non\n<u>不一定是“在……上面”，也可以表示主题、依据、影响对象</u>\ntax on imports\n翻译: <u>进口税</u>\n<u>进口税</u>\n\nby\n<u>不一定是“通过”，也可以表示作者、执行者、标准、截止时间</u>\njudged by modern standards\n翻译: <u>以现代标准来评判</u>\n<u>按现代标准判断</u>\n\nwith\n<u>不一定是“和”，也可以表示具有、使用、伴随、原因</u>\nproblems with the system\n翻译: <u>该系统存在的问题</u>\n<u>系统方面的问题</u>\ntremble with fear\n翻译: <u>因恐惧而颤抖</u>\n<u>因害怕而发抖</u>\n\nagainst\n<u>不一定是“反对”，也可以表示防范、对照、靠着</u>\ncheck the data against the original records\n翻译: <u>根据原始记录核对数据</u>\n<u>对照原始记录检查数据</u>\n\n<u>可以做一次介词训练</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Republican-penned <font color=\"#ffff00\">order</font> not only eliminated the strict net neutrality rules the FCC <font color=\"#ffff00\">had adopted</font> when it had a Democratic majority in 2015, but rejected the commission’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">authority</font> to require broadband providers to <font color=\"#ffff00\">do much of anything.</font>\n翻译: <u>这项由共和党人起草的命令，不仅废除了 FCC 在 2015 年由民主党占多数时所采纳的严格网络中立规则，而且否定了该委员会要求宽带提供商做任何实质性事情的权力。</u>\n\n-**order**：<u>行政命令、监管命令，指 FCC 的政策文件。</u>  \n-**had adopted**：<u>过去已经采纳。  翻译成曾经采纳的</u>\n-**authority**：<u>权力、权限。</u>  \n-**do much of anything**：<u>做任何实质性的事情，带有“几乎什么也不能要求”的语气。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe order also declared that state and local governments couldn’t regulate broadband providers either.\n翻译: <u>该命令还宣布，州政府和地方政府也不能监管宽带提供商。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe commission argued that other agencies would protect against anti-competitive behavior, such as a broadband-providing conglomerate like AT&T favoring its own video-streaming service <font color=\"#ffff00\">at the expense of </font>Netflix and Apple TV.\n翻译: <u>该委员会辩称，其他机构会防范反竞争行为，例如像 AT&T 这样提供宽带服务的集团公司，为了自身利益偏袒自己的视频流媒体服务，而损害 Netflix 和 Apple TV 的利益。</u>\n\n-**at the expense of…**：<u>以牺牲……为代价。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nYet the FCC also ended the investigations of broadband providers that<font color=\"#ffff00\"> imposed data caps on</font> their rivals’ streaming services but not their own.\n翻译: <u>然而，FCC 还终止了对一些宽带提供商的调查；这些提供商对竞争对手的流媒体服务施加数据上限，却不对自己的服务这样做。</u>\n\n-**impose data caps on…**：<u>对……施加数据上限。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nOn Tuesday, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">appeals court</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">unanimously</font> upheld the 2017 order <font color=\"#ffff00\">deregulating</font> broadband providers, citing a Supreme Court ruling from 2005 that upheld a similarly deregulatory move.\n翻译: <u>周二，上诉法院一致维持了 2017 年放松对宽带提供商监管的命令，并援引了最高法院 2005 年的一项裁决，该裁决支持了一项类似的放松监管举措。</u>\n\n-**appeals court**：<u>上诉法院。</u>  \n-**unanimously**：<u>一致地、全体同意。</u>  \n-**deregulate**：<u>解除监管、放松监管。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut Judge Patricia Millett<font color=\"#ffff00\"> rightly</font> argued<font color=\"#ffff00\"> in a concurring opinion</font> that “the result <font color=\"#ffff00\">is unhinged from</font> the realities of modern broadband service,” and said Congress or the Supreme Court could intervene to “avoid <font color=\"#ffff00\">trapping</font> Internet regulation i<font color=\"#ffff00\">n </font>technological <font color=\"#ffff00\">anachronism.</font>”\n翻译: <u>但 Patricia Millett 法官在一份协同意见中正确地指出，“这一结果脱离了现代宽带服务的现实”，并表示国会或最高法院可以介入，以“避免将互联网监管困在技术时代错位之中”。</u>\n\n-**rightly**：<u>正确地，作者明确赞同她的看法。</u>  \n-**concurring opinion**：<u>协同意见，即法官同意判决结果，但用不同理由或补充观点写出的意见。</u>  \n-**unhinged from…**：<u>脱离……、与……不接轨。</u>  \n-**trap A in B**：<u>把 A 困在 B 中。</u>  \n-**technological anachronism**：<u>技术时代错位 / 过时技术观念。  这个都能考,那说明每个词都不能忽略啊,包括上面的 hinge  连每一个意思都不能忽略</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the meantime, the court <font color=\"#ffff00\">threw out</font> the FCC’s attempt to block all state rules on net neutrality, <font color=\"#ffff00\">while</font> preserving the commission’s power to <font color=\"#ffff00\">preempt</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> individual state laws</font> that undermine its order.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，法院驳回了 FCC 试图阻止所有州级网络中立规则的做法，但保留了该委员会优先否决那些削弱其命令的个别州法律的权力。</u>\n\n-**throw out**：<u>驳回、否决。</u> \n-**while preserving**：<u>同时保留。</u>  \n-**preempt**：<u>优先取代、抢先排除，使州法无效。</u>  \n-**individual state laws**：<u>个别州法律。</u> \n-**its order**：FCC <u>的 2017 order。</u>  \n<u>同时，法院否定了 FCC 全面禁止各州网络中立法规的做法；但也保留了 FCC 在个案中阻止某些与其命令冲突的州法的权力。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat means more battles like the one now going on between the <font color=\"#ffff00\">Justice Department</font> and California, which <font color=\"#ffff00\">enacted</font> a tough net neutrality law <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the wake of </font>the FCC’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">abdication.</font>\n翻译: <u>这意味着会出现更多类似司法部与加利福尼亚州之间正在进行的争斗；在 FCC 放弃职责之后，加州制定了一部严格的网络中立法。</u>\n\n-**Justice Department**：<u>美国司法部。</u>  \n-**enacted**：<u>制定、颁布。</u>  \n-**in the wake of…**：<u>在……之后、由于……之后。</u>  \n-**abdication**：<u>退位、放弃职责。</u>\n<u>这意味着未来还会出现更多类似司法部起诉加州的法律战；加州正是在 FCC 放弃网络中立监管后，制定了强有力的州级网络中立法。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe endless legal battles and <font color=\"#ffff00\">back-and-forth</font> at the FCC <font color=\"#ffff00\">cry out for</font> Congress to act.\n翻译: <u>无休止的法律争斗以及 FCC 内部的反复拉锯迫切需要国会采取行动。</u>\n\n-**back-and-forth**：<u>来回反复、摇摆不定。</u>  \n-**cry out for…**：<u>迫切需要、大声呼吁。</u>  \n<u>直译：无休止的法律斗争和 FCC 的反复摇摆迫切呼吁国会行动。</u>  \n<u>地道意译：围绕网络中立的长期诉讼和 FCC 政策反复，已经清楚表明：国会必须出手立法。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt needs to give the commission explicit authority <font color=\"#ffff00\">once and for all</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">bar broadband providers</font> from <font color=\"#ffff00\">meddling in </font>the <font color=\"#ffff00\">traffic on their network</font> and to create clear rules protecting openness and innovation online.\n翻译: <u>国会需要一劳永逸地赋予该委员会明确权力，禁止宽带提供商干预其网络上的流量，并制定明确规则，保护网络上的开放性和创新。</u>\n\n-**once and for all**：<u>一劳永逸地、彻底地。</u> \n-**bar A from doing B**：<u>禁止 A 做 B。</u>  \n-**meddle in…**：<u>干预、插手、操纵。</u>  \n-**traffic on their network**：<u>其网络上的流量。</u>  \n\n---\n\n"},{"courseId":"english1","courseTitle":"英语一","id":"year-2022","year":"2022","title":"2022 年英语一","fileName":"2022.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/挖空完复习版本/2022.md","content":"People often complain that plastics are too durable.\n翻译: <u>人们常常抱怨塑料太耐用了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWater bottles, shopping bags, and other trash <font color=\"#ffff00\">litter</font> the planet, from <font color=\"#ffff00\">Mount Everest </font>to the Mariana Trench, because plastics are everywhere and don’t break down easily.\n翻译: <u>水瓶、购物袋和其他垃圾遍布地球，从珠穆朗玛峰到马里亚纳海沟，都是因为塑料无处不在，而且不易分解。</u>\n\n-**litter**：<u>乱扔、使……布满垃圾。</u>  \n-**Mount Everest**：<u>珠穆朗玛峰，地球最高处。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nBut some plastic materials change over time.\n翻译: <u>但有些塑料材料会随着时间发生变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey crack and frizzle.\n翻译: <u>它们会开裂并卷曲变脆。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey “<font color=\"#ffff00\">weep” out </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">additives</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们会“渗出”添加剂。</u>\n\n-**weep out**：<u>渗出、流出。   这里加引号，是比喻用法，好像塑料在“流泪”。</u>  \n-**additives**：<u>添加剂，比如增塑剂、稳定剂、染料等。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey melt into <font color=\"#ffff00\">sludge</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们会融化成污泥状物。</u>\n\n-**sludge**：<u>污泥、黏稠糊状物。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">All of which</font> creates huge headaches for institutions, such as museums, trying to preserve culturally important objects.\n翻译: <u>所有这些都给试图保存具有重要文化意义物品的机构，比如博物馆，制造了巨大的难题。</u>\n\n-all of which <u>所有这些情况</u>\n\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">variety</font> of plastic objects at risk is <font color=\"#ffff00\">dizzying</font>: early radios, avant-garde sculptures, celluloid animation stills from Disney films, the first artificial heart.\n翻译: <u>面临风险的塑料物品种类多得令人眼花缭乱：早期收音机、先锋派雕塑、迪士尼电影的赛璐珞动画剧照、第一颗人工心脏。</u>\n\n-**variety**：<u>种类、多样性。</u>  \n-**dizzying**：<u>令人眩晕的、令人眼花缭乱的。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Certain artifacts</font> are especially vulnerable because some pioneers in plastic art didn’t always know how to mix ingredients properly, says Thea van Oosten, a polymer chemist who, until retiring a few years ago, worked for decades at the Cultural Heritage Agency of the Netherlands, or RCE.\n翻译: <u>聚合物化学家 Thea van Oosten 说，某些文物尤其脆弱，因为一些塑料艺术的先驱并不总是知道如何正确混合原料；她在几年前退休之前，曾在荷兰文化遗产局，即 RCE，工作了数十年。</u>\n\n-**certain artifacts**：<u>某些人工制品 / 文物。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n“It’s like baking a cake: If you don’t have <font color=\"#ffff00\">exact amounts</font>, it goes wrong,” she says.\n翻译: <u>“这就像烤蛋糕：如果用量不精确，就会出问题，”她说。</u>\n\n-**exact amounts**：<u>精确的数量、比例。</u> \n-\n\n---\n\n“The object you make is already a time bomb.”\n翻译: <u>“你制作出来的物品本身就已经是一颗定时炸弹。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd sometimes, it’s not the artist’s fault.\n翻译: <u>而有时候，这并不是艺术家的错。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn the 1960s, the Italian artist Piero Gilardi began to create hundreds of bright, colorful foam pieces.\n翻译: <u>20 世纪 60 年代，意大利艺术家 Piero Gilardi 开始创作数百件明亮多彩的泡沫作品。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThose pieces included small <font color=\"#ffff00\">beds of roses</font> and other items <font color=\"#ffff00\">as well as</font> a few dozen “nature carpets” — large <font color=\"#ffff00\">rectangles</font> decorated with foam pumpkins, cabbages, and watermelons.\n翻译: <u>这些作品包括小片玫瑰花床和其他物品，以及几十件“自然地毯”——装饰着泡沫南瓜、卷心菜和西瓜的大矩形作品。</u>\n\n-**small beds of roses**：<u>小型玫瑰花坛。</u>  \n-**as well as**：<u>以及。</u>  \n-**large rectangles**：<u>大矩形。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHe wanted viewers to walk around on the carpets — which meant they had to be durable.\n翻译: <u>他希望观众在这些地毯上走动——这意味着它们必须耐用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, the polyurethane foam he used is inherently unstable.\n翻译: <u>不幸的是，他所使用的聚氨酯泡沫本质上并不稳定。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt’s especially vulnerable to <font color=\"#ffff00\">light damage</font>, and by the mid-1990s, Gilardi’s pumpkins, roses, and other figures were splitting and <font color=\"#ffff00\">crumbling</font>.\n翻译: <u>它尤其容易受到光损害，到 20 世纪 90 年代中期，Gilardi 的南瓜、玫瑰和其他造型已经开始裂开并碎裂。</u>\n\n-**light damage**：<u>光照损伤。</u>  \n-**crumble**：<u>碎裂、粉化、崩解。</u>  \n\n---\n\nMuseums locked some of them away in the dark.\n翻译: <u>博物馆把其中一些锁在黑暗中保存。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSo van Oosten and colleagues worked to preserve Gilardi’s sculptures.\n翻译: <u>因此，van Oosten 和同事们努力保存 Gilardi 的雕塑。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey i<font color=\"#ffff00\">nfused</font> some with stabilizing and <font color=\"#ffff00\">consolidating chemicals</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们给其中一些注入了稳定和加固用的化学物质。</u>\n\n-nfuse A with B**：<u>把 B 注入/渗入 A。</u>  \n-**consolidating chemicals**：<u>加固化学剂，用来增强脆弱材料结构。</u>\n-\n\n---\n\nVan Oosten calls those chemicals “<font color=\"#ffff00\">sunscreens</font>” because their goal was to prevent further light damage and rebuild worn polymer fibers.\n翻译: <u>Van Oosten 称这些化学物质为“防晒霜”，因为它们的目标是防止进一步的光损害，并重建磨损的聚合物纤维。</u>\n\n-**sunscreens**：<u>防晒霜。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nShe is proud that several sculptures have even gone on display again, albeit sometimes beneath protective cases.\n翻译: <u>她感到自豪的是，有几件雕塑甚至重新展出，尽管有时是在保护罩之下。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDespite success stories like van Oosten’s, preservation of plastics will likely get harder.\n翻译: <u>尽管有像 van Oosten 这样的成功案例，塑料的保存很可能会变得更加困难。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOld objects continue to deteriorate.\n翻译: <u>旧物品会继续劣化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWorse, <font color=\"#ffff00\">biodegradable</font> plastics, designed to disintegrate, are increasingly common.\n翻译: <u>更糟的是，旨在分解的可生物降解塑料正变得越来越常见。</u>\n\n-**biodegradable plastics**：<u>可生物降解塑料。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nAnd more <font color=\"#ffff00\">is at stake</font> here than <font color=\"#ffff00\">individual objects.</font>\n翻译: <u>而这里利害攸关的不只是单个物品。</u>\n\n-**be at stake**：<u>处于风险中、利害攸关。</u>  \n-**individual objects**：<u>单个物品。</u>  \n\n---\n\nJoana Lia Ferreira, an assistant professor of conservation and restoration at the NOVA School of Science and Technology, notes that archaeologists <font color=\"#ffff00\">first</font> defined the <font color=\"#ffff00\">great material ages</font> of human history — <font color=\"#ffff00\">Stone Age</font>, Iron Age, and so on — after <font color=\"#ffff00\">examining</font> artifacts in museums.\n翻译: <u>NOVA 科学与技术学院保护与修复助理教授 Joana Lia Ferreira 指出，考古学家最初是在考察博物馆中的文物之后，定义了人类历史上的重要材料时代——石器时代、铁器时代等等。</u>\n\n-first <u>最初的</u> \n-**great material ages**：<u>重要材料时代。</u>  \n-**Stone Age**：<u>石器时代。</u>  \n-**examining**：<u>检查、研究</u>\nFerreira <u>提醒说，人类历史中的“石器时代”“铁器时代”等概念，正是考古学家通过研究博物馆收藏的材料文物后形成的。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe now live in an age of plastic, she says.\n翻译: <u>她说，我们现在生活在一个塑料时代。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“And what we decide to collect today, what we decide to preserve…will have a strong impact on how in the future we’ll be seen.”\n翻译: <u>“而我们今天决定收藏什么，决定保存什么……将对未来人们如何看待我们产生强烈影响。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<u>一般情况下,题目提问的顺序就是按照文章的顺序下来的,第二题不会到太下面,目前没有碰到太下面的情况,找答案的时候根据题目的位置去文章对应位置找</u>\n\n1. Van Oosten believes that certain plastic objects are  B →C  \n2. \nshape <u>指的只是形状啊 不是材料本身.....</u>\n[A]immune to decay.\n\n[B]improperly shaped.\n\n[C]inherently flawed.\n\n[D]complex in structure.\n\n\n第二篇阅读\n\n\n\n\nAs <font color=\"#ffff00\">the latest crop </font>of students pen their undergraduate application form and weigh up their options, it may be worth considering <font color=\"#ffff00\">just how</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">point, purpose and value of a degree</font> has changed and what Generation Z need to consider as they start the third stage of their educational journey.\n翻译: <u>当最新一批学生填写本科申请表并权衡自己的选择时，或许值得考虑的是，学位的意义、目的和价值究竟发生了怎样的变化，以及 Z 世代在开启教育旅程的第三阶段时需要考虑什么。</u>\n\n-**the latest crop of students**：<u>最新一批学生。  **crop** 本义是“作物”，这里比喻“一批人”。</u> \n-**just how…**：<u>究竟如何、到底怎样。</u>  \n-**the point, purpose and value of a degree**：<u>学位的意义、目的和价值。</u>\n-<u>当新一批学生准备申请大学、权衡未来选择时，我们有必要重新思考：大学学位如今到底还有什么意义和价值？Z 世代在迈入高等教育阶段前，又应该考虑哪些问题？</u>\n\n---\n\nMillennials were told that if you did well in school, got a decent degree, you would <font color=\"#ffff00\">be set up for life.</font>\n翻译: <u>千禧一代曾被告知，只要你在学校表现好，拿到一个体面的学位，就会一生无忧。</u>\n\n-**be set up for life**：<u>一辈子有保障、人生从此稳了。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut that promise has <font color=\"#ffff00\">been found wanting</font>.\n翻译: <u>但这一承诺已被证明并不令人满意。</u>\n\n-**be found wanting**：<u>被发现有缺陷、不够好、不符合期待。</u> \n\n---\n\nAs degrees became universal, they became devalued.\n翻译: <u>随着学位变得普遍，它们也贬值了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEducation was no longer a secure route of social mobility.\n翻译: <u>教育不再是实现社会流动的可靠途径。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nToday, 28 per cent of graduates in the UK are in n<font color=\"#ffff00\">on-graduate roles</font>, a percentage which is double the average among the <font color=\"#ffff00\">OECD countries</font>.\n翻译: <u>如今，英国 28% 的毕业生从事的是不要求毕业生学历的岗位，这一比例是 OECD 国家平均水平的两倍。</u>\n\n-**non-graduate roles**：<u>不要求大学学位的岗位。</u>  \n-**OECD countries**：<u>经济合作与发展组织国家，通常是发达经济体。</u> \n\n---\n\nThis is not to say that there is no point in getting a degree, but rather stress that a degree is not for everyone, that the switch from classroom to <font color=\"#ffff00\">lecture hall</font> is <font color=\"#ffff00\">not an inevitable one</font> and that other options are available.\n翻译: <u>这并不是说获得学位没有意义，而是要强调，学位并不适合每个人，从课堂到讲堂的转变并非不可避免，而且还有其他选择。</u>\n\n-**This is not to say…, but rather to stress…**<u>这里省略了 **to**。  不是 而是</u>\n-**lecture hall**：<u>大学讲堂。</u> \n-**not an inevitable one**：<u>不是必然的一步。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Thankfully,</font> there are signs that this is already happening, with Generation Z seeking to learn from their millennial predecessors, even if parents and teachers <font color=\"#ffff00\">tend to be</font> still set in the degree mindset.\n翻译: <u>值得庆幸的是，已有迹象表明这种情况正在发生，Z 世代正试图从他们的千禧一代前辈身上吸取经验，尽管父母和老师往往仍然固守学位思维。</u>\n\n-thankfully <u>值得庆幸的是。</u> \n-**tend to be**：<u>往往是。</u>  \n\n---\n\nEmployers have long seen the advantages of hiring <font color=\"#ffff00\">school leavers</font> who often prove themselves to be more <font color=\"#ffff00\">committed</font> and loyal employees than graduates.\n翻译: <u>长期以来，雇主已经看到了雇用中学毕业生的优势，这些人往往证明自己比大学毕业生更投入、更忠诚。</u>\n\n-**school leavers**：<u>离校生，通常指中学毕业后没有上大学、直接进入工作或培训的人。</u>\n-**committed**：<u>投入的、有责任感的。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Many too</font> are seeing the advantages of <font color=\"#ffff00\">scrapping</font> a degree requirement for certain roles.\n翻译: <u>许多雇主也看到了取消某些职位学位要求的优势。</u>\n\n-**Many** <u>这里指 many employers。</u>  \n-**too**：<u>也。</u>  \n-**scrap**：<u>废除、取消。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For</font> those for whom a degree is the desired route, consider that this <font color=\"#ffff00\">may well be </font><font color=\"#ffff00\">the first of many.</font>\n翻译: <u>对于那些把学位视为理想路径的人来说，要考虑到这很可能只是许多学位中的第一个。</u>\n\n-For <u>对于</u> \n-**may well be**：<u>很可能是。</u>  \n-**the first of many**：<u>许多个中的第一个。</u>  \n-<u>如果你确实想读大学，也要明白：本科学位可能只是长期学习道路上的第一步，而不是终点。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn this age of <font color=\"#ffff00\">generalists</font>,<font color=\"#ffff00\"> it pays to</font> have specific knowledge or skills.\n翻译: <u>在这个通才时代，拥有具体的知识或技能是有益的。</u>\n\n-**generalists**：<u>通才、什么都懂一点的人。</u>  \n-**it pays to do**：<u>做某事有回报、值得做。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Postgraduates </font>now earn 40 per cent more than graduates.\n翻译: <u>如今，研究生的收入比本科毕业生高 40%。</u>\n\n-**Postgraduates**：<u>研究生学历者 / 研究生毕业生。</u>  \n\n---\n\nWhen more and more of us have a degree, it makes sense to have two.\n翻译: <u>当我们中越来越多人拥有一个学位时，拥有两个学位就合乎情理。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is unlikely that Generation Z will be done with education at 18 or 21; they will need to be constantly upskilling throughout their career to stay <font color=\"#ffff00\">employable</font>.\n翻译: <u>Z 世代不太可能在 18 岁或 21 岁时就结束教育；他们需要在整个职业生涯中不断提升技能，以保持就业能力。</u>\n\n-**employable**：<u>具有就业能力的、有竞争力的。</u>  \n\n---\n\nIt has been estimated that this generation, due to the pressures of technology, the wish for personal fulfilment and desire for diversity, will work for 17 different employers over the course of their working life and have five different careers.\n翻译: <u>据估计，由于技术压力、对个人满足感的渴望以及对多样性的追求，这一代人在其职业生涯中将为 17 个不同雇主工作，并拥有 5 种不同职业。</u>\n\n-\n\n---\n\nEducation, and not just knowledge gained on campus, will be a core part of Generation Z’s career <font color=\"#ffff00\">trajectory</font>.\n翻译: <u>教育，而且不仅仅是在校园里获得的知识，将成为 Z 世代职业轨迹的核心组成部分。</u>\n\n-**career trajectory**：<u>职业轨迹、职业发展路径。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nOlder generations often talk about their degree in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">present and personal tense</font>: “I am a geographer” or “I am a classicist”.\n翻译: <u>老一辈人常常用现在时和个人身份的语气谈论自己的学位：“我是一名地理学者”或“我是一名古典学者”。</u>\n\n-**in the present and personal tense**：<u>用现在的、个人身份式的表达。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nTheir sons or daughters would never say such a thing; it’s as if they already know that their degree won’t define them i<font color=\"#ffff00\">n the same way</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们的儿子或女儿绝不会这样说；仿佛他们已经知道，自己的学位不会以同样的方式定义他们。</u>\n\n-**in the same way**：<u>以同样方式。</u>  \n-<u>直译：他们的儿子或女儿绝不会说这样的话；这好像他们已经知道，他们的学位不会以同样的方式定义他们。</u>  \n\n---\n\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Enlightening</font>, challenging, <font color=\"#ffff00\">stimulating</font>, fun.\n翻译: <u>启发性、挑战性、刺激性、有趣。</u>\n\n-Enlightening <u>启发性的</u>\n-stimulating <u>令人兴奋的</u>\n\n---\n\nThese were some of the words that Nature readers used to describe their experience of art-science collaborations in a series of articles <font color=\"#ffff00\">on partnerships </font>between artists and researchers.\n翻译: <u>这些是 Nature 读者在一系列关于艺术家与研究人员合作关系的文章中，用来描述他们艺术与科学合作经历的一些词语。</u>\n\n-**partnerships**：<u>合作关系。</u>  \n-\n\n---\n\nNearly 40% of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">roughly 350 people</font> who <font color=\"#ffff00\">responded</font> to an <font color=\"#ffff00\">accompanying poll </font>said they had collaborated with artists; and almost all said they would consider doing so in future.\n翻译: <u>在约 350 名回应随文民调的人中，近 40% 表示他们曾与艺术家合作；几乎所有人都表示，未来会考虑这样做。</u>\n\n-**roughly 350 people**：<u>约 350 人。</u>  \n-**responded to**：<u>回应。</u>  \n-**an accompanying poll**：<u>随文章一起进行的调查。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSuch an <font color=\"#ffff00\">encouraging result</font> is not surprising.\n翻译: <u>这样令人鼓舞的结果并不令人意外。</u>\n\n-**encouraging result**：<u>令人鼓舞的结果。</u>  \n\n---\n\nScientists are increasingly <font color=\"#ffff00\">seeking out</font> visual artists to help them communicate their work to new audiences.\n翻译: <u>科学家们越来越多地寻求视觉艺术家的帮助，以便把他们的工作传达给新的受众。</u>\n\n-**seek out**：<u>主动寻找、寻求。</u>\n-\n\n\n---\n\n“Artists help scientists reach a broader audience and make emotional connections that enhance learning,” one <font color=\"#ffff00\">respondent</font> said.\n翻译: <u>“艺术家帮助科学家触及更广泛的受众，并建立能增强学习效果的情感联系，”一位受访者说。</u>\n\n-**respondent**：<u>调查回应者、受访者。</u>  \n\n---\n\nOne example of how artists and scientists have together <font color=\"#ffff00\">rocked the scenes </font>came last month when the <font color=\"#ffff00\">Sydney Symphony Orchestra</font> performed a <font color=\"#ffff00\">reworked version</font> of Antonio Vivaldi’s The Four Seasons.\n翻译: <u>上个月，悉尼交响乐团演奏了 Antonio Vivaldi 的《四季》的改编版本，这就是艺术家和科学家如何共同震动舞台的一个例子。</u>\n\n-**rocked the scenes**：<u>搅动场面、震撼领域、带来轰动。</u>  \n-**Sydney Symphony Orchestra**：<u>悉尼交响乐团。</u>  \n-**a reworked version**：<u>重新改编的版本。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThey reimagined the 300-year-old <font color=\"#ffff00\">score</font> by <font color=\"#ffff00\">injecting</font> the latest climate prediction data for each season — provided by Monash University’s Climate Change Communication Research Hub.\n翻译: <u>他们通过注入每个季节的最新气候预测数据，重新构想了这部已有 300 年历史的乐谱；这些数据由 Monash University 的气候变化传播研究中心提供。</u>\n\n-**300-year-old score**：<u>有 300 年历史的乐谱。</u>  \n-**injecting**：<u>注入、加入。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe performance was a creative <font color=\"#ffff00\">call to action</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">ahead of</font> November’s United Nations Climate Change Conference in Glasgow, UK.\n翻译: <u>这场演出是在 11 月于英国格拉斯哥举行的联合国气候变化大会之前发出的一次富有创意的行动号召。</u>\n\n-**call to action**：<u>行动号召，呼吁人们采取行动。</u>  \n-**ahead of…**：<u>在……之前。</u>  \n\n-<u>这场演出是在 11 月英国格拉斯哥联合国气候变化大会之前的一次富有创意的行动号召。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut a <font color=\"#ffff00\">genuine partnership</font> must be a two-way street.\n翻译: <u>但真正的伙伴关系必须是一条双向通道。</u>\n\n-**genuine partnership**：<u>真正的合作关系。</u> \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Fewer artists than scientists </font>responded to the Nature poll; however, several respondents noted that artists <font color=\"#ffff00\">do not simply</font> assist scientists with their communication requirements.\n翻译: <u>回应 Nature 民调的艺术家少于科学家；然而，几位受访者指出，艺术家并不只是帮助科学家满足其传播需求。</u>\n\n-**Fewer A than B**：A <u>比 B 少。</u>  \n-**do not simply**：<u>并不只是。</u>  \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Nor</font> should their work be considered only as an object of study.\n翻译: <u>他们的作品也不应只被视为研究对象。</u>\n\n-**Nor**：<u>也不。</u>  \n-<u>他们的作品也不应只被看作研究对象。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">alliances</font> are most valuable when scientists and artists have a <font color=\"#ffff00\">shared stake</font> in a project, are able to<font color=\"#ffff00\"> jointly </font>design it and can critique each other’s work.\n翻译: <u>当科学家和艺术家在一个项目中拥有共同利益、能够共同设计项目并且能够批评彼此的作品时，这种联盟最有价值。</u>\n\n-**alliances**：<u>联盟、合作关系。</u>  \n-**shared stake**：<u>共同利害关系、共同投入、共同责任。</u>  \n-**jointly**：<u>共同地。</u>  \n\n---\n\nSuch an approach can both prompt new research as well as result in powerful art.\n翻译: <u>这样的方法既能促成新的研究，也能产生有影响力的艺术。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nMore than half a century ago, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology opened its Center for Advanced Visual Studies, or CAVS, to explore the role of technology in culture.\n翻译: <u>半个多世纪以前，麻省理工学院成立了高级视觉研究中心，即 CAVS，以探索技术在文化中的作用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe founders deliberately <font color=\"#ffff00\">focused their projects around</font> light — <font color=\"#ffff00\">hence</font> the “visual studies” in the name.\n翻译: <u>创始人有意将他们的项目聚焦于光——因此名称中有“视觉研究”这一说法。</u>\n\n-**focused their projects around…**：<u>把项目围绕……展开。</u>  \n-**hence**：<u>因此、由此。</u>  \n\n---\n\nLight was something that both artists and scientists had an interest in, and therefore could form the basis of collaboration.\n翻译: <u>光是艺术家和科学家都感兴趣的东西，因此可以构成合作的基础。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs science and technology progressed, and divided into more sub-disciplines, the centre was <font color=\"#ffff00\">simultaneously</font> l<font color=\"#ffff00\">ooking to a time</font> when leading researchers could also be artists, writers and poets, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">vice versa.</font>\n翻译: <u>随着科学技术进步，并分化为更多子学科，该中心同时也在展望这样一个时代：顶尖研究人员也可以是艺术家、作家和诗人，反之亦然。</u>\n\n-**simultaneously**：<u>同时。</u>  \n-**look to a time**：<u>期待/展望一个时代。</u>\n-**vice versa**：<u>反之亦然。</u> \n\n---\n\nNature’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">poll findings</font> suggest that this trend is <font color=\"#ffff00\">as strong as ever</font>, but, to make a collaboration work, both sides need to invest time, and embrace <font color=\"#ffff00\">surprise</font> and challenge.\n翻译: <u>《Nature》的民意调查结果表明，这一趋势一如既往地强劲，但是，要让合作奏效，双方都需要投入时间，并接受意外和挑战。</u>\n\n-**poll findings**：<u>调查发现、调查结果。</u>  \n-**as strong as ever**：<u>和以往一样强 / 一如既往地强。</u>  \n-**surprise and challenge**：<u>意外和挑战。   这里的是意外的意思</u>\n\n---\n\nThe reach of art-science <font color=\"#ffff00\">tie-ups</font> needs to go beyond the <font color=\"#ffff00\">necessary purpose</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">research communication</font>, and participants must not fall into the trap of stereotyping each other.\n翻译: <u>艺术与科学合作的影响范围需要超越研究传播这一必要目的，参与者也绝不能陷入相互刻板化的陷阱。</u>\n\n-**art-science tie-ups**：<u>艺术—科学合作。</u>  \n-**necessary purpose**：<u>必要目的。</u>  \n-**research communication**：<u>研究传播、科研传播。</u> \n\n---\n\nArtists and scientists <font color=\"#ffff00\">alike</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">are immersed in</font> discovery and invention, and challenge and critique are core to both, too.\n翻译: <u>艺术家和科学家同样都沉浸于发现与创造之中，而挑战与批评也是二者的核心。</u>\n\n-**alike** <u>放在名词后，意思是“同样地、两者都”。</u>  \n-**be immersed in…**：<u>沉浸于、深度参与。</u>  \n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">personal grievance provisions</font> of New Zealand’s Employment Relations Act 2000, or ERA, prevent an employer from firing an employee without good cause.\n翻译: <u>新西兰《2000年雇佣关系法》（Employment Relations Act 2000，简称 ERA）中的个人申诉条款，防止雇主在没有正当理由的情况下解雇雇员。</u>\n\n-**personal grievance provisions**：<u>个人申诉条款，指员工可以因不公正解雇等问题提出申诉的法律规定。</u>  \n-**good cause**：<u>充分理由、正当理由。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Instead</font>, dismissals must be<font color=\"#ffff00\"> justified</font>.\n翻译: <u>相反，解雇必须有正当理由。</u>\n\n-Instead <u>相反 / 而是。</u>\n-**justify**：<u>证明……正当、合理。</u> \n\n---\n\nEmployers must both show cause and act in a procedurally fair way.\n翻译: <u>雇主既必须说明理由，也必须以程序公平的方式行事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPersonal grievance procedures were designed to guard the jobs of ordinary workers from “unjustified dismissals”.\n翻译: <u>个人申诉程序旨在保护普通工人的工作，使其免遭“无正当理由解雇”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe premise was that the common law of contract lacked sufficient safeguards for workers against arbitrary conduct by management.\n翻译: <u>其前提是，合同普通法缺乏足够保障，无法保护工人免受管理层任意行为的侵害。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Long gone are the days</font> when a boss could simply give an employee <font color=\"#ffff00\">contractual notice.</font>\n翻译: <u>老板只需向雇员发出合同通知即可解雇的日子早已一去不复返。</u>\n\n- **Long gone**：<u>早已过去、不复存在。</u>  \n<u>这是一种强调表达，比普通 **The days are gone** 更有语气。</u>  \n- **contractual notice**：<u>合同通知期，比如提前几周通知解雇。</u>  \n\n---\n\nBut these provisions create difficulties for businesses when applied to highly paid managers and executives.\n翻译: <u>但当这些条款适用于高薪经理和高管时，就会给企业带来困难。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs countless boards and business owners will <font color=\"#ffff00\">attest</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">constraining firms</font> from firing poorly performing, high-earning managers is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">handbrake</font> on boosting productivity and overall performance.\n翻译: <u>正如无数董事会和企业主会证明的那样，限制公司解雇表现不佳的高收入经理，是提高生产率和整体绩效的一道阻碍。</u>\n\n- **attest**：<u>证明、证实。</u>  \n<u>这句话带有作者立场：企业管理者会同意这个观点。</u>\n- **constrain A from doing B**：<u>限制 A 做 B。</u>  \n- **handbrake**：<u>手刹，比喻“阻碍因素”。</u>  \n\n---\n\nThe difference between C-grade and A-grade managers <font color=\"#ffff00\">may very well be</font> the difference between business success or failure.\n翻译: <u>C级经理和A级经理之间的差别，很可能就是企业成败之间的差别。</u>\n\n**may very well be**：<u>很可能是、完全可能是。</u>   \n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Between</font> preserving the jobs of ordinary workers or losing them.\n翻译: <u>也是保住普通工人的工作与失去这些工作之间的差别。</u>\n\n- **“Between preserving…” 是承接前一句的 “the difference between…”，完整意思是：<u>C 级和 A 级经理的差别，很可能既是企业成败之差，也是普通员工保住工作或失去工作之差；单独成句是为了强调后果。**</u>\n---\n\nYet <font color=\"#ffff00\">mediocrity</font> is no longer enough to justify a dismissal.\n翻译: <u>然而，表现平庸已不再足以成为解雇的正当理由。</u>\n\n**mediocrity**：<u>平庸、能力一般。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nConsequently — and paradoxically — laws <font color=\"#ffff00\">introduced to protect</font> the jobs of ordinary workers may be placing those jobs at risk.\n翻译: <u>因此，具有讽刺意味的是，为保护普通工人工作而出台的法律，可能正在使这些工作面临风险。</u>\n\n**introduced to protect…**：<u>被引入来保护……。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">If </font>not placing jobs at risk, <font color=\"#ffff00\">to the extent</font> employment protection laws constrain business owners from dismissing under-performing managers, those laws act as a constraint on firm productivity and therefore on workers’ wages.\n翻译: <u>即便不是使工作岗位面临风险，只要就业保护法限制企业主解雇表现不佳的经理，这些法律就在制约企业生产率，因而也制约工人的工资。</u>\n\n- <u>这里的 if 实际上是 even if 即便 即使</u> \n- **to the extent**：<u>在……程度上；只要。</u>  \n- <u>地道意译：即便这些法律不直接导致失业，只要它们让企业难以撤换低效管理者，就会压低企业生产率，进而限制员工工资增长。</u>\n- <u>这句好难 有时间细究</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Indeed</font>, in “An International Perspective on New Zealand’s Productivity Paradox” (2014), the Productivity Commission <font color=\"#ffff00\">singled out</font> the low quality of <font color=\"#ffff00\">managerial </font>capabilities as <font color=\"#ffff00\">a cause of</font> the country’s poor productivity growth record.\n翻译: <u>事实上，在《新西兰生产率悖论的国际视角》（2014）中，生产率委员会特别指出，管理能力质量低下是该国生产率增长记录不佳的一个原因。</u>\n\n**Indeed** <u>用来加强前文观点：管理能力差确实与生产率问题有关。</u>\nsingle out**：<u>特别指出、单独挑出。</u>  \n**low quality of managerial capabilities**：<u>管理能力质量低。</u>\n**a cause of…**：……<u>的一个原因。</u>  \n\n---\n\nNor are highly paid managers themselves immune from the harm caused by the ERA’s unjustified dismissal procedures.\n翻译: <u>高薪经理本身也并非不受 ERA 无正当理由解雇程序所造成伤害的影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBecause employment protection laws <font color=\"#ffff00\">make it costlier </font>to fire an employee, employers are more cautious about hiring new staff.\n翻译: <u>由于就业保护法使解雇雇员的成本更高，雇主在雇用新员工时会更加谨慎。</u>\n\n- **make it costlier to do**：<u>使做某事成本更高。</u>  \n- \n\n---\n\nThis makes it harder for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">marginal manager</font> to gain employment.\n翻译: <u>这使得边缘经理更难获得就业机会。</u>\n\n**marginal manager**：<u>边缘型经理，指能力一般、处在录用边缘、不太有竞争力的经理。</u>  \n\n---\n\nAnd firms <font color=\"#ffff00\">pay staff less</font> because firms carry the burden of the employment arrangement going wrong.\n翻译: <u>而且公司给员工支付的薪酬更低，因为公司承担着雇佣安排出问题的负担。</u>\n\n**pay staff less**：<u>给员工支付更少。</u> \n<u>企业还可能因此压低工资，因为如果招聘失败、雇佣关系出问题，成本主要由企业承担。</u>\n\n\n\n---\n\nSociety also suffers from excessive employment protections.\n翻译: <u>社会也会因过度的就业保护而受损。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Stringent</font> job dismissal regulations adversely affect productivity growth and hamper both prosperity and overall well-being.\n翻译: <u>严格的解雇规定会对生产率增长产生不利影响，并妨碍繁荣和整体福祉。</u>\n\n**stringent**：<u>严格的、严厉的。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Across</font> the Tasman Sea, Australia deals with the unjustified dismissal paradox by excluding employees earning above a specified “high-income threshold” from the protection of its unfair dismissal laws.\n翻译: <u>在塔斯曼海对岸，澳大利亚通过将收入高于特定“高收入门槛”的雇员排除在其不公平解雇法保护之外，来处理无正当理由解雇悖论。</u>\n\n**Across the Tasman Sea**：<u>在塔斯曼海对岸，即澳大利亚。</u>  \n\n\n---\n\nIn New Zealand, a 2016<font color=\"#ffff00\"> private members’ Bill</font> tried to permit firms and high-income employees to contract out of the unjustified dismissal regime.\n翻译: <u>在新西兰，2016年的一项议员个人法案曾试图允许公司和高收入雇员通过合同约定退出无正当理由解雇制度。</u>\n\n()\n\n- **private members’ Bill**：<u>私人议员法案，指不是由政府提出，而由普通议员提出的法案。</u>  \n\n---\n\nHowever, the mechanisms proposed were <font color=\"#ffff00\">unwieldy</font> and the Bill was voted down <font color=\"#ffff00\">following</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">change in government</font><font color=\"#ffff00\"> later that year</font>.\n翻译: <u>然而，所提出的机制笨拙难行，并且在当年晚些时候政府更迭后，该法案被否决。</u>\n\n**unwieldy**：<u>笨拙的、复杂难用的、难以操作的。</u>  \n**following**：<u>在……之后。</u>  \nchange in government**：<u>政府更迭、政府换届。</u>\n**later that year**：<u>那年晚些时候。</u>  \n\n"}];
